text: s- not much to mention-decent t- i thought it was fantastic . started off with a fine malty flavor and ended with some very good hop kick . carbonation was just right d- much better than i expected from an ipa . this is one of the better beers i have had in a while . one of the best tasting beers i have had . it may not be your typical ipa style , but get over it people ! this is a very good beer .  nice looking ruby brew with a long lasting off white head .  very smooth and not overpowering though . i wish this beer was n't so thin . i would 've liked it to have some more body .

the aroma is amazing - bourbon and chocolate and roasted coffee bean . burn malt aroma is up front , followed by fudgy chocolate . i was impressed - i 'll be getting this again .  a - clear copper brew with a fair amount of bubbles an enormous head and a thick cascade of lacing all down the sides - truly gorgeous .  if you 're looking to watch those love-handels , like amstel , this may be something to consider . it lacks flavour and proves to be very bland which is emphasised by it 's cardboard-like aftertaste . one positive , is that it 's very easy to drink if you can put the taste ( or lack there of ) aside .

aroma : this started out with a huge , beautiful hoppy , floral , citrusy nose . flavor : then , i drank some & everything went downhill . it was watery & disappointing .  a mostly clear dark brown with mahogany highlights , this beer is capped with a ridiculously long-lasting beige head with excellent retention . quite the stunner , this , it 's been a while since i 've seen a beer with such good head retention .  m - goes down as easy as any ipa would .

aroma : mostly muted , with some hints of sweet malts , and a touch of alcohol , but nothing pops out at you .  appearance : great looking beer . nice , topographical head appearance that is dense , uniform , and leaves a good bit of lacing on my clean glass ( hear that ? interesting phenomenon : when i drank about half of the beer a very dense formation of creamy head formed in the center of the beer forming an almost perfect circle .  mouthfeel is very light and highly carbonated .

s : thick chocolate aroma , chocolate malt , smooth coffee , heavy cream , vanilla bean , molasses . hints of plums and cherries reveal themselves through the overall bold aroma . t/m : smoky milk chocolate and sweet cream on the initial sip . d : very rich and smooth . a decent dessert beer , pretty average .  this is one impressive looking beer indeed .  mouthfeel seems little light for a big stout the carbonation level does n't help with lightness either .

very impressive aroma and what i would expect from an imperial pilsner .  a - pours a beautiful 2 finger head , slightly orange foam , with nice lacing , and dissipates slow and sexy . flawless .  m : it was watery with some carbonation .

s. pleasant but nothing stands out besides some citric and floral hops and a bit of malt .  appearance straight black in color with a dark brown head like the crme you find on top of an espresso shot .  mouthfeel was average but could have used more texture .

the nose is respectable given the style ( and especially given the brewery ) . it 's fresh and grain-like with almost no musty hoppiness . how can a beer that smells so respectable taste like this . krasniy vostok brews some amazingly bad beer .  it presented itself very dark red , almost chocolate-colored , with a firm tan head .  m : thinner side of medium in body , carbonation is medium as well but falls off fast .

sure , it 's yellow and does n't smell like much , but this beer really hits the spot sometimes ... a good reminder that beer need not be dark , heavy , unbalanced or produced on a small scale to taste good .  bottle poured into a tulip . ( a ) - pours a hazy golden yellow color that produced a huge 3+ fluffy white head with superb retention .  slightly darker copper appreance . nice strong stench that fills your nostrils . it has a very unique strong taste at first but leaves a nice smooth after taste . i have never had it on tap but bottled is just as good i assume . highly suggested if you have not tried and are a big bock fan ...

s - dry , sour cherries with a little bit of moldy sock funk . the distinctly earthy cherry character is specifically that of cherry pits and skins . the flavor is not as lively as the aroma , though it is still quite enjoyable , but the acidity does get in the way of drinkability a bit . like every cantillon beer i have had , i find myself inhaling deeply to experience the complex fruit aroma again and again .  pours a virtually opaque black with a great tan head that sticks around .  mouthfeel was kind of thin for the serving style .

very nice aroma , looked forward to the tastes and then , wham , tastes of sour and tart cherries with some caramel .  a : wow . what a beautiful beer . from bottle to pint , it pours beautifully , giving a thick , deep , deep red body with sediments within , about as buoyant as the brew itself . small amount of strong ivory head . minimal trace , but resonates . o : if i 'm feeling ambers for the night , definitely a beer i will gravitate towards in the store .  palate is average , could be more carbonated .

leaves nice lacing behind . a bit of citrus , most likely from an american hop varietal , but i had to do some sniffing . more of an imp .  appearance is unbelievable ! pitch black with thick creamy sudsy tan head with great retention ! perfect .  m : a light bodied beer that has a decent amount of carbonation and some robust drying qualities , sometimes a bit too much .

plain smelling . maybe a bit like cut straw . once again true to the style . i felt i had to give low marks for smell as it was nothing great .  poured chilled in flared glass . a : cloudy light orange ; billowy head ; great lacing and abundant carbs ; nice job !  almost like drinking beef jerky . there is very little in the way of hops and just a small bit of malt on the back end .

i was a little leery based on the aroma , but was pleasantly surprised by this smooth ale .  when popped i was concerned wit the lack of carbonation , when i poured into a pilsner glass , it came alive . nice one inch head with a beautiful aroma , great amber color whith a very rich hue .  m- a little syrupy , actually ... thicker than i 'd like to see for a single ipa o- love it .

smell is nothing much honestly . i was not expecting much after the smell . taste was exactly what this style should be . a bit on the sweet side , but overall exactly what i want in a pilsner .  towering and extremely thick white head .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , but seemingly watery with a very low dose of carbonation .

s - big notes of delicious fresh hops . one of the best smelling beers i 've encountered . t - man this stuffs good ! the caramel malt provides a nice backbone , but does n't get in the way of the hops . another great beer from surly , no surprise !  pours a slightly cloudy deep golden brownish orange color with massive pale tan head of sudsyness . lots of active carbonation moving about . nice amount of lace on the glass . halfway through the beer and there is still a tight , one-finger head hanging around .  a little too carbonated for my liking . a little smoothness would help .

smells unbelievably powerful . stong earthy hop presence melded with an apricot like sweetness .  that said this is far from a great pale ale . reddish amber in color with a huge fluffy head , lacing everywhere ... you really ca n't look much better than this . look stone , you make amazing hoppy beers .  the palate is average for the style .

dark with a slight amber hue , low in carbonation , small head , roasted malt in nose , dry malty flavor , between a brown and a porter .  poured into a la chouffe tulip a - deep gluggy brown/black pour , velvety deep tan half finger head and some nice lacing s - vanilla , molasses , coffee , dark chocolate , some nice hops , earth , wood , grass , charred and toasted malts and grains , some nice yeast and velvety smoothness t - flowers , nice hops , vanilla , bitterness , yeast ( very sweet ) , dark chocolate , charred wood , deep bitter-toasted-sweet malts , a very nice soapy note , slight citrus and tons of flavor m - huge body , tons of complexity , nice balance , low acidity and very nice bitterness d - for the stout lover or the lover of beers with velvety smoothness and lots of flavor , this one is for you .  fault : it lacks a little body , but hay , i could drink this to i fell over ( with a smile on my face ) !

appearance : dark and sleek nose : faint chocolate . not a lot in the aroma department .  ( bb date 9-04 ) pours a nice cloudy peach or light orange color ( almost blond ) . superb appearance !  light in body though it does n't live up to the initial crispness of the nose . carbonation seems appropriate .

a good example of a belgian dubbel for those just getting into belgian brewing .  pitch black color with mahogany edges , the aroma is full of dark fruits and chocolate . its got a bit more kick than most porters , but it really works . definitely in the top tier of porters  the smoked malt is a bit harsh on the palette , and the beer lacks enough body to temper the rough edges in this department .

s- not much nose from this tap but subtle hints of bread t- another great tasting offering from the boston beer co. nice balanced taste nothing overpowering clean and crisp .  poured from an 11.2 oz bottle into my brand-new authentic duvel goblet . light golden color with a massive foamy head ( fills half the goblet ) that stays around forever & clings to the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel is very thin and almost flat , which suits the scotch flavors but is a little off-putting from a beer perspective .

s= big booze comes from the nose . there 's a lot of roast to it as well as some odd estery sweetness to it . the only problem is that it smells a lot of alcohol . almost reminds me of wws in a way only less sweet in the nose . t= the taste tops the smell anyday ! wow this is a smooth easy drinking stout .  the froth slowly cascaded to from a thick and creamy tan head and reveal a dark opaque liquid . the head had excellent retention ( i do n't think it reduced in size at all ) and left a perfect lace . i tend to find nitro-cans or cans in general seem to reduce the smell and taste of the brew and in particular the malt .  mouthfeel was a little more watery than i expected .

intro : considered rare where i live ( massachusetts ) , the sculpin has quite a reputation ... appearance : golden haze with a nice lacing similar to smuttynose finest kind smell : great typical american hop profile ( citrus , lemon , mango etc . ) .fruity , piney ... no noticeable malt like dfh taste : hops all the way..all that i love in american i.p.a's..a bitterness that smacks you in the face like green flash west coast i.p.a..a faint trace of sweetness but clearly hops are the main course mouthfeel : good carbonation that maintains retention throughout drinkability : goes down like the best of them..although for $ 10 for a bomber in ma ( when you can find it ) i think it would be better to just mix west coast i.p.a & torpedo i.p.a cause that 's what it tastes like  translucent redish hues come through very nicely . pours a very large frothy off white head .  m - very light , slightly watery .

i tried and yeah ... drink this one fresh if you can . classic stout beer that is not a milk stout . not much on the smell but who cares ... .we are talking taste here and nothing else . silky smooth , creamy , easy to drink , an overall wonderful stout .  a-very dark chestnut colored , slightly cloudy , lots of bubbles . there 's a thick amount of cream colored head . the head stays and there 's a lot of lacing as well .  mouthfeel is somewhat grainy and perhaps a little more carbonated than i 'd like this style to be .

smells bready , a little hopy , light roasted malt . mmm nice soft roasted malt front , not too sweet .  a- pours black , two finger tan head . great retention , great lacing .  glass : two taster glasses from pib sib , and a duvel glass ( the duvel glass held the best head which is not surprising ) it pours golden with a strong off white quarter inch head ; immaculate lacing as its fingers drip softly down the glass . deep tones of pine and citrus , with subtle notes of bourbon . first sip brings hints of caramel , and the finish is dry with a slight fruit aftertaste .

i prefer to let mine stand almost to room temperature as to enjoy all of the wonderful aromatics before imbimbing . the perfume accented bouquet is very floral & fruity with some earthen notes . enjoy fraoch with rich traditional dishes such as arbroath smokie ( wood-smoked haddock ) , colcannon ( cabbage , carrots , potatoes and turnips ) and/or black bun ( fruit cake ) .  to me , this is just a beautiful looking beer . it pours clean and dark , a lush ruby colour with orange tones on the edges .  body is a bit thin and alcohol is slightly burning but nothing out of control .

there were hints of cinnamon and nutmeg in the nose , amidst the maltiness . not a lot of hop leanings .  there is a gorgeous 1-inch head that is nice and light tan with some tight bubbles and some intermingled bigger bubbles . i think i can float a dime on that head .  m : the body is quite light , too light i think . the carbonation is slightly too mellow , i would have liked it to be a little livelier and sparkling .

smell : definitely not as aromatic as i was expecting .  wow , probably the nicest billowing white head and clinging lace out of the 14 odd oktoberfests i have sampled this fall ! pale orange color is on the low end of the o'fest spectrum .  light in body , but not watery . a small amount of carbonation livens the beer , but does not define it .

s- average in smell , a lot less of the fruits and sugars yu get from other belgium beers . t- outstanding . sadly i only had one bottle or i would have had a second right behind it . all in all , very well crafted dubbel , and one of my favorites in the style .  pretty sure this is from one of the original batches ... a - pours into my duvel tulip a crystal clear light straw hue with a massive fluffy three finger head that slowly faded to leave big side lacing and a dense creamy white blanket . just excellent .  and maybe just a little bit more carbonation maybe ?

presented in allagash white glass with lemon . great foamy head with a strong lemon/citrus zing . a little bitter on the aftertaste , but overall it is very smooth . lightly carbonated and easy drinkability make this a very refereshing beer .  phenomenal retention and a bunch sticky lace .  m : fairly light-bodied with champagne-like carbonation . a bit rough on the palate . the brett is a bit too dominant , and the mouthfeel is a bit too carbonated , but otherwise , quite nice .

very nice .  pours dark brown , almost opaque , though it shines a deep ruby when backlit . light tan , very creamy head lasts all the way down .  mouthfeel is hurt a bit by this beer 's charictaristic carbonation .

s -- i smell corn , alcohol , a little hops , and not much else .  a : pours a deep amber color with a really big fluffy head with adequate lacing .  light body that feels a little thin until the moderate carbonation helps with the texture close to the finish .

pours a deep mahogany color with a small white head tha leaves enough lacing , smells of some caramel malts and not much else .  just a spot of lacing here and there one the sides of the glass has a wonderful color deep browns in the shadows and rusty amber in its highlights .  m- a little on the thin side , but the carbonation level is pleasant .

very enticing . t : dry ground coffee beans . i remember having a much more favorable experience then , especially with the taste , which i recall being as sweet and enjoyable as the nose . i 'll definitely have to try a pint again to see if that impression is reaffirmed .  a : a beautiful beer ; pours a crystal clear golden-amber color with a finger of foamy white head . most of the head stays for the full glass , there 's tons of lacing , and carbonation bubbles never stop flowing .  the mouthfeel was thin in body , but huge in taste .

s - a rather non-intriguing malt aroma is the only evident scent . t - earthy malt flavor complimented by a subtle hop edge makes for a unique flavor .  it could n't look better , perfect 5 for appearance .  full taste , slight choc/coff flavors and no alcohol flavor , it 's buried in the taste of the beer . it 's average when the fizz goes away and seems a little watery and the only thing missing over the cumberland 's porter is the aftertaste did not last and it seemed to miss a note inside the flavor . when i went back a week later , it was n't the same porter i 'd tasted , and was more like the other ringneck beers .

s : the beer smells of coffee and chocolate , but its a bit weak smelling .  this beer really looks great in the glass . darkest brown ( just a shade short of black ) in color with a large , lasting tan head and very good lacing .  feels really thicker than it looked .

quite a nice chocolate milk aroma with a red berry edge . really turned to a chocolate porto smell at room temp which i thought was nice . but did n't transfer into the taste or work with the thin body .  pours a glowing golden straw with a healthy white head . excellent lace and retention .  i had this bozone hefe weizen first time out of a growler filled at the bozone brewery in bozeman , mt . shit tasted soo good , and i needed moore . i fancy myself a ipa kinda guy , but this hef is like none other around . maybe a couple , but its dayum goood . not only does this beer taste great , but the color is beautiful . get some and get drunk !

the aroma is not terribly enticing and quite frankly reminded me of paint thinner with a dash of floral hops . once i got around the aroma i liked it .  appearance : dark black in color with a thick 2 '' fluffy head that lasts through the drink .  mouthfeel is light with less than average carbonation and slight alcohol warming can be felt .

i smelled this from the bottle and could detect a definite raspberry smell , however when i poured it into the glass , i could n't put my nose on any one smell except for the crisp raspberry and hops . maybe my nose is n't that distinguished yet ?  this poured out of the foil covered 750 with ludicrous foam . the bottle was split in a duvel glass and a maudite glass ; the head was to the top of each and almost never receded . finally , there appeared an iceberg of chunky white tan foam in the center .  mouthfeel fell a little short , but only because the carbonation was so low . felt okay , but with more carbonation it would be much better .

s : rye bread and malt , sweetness and yeast . t : rich coffee , toffee , malt , and brown sugar .  wow , beautiful color . a very hazy carmel brown .  light to medium mouth feel . tastes great.full flavor , with a little bite . for a dark beer it 's refreshing .

the dancer smells very good . you get pine and citrus .  poured from a bomber into a tulip . orange amber pour with three fingers of rich , creamy foam on top . very plush , sticky head .  it has a very thin mouthfeel .

it 's got a sour sort of scent .  appearance- pours a great two finger head with a very thick and everlasting foam for the duartion of the entire 11.2 oz of beer .  m- the carb is a little rougher than i prefer for my porters ... aftertaste is kind of burnt .

amber colored with an off white head that sticks around . has a earthy , leather , rope smell . medium bodied , it has a super smooth , creamy mouthfeel . a nicely crafted , well rounded lagar .  great 2 finger thick head that sticks around for a while .  m - good mouthfeel , though again similar to a stout . feels a little thin with the appropriate amount of carbonation .

smell , is a bit dodgy but the taste i would describe as a `` rising bitterness '' not sure how to translate that into brewspeak .  beautiful pour . looks like a wonderful iipa .  like an overpowering mix of graham cracker , butter popcorn jelly belly 's and allspice . take everything in the scent notes and add lemon citrus notes plus the potent 8.6 % alcohol and you have a recipe for disaster . the taste lingers and lingers . i truly , truly suffered through a bomber of this . my wife had about two sips and nearly gagged . i 've never been a fan of `` pumpkin '' beers , since there is never any pumpkin/squash taste and only `` pie spice '' , but was told that this was one of the better ones . this just reaffirms my belief that `` pumpkin beer '' is a complete waste of brewers ' time and effort , but it 's such a moneymaker that they ca n't refuse to make it . do yourself a favor and steer clear of this abomination of beer .

smell-not getting much of the classic banana aroma . i am getting some spice and some yeasts . taste-very sweet , sweetest hefe i 've had . overall-another nice hefeweizen from a texas brewery . better then the lawnmower , and be glad this beer is joining the lineup .  while this beer 's beautiful bright golden amber body sparkled with constant effervescence and the thick , creamy white head sheeted and even chunked the side of the glass , it was not funny .  smells a lot like hershey 's syrup with an alcoholic backbone . i think this beer just stained my counter -- this beast is thick , too thick for me to drink .

it had a lite scent , malt was present . it had a nice clean malt taste that was accompanied by a slightly bitter hop taste .  beautiful amber color with a thick off-white head .  the mouthfeel is a little anemic , with a lingering aftertaste .

a bit spicy in the nose but not very aromatic .  '' pours with a very substantial head , nearly out of control , enormous and sticky . dense yellow-white bubbles surge and froth , pillowing into a crowning mesa . rather auburn in color ; when held to light shimmers an electric bronze and metallic apricot , with streamers everywhere racing to the lip of the glass . stunning !  the body is heavier than i 'm used to for a wit , and while i 'm usually extremely impressed with great lakes approach to mouthfeel , i find this one a little too heavy for the style .

the aroma , sweet maypo oatmeal on a snowy winter morning . rancid and nasty .  this has to be one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen . fantastically ruby and perfectly clear .  next to no carbonation left - leaving the mouthfeel much thinner than would be preferred , even for a barleywine or a barleywine that has been allowed to sit for a while .

light , dry , nutty , wine-like ... perfect with foul ___ a : deep clear amber body with a quite persistent two finger off white head . s : not particularly aromatic ... just hints of toasted nuts , spices , neutral hops , and , believe it or not , alcohol . t : quite wine in its malt profile ... there is buttered rye toast , but at the same time i can almost taste white grapes .  this beer poured as black as the night with no light getting through . it formed a huge foamy dark tan head that refused to go away and remined me of a root beer float .  m - on tap at least it 's a little over carbed for my tastes , but i like my beers on the lighter side of carbed . medium-light body .

i 'm not sure whether i like this better than draught guinness or not . beamish has an original gravity of 9.75 plato - just under guinness , and the same alcohol content . it looks just as great in an imperial pint and has the same silky mouthfeel . its flavors offers a distinct chocolate note , a light touch of roastiness , and a sublime layer of wide bitterness .  appearance- pours a hazy dark reddish brown with a beautiful one finger super creamy off-white head . a perfect half finger cap and collar remain the entire beer along with thick sheets of coated lacing .  taste : same as the nose mouthfeel : medium bodied , under carbonated drinkability : alcohol is amazingly absent but the lack of carbonation holds it back a bit .

there was a light grassy aroma with hints of grain in the background .  [ best served in a trappist glass ] poured a medium murky yellow almost gold in color with a huge ( 3 to 4 fingers ) white frothy head that was fully lasting and had excellent lacing .  m : fairly thick but not necessarily creamy . medium-heavy with a mid-range carbonation .

has a mild malty smell to it .  poured a deep black so black i swear it sucked the light out of the room .  before expanding my palate yuengling used to be my favorite beer . i gre up in the dc area so we had plenty of it around . i still consider this a great beer for a night full of drinking , but not one that i would drink because i want to enjoy a beer . i still love you yuengling and i ca n't wait to have you again ... stupid yuengling does n't ship to ca .

big cliffs of frothy lacing left behind . s - earthy lemongrass hops over pale malt . t - lemon and orange citrus hits up front .  look : orange yellow color , cloudy , huge dense fluffy head with uber good retention and lacing smell : blast of brett funk , with cloves , pepper , citrus taste : up front : brett funk , spices .  mouthfeel : the high carbonation is the only shortcoming of this beer .

copper in color , very yeasty , with a slightly sweet finish -- this beer reminds me of anchor 's steam beer because of the yeasty smoothness . it is strong like sierra nevada , but without sierra 's spicey after taste .  very good half inch withe head that lasts almost the entire pint and leaves good lacing .  mouthfeel takes a hit for thinness , though it 's not at all watery and would be difficult to have it be much thicker and work with the wine elements .

s - oh god . burnt rubber and melting plastic .  a : gorgeous look to this one . dark amber body , with a two-finger cloud white head with great retention and enough lacing to make you wan na take a spoon to the sides of the glass to get your money 's worth .  m- medium , with low carbonation .

nice head with an average smell , nothing special in that department . nothing really to complain about .  a - the body is the color of deep mohogany . it has a thick nitro-like head with excellent stamina . ~ this is a good drinker .  s- mmm chocolate . d- as far as taste goes this beer is delicious , yet again not complex but very chocolate and the low alcohol is completely hidden , so id have to say the low abv works in its favor m- thin not exactly watery but still thinner than i would like in a flavorful beer .

s- very little smell at all , i can only catch a faint maltiness .  pours a deep black color with a thick , white , creamy head which does n't go away .  there is a slight fruitiness going down that leaves a pleasant finish . drinkability : this is a very drinkable beer , and one of the best of bg 's light beers .

the smell is amber malts and rye , a nice aroma . cough , hack , cough ! !  pours with a black body topped by a brown thick lasting head with good lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and kind of watery .

never had a coffee beer pour orange , was expecting brown . aroma does n't have coffee in it , starting to wonder if there was a mislabled bottle or something . smells just like a pale or ipa without coffee . lame attempt at explanation from shop keeper was that its the mild ethiopian coffee and our american palates are n't in tune with it .  this pours a dark brown with little amber , ruby hues . a great sticky head that also provides some great side glass lacing .  mouthfeel : medium mouthfeel , slightly syrupy , okay amount of carbonation , some hop tingle on the tongue , a bit bitter , and leaves mouth with a sweet/stickey feel and very slight dry feel .

aroma : a rum soaked raisin/plum nose . strong bouquet . some oak and alcohol smells too .  bottle , it 's a beautiful golden red color with ample head and fair retention .  mouth , although nicely coating , is thinner than i would have preferred .

s : for aroma i detected light hints of wheat and sour green apples , fairly simple , with musky grains .  deep red , slightly opaque with a great big 2 or 3 finger head . left lots of lacing when i finished the glass there was lacing almost top to bottom .  m : nothing special here , light and easy on the palate .

s : not much in this department . very light nutty chocolate aromas , sort of like the nutella factory a mile away caught on fire . t : the taste is a huge improvement over the nose : dark chocolate nuttiness , like a fresh baked batch of chocolate chip oatmeal cookies . it 's tasty , but it wears on you a bit .  the beer poured into the glass black with some slight brown translucency . the head was tan to brown , large , and in charge lacing , no coating the glass from top to bottom .  the texture was thick , and left a thin film in my mouth almost like when you eat too much syrup .

roast malt nose with a slight smell of shoe leather . not a very good smell for an ipa . not much hops in the nose just malt .  can : poured a light golden color lager with a large pure white foamy head with great retention and some lacing .  m - silky , almost to the point of feeling oily .

s- maybe a little brown sugar , or molasses but mostly all i smell is malt t- made me say `` oooohhh '' after i tasted it for the first time , really nice carbonation rolls over the tongue , the flavors present i really have a hard time pining down , *takes few sips , its almost wine like , malty , a little fruit in the background , slight oak flavor , very nice , brown sugar or almost burnt molasses in there too , i can taste the booze but it is no where near over bearing . m : after the flavor , quickly comes the dry finish , so much so that my tongue is parched , mouth feel is nothing special and i would of liked it a little more viscous d : amazing the flavors and the look make up for the smell and mouth feel to make a really great collaboration for the right price of 2.99 for 8.8 % abv it really is a bargain , i will be cellaring some and getting more to drink now .  pours black with a large , thick light brown head that persists .  seems a little thin compared to others in the style , almost watery in the finish which is the only thing really detracting on this one for me .

smell : kind of weak on the aroma . a sweet malty/caramel smell to it . a little spicy .  a : it 's a dark brown color with a light tan head about a thumbs width . the head on this beer is very full and creamy . there 's great lacing in the glass .  this beer pours a dark brown but is clear enough and still enough that you can almost see through it . the taste is nice with a nice roasted malt character . i believe i can detect a little bit of a caramel malt type of flavor in the undertones . elegantly simple and extremely drinkable .

typical pils smell , not much else . then the corn takes over turning it into a corn beer . a very drinkable beer , could and would have another , although , the thick body is filling .  excellent head retention and lacing , with very good legs as well . pretty impressive looking .  very fizzy , easy to drink . light caramel flavors dominate when carbonation has n't taken hold already.. fresh baked bread and nothing offensively bold in terms of the holy trinity of yeast , banana & clove . finishes a bit salty , leaving behind a oceanic yet grainy aftertaste which is a little strange.. and honestly , the only real drawback to this beer .

nose - lots of wheat with some lemon/citrus aroma as well . having never seen ( or smelled ) a lemon myrtle plant i ca n't say if that is what it smells like but i imagine it is . overall - pretty solid beer , tastes good and has a nice enough body . the nose could use some work ( if it smelled how it tasted i would be all over it . )  poured a dark black color with a darker beige head on it .  winish , also slightly floral , the start is mildly sweet , the top skimpy . finish purposeful in its acidity , the hops masterful in their spicy bite and the aftertaste long lasting and quite bitter .
very faint smell . tropical fruit and floral aromas are there .  i love the color of this beer . can .  m - sharp carbonation is a little oveer the top .

is n't emmitting much of a smell , but the taste more than makes up for it .  pours a deep , dark red with a decent head . one of the nicest hues i 've seen .  this is by far the worst brown ale that i have ever tried . it looks and smells ok and the mouth is decent but it just tastes bad ... i cant explain it .

recently i noticed it again in the dark bottle and gave it another try . no skunk taste this time . it has all the flavors but they do n't jump out at you . hoppiness right away followed by nuttiness and sweet flavors , again not overwhelming but definitely all there . decent mouthfeel .  jet black with a finger mocha head .  m : creamy , but kind of thin .

the smell is common for a stout , with the presence of barley being more than detectable , but overall the scent is fainter than i expected to be .  almost no head what so ever . what was there was dark brown and had good retention and left alright lacing . beautiful beer .  t/m - starts out smooth and thick feeling with a light caramel malt flavor . a sharp bitterness and carbonation bite hit and the malty flavor increases and becomes sweeter . d - i see nothing `` belgian '' about this beer , but for a bock i think its very good .

the smell is citrus spicey and sweet . i was impressed with the complex aroma . taste was a let down from the smell .  '' a : motor oil with satanic red head . i love it already .  medium body with the tight carbonation found in the style . this one happens to be a little under carbonated for my tastes , but perhaps it is the batch .

a- very pale light yellow beer and a frosty snow white head . s- earthy/grassy hops . not very strong . t- light , peppery herbal hops . nice dry and clean finish . light and easy drinkin ' with a nice hop snap .  great looking beer .  s -- caramel , toffee t- it probably has more ibu 's than the typical db , but the traditional/textbook db flavors are all there . m- moderate ( a little `` lighter '' than the typical db . ) d-this is a very drinkable double bock .

fresh but average .  keeps a smooth leftover skimming thats favorably thick and the lacing clouds the glass with a heavy sheeting . wow ! looks scrumptious !  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with little carbonation .

s : really malty - almost like a candy smell . hops are there . i 'm not really sure how this will taste . reminds me of a belgian ale . t : tastes like it smells , but in a really good way .  poured from 750 ml bottle into a chalice style glass a : awesome ! mostly clear golden color with a touch of orange in the light ; abundant puffy white head that lasts and some great lacing .  i 'd call this one dangerous winter warmer .

reviewing from notes . i had this beer during oktoberfest 2010 in munich . an amazing experience .  superior lacing & similar head retention s : dark fruit & leafy hops , that 's about it.. t : follows the nose a touch of dryness & some dark chocolate up front .  body is a little thin , lacking that creamy mouthfeel that would make this beer better .

s : citrus and pine , not as strong as i would like but good . my guess is this is n't past it 's prime fwiw . t : it has the perfect amount of bitterness for me , finishes dry , grapefruit is prodominant m : medium , carbonation is about right o : overall this is a good/very good ipa . if you like good ipa 's i would recommend this for sure , i just think its way overpriced .  tremendous head and excellent light orange/yellow color . highly carbonated .  i had this year 's version at the brewpub and while it is not as good as great lakes ' christmas beer or sn celebration , it is still a very good beer . you can really smell the cinnamon and taste the blend of malts and spices . if you are in the toledo area it is worth the stop at maumee bay brewing co. for a pint or three or maybe a stop at the andersons or other store for a bomber .

i was expecting a bit more from the aroma , but it was very subtle . nothing all that interesting - i sure hope the flavor is a bit more exciting .  color is a deep sable brown , head is tan and fairly persistent .  body is a touch too thin .

smell : had to let it sit for a bit to get a better smell . once a bit warmer , a fruity aroma comes through with a grape tartness . definitely notice the grapes and perhaps lemon ?  jet black body with a cascading tan head . laces the glass like a good belgium beer .  nice caramel notes on the front , just hate the feel and finish ... the alcohol is hidden very well , despite the finish still easy to drink . too much harsh hops for me to love it , but this is still pretty good and worth trying

nice clear darker amber color with a quater inch off white head that stayed around for most of the beer . s- i smell a lot of malts upfront ... i do n't know if that was suppose to be but i got a huge malt body from this . piney hops come through but very faintly . i do n't know if this is the way it 's suppose to smell but it 's not what i expected for sure . huge citrus hop taste with a nice malty backbone .  it looks perfect . the head stays around quite a while and leaves some great lacing .  m - crisp and refreshing for sure . almost no carbonation on the tongue but the beer is still carbonated though i would n't say its `` smooth per se '' .

smell is subdued sweetness with some peach and light spices .  poured into a perfect pint -- a=nice copper color with white 3 finger head .  sure , the mouthfeel was ok , but it did nothing to improve the taste .

smells like a muted ayinger celebrator . not bad , but totally unremarkable . taste : creamy and smooth , with mild chilies and cinnamon up front , cocoa finish .  glad to find this at the local beer store ... a : perfect pitch black with a thick 2 inch mocha colored head that slowly fades . exceptional !  the mouthfeel is average , as is the carbonation level .

i tried tis one last ; pours a deep gold color w/ a fluffy white head which dissapates quickly , some lacing ; very faint aroma , mostly hops , but some fruity , malty undertones as well ; thin , `` watered down '' flavor , some tangy yeasty flavor , but w/ too much hop bite and a slight `` metallic '' aftertaste ; a light bodied-high carbonated mouthfeel , a bit too light & bubbly ; i just got into wheats , so i 'm not an expert , but this 1 is a no-go w/ me ... .  color is brown , pretty dark , with real deep and dark garnet highlights . head is perfect , great retention , nice texture-creamy , perfect size and very nice lacing .  smell was average , mouthfeel a bit on the thin side .

s - not a very strong order here . a slight hop and grass smell . t- interesting taste here . starts and ends slightly bitter . notes of fruit . d - even through i really enjoy this ale , i do n't have the desire to have one after the other .  sure it 's only appearance , but what other beer looks as cool as this right after you 've poured it ?  mouthfeel was decent , although rather watery .

well the aroma right off is funk . i asked if it might be the brett triple but it 's the regular . the aroma has a sour yeast component , no hops ( fine for a tripel ) and mostly base malt and candi sugar . kind of a strange aroma .  appearance : a monster three finger head that has really good retention .  m : body is on the light side of moderate . carbonation is on the high side of moderate ( a little much ) .

bire de couleur rose-orang avec la plus grande quantit de levure et de grumeaux de peau de bleuets que j'ai vue de ma vie , on dirait un porto vintage de 20 ans qui aurait t brass . nez fruit aigre , en bouche on se bat avec des grumeaux c'est dsagrable .  aggressive pour leads to a massive mocha colored head , billowey and frothy . excellent retention , at the end leaves a plateau in the middle of the glass , like you might find in hot chocolate .  first of all , this beer predates the craft beer era . it 's makers brew a tastey brown lager that they call a porter , and they make this delicious pilsner that they call an ale . they were doing this when our fathers were toasting our european heritage with schlitz . it is light bodied , as it should be , and very drinkable . i suppose i can understand that if someone was expecting an ale they might misjudge this beer - but close your eyes , forget your encyclopedeaic knowledge of beer names - and imagine a time in 1975 when the best pilsner on the east coast was called an ale .

s : syrup , booze , berry , fruity , pancakes ( maybe blueberry pancakes , because it takes me back to a memory of a pancake restaurant on hwy 26 from portland to the coast ... when i was just a boy ... a ; ruby brn and clear t : syrup , some berries , pretty blended flavors , booze there but not as strong as nose m ; medium bodied d : pretty good for abv overall : pretty tasty , and some interesting flavors of berries , sugar , and baked goods .  it was pitch black and thick . it had a 2 finger dark brown head that slowly settled into a constant foam . no visible carb but great lacing that stuck around till it was finished .  light mouthfeel .

s : very sticky , piney hop aroma but it is a little hard to detect t : the hop profile follows the nose : resiny , sticky , piney hop attack with an ample nutty malt background .  pours a thick hazy apple juice color , has lots of carb action , and a three inch head with stability that dissipates slowly with lots of lacing .  3.0 m : light body , too light for my liking .

a - deep brown , with a great , foamy tan head that retains very nicely s - coffee and chocolate malts . an inviting smell , but nothing that blows me away t - true to its name , there is a very nice smokey character to this beer .  loose but pillowy like head of two fingers with a white colour . crazy , thick rings of lacing with a full finger of retention . beautiful .  what happened pete ? ? this was once a distinctive brown/nut brown ale , but since being bought out , this beer has fallen quite a few notches . to my tastebuds this is just a mere shadow of it 's former self . i forget where i read it , but someone said the whole portfolio seems to have been `` tweaked '' , with dissappointing results .

nice and brown with a short head , doryman 's dark ale also has a malty aroma and a great flavor from the roasted malts and cascade and mt . hood hops . it is a very good brown ale .  fiery burnt orange , a little hazy , topped with a good inch of ivory foam . looks terrific . smells hoppy , as i expected .  the mouthfeel is strange . there is consistently this sharp little flavor in the background , but the body is medium , maybe a bit more full , and the carbonation is pleasantly on the low side of sharp .

s - sharp malt and lemon zest . t - nice medium malt flavor , citrus twang and bitterness .  the beer pours a very dark black with a light tan head . the head rises about 3 finger and has decent retention falling slowly into a creamy head that coasts the beer . good lacing .  feels light bodied with tons of carbonation .

smell is hoppy and alocholish .  large ( for a beer ) bubbles consistantly make their way to the head from the depths and sides of the glass , giving it a seemingly permanent finger 's worth of head . absolutely gorgeous .  moutfeel is about right , seems to be a bit high on the carbonation for me though , but i can deal with that .

the nose was not very apparent but did offer some slight citrus notes . not overwhelming by any stretch of the imagination , it offered very clean and crisp flavors that were light in a good way .  a : pours a translucent amber with coppery highlights against the light . the head is 3 fingers of fluffy cream colored foam that collapses over several minutes into a dense half-finger cap on the brew , leaving substantial lacing in its wake . even to the end of the drink there is a substantial cap .  smoke lends clean dry finish to this smooth , medium bodied stout-like beer with flat carbonation .

i really love the assertive but not overbearing coffee notes in the aroma .  appearance : pours a dense , 2-finger head that recedes gradually and leaves beautiful lace on the glass . color is desribed on the bottle as being `` tawny , '' and i could n't agree more . bright and clear , no sign of haziness . gorgeous presentation .  the mouthfeel is a little uneventful .
smells pretty good .  appearance : pours a beautiful clear mahogany with tow fingers of tan head and good retention .  m - the feel is nothing special ; kind of thin and light on carbonation .

the taste is a little flat as well ; but in all fairness that would n't have been as noticeable if the aroma was n't so pleasant .  look is straight up orange , one inch fluffy cream colored head sinks to half its original volume , very nice lacing as well .  medium bodied , highly carbonated and prickly from the hops . i 'm a little put off by the amount of carbonation and i prefer the sweeter stouts .

the nose is pretty faint , i ca n't pick up much chocolate or chili spices .  pours a perfect golden color in my tulip glass with a huge white head like whipped cream . the head is so massive that it takes me about five minutes to pour a glass while waiting for the head to subside a little .  the body is a bit on the thin side , which is n't bad for the style , but does n't do anything to set this beer apart .

cinammon malty nose - very minor . toasty hearty deep malt taste backed by a medium bitter .  pours pitch black , i mean the darkest black i have ever seen in a beer ( this is my first russian imperial stout ) . i decided to pour the whole thing in my pint glass and it seriously looks like the glass is actually tinted a piano black . amazing . very dark brownish/tan head that looks creamier than the average stout or porter . a crazy looking beer .  mouthfeel is thin and smooth . about par for the style .

the smell is perhaps not this beer 's strongest asset , but it 's still fair , and more interesting than most local lagers , truth be told . butter , fruit and leafiness , with a strange something in the background that 's a bit off-putting . the taste more than makes up for the nose , however . not overly thin ; nice to see a lager with a bit of meat to it . a great sessional ( given the abv , probably a plus !  poured into tulip at 40 degrees . pours with a 1/2 glass full of thick , tan head which fades to heavy film and leaves a ton of lacing .  and now i know why people say it tastes like chocolate syrup , because it kinda does . but this is really good if you like chocolate . probably 1200 calories in this bottle . but who 's drinking beer and watching calories ?

the aroma is decidedly hoppy , citrusy like cascade hops .  but humor me if you will : the ale pours in a lovely golden nitro-fied cascade like so many other nitro-cans with a mouthfeel people seem to like or hate .  m : who cares ?

the color is a nice amber color not too amber , but decent , lil too much of a carbonation feel when i drink it , overall this one was a good hefe , i could really see drinking this one again , or even becoming a staple in the choc line up .  pours an absolutely beautiful deep amber color with a thick creamy head . excellent head retention .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , a bit drying on the back end .

this is a truly excellent beer from the first sip . a confident beer , which , unlike many high-rated american beers , does not rely on extreme bitterness or high abv or some other exaggerated quality to give it distinction . it aims to be a rich , full-bodied porter , and it hits the mark . not much to the smell , in my opinion .  pours a very nice reddish brown color with a fluffy 2 finger head taht slowly settles and leaves a nice lace as it goes down .  m : quite creamy , but rather thin bodied ( kind of like guinness , really ) , with a slightly dry and underwhelming finish .

it smells of cherry , predominantly . i served it fairly cold and it was enjoyable . more cherries came out as it warmed up , which i let happen to get that aspect of the beer but i actually preferred the more subtle cherry flavor when it was cold .  hazy deeper yellow appearance with a huge mousse-like head . very attractive and dense delicate laces .  m : here is my biggest complaint about this beer . it 's just hard for me to get past that much carbonation . d : despite the issue with the overwhelming carbonation .

had this out of a bottle ... a : crisp golden yellow color with a very large thick head ... s : some fruits and some crisp hop smell ... t : some apple , peach and a hint of lemon .  great head and retention . beautiful color .  m= light as hell . medium and average all around .

since my smeller is n't to good i 'll have to say it smells of a roasted coffee and also i detect a slight sweet or licorice smell .  pours a golden hue with ample head and generous lacing .  m- i would like just a tad more on the mouth feel but it works well with the hoppiness of this beer .

smell is roasted and smoky , name suits the smell well with stovepipe because that is what it smells like . taste is strange for me .  pours with a thick sponge like brown head , and has good retention .  m : at first , the mouthfeel was a bit thin .

doesnt really surprise or overjoy me here , just a nice aroma . t-very nicely balanced with a sweet and malty body and a crisp and dry bitter hoppiness near the finish , its complex yet simple at the same time , also quite refreshing and not heavy on the pallete or stomach which makes it a good session beer but also a good beer to have with a meal .  a : exceptionally bright amber/gold with a dense pure white head with excellent retention .  poured from a 12 oz bottle into a imperial pint glass . has notes of citrus and pine hops plus some apricot hints in there too . first taste it has upfront hop taste like a 90 minute ipa with a smooth fruity taste on the finish . this beer is a very refreshing ipa with a not to much fruit back but just enough to make it refreshing .

lacing is excellent s-faint hints of lemon and slightly biscuity malt t-very refreshing slight citric quality on first sip . the presence of hops remains true throughout ( fuggles maybe ) . d-this is one damned fine sessionable brew .  a - a tall , vigorous pour unleashed a monstrous three-finger faded sepia-colored head . just fantastic retention and thick lace covering most of the glass . the beer has a fine haze to the lightly bronzed orange-amber .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and slightly over carbonated for my tastes .

smell - very nutty followed by extremely subtle aroma of some sweet fruits .  very sharp appearance to this bottle . poured into tulip a : black as night . excellent head formation and retention . this is exactly how a stout should look in the glass .  the aroma is all one note with lots of sweetn raspberries . the beer is very light , it goes right down without much lasting flavor .

it was served on tap in a 22 oz . the smell left a little to be desired . a few hops and a slight bitterness , other than that there wasnt much of anything to speak of . the taste was much bolder than the smell .  appearance- an exceptionally enormous head graces this clear , glowing red beer .  hirter morchl is entirely different from this . my main gripes are that the body is light ... extremely light , but a lack of complexity is something rather commonplace in this style of beer . the remarkably dry finish of this beer really seals the deal for me .

the smell is a little muted ... a little spice , and a touch of pale malt . the smell could be a much more intense and interesting . the beer , however , has a very flavorful taste ... malt , honey , peppery spice ( peppermint-esque ?  this is a beauty with a full , sticky head .  the look is a see-through brownish red which let me know right away that it will lack in flavor . the smell is very sweet and dry with very little bitterness present . it tastes very much like it smells and is much too sweet for my taste . when i think of beer , i think of something that at least has some bitterness and balance but this one is pure sweetness . it also leaves a fruity aftertaste which reminds me of applesauce . really not a typical beer taste and not in a good way . i was expecting something different and original and it sure was different but i will not be buying it again .

aroma was great . smelled of slightly tart granny smith apples , a little spice . the smell was strong and i could n't wait to down this brew . how it smells so good but tastes so bland .  a truly wonderful looking beer .  i thought this was a great beer . very malty . i agree with one of the other reviewers - i thought they were using centennials but none of the waitresses knew what i was talking about and the owner/brewer was n't around . drinkability was pretty good , as i downed about three during dinner itself .

not much in the way of a head , lace or fresh hop aroma but otherwise a nice classic ( british ) ipa .  pours a huge foamy whitish color head , rocky , lastingish .  a bit watery actually . overall a simple classic belgian dubbel . i could drink this stuff every day , it may not be the most in your face dubbel , but thats what makes it great . just a simple session dubbel .

very pleasing creamy amber beer . beautiful orange amber color with a slight cloudiness that gives the beer a frosty jewell-tone look in the glass . a bit woody or astringent on the tongue . malty flavors dominate with hops coming forward later . an interesting style that produces a lot of flavor for modest alcohol .  tumbling cumulus of pure white towers above brilliantly clear gold .  carbonation seems high for an ipa but head and lacing are a bit below average . at first sip it is a refreshing / light to medium pilsner body that encourages you to gulp a little more confidently untill a few mouthfuls later you are in a caught up in the aroma all the while never minding it . this is a classy beer and makes one feel classy .

honey , pear , and vinous aroma with a hint of cocoa .  standard pour yields a giant frothy , coarse , 4.5 finger white head that sticks around . outstanding looking beer .  this brew is a bit thin otherwise .

s - orange , vanilla , and chocolate is mostly what i get . smells alot like a chocolate orange .  it is a beautiful dark ( almost black ) beer . it has thick tan foam and a decent amount of lacing .  i thought that the dundee kolsch-style ale was pretty good overall . not the best , but a beer that should be tried . a yellow-to-faint-amber-in-the-middle . the beer left a good 1-1/2 inch head . i could defintely taste biscuit flavors and a hint of lemon zest . the beer did not catch well in my mouth as i kept thinking of the smell .

s : very subtle aroma with some greasy somewhat citrus like hops and some porter like malt , very faint this needs some work in the dry hopped department perhaps . t : the taste is great though .  a : nice golden color with a huge pure white head , which was quite surprising for a cask beer with full on lacing . super good looking .  mouthfeel is kind of bleh , not bubbly enough .

perhaps a bit cold , i ca n't catch alot of notes in the nose yet . i 've had this before but it really has been over a decade for sure .  nice foamy head sticks to the glass like a wonder . great looks .  it is a little too light for the style . o- very good impy stout .

immediately the resemblence to flemish sour beers is noted in the aroma . label states that this beer has saccharine - so is this the saccarin version even though i got it in the us ? the sour is so strong in the smell that the taste is actually underwhelming - there is a malt undertone that seems to reduce the sourness and it feels like you took a rodenbach and cut it 30 % with a non-descript brown malt ale . at 3.5 % abv this beer is very drinkable and still very tasty with nearly 3 years of age in the bottle .  intriguing looking and extremely inviting .  most pale ales leave me with a thin watery feel and this one 's no different . the carbonation is right and it 's good on a hot day .

aroma is predominantly of sweet , bready malts , some good toast , and a faint hoppiness . not bad .  the pour was beautiful . a medium to full dark color , less than any stout or porter , but bold .  body is slightly thin on the overall taste .

12oz can poured into a pint glass a : very dark brown , with a lingering 1/2 finger head s : lots of cooking ingredients , especially ginger , brown sugar , and cloves .  poured from a 750ml bottle into a tulip . pours a reddish orange with a thick white frothy head . head has shades of orange as well . great lacing .  consumed on 11/8/2009 at breakwater brewing with largadeer . i saw that this was a gabf gold winner and so i immediately ordered it . at this point i looked back up at the board and noticed that it simply read `` gold medal winner , '' rather than the `` gabf gold medal winner '' that i had imagined . the nose is medicinal berries and cherries with a mild tartness and a strong sweetness . the flavor tastes like cherry cough syrup . there 's a touch of tartness but it 's subjugated by the artificial cloying sweet flavor . when a gold medal is given to a beer like this , i ca n't help but suspect one of two things : 1 . it was entered into the beer special olympics . i consumed 2oz of this and could stomach no more .

the smell of this brew is quite muted at first until it gets a chance to warm up . the taste of this brew is a nice turn-around from the aroma . the roasted grain quality is right upfront with a mild bitterness accented by citris-like coffee and light hoppiness .  this is quite an exceptional warm flat beer .  m - medium with light carbonation , seems a little flat .

smell - urine smell . animal urine .  good 1 inch of clingy foam . looking delectable .  these guys are cranking out the brews , here 's another nice offering i had the chance to sample . very malty aroma of caramel , which slides over into the quaff . a very sweet dopple , i 'd think it could use a bit more hop balance - but some really like the sweeter beers . still a tasty treat , served in a 10oz pilsner type glass , since it weighs in at 7 % .

smell - strong corn and grains . sweet and pretty one dimensional . slightly boozy .  it was a super dark color , so dark , you could see nothing through it , which was totally awesome .  '' fits this perfectly . lingers in the mouth perhaps a bit too long , but otherwise a great and easy to drink beer .

pours an effervescent apricot with 3+ fingers of sand colored head.good head retention & lacing s : slight breadyness t : slight breadyness & peppery hops up front , along with a bit of piney hops .  jet black pour with a delicate tan head that floats around up top for most of the session .  mouthfell was light and effervescent .

aroma is acetone .  the head is off white and tops 2.5 '' with lots of great retention . tons and tons of coating , spongy lace cling to the glass . a real beauty of an ipa .  because the hops and the malt do n't overwhelm you the mouthfeel is light to medium while drinkability is exceptional .

picked up a bomber to try ... - really dark viscous stout ... rich solid black/brown , mild finger of head , rich mocha colored ... down to some minor spotting ... looks delicious . - nice sweet chocolate ... slight bitterness ... and a touch of rubbing alcohol booziness.. some grains , oatmeal.. etc , . thank god the taste does n't mimic the scent too much . - overall this is a fantastic stout , and and quite pleased with it.. one i would certainly purchase again .  i 'll start with this next time because it was just beautiful beer . darkest i 've ever seen with a head that filled a hefe glass with just a 12 oz bottle .  the first swallow is sharply bitter , much starker than an american ipa . this is woody and tangy more than the citric fruitiness we yanks have come to expect from a beer labeled ipa , unfairly . with a solid malt undertow and a nicely balanced bitterness , i feel this is a very under-rated offering . ( # 2688 , 2/6/2007 )

( s ) - a very light roasted component with a nice rustic dry nuttiness behind it .  this beer has a very nice color : sunburst ruby . and the head is great for a beer of this strength .  feels a bit coarse and chewy on the tongue .

it retains the phenomenal , meaty , charred scent characteristic of aecht 's brews , but with a slightly richer flavor that 's more in line with what one would expect of such a well-presented beverage .  new holland dragon 's milk pours a beautiful black with just a bit of garnet showing when held to the light . a fluffy ivory head sits on top .  m- quite smooth but somewhat thin . decent carbonation .

s - smells bland , nothing special . no `` nose '' at all , really . smells like any old lawnmower ipa .  appears a clouded honey golden with a huge billowing creamy chunky white head leaves fine lacing all throughout the glass .  mouthfeel was a bit thin , considering the flavour .

i am only getting faint burnt and caramel type of smells . t : a pretty good taste , but overall light and not overpowering . this tastes like a great beer for people who are only used to huge american macro lagers . o : a great session beer . i do n't think it is anything spectacular , but it is good .  it does n't get very big , but it is that sort of short seductive creamy head i enjoy . perfect never ending retention .  m : aftertaste is short , but lovely bitter . body si medium as well as carbonation , but it lacks some smoothness .

smell : light malt sweetness , grass , and a hint of lemon rise from the glass .  a hard pour of a couple ounces produced a huge beige/white head that went up about three inches and took forever to settle down . when i finished pouring there was a very rocky head that hung around for quite a while longer . beautiful beer .  i had tried this with the sample pack and was n't too impress with it or any of the schell beers for that matter . i went to new ulm for the oktoberfest they have and while i was there took the tour of the brewery . while most of the samples were bottles still , they just had a better feel to them . i agree with other posters that the hops hide a bit of the other toasty , bready flavors associated with this style . i really enjoyed this brew and would recommend it if you can find it on tap , skip the bottles unless they are really fresh .

the aroma was malty and sweet ; there was a definite sugary-honey smell with only a hint of hops bitterness .  appearance : golden hazed beauty in a robust 20oz tulip shaped glass with a magnificant foaming white head leaves great batches of belgian style lacing , wow .  the smooth , medium body ends with a very dry , astringent finish . it 's a little soapy and there 's a hint of orange peel . this is an aggressively hopped american ipa . only drink it when you 're sure you do n't need to taste anything else that day .

it smells good for sure , just not very pungent .  really nice ! very nice overall with an amazing appearance , unreal head retention , great flavor and very pleasant mouthfeel .  medium-full bodied , creamy , but somewhat chalky . well carbonated .

very nice , though . o- enjoyable , would prob .  upon pouring this beer , a beautiful cascade of carbination formed a substantial head on this beer .  m : a little thinner than i expected from the look of the pour and for the style .

s - smoky bacon with maple on the side . t - sweet maple with a little grapefruit sourness to it .  large , creamy , light lavender head leaves great lacing down the glass .  mouthfeel was ok ( i think ) .

s-light to moderate aroma of caramel malt and slight citrus t-big inital hit of bitterness , gree and grapefruit hops . i might categorize this as an american ipa but what the hell it is good and i could have many .  this is a positively gorgeous looking beer .  m : medium body , lots of prickly carbonation . a little too prickly .

i am not a huge lager fan , wheat beers are not my thing ... . and red beer ... i think red dog ... well i was very let down by the taste of their ipa , the beer was a total let down on taste , it tasted like a watered down ipa , and again the ingredients did not mesh well . i see some people like some of their beers , maybe i was there on a bad day , maybe ... something but i would advise all to avoid this brewery  pours a deep hell-fire red with an awesome off white head that would not go away . this beer looks and tastes like the definition of `` strong '' .  the bourbon is faint . watery . taste does not stay with you as long as i would desire , which is a shame , because it tastes good o- this is an excellent beer , and one that i would drink again . it goes down very smooth , and it would be pretty easy to knock back several .

s- very funky smell . metallic and spicy tuna . not the best i 've ever smelled . t- tons of clove , banana , yeast , a little sweet , dark fruit , spice , chocolate .  thick white , fluffy head holds together for a really long time . a very good looker .  mouthfeel seemed a bit thinner than most quads , almost more like an old ale , very little carbonation .

s : bouquet is a bit more quiet than i had expected . t : semi-sweet , with dark chocolate , molasses , and vanilla on the front , and semi-sweet chocolate continuing on the finish .  poured a black color with a super-thick light-brown head .  this attractively-packaged ( black panther on the bottle , tying into an indiana legend ) pours ( or is it purrs ? hahah ) a deep black with lots of tan bubbles . some minor lacing . aroma is chocolate malts , with a little roastiness . the taste follows closely , with a pleasing burnt cocoa finish . quite tasty and highly drinkable !

there is a nutty and a malty smell to it .  pours a deep brown that lets no light through . the best part is the head on this . tan , chunky , and thick , this 2 inch creamy show-stopper stays all the way down the pint , leaving gobs - literally the size of marbles - stuck to the sides with every sip . absolutely fabulous .  medium bodied , with an evident hoppy prickly texture .

s : nutty , hazelnut and/or almond here . earthy dirt aroma comes off the glass here . t : wonderful taste here on this brown .  a hard pour created a very delayed but huge head which was dark tan and dense and creamy . i 've never seen a beer head develop so slowly .  m : no carbonations to speak of .

funny thing , after about a minute or two i can hardly smell this beer at all .  deep amber with a cream colored rocky head that retains well . i think this beer would be better classified as a barleywine considering its lack in forward hop flavor .  the brew was medium in body with a gusher load of carbonation which had a sweet , fruity , lacto , sugary , and out of place tart finish . drank decent but once again i 'm dissapointed at the fact how lots of shorts beers i 've had have been infected .

a thick creme head sat on this puppy the entire session s- light roasted malt with a touch of sweetness . somewhat subdued but still intriguing . t- the nitro changes this beer to another beast . almost ordered a bottle of a milk stout but enjoyed this a ton . sooo delicious on nitro .  beamish pours in a way that i 've only seen it and guinness do , with a cascade of bubbles that start at the bottom of the glass and slowly float their way up to the top to form a silky , cream-colored head . the beer itself is just plain black . as far as i 'm concerned beamish is just what a dark beer is supposed to look like . it does n't reach the level of complexity of some of the best dark belgian beers , but i do n't think it 's supposed to .  mouthfeel is on the low to medium level with a higher carbonation . i would prefer a fuller mouthfeel with less carbonation .

it smells slightly spicy . it also smells slightly honey like . i hate to say it since i like most alesmith beers , but i am not too fond of the aroma of this beer . this beer tastes quite syrupy .  pours an opaque with a large brown-chocolate mousse looking head that disapates slowing and never really goes away , very good lacing .  carbonation is average .

great cling along the glass as you go , the beer has toasted oats and honey sweet aromas . some light spicing on the nose , too .  beautiful hazy amber color , with a white semi-dense head that dissipates quickly .  a light bodied feel at the front , it then gradually gains weight .

this beer has a wonderful hoppy aroma that was very welcome here in europe where the ipa breed is thin .  pours out to a hazy burnt orange , forming a tall off-white head with superior retention and nice thick sheets of lace .  medium bodied , carbonation is very noticeable , very tame malty sweetness that leads into a somewhat `` thin '' finish .

huge bops on the nose piney and resiny as can be and then a burst of citrus at the end , some light cereal grain and coffee eaters as well . toffee is there as well a bit of sweetness with a forever finish . great ipa and not one that falls into the everyday category  pours a crystal clear shade of straw with a massive four finger head of snowy white froth . great retention with a spectacular coat of lacing .  quite pleasantly medium and very appropriate for a regular ipa , the mouthfeel felt short of expectations for a dipa .

it pours darker like a stout but has a cream colored head which stays thin on top until the last drop . s. smells very malty . does n't have the same smell as most traditional ipas .  the thick , creamy , well retained porcelain white head sits atop a brilliant , crystal clear perfectly golden hued brew .  this is the first yorkshire ale i have ever drank , so take my review with a grain of salt . the smell was good , but it almost smelled like a porter , which from the reviews i have read thats about what to expect . the taste was a strong but not overpowering of mault . overall a very drinkable ale , just not quite as strong or think as a porter , but i think i would have been confused if not for knowing what it was when i bought it . i 'll have to drink more to get a better idea of what it should be . nice drinkability though .

pours a hazy orange tan ( looks like 1/2 lemonade 1/2 tea ) with some thin bone-white head that leaves a little spotting . somewhat muted , but definitely east coast style with lots of caramel malt sticking out through the leafy dry hops . nice clean , somewhat sweet finish . notes : this beer is rather interesting because it seems to be backwards in mouthfeel for an ipa : it 's really bitter right up front but finishes sweeter .  2011 vintage - fresh this beer was purchased fresh as a single from total wine in richmond , va - poured into a dfh snifter pours fantastic , gargantuan head.. like.. huge head.. i was n't expecting that at all . beautiful ruby color with a blonde leather looking head . looks like the head on a root beer float , lots of protein in there and the foam is smooth and palatable almost like whipped topping .  m : dry , medium-bodied , overcarbonated initially though .
s - light malty smell . t - smooth yet a lot of bite .  it was a beautiful looking pour but it took me a while to finish this one .  m : neutral .

it 's like a cinnamon espresso mousse cake in the nose , seriously interesting smell i 've never had in a beer before . nutmeg , maybe a little malt , no hops at all , brown sugar , and overall a 'vanilla frosting ' smell . very alluring if you like confectionary desserts especially .  reviewed 10/26/2009 ( tap @ flying saucer , houston , tx ) : pours a strong golden red color semi-cloudy body , big foamy head , off-white , very lasting .  mouthfeel was too light in my opinion nothing special , but nothing wrong . too thin for my liking .

sour fruits/spices crossed with light sweet malt scent . more sour bite with tart fruit undertones . i 'm just starting with the saisons , but i could definetly enjoy this as a summer long brew .  drank on-tap at staminee de garre , brugge , belgium served in a signature garre goblet the beer poured a crystal clear amber color with a near three-finger head of super creamy , off-white froth .  unfortunately , the mouthfeel is a bit thin ( again - it tastes more like soda than beer ) , though the beer is quite easy to drink .

amber highlights and a pretty amazing head . smells like european hops ... the goldings i 'm guessing . in general , the nose is a little muted .  a : beautiful dark amber color with an excellent bubbly head that lasted the entire beer . laced in feathery clumps that only attended to the wonderful appearance .  m : light to medium body . medium level of carbonation .

smells of light roasted/burnt malt with surprisingly no hops .  a - copper color with exceptional clarity . nice head that is perfect to drink through .  pours a opaque black colour with a medium frothy tan head . aroma is creamy with some hints of coffee and chocolate . initial taste is very creamy ( milk shake ) , coffee and some cocoa . minor bitter hops in the finish . great head retention and lacing was slapped around the sides of the glass nicely .

the smell is another story . fantastic mix of malt/hops with fresh pumpkin , allspice , cloves , nutmeg , cinnamon , coriander , orange peel etc.and still not too overpowering .  stone arrogant bastard pours a very clear dark amber color . the head is light tan and has great retention .  the mouthfeel is light for a stout , but this is a minor point .

bomber into tulip glass , 2005 edition consumed from cellar temp . caramel malty sweetness in the nose balanced well with a touch of hops , tho it is a bit too faint - maybe a bit herbal ? smuttynose nails the mouthfeel - excellent carbonation tickles the tongue intensely and then settles into an impressively full and malty body , actually seeming fuller than it is ( a neat trick , really ) , some alchohol-type warmth and a nice soft malty remainder bringing up the tail . a brew that 's not hard to quaff , and important to savor .  pours a beautiful translucent , dark golden honey-brown .  heavy alcohol , extreme spice , honey , grapes and pepper . oof - this is where my `` inexperiance '' as an advocate comes in . an immediate peppery sting inflames the mouth and the grapes , saffron and alcohol kill them off . wtf is saffron ? sorry dfh .
s : subtle . hoppy up front with a nice caramel malt backbone .  big vanilla head . larger bubbles provide decent lacing .  m : good , not great . i drank one and thought it was on the thinner side .

pale yellow at first with a big head , cloudy after the bottle was fully emptied thanks to yeast . looks neat as the sediment is still floating around in the beer ... turns pretty opaque once the yeast disperses in the glass dry wheat nose to it ... sort of buttery characteristic to it as well . doesnt just try to be a hoegaarden clone like blue moon , and doesnt go goofy on the tea flavored spices like sam white or great lakes holy moses .  huge and lofty , puffy , creamy laden capping tops it off that hardly ever moves from its position . one impressive cap on this sucker , it lasted til the very last sip .  unfortunately the beers characteristics disappears quickly . not that it should be the goal of a beer drinker or a characteristic of a good beer , but one could probably get really drunk off of this tilburg offering . it 's maybe a little too sweet for it 's own good -- and definetly more sweet than most brown ales .

s - chocolate , chiles , and some coffee .  steady stream of carbonation rising from the bottom of the glass . three fingers of creamy frothy head clumps together as it falls and leaves tons of irregular lacing . great retention .  slightly thin body for the style and the abv , just a light alcohol presence in the finish , well hidden .

smell - sweet caramel malt . not catching much in the way of hops .  this beer looks incredible with a deep copper-red body .  mouthfeel/drinkability- light body and decent carbonation however the aftertaste and taste in general make this beer nearly undrinkable .

the aroma is on the mild side , nothing really jumps out at me .  neutral amber color with the slightest chill haze . an absolutely beautiful looking beer .  m : thick body that is slick on the tongue . lower then average carbonation .

smell was average with a good taste .  appearance - pours a big loose three finger pancake batter/seafoam head with great stick and good retention .  m : i am not a fan of the mouthfeel . instead i got a thicker mouthfeel that coated my tongue just a little too much which is what i think gave it the not so great finish .

s - the amount of mead qualities i 'm picking up are impressive : floral , spice , dry and sweet base . d - i really liked the nose on this brew , but in the mouth i was not quite so impressed ... seemed underwhelming , but for a style so rarely done , i love to see it .  limfjords porter ( double brown stout ) is a pitch black liquid with a huge , soft , bistre colored head that has outstanding retention and lacing . it 's a unique look .  m : average feel , clean , and dry , d : enjoyable would love to have this mid summer .

smell : a little sour like it may have gone bad . not a pleasant smell . taste : big roasted , chocolate , creamy taste .  gorgeous pour - cloudy copper under a two finger tan head that manages a lovely crown above the glass then settles ever so slowly , leaving magnificent lace .  the beer seemed highly carbonated .

the aroma was weak , as some floral hops and caramel were mildly detectable .  bottle : poured a burgundy lightly hazy color ale with a huge light brown head with perfect retention .  a very good and heavy beer . must be sipped an not chugged , though no good beer drinker would do such a thing . highly recommended .

the nose is rich and malty and smells like fresh brewed coffee grinds .  a-is this a brown ale or a stout ? a black color , with a two finger dark head that leaves behind a perfect lacing .  first off , i went in expecting leinie 's berryweiss , and was pleasantly suprised that it was not that type of drink . a nice crisp berry scent , which is balanced in flavor by the malt . is it a `` chick beer '' ? maybe . yep . it 's not zima , it 's not boone 's farm , it 's just kinda ... .good .

clove , bubble gum , allspice , and other smells all mixed otgether . a very unique aroma . t - spicy malt dominates up front .  pours a deep , deep mahogany with a two-finger , coffee brown head with a bit of reddish hue . great head retention and lacing throughout .  mouthfeel is crisp with a light to medium body . however , it is over carbonated so it feels you up rather quickly and then you are constantly burbing to make room . as is , the over carbonation is very distracting .

have to wait for the foam to subside before noting anything on aroma . aroma 3/5 nice malt aroma to it , slightly toasty and sweet perhaps .  a - massive , thick head of light-beige foam . hazy brew of golden-amber ale looks great . the head settles to a finger of thick , unrelenting foam .  m : i did think this beer was a bit thin and could have benefited from a little more texture as a result carbonation was a bit high .

a little too boozy i thought . the abv was well hidden , except for the smell , and its best enjoyed warmer .  a - pours a dark black with a thick and luscious head of mocha-colored foam that never fully dissipates , leaving behind sticky lacing as it recedes . beautiful !  the palate is typical .
