s : rotten cranberries and nothing much else .  bottle : poured a deep hazy amber color ale with a very large foamy head with nice off-white foamy head with good retention and some very good lacing .  mouth feel is a bit carbonated for my likings ( macro'ish ) .

s : hints of citrus and banana . the appearance and smell , while average , are less important than mouthfeel and drinkability , both of which were excellent .  poured a murky dark copper hue with a two and a half finger pillowy white head . there was excellent retention and sticky lacing .  lightly oily and thick on the palate , but undercarbonated , unfortunately , even for a low carbonation lover like me .

the aroma was very mild of a hay like malt , citrus hops and a moldy yeast with hints of fruit ( peaches i think ) and honey .  pure black and pours an inch thick espresso-colored head which laces nicely as it recedes .  finishes crisp with a sort of biting feeling in the back of the throat .

central waters perhaps ? it smells of sweet bourbon , warm alcohol , and dark fruity malts . this is going to be a nice afternoon ... t & m - tons of alcohol here . maybe it is just because it is the first beer of the day , but this hits hard . i feel it in my nose . the carbonation is low and body is a bit weak , so not much of the complexity i thought i could smell really comes out in the flavor .  poured an inky black with a big billowing creamy tan head that left lacing all the way down my glass . this is one good looking beer .  the fizzy yellow stuff of the great white north , as far as i 'm concerned . that 's right , corn . prominent in the aroma and taste , along with some traces of malt and hops . i was quite thirsty after a bout with us customs , and this failed to satisfy . difficult to finish .

s - smelled like a lager sort of to me . i didnt like the smell that much but smells are decieving .  pours with a large amount of foam , rose up very high above the glass , pretty amazing to me , takes the cake for the best pour i 've seen , but i have n't tried that many belgian beers yet .  great brew to enjoy on warm or hot days . apricot aroma eclipses any malt or hops on the nose . taste is predomanantly apricot/peach , with just a slight bite of hops in the finish . the clean malt helps to balance out the apricot . a great , simple , summer session beer for hot days .

a - a smooth thick head sits atop a topaz body s - pretty lacking here , slightly floral t - again , a bit light on here .  a very promising looking ipa .  mouthfeel is on the light side , with a little more acidic carbonation than i 'd like in this sort of beer .

smells mildly of malt .  this ipa is much better than the rolliing blackout that they seem to have discontinued . a medium amber color topped by a foamy off white head that settles in and leaves grade a lacing so thick and beautiful , that i swore i could have been in england drinking ultra fresh cask ale .  a little bit thin in the mouth , feels almost like water .

the smell is a little grainy with hop oil but is quite unrefined for my nostils . i can dig the wheat-like aroma ( not used to that in an ipa but it 's cool ) . the hops are resiny and full of kick ! i like the viscous hop oil resins . i love the pefect carbonation and the alcohol roundness is right in line . suddenly i loved everything around me and could n't figure out why - then i realized i had 9 % of goodness going down the gullet !  a - this looks as all stouts should look .  mouthfeel ... light , a bit watery .

aroma of lemon and some spices . overall , very smooth and extremely drinkable . mouthfeel was light , fluffy and smooth . extremely drinkable .  looks like a dream . a deep ruby red with very little head .  a little rough going down , but over all very nice .

smells of milk , light roast and smoke , and creamy oats .  pours an orangish brown with a creamy white head . excellent lacing and retention .  smell - cereal , caramel , floral notes , pine , grapefruit taste & mouth - there is an average amount of carbonation on the tongue and the beer comes across as slightly watery .

nose is roasted malt , cocoa , coffee and a lingering sour funk ... uh oh .  pours with vast amounts of head to peak out at about two fingers thick , from my 8oz bottle . the body is nice gold , and quite clear .  loaded with fresh hops flavor , spicey , that good bitter smack finish . i used to prefer darker beers to american pale ales , but this beer is the one that changed my mind . this beer goes great with crawfish and pizza .

i did n't pick up a whole lot of aroma from it , so when i took my first sip i was a lil ' shocked at its flavor .  out of the bottle this brew was a light copper color with a huge , foamy , tan head . great retention and it left sticky ribbons of lacing all down the glass .  mouthfeel was disappointingly a bit too thin and watery in the finish for such a big beer .

the nose is n't anything special , since it is too mild and nondistintive for my liking . with that said , i do detect the presence of mineral qualities along side lightly roasted and sweet caramel malt aromas .  a : beautiful - pours perfectly in the glass - head lasts longer than i ever could imagine from this brewer and the lacing is amazing - perfect .  i can only describe this as a gimmick beer , because the bottle was interesting , and the beer awful . funky metallic/brown sugar nose . malt had an odd dimension , which , coupled with the alcohol in the beer , hinted at cheap sour mash whiskey . one of the few beers i have poured out half-way through and gotten something ( anything ) better from the fridge .

a nice strong whiff of red ripe grapes .  the pour was a light golden yellow with a whole hand of head that very slowly dissapated and left a thick white foam on top of the beer , this held on throughout the drink .  drinkability : body is a little undercarbonated .

a very underrated style and one of my favorite styles of beer . pours a beautiful dark red color , huge off white foamy head to it . get a bit of caramel in the nose and a hint of booziness .  a : tiny crack of a noise upon opening - however , 1 finger of head upon an aggressive pour . head retention is beautiful - a pillowy , rocky , tan-colored head . gorgeous .  mouth is lacking in carbination expected . also a little thinner in the mouth than expected .

nice scent , very sweet and malty , though , not as deep as i like in my browns .  pours an inkly black , with just a bit of brown visible around the edges . thick mocha head that fades quickly , but leaves plenty of lacing .  mouthfeel : i 'm used to stouts , so this seemed thin , and therefore a double-edged sword . drinkability : the thinness of this beer makes it so easy going down , you 'll want to have another .

poured a clear orange-gold into a tulip with a finger of quick-receding soapy white head . very mild , slightly grainy aroma . moderate carbonation and a light mouthfeel without feeling thin . wheat and sweet caramel up front with a little grassy bitterness on the finish . mild , drinkable , and pleasant enough with a little extra malty sweetness to keep things somewhat interesting .  pours with a nice inch of foam , which leaves rings of lace all around the glass .  sampled this at the brewery ( portsmouth ) at the end of the tour which is short but wonderfully informative ( thanks byron ) . it didnt hurt that i was a few pints deep from the restaurant already . its been 2 weeks and its almost gone and i have to say its great for a stout . it pours thick and has little head retention so presentation isnt off the charts but taste makes up for it .

smell : toasted malt and ... [ crickets ] . not much in the nose at all . taste : toasted grains , sweet moist pine , wood , somewhat spicy hops , and caramel ?  pours a very nice pink with some white bubbling . actually , quite a gorgeous beer .  m - slightly thin mouthfeel , not very viscous . fairly bitter , but very filling .

the smell was nothing memorable for this style .  this beer poured a dark copper color with a two finger high off-white head . everything about it was enjoyable , including the color and head on this beer , which was superb and perfect .  the mouthfeel is on the thin side , very drinkable , & coats the mouth & throat . funny that the irish dry stout is distinct from milk stouts , because i feel the style is very lactic feeling .

smell- a little sweaty but eventually shows the a decent roasted and lightly smoked malt aroma .  one half of the black and tan and the yin-yang . a : pours pitch black with medium tan head .  mouthfeel - the feel is affected by the flavor .

wonderful aroma , ultra funky like reinaert flemish wild . i do n't care , it smells awesome , if a little weak . i ca n't believe something that smells this good could be so bland .  i had it brought to the table and did n't know to ask at the time , but given the incredible head retention and relatively flat body i would bet it was . thick creamy head with ridiculous retention s - mellow , soft .  mouthfeel : medium body with smooth carbonation and a finish that is a bit gritty .

smell : i do n't get a very potent smell off of this brew , there is some darker grains detectable , but not much of an aroma . drinkability : its drinkable .  a pitch black stout with a wonderful coffee colour head .  mouthfeel is alright for the type .

i only detect some light citrus hops while taking a great deep sniff . taste is a nice hops snap with a substantial malt backbone .  pours an opaque chocolaty sable with a thick tan head that persists and leaves some thick lacing .  mouthfeel was average .

nice look . s - a bit of caramel malt and crisp pine hops . a fairly mild aroma . it is nothing to fuss over , but it is easily sessionable and has a great flavor for barbecues .  guinness 250 anniversary stout is a brownish black beer with a thick , foamy , dimpled beige head that has great retention and leaves nice lacing on the glass .  this is a decent beer . more of a i crave a new style beer type . i tasted nothing oatmeal about this beer . mainly tasted of a dark coffee flavored beer . but it was a decent fun experience .

i was expecting the aroma to be pretty potent and i 'm a little let down . the taste is actually a big step up from the aroma . i get some sweet caramel malt and vanilla with some bitter grapefruit in there as well .  pours slightly hazy orange amber color with a nice 3 finger off white head with incredible retention that reduces to a thick cap that lasts .  m. mouthfeel slacks a little . maybe a little too much carbonation and a little too thin .

the head is incredible robust and leaves several rings of lacing.nearly perfect , however i like to see a tad more orange in the color of ipas s - could n't get much here . a little bit of malt and an ever so slight grapefruit smell . t - a bit of grapefruit flavors upfront . the body was very well balanced with biscuity malt flavors mingling well with the hoppy , fruity notes .  nice dark opaque color that appears black until you put it in front of a strong light , in which case piercing garnet hues emerge . exemplary 3 finger head of fluffy tan foam reaches up to the rim of the glass and as it recedes , leaves tons of intricate lacing .  as a wee heavy beer it does a great job , low bitterness w/ ample sweetness mouthfeel : hmmm ... .a little to watery and at times you can feel the sugary syrupness of this beer .

poured from a bomber into a pint glass , this beer pours with a smell like you are actually peeling a tangerine . i 'm impressed so far . picture perfect for a wheat . as i said before , it smells like an actual peeled tangerine . when you get your nose deep in there you get some effervescent versions of the citrus smells , and the constant flow of bubbles also shows a high level of carbonation . with the nose of this beer , i was almost expecting a mouthful of orange crush , but the citrus aspect was a nice balance rather than an overpowering ogre .  i never thought i would see a beer that deserves a `` 5 '' in appearance , but i always thought it would have to be a stout with perfectly milk-chocolate , marshmallow head . this one is orange , virtually the color of the can , hazy , with nice carbonation and a replenishing head . just gorgeous .  m : overly fizzy and carbonated , very spritzy .

650ml bomber poured into tulip april,15 2011 a clear copper with not much for visible carbonation but somehow produces a thumbs width of cream colored foam the has a short life but leaves a fair bit of lace s nice nose with tangerine , grapefruit , guava , pine and toffee , pretty strong tropical fruits going on here and i like it a fair bit , this is what i think of when a big west coast dipa is what i 'm thinking about . i could smell this all day t now its all about the rind of the big citrus fruits i could smell and there 's a little more pine , something should be said for how well concealed the booze is and it has some earthy tones but compared to the smell it 's lacking ( still good though ) m fairly bitter but i would n't guess 100+ ibu 's but i 'm not that surprised i suppose , leaves some grit on the gums and i 'd be tasting this even after a few lagers o a solid dipa and if .25 increments were an option here they would have been dropped a couple times so i 'll make up for it in the overall i 'm a little surprised how fast this bomber hit my gut ( and my head for that matter ) but what can you do ? world class smell going on here and its very drinkable for a big hop bomb that should make this one worth seeking out if your a hop head  a- pours a pitch-black hue with brown highlights , head is brown , foamy and pillowy monster that is reminiscent of a wendy 's frostie , good retention , moderate lacing on the glass s- nose is big time malts- cocoa , coffee , molasses , brown sugar , some dark chocolate bitterness and a touch of citrus in the background ( reminds slightly of a karl straus chocolate-orange porter firkin ) t- initial taste is bitter dark chocolate and espresso , followed up by some tart and dark fruit flavors ( fig/plum/cherry ) that are a bit of a surprise , and finishes with slight hop dryness m- surprisingly light-to-medium bodied , texture is watery-to-creamy , and carbonation is subtle d- solid and tasty porter that is easy to drink , i think it captures the style well but is not ground-breaking on any front , a touch too bitter for my taste , but a good overall performer buy again ?  a lot thinner in the mouth then i imagined it to be .

i dident except much from this one when i poured it in to my glass , i wasent impresed with the color , or the faint sent it pordused but that all was quickley washed away when the first sip hit my lips . this has a hopy bite to it , way more than i thought would come from a 5 % abv beer . all and all i would recomend this beer and will dirnk it agan if it ever crosses my path agan  this is a great looking brew . pours pitch black with a huge thick + sticky chocolate milk colored head . great retention . as you pour the beer you can see how thick and heavy it is . awesome to look at .  my first thought when i had this beer was yum . that 's a nice smooth sweet beer . when i smelled the beer i thought it smelled like lemons or fresh oranges . it has nice golden color , the beer had about a 1/4 inch head when i poured it into a tumbler . apparently it 's hops are nobel so if i drink enough will i become a duke .

smell : surprisingly dull caramel and malts . simple but incredibly delicious . drinkabililty : this is a very drinkable brew , and worth seeking out as much as the 8 and 10 from this brewery .  eliot ness pours with a beautiful two finger thick head that dissipates quickly , but has delicate lacing that sticks to the glass all the way through . the body is dark golden amber and is cleanly filtered for a truly clear presentation .  yielded a monstrous thick white head.a very cloudy yellowish-orange.very inviting aroma with hints of spiceskind of smells like unibroue 's la fin du monde.a very crisp mouthfeel almost harsh like seltzer.very citrus flavor with a slight bitter finish that lingers in the back of the throat.a bit but not much lace.high drinkability with this one.very crisp , clean , and refreshing .

very faithful interpretation , particularly in terms of appearance and aroma . beautiful toffee brown hues match well with toffee caramel malts and fresh passionfruit .  a : it poured a massive three finger slightly off white head with a blend of giant and dense small sickly bubbles that slowly receded to a full thick cover over the liquid and left a dense thick curtain.the body was a dense and cloudy golden-orange .  nice and crisp . not too much effervescence in the feel . light on the tongue .

smells of pale malt , grain , slight hops , hint of sweet malt , and a sulfur aroma .  this beer pours a dark cloudy auburn with an impressive head despite not being as tall as some of unibroue 's others . gave it a `` 5 '' for the appearance in part because of the great artwork on the bottle that lured me in .  body is a little thin for an imperial stout , although this beer is on the lighter end of the spectrum for the style .

smell of molasses and sweet dark malt .  especially nitro stouts , with their cascading after the pour and thick , creamy meringue like heads . in a pint glass or snifter these brews have an uncanny ability to look amazingly inviting .  the body feels a tiny bit watery . the oatmeal smoothness is nice but the watery body needs to be thickened .

smell : caramel sweetness , butterscotch and old oxidized booziness .  retention is sick and lacing is great as well . awesome looking beer .  m : light to medium bodied , with low carbonation . i can only suggest more on the mouthfeel and carbonation .

big horsey smell when i finally got the slightly moldy cork out of the bottle . that original smell went away , too .  the carbonation is fantastic -- tons of bubbles like schools of fish . what a great looking beer !  the mouth feel was very heavy , but not very viscous with only a slight carbonation . kind of felt watery . this is a very nice beer , but the mouth feel is a big turn off .

s- has a serious cleaning product smell .  what a beautiful beer ! this imperial stout pours a beautiful black with a thin caramel head .  m - the feel is a bit coarse but the texture helps to bring out the nice flavor . ~ i will suggest to mt ba buds that they partake in this foreigner .

has notes of citrus and pine hops plus some apricot hints in there too . this beer is a very refreshing ipa with a not to much fruit back but just enough to make it refreshing .  the beer appeared dark clear mahogany with 2 fingers of nice fluffy foam on top .  bottom line : great introduction to sour beers . very mild and subtle sour/brett flavors . extremely approachable by even the mildest craft beer fan . nice brown color hints of dark fruits . sourness is extremely mild yet compliments the malts . very little if any hop flavor . exceptionally drinkable . bottle and draft nearly identical . great go-to flanders red but seems more like a sour brown . availability makes this a great 'trainer ' . a-

the appearance is very average for a lager , and it has virtually no smell . it 's like drinking a soft drink ... very fizzy , and it does n't have a wattery aftertaste .  super interesting . dark black with a huge thick , creamy head that last forever bevore fading to a creamy floating film . awesome foam walls of lace the aroma contains faint dark raisins and prunes with hints of vanilla .  s - overwhelming peach . that is all this beer has , and i found it to be utterly unbalanced . d - my partner and i drank many different beers over two weeks in belgium . also , i do n't think this has any lambic as in it , as that it not claimed by dubuisson on their website .

smell is hard to detect . it does have a grassy , citrus hint to it though . nothing extraordinary , but refreshing .  pours out to a sparkingly clear rich amber , forming a voluminous creamy head with superior retention and very nice lacing . great looking beer .  mouthfeel is firm and a bit spicy with the hops , but the drinkability is awful .

a nice light bodied lager , that is good from the tip of the tounge to the back of the throat . ( edit 5-25-06 ) now i had road dog and i ca n't pick a favorite flying dog anymore .  cloudy yellow-gold with an awesome initial head . huge and rocky with excellent retention and patchy lacing .  d- good for the style , especially with this abv , but still quite boozey considering how thin the mouthfeel is .

aroma - boozy and sweet . mediocre ; very abrasive . taste - strong toffee/caramel notes .  extremely foggy light copper . excellent head retention .  moderate body , with a little bit of a gassy , bubbly feel . ultimately , although i quite like this beer , i think it would really shine on cask ; the carbonation is a little too prickly and gives the beer too much of a mineral water feel .

sweet grain cereal , a touch and i mean a touch of perhaps bananas and cloves ? this has the subtle aromas of a hef but extremely subtle . im actually rather ok with this aroma .  clear ( semi-clear in later pours ) , vibrant amber straw color . lots of fluffy head that barely fades . lots of thick , pillowy lace all the way down the glass .  the feel was a bit oily and slightly metallic . this was easy to drink , but lacked the super fresh feel i expect from a harvest ale .

straw like color . grassy nose with a weak citrus scent .  wonderfully frothy retention and good puffs of lace .  mouthfeel- a little syrupy , with some sand.. drinkability- not coors light . gulp gulp , ph

i enjoyed the fruitiness of this beer . the malt was in the background but stood up to the apricots to balance the flavors .  pours onyx black with a dense medium brown head .  m : this is , by far , the weakest aspect of this beer . it 's just too thin and watery for the style . good carbonation helps save this from being a below average score .

there was almost no nose to the beverage , but what was there was citrusy and a tinge of hops , maybe a little yeast .  pours a one finger off-white head that fades very slowly , leaving a good lace . nice crystal clear amber color .  m - medium mouthfeel , a little lighter than i prefer my imperial stouts to be .

the aroma is chocolaty with a bit of a vinous character to it . some coffee in there as well .  lightly hazed golden orange , topped with a craggy ivory head . clotted lace clings all over the glass , really great .  t-this does n't taste like a double ipa to me , but it does taste like a very good east coast ipa , heavy on the citrus , heavy on the hops , no alcohol to be found anywhere . m-a bit oily , which is o.k . ) by me , carbonation is a little lacking for my taste ... still , this is a good beer if you like hops ... d- ... .wicked drinkable .

s - very light nose . a hair of roasted barley and some bittersweet chocolate . surprisingly low on chocolate for how the beer was described .  served in a saison dupont becker a-beer has big white fluffy head that leaves thick amounts of lacing . color is a pale gold with very active carbonation .  my main complaint is the mouthfeel , which is a little lacking given the style . a porter should be a little bit thicker , with more substantial body .

s : floral hops ; lemon peel , citrus and grapefruit . not a lot here . t : floral hops ; lemon zest , grapefruit and orange rind .  a - brilliantly clear straw color with a thick white head that settles into a thick collar ; very pretty s - grainy malt with a noble hop aroma t - strong grainy malt flavor up front and through the finish which has an abrupt , crisp hop bitterness ; hops add a lemon-like dimension to the flavor ; yeast esters are present but restrained m - medium-light body , moderately high carbonation d - this is a decent american blonde that is nicely balanced between the malt and hop .  mouthfeel is watery with a crisp finish .

s : a little funky , almost a put-off . once familiar with the taste , not noticeable . it could really stand for a bit more alcohol and spice , but still very flavorful .  golden yellow color with a perfect small bubble head . lots of lacing .  mouthfeel is medium bodied .

kona 's pipeline porter pours the perfect color for a porter- dark but not pitch black . the coffee flavor is done flawlessly with a perfect balance that lets you know it 's there , yet does not overpower the more subtle flavors of deeply roasted malt ( black patent ? the mouthfeel is perfect for a porter in my opinion . they 've done a great job of keeping this just the right fullness in body to keep it from falling into stout or brown ale territory . all in all , a great beer that proves to be compelling and highly drinkable .  just opaque black with a prodigious cinnamon-colored head that , instead of falling , forms swiss-cheese-like holes that undermine the head 's structural integrity until the whole thing slowly collapses like the ottoman empire . very nice lacing , too .  m-medium-high carbonation overpowers a medium but forgettable body .

s : very faint hints of some sweet malts , vanilla , and some burnt caramels in there . smokey even . t : slightly sweet malts are carried with some real nice bittering here .  a - wow . gorgeous and large pure white head . perfect .  mouthfeel is thin and carbonated with a little slickness .

on tap at player 's retreat , raleigh nc waitress served me a uber-golden , clear ale with a fair amount of carbonation . aroma was n't anything special : a bit of wheat and some yeasty fruit notes .  beautiful color and chrystal clear , no much head retention but i wasnt expecting any .  m : smooth and creamy but the carbonation is a bit too much .

s-light roasted notes with a bit of chocolate .  stunning visual pour with dark red-brown crystal clear body topped with big head that fell fast .  mouthfeel was medium with a slightly unpleasant astringency in the mouth .

not much in the aroma department , kind of bland .  a : it poured a thick , frothy milk chocolate head that slowly died to a thick lace . it 's jet black with a thin amber brown hue .  m : extremely oily .

a good aroma , slightly hoppy , although not very deep , with slight sweet tones to it .  into a tulip , pours a very large beige head atop a murky amber body .  feel is not as light as i would like but great and the carbonation is really good .

smell : sour coffee , in the main . i say `` irrational '' because i 've never actually tasted green , unroasted coffee . coffee is the strongest , and it 's nowhere near as sour as the smell implies . but there 's also a noticable caramel presence , some wood-y notes , and a vague fruityness .  bottle : poured a hazy dark yellow beer with a huge head with incredible retention ( i never though id mentioned that in a review , but the head was so persistent that it was still there 30 minutes after the beer was poured .  there is also almost no after taste to be found ( weird ) mouth-feel : extremely dry with a light bodied feel .

diacetyl and brown roasty malts are evident in the nose . diacetyl is just a little bit out of hand . diacetyl is evident , but not overpowering . the diacetyl is the only factor keeping this from being one of my favorite stouts .  thick , pitch black liquid ( if i can call it that ... ) with a mammoth crown of sticky , brown foam that takes a while to settle . head is the consistency of meringue .  this has got the same funky yeasty flavor of the balcones fault pale malt whithout any of the body to back it up . leaves a bad aftertaste . i can actually see the other guy saying it was watered down with pickle juice , but watered down with watered down pickle juice . it 's got a lot of flavor , but it 's a bad flavor .

an attractive beer . s- malt . touch of hops . t- taste better than smell .  ( from notes ) 12 oz bottle poured into a .5 l paulaner mug a - beautiful copper color . pours a nice creamy white head the quickly recedes . awesome fall colors .  mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side , which is my only real complaint about this beer , and there 's a bit of warming in the back of the throat .

s-sweet caramel and sugar . roasty cinnamon and cream . t-starts with a bit of a bite on the front end that is very unique and reminds me of burnt espresso/cappucino beans .  abt 12 pours to produce a beautiful thick khaki colored head , which sticks around for a while , and eventually forms into clumps the rest of the way through . the body of this brew is a dark caramel color with slight reddish hues .  this brew poured a medium head of small to large sized white bubbles that left very little lacing . it has a wheat yellow body with a mild if any aroma . it has an initial bite that lingers slightly into the aftertaste . it has a mild hoppy malt flavor .

( some lacing ) the aroma is of spice and yeast . the flavor matches the aroma nicely .  deep orange color with a thick foamy head with tons of lacing . the brew is more opaque than clear . the highlights are its fantastic looks and excellent mouth feel .  mouthfeel is light-bodied , a bit watery , nothing special .
smell - coffee aroma but felt it lacked .  appearance : wow ! huge frothing head that forced me to ease up on the pour .  mouthfeel - low carbonation and lighter than i expected . a little sticky .

aftertaste is a bit dusty with an olive aroma . great beer to pair with foods of the same variety !  super dense off-white three finger head shows outstanding retention leaving sheets of stubborn lacing .  m : a little light on body and sharp on carbonation . nothing special on this front .

all the flavors seem to jump out especially as the brew warms . i had this one at just over celler temp . nice roasted malts and chocolate a small touch of coffee not overly done in anything and all the flavors blend to form and intense drinkable experience you and expect going into a beer like this.awesome  anderson valley poleeko gold on-tap at world of beer coconut creek , fl a- best head i 've ever seen on a beer . golden hazy color gradient in pint glass , white head 1.25 '' . m- wow , so creamy a smooth with the great head medium-to-light body ale . d- very drinkable and only 5.5 % abv i really could have had a couple more that night .  it was watery with some carbonation and a slightly bitter aftertaste .

appearance reddish-brown body ; tremendous , tightly carbonated off-white head that doesnt hang forever but it certainly is strong enough to paint an ample set of lace smell big sweetness ; toffee ; some dark fruit ; some grains ; very enjoyable taste toffee , caramel and a solid roasted malt flavor take off to open and they almost make it to the end before being tripped up by a good slam of hops and a moderate dose of metallic for a close ; bitterness carries a bit strong for the aftertaste mouthfeel medium body ; rather smooth ; hops barge in late to send the experience in a downward spiral drinkability aftertaste takes the drinkability down a bit since it carries the strong bitterness into the next experience ; the initial smoothness helps the cause  great looking beer .  mouthfeel - it does n't really differentiate itself . the carbonation is low , as is normal amongst dark , high alcohol beers . it 's particularly dense , milk is probably a good comparison , and it feels like it sticks to the inside of your mouth somewhat .

12 oz bottle poured into a pint glass creamy colored head with good lacing down the glass aroma is seriously lacking , in fact it 's hard to detect that this is an ipa at all from the nose . serious deficiencies here . moderately drinkable , but a very mediocre attempt at american ipa . after enjoying some of the deconstructed beers i 'm disappointed that they played it so safe with this one .  16.9oz bottle a- pours a dark brown color with a massive light tan head that sticks around forever and leaves a good amount of retention .  mouthfeel is very crisp with medium-high carbonation . lite bodied , and it goes down a little thin and watery .

not cloudy like most beers of this type . smell is rather dull , does n't smell like much really .  served in a tulip glass , for the low , low , price of $ 10 ( ! a - served with two fingers of tan foam that settles to a thick cap and glass-coating lace . very , very , dark brown body that has some faint transparency at the fringes . as far as dark saison 's got this is reference quality .  mouthfeel : light to medium body , a little alcohol warmth .

very nice smell . t- bitter coffee and chocolate . this beer is strong and biting .  12oz bottle into my orval glass ... black with a dark tan head , good retention and lacing..the aroma is way too sweet , mostly all chocolate , with pine and alcohol .  thin of body , which is somewhat disappointing . carbonation lightly massages the tongue and causes moderate fizziness in the beer as it moves .

smell- big wet pine needle aroma , bit of lemon juice smell .  pour is fat 3 finger head and luckily used my duvel tulip . body is rich glowing amber and very fine looking by ipa standars .  mouthfeel/body is light/medium , it seems a bit thin and is well carbonated .

pours a nice clear yellow that has a huge white head . smell is almost solely of barnyard funk . slight lemon and a hint of brett on the end , but i was hoping for more . the chardonnay barrels have played a great role on this beer . very nice lemon zest with the tart brett flavor at the end .  appearance : pours with over three fingers of light tan head . the lacing continues all down the glass as i drink , very nice ! the beer itself is a rich orange/copper color and perfectly clear . drinkability : with amazing head retention and lacing , coupled with a spicy yet well balanced flavor , this is a winner .  the mouthfeel is full , but the carbonation is a bit high .

not a great beer if you want to call it beer a- looks like grape juice , but maybe a little lighter s- blueberry muffins this is not ... smells like a candy with fake flavor , maybe like a starburst candy , even though they do n't make a blueberry i do n't think t- bad ... overly tart without a ton of blueberry flavor actually present . confusing , as to the coloration would hint at a better flavor ... m- almost a gross creaminess .  poured into a pint glass a : aggressive pour yields 2 fingers of tan head with great retention . very good looking !  medium bodied but with a rather thinnish , pallid mouthfeel .

12oz into standard pint . s- mild hop bitterness , pale malt . t- follows the nose , a pretty decent hop bite and a strong enough malt backbone to have me scratching my head on this .  starts out with a spectacular pour ; a clear ruby copper with a never-ending ivory pillow floating on top lacing like a boot on the way down .  purchased as part of the 12 beers of winter sampler case . it smelled like cranberries and soap . not enticing in the least . the flavor was n't much better . the label claims a number of spices found in this beer , but i was hard-pressed to find them . extremely bland . the base of the flavor was that of acidic berries . i tasted slight hints of nutmeg and some hops , but that is about it . it was a fight to get through it .

s : sniffer must be off today ( worried how affecting taste , but onward ) ... real light smell , reminds me of standing in a field n the summer . t : light , clean , wonderfully spiced .  dark as night with a high frothy cream-colored head with about the best retention of any beer created . also looks amazing if you can manage a proper black and tan pour !  m - feels slightly thin .

a brief but very nice malt aroma , followed by nothing , nothing at all .  a : pours dark brown but not quite black , capped by a two finger , rich brown head . retention is good for style/abv and a good deal of lacing is left on the glass .  the carbonation is medium-high and body is medium to medium-light giving this beer a very high drinkability .

aroma is of wheat and spices ( cloves or nutmeg- i have difficulty distinguishing between the two sometimes ) . maybe some hops poke through , but it lacks a little in this department .  the huge champagne head and pink hue were beautiful , but it tasted like sour patch kids without the sweetness .  kinda thin and tinny .

12 oz bottle , no freshness dating , english flag on label , so we know what kind of ipa this is supposed to be . soft malty nose . well done , british style ipa . hop cravers will feel slighted , but balanced beer lovers will rejoice .  nice rich beer looks great , nice dark brownish color .  mouthfeel is ok , suitable for this type of brew .

the aroma was slight and first suggested metal with occasional hints of apple and something like pipe tobacco .  a - stunning beer . an aggressive beer pour gives a finger white , tiny bubbled head which proudly sits on top of a brilliant , see through golden yellow . very inviting , and it 's literally screaming drink me .  m - a little soft on the carbonation but with a decent if not great finish .

powerful notes of banana and clove with subtle spices . d - this one delivered the right smell but not the right taste .  great head retention , shrunk down to a thick ring which lasted throughout . lacing was among the best i 've seen .  medium to full bodied with a very water type mouth feel at first that ends with a bit more girth in the finish .

appearance : rich amber with a foamy off-white head and some very nice lacing . smell : very mild citrus over some toasted malts . very mild - too mild . still , could use more aroma . wet hop american esb would be a more accurate description .  served in an allagash chalice with a giant rose colored head . the body is a nice plum color .  tart mouthfeel with slight thickness .

the top is a pale tan standing at a few inches tall . s - malt and yeast with hints of hops . t - piny bitterness with a light , dry hoppy finish .  pours pitch black into the corsendonk tulip , and an aggressive pour produce a thick and sexy tan capper , sheets of lace on the way down .  a very smooth and well integrated taste..the buiscuity malts and hops blend near seamlessly . ok palate for the style but the extreme balance gives the impression of boredom ! but overall this is a charming and very drinkable pnw lager
the smell isnt that great moslty just hops .  this is a beautiful looking beer .  m - the mouth feel is softer than the german original is is dryer than many hefes as well .

s : light wheat , apple , apricot , slight malt , and yeast . t : apple , malt so overpowering w/ corn that i ca n't taste much else - and i love it like thanksgiving !  an ultra dense and creamy head tops off this deeply golden and very clear brew .  thats the only thing separating this beer from chocolate milk , well , also without any of the heaviness associated with milk . this is a beer you can drink and drink , so it 's my wednesday night drink of choice .

s : hops , hops and then a few more hops . a slightly honey and flower and a slight caramel malt smell .  pours a beautiful clear copper with a touch of chill haze . impressive white foam , which settled to 1/4 inch and remained for the duration .  i work at a distributer that sells this beer so i had to try it . at first open i thought that the high alcohol smell would make for a bad beer . after a couple sips , it was actually pretty good . i would compare it to miller high life ... .except that you get smashed after two or three beers . since beer is for the purpose of getting drunk ... this is the right one . if it taste good and serves it 's purpose , why not take this one . since i do work at a distributor that sells high end beers , if anyone ask for a good beer that will serve its purpose , i will highly recomend camo & gt ;

babayaga pours black , no hint of light even when directly backlit , yet it does n't feel as dark as many larger stouts would pour . the nose is fairly muted , but i can discern some chocolate and a little bit of rosemary . the carbonation is pitch perfect , on the low end of the spectrum but still very lively .  pours into my tulip glass a clear luminous golden peach color . great fluffy white clouds of head laze about the glass for what seems like hours , finally sinking to swaths of sticky white cotton candy lace .  mouthfeel is slightly thin .

it looks fantastic , but a little light on the aroma . the flavor is mild and well rounded .  this thing has a huge head on a a nice orange/amber body . the head is fluffy and looks delicious . lots of sticky lacing .  m - coarse throughout ranging from a small to large graininess . certainly a sessionable brew and another notch in the winner category for the folks at new glarus .

smell - amazing hoppy aroma . it 's pretty complex . i do n't have a good nose . but it smells very good .  on the pour : dark chocolate opaque , it almost seems to absorb light.i have a glass full of floaties moving up and down the glass in a dynamic and entertaining little dance .large bubbles make up a tan and coffee swirl head.the nose is sweet fruit and pepper .  then the aftertaste.. i have now experienced the dreaded `` band-aid '' sensation .

aroma is very subdued ... mostly fig and a hint of smoke . definitely one to try if you like your winter warmers without the spices being overdone .  the beer pours a hazy deep golden color with the thickest , stickiest head i 've ever seen . half the pilsner glass is crowned in meringue like foam and once that dies down and there 's room for another pour there 's another two inches of new head . incredible - must amazing pour . beyond the taste this may be one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen .  m -- -fine , i guess .

the smell really was not there for me . i could tell that it was very hoppy though and that some fruit was present . drinkability was also fantastic .  jet black with a thick cappuccino head .  great session brew . burnt flavor that lends an espresso taste with some chocolatey notes . good hop bitterness in the finish . my only gripe is that this brew turns watery in the finish . still , went down easily and quickly , def . worth a try .
not much smell . thick and creamy .  beautifully dark , nearly black body with a creamy tan head .  just mildly bittered and the flavor is really great despite being a tad light bodied .

spots of soapy lacing left behind . smoked malt aroma with lots of toasted malt without feeling burnt along with some faint sweetness .  pours into my duvel tulip a brilliant golden orange . it is slightly hazy but tons of tiny bubbles ca be seen racing towards the head which is 4 fingers of mountainous white foam . as it recedes it leaves nice belgian-styled lacing .  m : medium-bodied , carbonation stings the tongue early on .

smells mildly perfume and grainy .  a - pours black , completely opaque . even brown/black head s - very faint smell , subtle hints of sweetness and bitterness t - extremely complex taste .  thinnish initially . sturdies itself somewhat as it rests , but remains airy and light . nice enough .

the aroma was one of herbs mostly , but nothing to powerful . the taste was clean and almost sharp , a good example of the style .  there is a nice thin but frothy beige head and a glistening pattern of carbonated bubbles along the side of the pint glass .  whatever , it 's tasty and pretty nice to drink . overall , its smooth , but almost slightly sour porter . definitely worth a try .

typical smell imparted by the lager yeast on the nose , along with a touch of alcohol and some bready malts .  pitch black with a lasting thick soupy head .  as with most nitro cans , great head , and as always , watching a guinness poured right settle is pretty satisfying . the usual guinness metallic taste , not a really strong smell or anything . nothing too overpowering , this remains an extremely drinkable stout . much better compared to that guinness draft bottle junk that 's supposed to be drank out of the bottle . to me , the exceptional part of the guinness is the appearance , and you miss that with the bottle . better from the can .

a faint aroma . hints of roasted malt , charcoal , cocoa and bread . hop aroma is very faint but some notes of fruity esters detectable . a great porter from the guys at mudgee , this ticks almost all the boxes for the style .  color is a rich deep brown , almost black - which i like in a porter .  the mouthfeel was a tad below average .

a - golden yellow but not straw coloured , it 's almost like a work of art to look at and it makes you want to drink it all right away in one gulp . beauty . what is there is pleasant though , and nothing like a macro-lager 's smell . t- exemplary . this is how a pale lager should taste .  excellent lacing and incredible head retention .  the mouthfeel is somewhat disappointing . i like gueuze to be effervescent , or at least moderately carbonated , but the carbonation i find here is quite low .

smell is where this one shines , featuring heavy doses of sweet , chocolate draped coffee against a malt backing . the expected maltiness is there but a surprising bitterness joins it in the second half of the sip . this is a decent beer but a little too hop influenced for my taste . i understand the desire to add hops to everything but honestly think this brew would be more satisfying if the natural coffee malt was allowed to star on the stage alone .  large , two-finger creamy white head that fully diminished . beautiful lacing decorated the glass as i drank . this beer looked absolutely amazing when it was served !  a bit surprising then that the flavor is what it is ... the first sip : a bit thin . the last sip : quite thin .

poured from a 40 oz bottle ... .gee , maybe i could get a 6 pack of this stuff sometime ... the pour foamed up pretty well , smell was allright thought it might be good afterall .  pours a cloudy deep orange with massive off white fluffy head and awesome lacing . the head stays nice throughout - a great looking brew .  mouthfeel the high carbonation makes this one a little rough .

aromas are very nice . i mostly notice sweetness , and hops .  seigneuriale a very sparkling burnt sienna ale with highlights from vermillion to pink . the off-white head is thick , smooth and soft . it tastes like a dimly lit room with leather walls and dark wooden furniture .  it 's really malty , which probably makes it seem so highly carbonated . the carbonation and sweetness would probably prevent this from being a session beer .

fairly straightforward aroma of oats and subdued roasted malts , but sadly , not as strong as i would have hoped .  pours nice and dark , even darker than arrogant bastard and almost as dark as a porter . has a reddish hue when looked at up to the light .  m - a little slick for my liking .

smell : smells a little bit like harpoons chocolate stout with some belgian esters comming through . if i didnt know it was a belgian imperial stout i would have guessed that there was some sort of belgian yeast strain in it because of the musty fruity belgian aroma . has an adjuncty aroma to it aswell . taste : tastes very rich , mocha , chocolate , milk stout like sweetness . might be the dryest imperial stout i have had . leaves an especially dry feeling inthe back of the throat uncharacteristic of this style .  drank from a 24 fl oz bottle purchased at liquor world , cambridge , ma poured a dark , crimson-amber with a tight , fluffy , two-finger , sea foam head that slowly faded to a clingy film . outstanding retention .  thus one can use a more substantial body , but the hops drove this one . solid beer

s- my nose is not very sharp , but i believe i detect a slight smell of burnt chocolate even though ive never smelled burnt chocolate before in my life . it swallows wonderfully . m - silky smooth with what i would call a medium body . d - this is really good beer . it is flavorful and heavy enough to let you know youve had something besides water , yet light enough to leave room for a few more . it is immediately tasty .  a gigantic head that keeps going and going . flecks of red coagulated proteins , but no apparent oxidation . top notch lace .  m : the feel is a tad watery and a weak-point of this brew .

this pint did n't start out throwing much of a nose , but it could have been that my own faculties are still packed with red waimea canyon dirt .  pours a big head that retains very well , and with al= wonderful lacing .  mouthfeel is some-what sharp .

just underwhelming . t - the hops and malt kind of hit at the same time .  this beer should probably served in a weizen glass . a & # 8211 ; huge white head , 2 or 3 inches high , cloudy orange-amber . impressive !  i do n't get the big deal . my friends are always so excited about # 9 , but this is one of my least favorite beers around . i 'd rather have a coors light . the apricot flavor is boring and frankly just gross . of all the fruits . the first sip was almost okay , and each one after was worse .

the nose is quite understated and offers little more than vague cannabis and evergreen notes ; it is pleasant , but perhaps overly mild .  pours a deep brown/black with a nice sized long lasting rocky tan head that leaves lacing on the surface and sides .  almost bad enough that i thought about just dumping it out . but i 'm a huge mikkeller fan and could n't believe that they could make a beer as bad as this one smelled . this is one terrible beer . i 've had the bourbon and red wine versions in this series and they were both outstanding . the taste is very complex in it 's awfulness . it 's just a combination of toxic flavors that you do n't normally identify with beer . burnt rubber , iodine , paint thinner , magic marker . truly disappointed by one of my all time favorite breweries .

nose : light malt , not much happening for me ... malty from the start , with sweet caramel , some breads and candied sugar . no real hop presence until the slight bitter sweet finish .  poured from a bomber into a tulip . well themed beer with a quirky name . big juicy foam like head , 3 fingers deep . hence the exeptional appearance rating . thick sticky lace , resembling real sponge along the glass .  the mouthfeel was a bit sharp at first .

nose is a little less reliable , with some coffee and hop balance extant but not much else ; somewhat lacking and dull in the sniffer to be honest . taste is sweet with coffee and hops and plenty of malt sugar .  that 's what is written at ddc and on their website ... a : extremely gorgeous . not brown at all , only red . the head is off-white and strong , even if the brew does n't look much carbonated at first .  taste : extremely spicy top note with intense ginger and nutmeg notes are balanced by slightly dry , caramelized wood and some citrusy coffee in the mold of a yergicheffe that 's at city roast levels . ripe currants , molasses , and fruit skin bitterness with a hint of cider flavors emerge as it warms and opens up . definitely not as roasty as one would expect from a black ale . finish is grassy and citrus bitterness , a little dry , quite spicy , a little yeasty with a touch of banana . notes : awesome , amazingly drinkable and unique beer .

aroma is dark coffee with alcohol and a hint of chocolate .  pours pitch black with a good three finger of puffy light brown head . the head lasts a good ten minutes .  m : a little too much carbonation for my taste .

i was intrigued by the complex smell of the grapes mixed with the spices and the faint belgian yeast aroma .  colour is a rich brownish-red . big two-finger head fades with mild lacing . a moderate amount of carbonation is visible . appearance is beautiful but the taste was a little run of the mill .  mouthfeel : good medium body but just a tad under carbed overall impression : its surprisingly good for a gimmicky beer ; very nice taste and very drinkable .
the nose is very quiet .  greedy bleached-brown soft-serve ice cream head that slowly recedes to reveal deep glacial crevasses . truly magnificent .  not a whole lot of body or mouthfeel to this .

bottle into pint glass appearance- dark black , impossible to see through , nice 1 inch off white head smell- not too much there for smell , a bit of roasted malts taste- the first sip was much more bitter than i expected , more than the guinness draught , tasted some roasted malts though when it warmed up and i got used to the different taste mouthfeel- heavy to say the least drinkability- a heavy stout and i could only drink one of these in a sitting overall- very good stout , takes a little getting used to when i am used to the guinness draught version  bottle poured into a standard pint glass black cherry in color with a huge , chocolate brown head of foam .  i actually like a few of the canadian brands better ( as some have the actual raisins and what not in the bottle still , and better carbonation levels and lower abv ) . taste is great malty , sweet , and very filling ( it 's nutritous to boot ) . i only generally drink water , tea , coffee , beer , wine , spirits , juice , and dairy ( kefir , etc ) . this is the noly soda type beverage i drink and it is absolutely stellar hangover relief ...

a - pours an amber colour , inch head with moderate lacing s - very malty , but loses a few points for being metallic t - a very balanced hoppiness and maltiness , i detect some toasted caramel in the malts m - medium to light bodied d - a very good lawnmower beer a really good beer for the value .  a beautifully looking beer .  very good mouthfeel , maybe a bit too carbonated , but very drinkable .

a - pours a pale copper color with a one-finger head s - smells of some faint caramel and toasted malts . m - slick , buttery mouthfeel with a full body and a nice touch of carbonation d - this is very good beer . very malty and full of flavor , it is really easy to drink .  pours completely clear with a thick pillowy head that sticks around for awhile . great carbonation level along with a perfect deep copper color .  m : thin body with a medium mouthfeel .

nothing much jumps out to the nose , but the smoothness of the product down the hatch is incredible . pleasant bitterness , nice body , all in all , a great beer , and one of my favorites .  poured into my pint glass the beer is duh black as coal . superb retention . after a serious wait the glass is covered with sticky webs of lace .  mouthfeel is slightly stringent and a bit on the thin side .

no lacing smells like an exploded skunk . so much skunk aroma i can taste it , wet grain and strange hop twang .  when poured this beer , i was really loved how it looked . perfect color for a brown , and great head with some lacing .  the flavor is nicely malty to back up the yeasty fruit and spice but the body is a tad thin .

the aroma is strong and pleasant but completely one-dimensional .  absolutely exceptional appearance ! poured a huge very thick beige head that actually retained its height .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with pretty high carbonation , remember it gushing , and the carbonation is the only thing that stops this from being higher .

after it warms it has a dark fruity smell . the ale is a nice lighter addition from stone but full of flavor .  a cloudy amber brew is poured into my snifter glass with a full two fingers of light tan head and most of it goes nowhere as i stare it down ... what does recede leaves behind some slightly roasted marshmallow foam sitting on top .  the main surprise hit me with how light the mouth feel is for something so dark and with such a rich aroma . great taste that did n't weigh on me and created a nice appetite .

smell was cherries ! pure cherry pie filling . this one is not complex but it is well fashioned . a world class fruit beer .  this one poured absolutly beautifully . a fanatastic thick hazy ruby brown liquid that was almost opaque . a huge pillow like white head formed on top that did not want to give up any ground , i swear it would stay there all night .  mouthfeel seems a little oily , yet at the same time , a little thin .

with the foam gone , the beer yielded sweet , chocolate aromas with a very light roast . whatever was lacking in the aroma was trapped in the taste , in a good way . it 's not intimidating , like the czar . another success from a great brewery .  a : pours pitch black , 2 finger deep tan head , settles into a full , yet thin , cap , leaves lacing everywhere and desperately tries to hold on , which it eventually loses . held to light , it 's letting zero light through .  for real , closest mass-produced craft beer to snpa . coppery , high crystal malt appearance with nice head and typical bottled carbonation . grassy . flavor is a bit bitter at first followed by some mild hoppy/flowery/cascady flavors . bite at finish . not too much but bitter enough to say this is a pale ale . fine everyday drinking pale ale but nothing exceptional or cheeky . b+

this compares well with others i 've tasted in the category . the color is a clear gold with a white head that lasted long enough for me to finish the glass , which was n't long because it tasted so good . the flavor was nicely malted with caramel and honey notes which clung to the palate briefly and went down very smooth with not much aftertaste . this beer was quite drinkable and immediately wanted another .  reviewed 9/24/2008 ( draft @ flying saucer , houston , tx ) : pours a very dark red-brown colored body , somewhat transparent looking , with a big frothy off-white head .  the mouthfeel is average for the style , medium bodied , slightly creamy , and of course rather oily .

smell is somewhat muted at first but starts to open up as it warms . nice slightly sweet apricot presence mixed with sour wheat .  on tap at the san bernardino location ... a - brown with reddish hues and a one finger tan head that follows you all the way to the finish . lots of sticky lacing to be had here .  m - a little chewy , a little thin and watery , however it is silky smooth as it goes down d - really impressed with this imperial oatmeal stout .

for the most part , the aroma is clean , with mineral crispness backed by a lightly toasted malt note and a kiss of floral , grassy hops . it 's subtle , but underwhelming . very nice flavor to this esb -- was n't expecting much given the aroma , but things start well with a spicy tinge from the hops .  appearance - cloudy amber brown bod with a big light brown head with great retention . retains its structure as well as cool whip .  m - mouthfeel is a little light .

the aroma was light , as citrus tones and malt were tough to pull out .  pours an effervescent mahogany/black with 4 fingers of mocha colored head . insane lacing & head retention was damn good as well s : musty & sour with hints of oak & chocolate .  m : feels a tad thin , i 'd say its light-medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

good lacing & head retention s : roasty , malty & nutty t : roasted malt & too much coffee up front .  it pours jet black , with a beautiful brown head of foam .  m- light in the mouth , but could use more carbonation seem to be lacking here .

not a terribly strong aroma , malt and caramel .  appearance : beautiful , highly carbonated amber color with a thick , white , two fingered head .  mouthfeel is a bit thin for a beer that has this much flavor , i like it now , but would like it better with a bit more body .

nice smooth aroma . t - coffee , roasted malt , mild cola aspect .  very beautiful to say the least . sheet s of lace cling to the sides of the glass creating a sort of wallpaper effect .  m : not quite as smooth as some stouts , has the right amount of carbonation though .

just a whiff of roasted malt , that 's it . turns out to be just a tease , because it belies a sturdy , pleasantly ( read : not overly ) roasty body , with more than a trace of bittersweet chocolate , and backup depth and texture from the oatmeal . if this was my first stout , i think i would have overcome the guinness stigma long ago and explored what the style has to offer .  pours a solid black with the beautiful guinness head .  smooth entry - softer and thinner mouthfeel than tradition for style . while the mouthfeel detracted a bit - i enjoyed the flavor profile .

subtle smell , would like a bit stronger aroma .  a : very nice dark orange/red looking beer . fully transparent . head is tan and ridiculously strong and lasting .  i poured this beer into my tumbler at 50 degrees then poured it out of my tumbler and into the sink . the bber was a light mahoganny color with a light orangy looking head . the smell was of sour something with a bit of a caralally smell . the taste was sour gross sour yuk ... too me . the sourness was just overpowering of rotten fruit and bout gagged me . i will not buy again .

my wife , who is sitting next to me as i drink it , even commented that it smells good . taste is where this beer really falls flat for me .  a- as soon as i opened this i knew there was going to be alot of carbonation and head . giant , pillowy orange-tinted head on top of a hazy orange/amber colored body .  i have not been a fan of most pumpkin beers i 've tried , but this one was a very pleasant suprise . the taste was very much like pumpkin pie as well , and while it 's more heavily spiced than some others i 've tried , schlafly managed to not over-do it . this beer would be perfect right after thanksgiving dinner .

the scent is rather light .  a : chocolately brown beer with a huge 2 finger head dissipating slowly , s : dates , molasses , cloves .  this rating is for the green bottled version . i was sorely disappointed by this version . i 've had the brown-bottled .5 liter version in the past and liked it a lot , but this version is terrible . i can only assume this is horrible because of the green bottle and the associated skunky flavor . why in the world is the brewery sending us this inferior version ? i just do n't understand making a world-class beer , but then ruining it by putting it in a green bottle .

not much to say about the smell , the malt and hops are subtly present in the nose . the taste however is big . full maltiness right from the start , not particularly sweet , some hoppy bitterness .  pours perfect with a two finger thick head , and an ultra clear copper colored body .  nice and drying , though the carbonation is a little lacking .

s : big burst of co2 hits the nose and throat as soon as i get into the glass grassy with touched of lemon and just a bit skunky . t/mf : much better than the aroma had initially indicated .  22oz bottle this beer poured a dark brown , almost chocolate milk , colored creamy head with a pitch black body . easily one of the most beautiful heads i 've ever seen on a beer .  was light on tongue , still there was carbonation that froze the tongue .

picked this up at grape vine market in austin , tx . aroma : mild fruity esters couple with an earthy hop with a belgian yeast twist . appearance : careful pour leaving behind a thin sediment layer in the bottle produces a bright , painfully clear straw yellow cup with a spotty cover of pale white tiny bubbles that struggle to even collar the glass and never seriously think about lacing . a slight earthy , maybe peppery hop note , a belgian yeast taste , a little light fruit , lemon peel , but im really reaching on all of this . i expected the tripel to be more intense than the singel , but this is lighter and less flavorful to me .  there beer looks really good and has a strong hop aroma , but the taste leaves something lacking .  m - high carbonation and medium to full body .

the aroma was a bit muted , smooth caramel and cereal notes slightly.tasted creamy as ever and nice and malty . a very good example of the style .  pours an opaque black body with well over an inch of light tan head that persists nicely and eventually subsides leaving some decent lacing .  thin mouthfeel with light to medium carbonation .

this is a really different beer . ok well the peer pours a murkey rusty color with a very thin off white head that immediatley dissipates immediately . the beer smells strongly of the wintergreen and the sasafrass . overall an intersting beer .  chimay tripel pours nicely and produces a beautiful bright white head , which sticks around through out the whole session .  christ , the taste is skunked too , i really do n't know if i can get past this , it seems kind of outrageous . the untainted part of the taste has some vienna or munich malts , tough to tell . just a bit of nobel hops in there as well . it 's absolutely ruined by the skunked flavor . i get that the skunkiness can be somewhat appealing to some people , but thats for a pilsner or a euro pale lager .

smell : roasted malt and absolutely smokey .  this beer looked dark , dark brown at a glance , but what blew me ( us ) away was the colors that crept in along the sides . the head was a slightly rusty tan that replenished itself with a swirl . this is clearly one of the most beautiful beers ive ever seen .  the mouthfeel and malt profile is just a tad lacking when compared to good ( unskunked ) european pilsners .

not impressive , but nice enough .  retains amazingly . laces splendidly .  was interested to try this beer as it is advertised as `` america 's original '' or `` oldest '' lager . tasted like a typical american macro lager , not much now to add .

not a favorite of mine , but a very good beer & when taking into account it 's modest price- a real bargain .  a - very deep amber in color . beautiful beige head with good retention and very small , fine bubbles .  smell : malt , caramel and a hint of smoke taste : again , malty , not much bitterness or hops detectable , carmel and smoke in the background mouthfeel : a bit thin ... i had expected it to have more body drinkability : yes , i would drink it again .

verry mild aroma which gives off a smidge of toastiness . overall : 3.85 appearance : 4.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 4 | mouthfeel : 3.5 | drinkability : 4 737  weihenstephaner korbinian is a solid , crystal clear , brown-red beer with an oily , bubbly , beige head .  i had this at isaac newton 's in newtown pa.poured from a bottle into a snifter.pours a cloudy light amberish color with ridiculous white frothy heading that stays bubbly to the very end.smell is very faint light hops light malt nothing to get nutty about.taste is very sweet like a soda i took a sip and ended up with a mouthful of foam . i would have guessed this was a light beer but with 6.9 % alcohol ( stated on bottle ) this kind of a heavy hitter .

smells sweet and malty . a bit of orange and grapefruit permeate the nose .  lush , billowing mocha head and sticky lacing atop a deep ebony body . alluring to say the least .  m : oily texture with average carbonation and a bitter finish . the mouthfeel is the weakest aspect of the beer .

s - basic roasted malt , maybe a bit of toffee , nothing overwhelming or particularly memorable . t - much better than the nose .  i do n't care what the overall sentiment for guinness is , the appearance is perfectly brilliant .  mouthfeel : nice mouth-coating , but a much weaker carbonation than i was expecting ( the tap ? ) .

i had this on tap at ashleys , a bartender recommendation ... it pours nice and black with a full creamy head that has really nice lacing , my hopes are high ... the aroma is really dead , hard to pull anything out but a little roast coffee , my hopes start to fade ... the taste is better than the aroma , it has a light flavor but not much here and its super thin to drink .  pitch black with a huge , creamy , thick tan head . even a relatively easy pours produces a heavy handed head .  felt a little too light and watery .

smell : very subtle . would have expected a little more . light , grainy malts and a very gentle , slight floral hop presence .  amber on the base and a thick and frothy light tan head that slowly settles to a thick cap . the settling head leaves behind a solid wall of lacing . solid lacing all the way down the glass .  i think this is one of lost abbey 's better brews , most of the others i have tried had low carbonation which took away from there overall enjoyment .

the smell was average a little hoppier than some . the taste was great . very hoppy all around with a little more malt at the end .  pours thick and vicscous , looks just like a great imperial stout should . head takes a few seconds to get going , but then billows right to the top of my glass . high and puffy , mocha in color , perfect consistency , lots of lacing left behind . just great .  i get orange and coriander on the finish , which is a bit weird ... i wish it was a bit thicker , but i 'll take what i can get .

this is called rodenbach alexander , in that order , not vice versa . extremely vinegarish on the nose , so much so that it 's difficult to pull out anything else . some essence of wet wood and cherries floating about . really strange , lovely progression .  deep amber liquid capped by a foamy head that holds together beautifully .  when i first picked it up i thought belgian dubbel right away and it made sense to me when i found out it was rye ale . the beer is thin , at 6.3 abv a very sessionable ale and i bet this is really something fresh on draft .

the smell is light but is a definite bready malt smell . at first , you get a blast of toasty/bready/biscuity malt and along with the smell , i start to think it 's going to be like some of the dopplebocks i 've had .  pours into my stange with a nice fluffy white three finger head . it sticks around for awhile before leaving some very nice lacing behind . this beer is pale pale gold , and very clear and bright . it looks like a stalwart german pilsener .  body is between light and medium , a tad too thin .

3.0 s : weak smelling . mild coffee and chocolate and herbal hops . a hint of some off aroma that i ca n't put my finger on . 4.5 t : nice strong taste , something that most stout makers forget to do .  pours hazy dark gold/orange with beautiful one-finger eggshell head that lingers .  light body and aggressive carbonation .

pretty weak .  a : poured a deep wine purple with a half finger head and light sticky lacing left on the glass s : i was getting some funky corky aromas with good grape notes that made the cut with slight acidic tartness .  5 it 's a bit thin and the carbonation works to emphasize that .

it was poured into an oversized brandy snifter ... appearance : pours pitch black , with almost no light coming through . smell : not much of one . hints of malt and bitter chocolate , and maybe a little coffee , but it was all very subdued .  pours a pitch black color with a brown one-finger head into my glass . good presentation i 'd say .  m : the medium light body is semi-dry and could stand quite a bit less carbonation .

aroma was about the best thing - beery , a little hop and malt .  breathtaking looks of rusty golden coloring sporting a mountainous creamy head that subsides after a few minutes into a frothy one-finger plateau .  body is very flat and smooth .

pours a dark brownish orange/yellow , little head that disapeared quickly smell is of a brown ale , dont detect any kind of spice , such as pumpkin , or cinnamon , just the average ale smell taste is above average , more of a amber ale taste , but thicker moutfeel with a bit of spark of carmel , a little sour flavor to it .  a- this beer is a yeast hazed golden color with a moderate amount of carbonation rising to the top . the head is nice and white , and has a cloud like texture that is dense . the lacing is also excellent , with dense bubbly goodness clinging to the glass like nothing .  mouthfeel was quite average for a belgian brune .

s - pretty average smell .  corked and caged , with black foil covering , and a hangtag noting this is the 2004 holiday stout . poured into an imperial pint glass , formed 1 1/2 '' of dark brown head over the opaque dark brown/black brew .  the mouthfeel is neither here nor there . carbonation starts high and fades .

superior head retention & lacing s : lemony hops & a little breadyness t : lemony hops , crackers & whisper of honey up front .  ebony in color , the head chocolate brown and meaningful in size , a creamy texture with the remnants being a fine sheet of clinging lace .  m- somer orange honey ale is thin with a light carbonation , slight snap of carbonation at the end .

pours to a thin head and a decent malty aroma . color is a bit darker than a sam adams lager and with a hint of ruby .  awesome looks ! s : mainly chocolate with some roasted malts notes ... t : chocolate and roasted malts with a very good finish with bitterness .  the mouth feel was pretty average , has a slight alcohol bite at the end of it .

aroma is of coffee and chocolate malts , with some hoppiness apparent as well .  a : clear , deep vermillion body with a ridiculously persistent , creamy off-white head .  when i first saw andygator after it had been transferred to the growler at the abita brew pub , i thought what a beautiful bronze to golden color . just a hint of hops comes out when you sniff it . then the taste , i told my wife it was like liquid gold . this beer is a the top of my list . now that could be because it has n't been easy to get or because it is so very good . we soon went by the bulldog on magazine in new orleans . i had the andygator on draft , my what a killer brew .

aroma : surprisingly peppery upfront with some dark fruit and cherries blending in . the aroma is quite light overall with only subtle hints of chocolate and caramel trying to come through . not a whole lot in the nose on this one . appearance : initially you 'll think this beer pours a jet black , but hold it up to the light and you 'll find a deep cherry red with nice clarity . overall : while the beer lacks aroma characteristics , the real payout is in the flavor and body .  the head looks outstanding -- insanely dark coco powder color .  m - a little like bodied for a stout , but still light and creamy .

this 9.5 % porter does a fantastic job of masking its high abv . the appearance is a nice dark color , with a head that dissappates shortley after pouring . we 've found it goes great with chinese food . it has a metallic aftertaste .  750ml into a tulip . pours a crystal clear , new penny copper color , frothy dense white head , sticky lacing .  mouthfeel : fizzy and frothy . light and very very dry .

definitely one of the best bottled hefe 's i 've had ( perhaps the higher alcohol keeps better ? s : big banana aroma , with cloves , cinnamon , nice breadyness & hints of bubble gum fruity esters . t : banana , candied pineapple , well-rounded spicing , vanilla , warming alcohol , modest bitterness , pleasant breadyness , bubble-gum fruity esters in the finish .  amazing retention .  the texture is smooth and a little bit thin on the palate with a good carbonation and a medium body .

rye grain and mostly citric hop on a rather faint nose .  pours very hazy orange-amber color with a very dense 2 finger off white head with fantastic retention that reduces to a very thick lacing cap that lasts for the rest of the glass .  sweet with decent carbonation . no real aftertaste mouthfeel : very thin and lacy , not one to linger on your tongue for long .

smell : nose for me on this one is quite minimal and faint . full body , full flavor , yet oh so drinkable ! overall : a great stout for somebody who does n't want to be overwhelmed by the 'big ' that is so common of this style yet keep from compromising the flavor .  motor oil black pour , inch and a half of head .  moderate hoppiness . slightly thin tasting , but not in a bad way . highly drinkable .
s - smelled strong . nothing too unique .  pours a beautiful pitch black .  has a very rough bitter mouthfeel , very carbonated , but the flavor is definitely there to make up for it .

three rivers is the only place to drink beer in farmington nm . make this brewery your first stop if your just passing through town or visiting for the weekend . the chaco nut brown is a great beer but i did rate it low in drinkability due to my dislike for nut browns . this does n't mean you should n't try it but you schould enjoy this style of beer .  it is exceptionally clear in dark sensuous amber with a thin velvety head and cluster lace . gazing into the rounded body of the glass , it looks like an amber crystal ball .  lighter than expected on the palate . crisp . the low hop content ( 33 ibu ) is lost in the malt and alcohol . in fact its all malt and alcohol and a bit too cloying at that . i often wonder if some brewers actually taste their beers before they release them , because not only does this taste like one of my first homebrew bombs , but i agree holy jesus , what are these goddamn beers ?

the smell is average , the taste ok , but there is a weird aftertaste .  the black body of this brew is topped by a medium thick to thick creamy , brown head with a good amount of lacing left behind .  m : fairly light body with matching carbonation . a little less substantial than would be ideal .

s : pretty light on the nose , malt with a hint of pear ( ?  a- black with some dark red tints ; sticky , off-white head .  citrus and spiciness to the nose . malt sweetness ansd hop bittering very balanced . dry finish . smells get even better as beer warms . oh yeah , i 'm not so fond of coors either , but this definitely is not a coors lite . if they marketed this beer with scantily clad fine chicks it could become my favorite .

on the nose it 's a pretty distant but pleasant group of notes , mostly roasted malt and burnt coffee , some dark , wet grass . in the mouth it 's a good deal thinner than i associate with the style , but pleasantly fuzzy on the way down .  ap : heavy black , thick tan head , very fine head , great retention , nice lace t : boozy , sweet heavy lost abbey bourbon aged beer character , alcohol and roast balance the sweetness well , lightly toasty , good roast at end , prune hints , spice ( rummy/alcohol ) , very complex dark malt characer , heavy sweet brown sugar , good roast , burnt hints , good representation of lost abbey barrel aged beers m : creamy , not too full , medium very fuine carbonation , body a bit lighter than i would prefer .  ambrosial at the front , the top quite thin and the finish minimally carbonated , hops all mingled in with the other spices , different '' for sure , pleasant to the palate , and the aftertaste quite dry and bitter also long lasting .

this was an amazing beer at the start..biggest head i have seen to date . grainy malts came through in the nose , some hoppyness , although not as much as i expected and hints of metallic . good beer in my opinion .  a : very sizable light beige froth of head rises up and out . tons of frothy retention and lacing .  feel is ok , a bit on the thin side . i think a bit more carbonation would help .

a slight maltiness to the nose , nothing that really stands out here .  appearance : great copper coloring and an excellent head that commits itself to the whole consumption . a standout in this category .  fine mouthfeel .

eh , pretty soft smelling . better smelling than a budweiser , at least .  pitch black with a large head . i 've never seen a head like this on an imperial stout ! the head did recede into some nice lacing after about a minute .  liking the medium-high carb , but the mouthfeel is a little watery for my tastes .
