s - roasted coffee , dark 70 % chocolate , but generally mild .  huge four finger head in matching duvel glassware . head rises like a loaf of bread , forming one inch tall chimney in middle of head . creamy white in color , like a huge cumulous cloud on a mid-west summer 's day .  there is a creaminess that helps the mouthfeel but the carbonation is low which makes this beer seem watered down .

s - faint . roasty with some woody notes . t - nutty , smokey , chocolate , roasty notes .  the bottle poured out a jet black body with a three finger high light brown head .  this is a thick creamy beer and if it had less carbonation i would feel like i 'm drinking a glass of hershey 's syrup .

chocalate , toffee , a sweetness that i just place , and a remarkable aroma that faintly reminds me of soy sauce of all things .  pours with a 2 '' dense head that continues to grow in the center of the glass , resulting in an ice-cream-cone like appearance . leaves nice rings of lacing down the glass as i sip .  mouth -the beer leaves quickly and body does n't add much to overall characteristics , but nice tingling on front and clean but not dry finish .

s : a pleasant floral aroma , and a big grape aroma - not like wine , but rather kinda like grape bubblegum . t : herbal flavours and grape , with quite a tartness to it .  good looking brew .  i noticed to yeast in the bottom of the bottle after i read that it was bottle conditioned on the label . the malt comes through as i drink . there is the malt backbone with some hops . i guess i 'm just so used to ipa 's and dipa 's . this is a really drinkable beer .

awesome fresh cut pine aroma ... .like a fresh cut christmas tree . tastes insanely fresh and hoppy with lots of citrus and a touch of tropical fruit , maybe mango . soft mouthfeel .  appearance - black . it looks fantastic . i ca n't imagine a much better looking imperial stout .  the palate is average for the style .

aroma seems as if it is trapped underneath the fluffy head , is of roasted grain and a bit of coffee .  poured a black hue with a two finger creamy off white head . there was excellent retention and very good lacing .  it is a little on the watery side . the carbonation is good though .

aroma is a bit disappointing , just a hint of malt and hops .  16 oz nitro can , marked l6 156 ml and 16:40 826 , poured into a pint glass apours a solid curtain of tan bubbles that rise to the top , producing a solid black liquid and a 2 inch creamy tan head that stays until the bitter end . picture perfect , lacing is thick and abundant sfaint chocolate , malty , mildly sweet , a little sour twang is there , too , very nice tbitter roasted coffee and mild chocolate , nothing real sweet about this one , starts bitter and stays bitter , finishes on the dry side msmooth and creamy , just a bit chalky , full bodied , perfect carbonation for a nitro can da very drinkable stout and a sessionable choice to boot .  mouthfeel is good . almost completely non-existent carbonation .

this beer had an average sized white head with fine-large sized bubbles when it was poured and it was mostly lasting.the body was uncarbonated and clear with a pale yellow hue.the nose was that of corn and the flavor was lightly bitter tasting.it had a smooth mouthfeel and it was semi-thin and watery in texture.it was light bodied and it had excellent lacing .  stayed with me all the way down to the last drop , leaving an amazing ring lace . check out my twitter for the picture , it makes me very happy .  ... but good for the style m- a little bit of stickyness to this light bodied brew ... medium carbonation d- probably the easiest 40 i 'll ever finish

where 's the nose ? very light aroma of bark .  a : beautiful ruby , red , tannish ( ? ) head s : part lambic frambroise , part belgium ale t : sweet lambic tartness with the sweet malty background .  m - surprisingly light mouthfeel for a porter .

this smells damn good . t. this beers bitterness really jumps out at me .  it pours out a beautifully glowing orange hue and had a giant head that grew quickly out of control .  m : a little flat in the mouth , sticky and slick in a disquieting way .

no balance here , the hallertau hops are very floral on the nose and intense on the palate . overall , a nice beer . one of kind , for sure .  a - golden yellow with impressive white fluffy head . my second pour produced a bouquet of head that hugged the top of my glass like a dome . great lacing also hugging the glass . very impressive .  looks the part ... .pitch black ... no light shines through ... very slight tan head ... sweet chocolate for an instance then a soft whiskey aroma emerges and mixes in ... .good not great flavor ... some nice burnt malts ... also a hint of sweet chocolate ... the bourban aging adds a nice bite on the finish ... i wish the flavors were more intense ... .this is a subtle beer ... mouthfeel is creamy , easy drinking and smooth ... a bit too think for my liking ... needs a bit more body ... creamy+ velvety+ thinnish= a stout that slides down easy..problem is that is not exactly what i 'm looking for in this beer .

aroma is distinctively american ... catty and citrus ... lite smell of toasted pale malts and a touch of yeast fruitiness ... nothing to write home about .  a - really beautiful head that starts huge then turns into a bumpy , frothy foam with pretty lacing .  m- a bit thinner than i would like in my stouts and missing the creaminess or carbonation levels i expect but still a bit of chewy character and the flavors do fill the mouth well .

pours completely pitch black this beer consumes all visible light spectrums emitted , large tan head viable forming a robust carbonation and honorable smell . aroma has hints of dark fruit/herbal/grassy/citric hops which would be a bit different than your average beer from this style . this is the worst version/beer/idea for a russian imperial stout i 've ever had .  poured a nice rich amber copper with a big off white head .  very crisp and a little dry but with oiliness in the end ( if that makes sense ) .

a=deep amber with cream colored head , average carbonation , dissipating quickly s=smell encourages tasting , light bitterness noticable t=good light bitterness , light aftertaste m=enjoyable feel , easy drink d=easy to drink , lighter alcohol heightens drinkability .  white with rose-ish accent to the head . ruby red color .  the mouthfeel is fine for the style . carbonated water , basically . overall , this is , well , carbonated water .

s : sweet biscuity chocolate malts . this is not anywhere near hop forward like old guardian and bigfoot . sadly that is what i love about those 2 .  insane retention means it 's sticking around for quite a while . as it slowly lowers , the sides give way to create the plateau with ridiculous amounts of lacing left on the glass . the color is a deep orange-amber that looks thick and tantalizing .  m - a little thin , but highly carbonated .

a - pours a clear ( some might say crystal ) yellow with a gorgeous head on it s - at first i thought this was going to be a very old beer as it smelled very off on the first couple of whiffs . but as it warmed , hints of banana , spice , and clove came out of hiding . t - very clean taste - all the scents noted in the smell took over the palate .  look : pitch black , dark brown head , great lacing and good retention .  this one was probably made when hops were fresh last fall . aroma is very much hops , but not overly annoying hops . flavor is also quite nice and pleasant , hops are strong and clear , with a mix of the fruit flavors mentioned before and herbal/oily/piney that works pretty well . however , the end of the swallow is like choking on weeds- almost like an alcohol burn , but it 's a hop-oil burn . but other than that , this is a very nice beer .

a - very very dark and rich , although only a tiny bit of brownish head and little to no lacing . s - i did n't catch much of smell , maybe a bit of oatmeal , again not that strong . o - very enjoyable beer .  pours a nearly impenetrable black hue with a one-inch layer of light tan foam that fades away to a lingering bubbly cap that clings easily to the walls of the glass , leaving behind gorgeous well-formed rings of lace as it empties .  mouth feel - mouthfeel was good but nothing special .

very good lacing & super head retention s : piney hops & a little malt t : huge piney & citrussy hops up front with rich cakey maltyness filling in with a little fruittyness as well .  appearance : top marks because i 've never seen a beer so dark ! in a round goblet it looks like a exactly like a black bowling ball .  seriously , is this beer or just a bad soft drink gone bad ... der ? i could n't quite place the smell , but from what i can remember , this is what malta smells like . does n't even resemble malt or beer , just a sickly sweet sort of caramel . i took maybe two sips and gave up . did n't taste like beer , let alone porter , and certainly not like a real baltic porter . waste of $ 2 .

aroma : not particularly aromatic , though raisins and green apple malt suggestions are detectable . drinkability : very drinkable beer , though not as complex and full-flavored as some other belgians i 've drunk recently .  pours a cloudy pale amber with lots of suspension , huge thick white head that reluctantly gave up ground but only to leave behind and enourmous trail of lace , yummy !  this beer has a lower level of carbonation with a slightly flat and watery mouthfeel . overall , this is a good beer with some nice smells and flavors but the mouthfeel is a bit lacking .

aroma is dark caramel , light golden fruit , dry cocoa , and an earthy noble hop notion . flavor is on the mild side foir this style , but still very authentic and tastey .  black with a quarter-inch , creamy brown head that remains . very nice .  the mouthfeel is on the lighter side of medium bodied .

this beer is great . being from ct and living on li its hard to find this beer . my girlfriend and i were up in ct this weekend and found a 4 pack at ct beverage . i 'm happy this beer still exists . i used to be able to get it at my current place of work port jefferson beverage , but there are apparently shortages . i wish that they could brew more .  this one is really , really , really dark ! ! black liquid in a bottle !  m : a hare thin for the style , a bit hi for the carb .

very pithy bitter and yet very smooth and malty at the same time . aroma is not too swell . i would love a citrus and/or tropical fruit blast here , but i 'm just not getting it . the smell of the grain obstructs the hops for sure despite having a pretty on point malty ipa flavor . if sly fox lessened the bittering addition and added a great deal of late additions and dryhops then this would be a well known world class east coast ipa .  the head retention is incredible and keeps a decent layer of foam covering the surface of the beer and the sides of the glass .  the mouthfeel is medium-light , and actually about the only thing in this beer that is sorta ok .

has some aroma , but not very much .  very nice tan head that recedes slowly , leaving decent lacing .  mouthfeel -- nitro has none of the joys of spot on carbonation , and at times the lack of it ruins the drinking .

s - mild aroma , alcohol , vanilla , and roasted malt . t - oakiest of the series it seems .  no joke ... the blackest beer i have ever seen . it is almost actually black . brown head with what seems like a faint reddish hue . i 'm not sure i would have ever guesse this was a stout , imerial or otherwise , but the taste is quite an experience ( understatement ) . a double stout ?  slick mouthfeel is thin for an imperial .

candy sugar aromas , barleywinesque actually . i 'm going to give the last bottle the full treatment , see you in a decade ! smell : malty and sweet , like a nice dipping sauce for chicken -- weird ? maybe .  appearance large fluffy cream colored head with excellent retention .  moutfeel is pretty thin .

upon opening bottle the initial aroma was full of of skunky ammonia note that made me suspect a bottle gone bad . however the skunkiness quickly subsided and left behind a more familiar barnyard funk that you get in the flagship saidon dupont . light honey-like sweetness and some malt backbone can be detected .  pours a beautiful light gold with a one of a kind , thick and frothy white head , most of which will be at the end of your glass upon completion .  nice clean alcohol as it warms or as i feel it ... not sure which is having that effect on the taste : -/ dry , mildly carbonated and very much the viscosity of water .

smells faintly of chocolate malts , a bit roasty or woody i 'd say . overall a very drinkable beer .  a- black with a tiny hint of brown around the very edges with a gigantic creamy-frothy head .  i like this hefe . not as spicy as a schnider but still a good beer . pale/white in color . great wheat head . banana frutiy esthers are not over done .

the smell is similarly nondescript but without any bitterness , which i appreciate .  appearance : this belgian pours a beautiful honeycomb color with well stacked off-white head . lots of beading . very clean and tight appearance .  very little carbonation ( too little as the matter of fact ) . medium bodied ( which is thin for the style ) with almost no carbonation .

the scent was so inviting i could hardly wait to taste it . when i took my first smell of this beer , i was greeted with such a phenomenal scent that i was sure this was going to be one of the best stouts i 've had in a long , long time . however , the taste did not match the scent and i was disappointed . there is a good taste to it , but it just did n't live up to the smell . with a 4.3 % abv , i could see sitting with friends and drinking this in an evening at the pub .  pours an absolutely gorgeous transparent amber-ruby color with a nice , soft tan/white head .  might as well have drank a miller light and put some food coloring in it.poured a dull pink collor with excessive carbonation . tatsed like you would expect a bad pilsner to taste . i would wright more but the opening statement pretty much sums it up .

this bottled batch is about a month old and it seems well made but short on flavor and a little light on body for me.the fizz is good and the lacing is respectable , and it 's pretty to look at , but i keep waiting for more flavor . ab must be doing its research on what it 's customers like , but this one falls short .  welde bru zwickel is a great looking zwickel . it came out to me from the tap with a good two finger thick bright white head , which was very tight and creamy looking .  hops - wheaty/earthy/spicy mf 3.0 medium body on palate , semi watery on finish for an ofest beer d 4.5 - i dig this stuff , the brewer , the facility and the whole vibe .

smell is really faint .  thanks to r moe nay for this one . golden amber body with a nice thick head and lacing . a real beauty here , competes with christina ricci and taryn manning .  initial flavor is very much cream , almost like chocolate milk . low hop flavor does n't get in the way of all the malts . very drinkable beer . while the complex malt profile teases the tongue , it still in some ways is just another cream stout , just a more expensive cream stout . worth a try , but would n't want to spend too much on what could be more affordable in other brands .

also found `` cat-pee '' in the aroma . husband did n't like it as much and ended up adding a dash of raspberry syrup to his , which i tasted and must say was quite nice . instant raspberry wheat beer .  pours a hazy golden orange color with a huge dense whip cream like head . awesome lacing , this is how beer should look . i like more spiciness to my saison but this was still very enjoyable and it looks fantastic .  really yummy - would be great with meat or fish . m..just average here . a bit drying , but not as much as anticipated .

nice , but not very strong . nice , thick mouthfeel and tastes of caramel and hops .  pours a bright , hazy orange with a 2 '' fluffy white head that leaves gorgeous sticky billows on the sides of the glass .  taste & gt ; sweet , full body with a huge punch that softens , leaving in its wake a honey and resin hang . it is delicious mouf & gt ; easy , but not amazing drinkability & gt ; great !
smell is of corn taste is smooth ! a little sweet corn like .  pours a solid black that does n't let any light through .  medium to thin body with smooth mouthfeel .

fresh aroma of citrus and light malts .  12oz bottle to tulip . wow , this is one awesome looking beer . a beautifully dense head capping a brew that is the deepest of amber , with a shine that would make any ruby gemstone jealous . stunning .  m : feels a bit viscous .

light hint of malt and earthy hops evident in smell . good buzz from the abv , another excellent offering from great lakes , but overall not quite as good as last year 's oktoberfest .  pours the deepest black i 've ever seen- not a tinge of amber to be seen around the edges of this glass at all . head lingers , minimal lacing .  m- the mouth was ok , again really unremarkable and watery light .

12 oz . the aroma is fairly muted , but still has enough `` c '' hops to contribute some grapefruit and pine notes . crystal & honey malts lurk in the background , but fail to create much of an impression . excellent finish to the medium-light body , and the carbonation level is beautifully crafted . all in all , a solid pale ale by the talented new belgium staff .  a- the beer pours a dark amber that shows great clarity and a nice change of color with deep ruby tones when held to light .  mouthfeel is a little thin and watery , with a rather low carbonation level .

aroma is mild but pleasant , like a sweeter version of your typical american lager .  the beer pours a deep burnt amber color . this may be one of the most appetizing pours i have ever seen and the aroma grabs my attention too .  m - a little harsh on the palate ; only average part of the beer in my opinion .

it does n't smell so much . slightly malty i suppose . in contrast to how heavy it looks , it 's goes down incredibly smooth and fast . i find it to be the perfect stout , since it 's not so heavy . the drinkability for a stout i 'm not sure can be matched .  a - light caramel color with an extremely rich , dense tan head . stellar head retention .  a light to medium mouthfeel . so drinkable !

aroma was almost negligible ; some smoke and bitter coffee , caramel .  cool little labeled bottle . pours a dark black with just a hint of ruby red with a light tan head .  light in body , almost thin , the carbonation is nice a little light though .

s : light notes of chocolate , alcohol , raisins , and a splash of coffee .  this poured a gorgous hazy burgundian brown with a nice creamy tan head . the head looks like a root beer float , lots of craters and variation in bubble size . kinda cool . this beer does kick your ass via alcohol but it lacks the flavor that i would think it would need to have to justify the stellar rankings it has gotten .  m : light as it gets . crisp , refreshing beer . overall : light beers are why i thought i did n't like beer in my early drinking days .

the waiter had it described as an `` english-style session ale '' and their website has a mild ale listed as available right now . i got the abv from my server . i should also offer the caveat that this is only the second cask ale i 've ever had . i did n't get too much on the nose ... just some butter and bittering hops . it was everything this yank ( i admit i do n't know as much about cask ales or mild ales as other bas , but i 'm trying to learn ) would look for in a sessionable ale .  the appearance is a beautiful honey brown that calls my name and says `` drink me .  mouthfeel seems dominated but a fast carbonation , over a thin to medium liquid .

smells toasty and malty . not a strong smell however .  poured a really dark ruby red to blood red color , from a 650 ml bottle , with abv on the label . visually this beer is almost close to stunning . massive two finger foamy frothy head that dissipates slowly and leaves some really nice lace . for some reason there is uneven distribution of the head , with a lot of it ending up at one end of the surface . good head retention though .  while this beer did n't disappont me it did n't meet my expectations of it . of course being a hophead rarely can a beer more hoppier than usual surprise me . it did have more hops than the average beer drinker would prefer imo . the taste was hoppy yet with a good malty balance . went well with the food and was very drinkable ... ... ... ... ..cheers

i had this on cask , gravity pour , day two of being opened . there was n't a specific aroma that stuck out easily , which i found surprising for a double ipa . aside from the basic citrus and pine smell , there really was n't much else coming through to the nose . overall , it went down quite easily , was very smooth , enjoyable and packed a wallop : ) i had two 20oz imperial pints .  the most impressive aspect is the head , which is cloud-like in texture , and tenacious in retention .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but not exceedingly so .

the smell was great ! cherries and banana were apparent along with tropical sweet fruits . the taste was almost as good as the smell . bitterness from the hops will be more diminished with time but are a nice addition to the young product .  immense , extremely fine , slightly sticky , bright white head settles slowly to a complete , rocky cap leaving good lacing . great looking beer !  taste while similar tends to be swayed by the aggressive mouthfeel . one thing i did n't like too much is the cakey dry mouthfeel that leaves a coat to remember .

had this in bottle after a trip to my local beer store . honestly this was hard to drink..very malty , with a very heavy alcohol taste . if you want to start on a lagunitas brew i suggest hop stoopid .  huge light-tan head that is creamy , stays , and sticks . beautiful , although surprisingly pitch-black body for a porter .  i love octoberfest beers and i love flying dog , i think they are one of the best micro 's around . their version of the octoberfest is not anything impressive but it is pretty tasty . you may drink one and not like it , but give it a second try . it has a great taste and has great drinkability for those fall football days .

this a very dark for a marzen , almost brown . this beer is very drinkable , very tasty with a noticably pleasant mouthfeel . the hops are noticable but very well balanced , though i personally prefer marzens with a dry hopped aftertaste . last week i had numous grey lodge patrons tell me how much they loved this beer .  pours black with a nice two-finger , dense , tan head .  disclaimer : i do n't drink yellow beer very often . started out my evening with one of these , as one of my friends who prefers a sharp pils to just about anything else has had very positive things to say about this beer . overall , this was drinkable , and had a surprisingly noticable saaz hop flavoring to it . at the same time , the sourness left on the palate reminded me of why i do n't venture into euro-lager/pils land too often . but , i still enjoyed this beer , and would have it again if i was feeling pilsy .

there 's no aroma to speak of , perhaps some maltiness , but nothing remarkable . along those lines , it has a sweet taste to it , and very mild hops .  poured into a dfh tulip , formed a 1 1/2 '' beige head above the slightly cloudy golden amber brew . meringuey head is n't going anywhere fast , snow-coning above the rim , with tons of hunky lasting lace .  had this beer tonight at the flying saucer , fort worth , texas , on the `` buy the beer , keep the glass '' night . i may be biased a little here due to my liking for whit biers , wheat beers , and hefe-weizens , or it may be that i got there before the `` buy the beer , keep the glass '' night oficially started at 7:00pm and drank a guinness while i waited , but i really liked this beer . my server brought out a 500ml weizen glass from the brewery , and a 500ml bottle of beer . the label states it was bottle-fermented , so the proper hefe-weizen pour ( pour 7/8 of it , swirl the bottle to rouse the yeast , dump it on top ) was required .

huge mountains of finely packed bubbles , on top of a sandy amber sediment heavy beer.hops noted in the nose . on taste starts bitter and grassy , transitions smoothly into malt and carmal then slides back into dry.a real nice beer . this beer has a real classic ale flavour to it and the body is about perfect .  a billowing , almost beligian-esque head crowns the oracle . head is brilliant white , almost bleach white and made up entirely of tight carbonation bubbles .  in terms of the mouthfeel of the beer , that 's probably the best point . the carbonation is what you 'd expect of a macro beer , and rather well-balanced .

s- bubblegum , citrus ( grapefruit ) . bubblegum maybe at first but then morphs into a few different things mid-swig . perfume tasting ( ? ) , check . m- actually the mouthfeel is n't that bad but it was really hard to focus on that while i was drinking joan rivers perfume .  a : pours a brilliant clear gold , foamy white head , lots of lacing , great retention s : nose is chock full of fresh wet hops , notes of pine , resin , and earthiness come through , biscuit malts come in in the middle t : taste features brisk hop bitterness up front , some juicy fruit quality comes through in the middle along with malts , the finish is bitter .  this beer pours a crystal clear red-orange jewel with a thin , frothy white head that 's mostly diminishing . the aroma is like sweet baked goods in the oven ... maybe apple crisp ? once in the mouth , the medium-bodied ale starts with the twang on malt that turns into green apple and perhaps melon ... with the slightest hop bite to set it off . it has a very fresh , bright aftertaste of small , shiny green apples . nice ! ( rated jan 30 , 2007 )

an off grainy , buttery , and dms cooked veggie nose .  the brew looks gorgeous when poured into the chalice i drank it in - almost a ruby color .  tastes hoppy but much smoother and more nuanced than expected . this is not your average hop bomb even if it claims to be . it 's a little blah on the pallat though .

awful , awful beer . one of the worst beers i 've ever paid good money for .  picture-perfect beer -- dull cloudy gold with an immense pillow of sticky , long-lasting lace .  m - pretty light bodied and real smooth . this is probably the weakest part of this beer .

s : light mineral and cola aromas with roasted malt , chocolate , and coffee all contributing but nothing overwhelming . hops are mild and earthy .  a - pitch black with a wonderful , creamy tan head . very good head retention and lovely lacing on the glass . this is a very appetising beer .  m- a little thin and watery with little carbonation .

sweet , boozy aroma with a bit of spice .  i would normally hate to say anything bad about my favorite domestic beer company , but this scotch ale was simply a huge disappointment . it pours a beautiful dark amber , which would lead me to believe i was about to enjoy another wonderful sam adams ale , but that is not the case .  nice clear beer . they filter well at this brewery . the taste is caramel notes finishing with hops on the tongue . is this a winter warmer asks the alstrom brothers ? i think not . a drinkable red ale that delivers the goods .

s : sweet malty and wheat smell . flat , one-note , and clean . kind of reminds me of the smell of a rainy day . t : lightly roasted barley and some kettle corn sweetness , dry toast and apricot .  champagne-like in appearance , clear gold and effervescent , with a billowy , perfectly white head .  the mouthfeel is really thin and i just ca n't get over that , unfortunately .

after the initial sip the chocolate stands out the most , especially in the smell . surprising for an english bitter .  pours ruby amber ( pure ruby when held to the light ) with a thick beige head . getting good lacing and some rings .  the hop that is there sure is pretty t - so much different than the smell . a really sweet malted barley starts up front and than a boat load of citrus , pine and floral hops punches the malt in the groin grassy and loads of citrus m - light , but not unpleasant and actually it is super nice .

did n't have time to stop at the local store that sells micros so i picked up 4 of these they were the same price as the same old same old irish stout and i would always rather try something new.. the color is black but when put to a light is more of a very dark ruby red..i do n't think there is much room for it to improve on the look of the brew as far as a stout goes its pretty much perfect ... .if i was disappointed with anything its that i did n't smell much maybe roast with a sweet scent that i cant quite make out -- but basically very plain smelling-the taste was very good coffee and cream but not to bitter like some stouts get a touch of bitterness in the end very similar to guiness but oh so much better mouthfeel almost like a milk stout- i think the feel of this brew is perfect so so creamy makes me want to keep on drinking them ... definitely my nice fav nitro beer when i cant find a micro to drink .  a : perfectly clear reddish golden , great frothy white head with superb lacing .  as far as feel goes , it was a little bit light . the flavor was pleasantly intense , but it ended up feeling a smidge watery . however , with that less substantial body came superior drinkability .

smell was wonderful , a sweet caramel and lots of malt .  nice dark between black and red color .  mouthfeel is a little dry once you kill one or two of these bad boys , but the taste and smell definitely makes up for it .

the aroma ... what aroma . it 's very muted with only remote grains and citrus to be found if you 're part bloodhound . overall it seems like the only time i rave about pale ales is when they creep in to ipa territory , but if you 're looking for something a little more pedestrian you could do a lot worse than this .  a : just like it 's sibling , a beautiful beer . a rocky ivory head with very good retention very nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin , with the alcohol running to the back of the throat .

aroma is light , some tart sourness you can pick up but really not much at all . very smooth drink and tasty , you could easily drink a lot but it could easily also have some more robust traits .  `` bottled on 10-04-04 '' `` best before 10-03-09 '' fantastic pour , leaves a huge head which slowly morphs to a rocky , puffy 1/4 inch irregular head , leaves truly world class lacing , at once wispy , puffy and very clinging .  the mouthfeel is a bit light for the style , though drinkability is excellent considering the abv .

intriguing . taste : hmmm , it kind of tastes like seltzer water in a way that only michelob ultra has before .  poured a dark black/brown with a light tan head , a solid two fingers thick that lingered for a little while then faded quickly .  had a pint glass of this from the bottle . a-gem brown , rocky beige head , very dense . s-malty , metallic and some vanilla t-smoky , malt front , snap pea flavor in the middle , and some hop bitterness at the end . very little vanilla flavor at all m-medium d-very little vanilla flavor to this brew . the other competing flavors were some what off-putting

this beer was much darker than i anticipated . this beer smelled a little confused i thought . it did not smell quite balanced to me .  brew poured to a very deep brown with a large brown head that broke down slowly and lead to incredible lacing through out the brew . the brew is all about the malt , as the roasted malt and caramel flavor overwhelms the nose with a little fruit sweetness that is also detectable .  the mouthfeel is thus fairly thin , but finishes with a nice clean dryness .

i have to give it a 5 because of that head , unseen for an american micro , let alone a spiced pale ale ! smell is on the soft side , ginger and tropical fruits .  bottle ( 2011 ) k & b wine cellars san diego , ca a dark as night pour but with some dark ruby edges along the edge . big and thick , persistent , chocolate milk head . leaves the glass supremely messy .  even though its a little thin , i consider this the tastiest beer i have ever had . ) that makes your mouth water . except for my homebrew , i have never tasted anything like this in a beer . it almost tasted like grapefruit juice with lots of hop flovor and not much in bitterness .

s : smells mildly skunked . t : tastes very similar to smell . d : beyond the skunk , i could probably put quite a few of these away . very nice .  the beautiful , thick head thins out and is resilient as the beer is consumed , but remains a calm product of the perfectly balanced carbonation . very rich with the alcohol well hidden .  mouthfeel is defined by the linger dry bitter booze burn between each sip , it 's not very pleasant maybe even a bit abrasive . medium bodied hop oils textured with moderate carbonation , probably the biggest turn off so far .

the aroma was not much , a little hoppy and sugary but nothing else that stood out as a flavor . the taste was quite yeasty and pulled off a belgium flavor . overall , the beer needs to age and create a distinct pangea characteristic , but i enjoyed what i tasted at the moment and look forward to see how it develops .  here it goes : even without the nitro , the head rises nicely and the retention is excellent .  bottled september 2007 , batch 02565. pours oil like , midnight black with a thin brown head , and some lacing . smell is of cocoa , wheat , some vanilla , and a touch of caramel in the back . taste is a little flat , cocoa , vanilla , a little smoke , some nuts , and slight coffee , ends on the dry side .

a-pours smooth medium straw color with creamy white head . s-crisp malt sweetness intermingled with some hop spice , light caramel malt aroma light on the nose . t-clean malt sweetness apple , pear , light caremel malt , nice mellow malt flavor with lingering light spicy hop bitterness in the finish .  can ( 2011 ) holiday wine cellar escondido , ca clear amber throughout with golden honey edges and a thick and sticky off-white lace that leaves spiderwebs and sheets of lace down the glass . gorgeous .  mouthfeel could be a bit smoother , as the beer has a slight syrupy note as it slides down the tongue .

s : a very interesting aroma that grew on me substantially by the end of the glass . absolutely unique , pungent , and oustanding .  a : pours a beautiful black that has a wonderful bubbly light brown display that turn into the creamy head of tiny tiny bubbles . one nice looking beer .  the only thing i mark this beer down for was it mouthfeel . i tought it had a very light mouthfeel and certainly no creaminess .

the smell is light and not all that complex . imo , many of rogue 's offerings have very average smells , but are extremely tasty brews .  the pour was very promising . it showed yellow and mud colors and erected a noisy , tall , baby swiss cheese-patterned head .  i find it rather thin for the style . carbonation is borderline too high d : this is a very smooth drinking beer with a very minimal alcohol presence .

that being said , this is a fantastic smelling beer . pineapple upside down cake all the way , with huge sweet bready notes , caramel , tart cherries , some raisin , and , implausibly , tropical fruit . the aroma really impressed me and i love bready beers .  a : pours a clear deep golden with 2 fingers worth of white creamy head . settles to a finger thick head the entire time and leaves thick walls of lace all over the glass . about the only good thing about them is the appearance of the beer which is perfect .  m : medium and dry but a bit watery .

the smell is pretty mild , without a ton of hop aroma .  appearance : pours a hazy orange-gold color with a very large , fluffy white head that dissipates very slowly , leaving behind lots of thick ring of lace with some spots above it , and a layer of head that remains on top of the beer .  grapefruit and pine explode on the palate with a great full bitterness for a floral and slight cookie finish that is fairly dry . full prickly carbonation , though a tad on the lighter side in body , the only issue that prevents this beer from being a straight up `` a '' quality .

s- i get some funky vinegar scent with the booze and roasted malt . i hope i did n't get a bad bottle .  the head is a monster . i am looking at about 3.5 fingers of amber / tan head . the retention is fantastic . the lacing on my glass is like pancake batter . a visual treat for the beer lover in me .  the mouthfeel is a thick , sweet molasses that coats the mouth and seems to hide some of the flavors if it is n't sipped and had with food .

appearance : dark amber with a small head aroma : slightly hoppy and with a little citrus . not a strong smelling beer , i had to work to get a smell palate : grassy with citrus ; floral ; bitter finish that feels good on the ol ' mouth .  great guinness like , nitro-tap head . excellent retention and lacing .  positively wretched . mouthfeel : light-bodied . medium carbonation .

a very nice smell for a dry irish stout .  the beer poured very nicely into a pint mug : an amber brown colour with a decent off white head that displayed excellent retention and showed good lacing all the way down the glass .  m - this one coasts all the way down .
a really good smelling wit . in general , this was a good beer .  looks damn good .  thin watery mouthfeel with a medium dose of carbonation .

feh . skunky and foul smelling .  i 'm not sure if it 's the condition of this bottle , or the way it was poured , but this brew is one of the most visually appealing i 've ever encountered . it 's settled nicely at about a half inch , leaving some terrific icicle lacing . ( and the glass looks terrific as well ... )  the mouthfeel is ok does n't really stick to your mouth , but the taste lastes awhile .

faint whiff of malt and clove are all i get . slightly flowery . quite a bite to it , though , despite the weak nose .  a perfect pour of a midnight black brew with a deep brown head on top that leaves sheets of lace all over the glass as the burnt 6000 mile oil is consumed .  mouthfeel is a little more thin than one would like but i think that is part of what makes this beer extremely drinkable as it leaves the mouth feeling clean .

great smell . t : lots of roasted and dark malt , not as much chocolate , but still good . tastes more beer like than i expected as well . pretty good and surprisingly full-flavored .  it was a beautiful bright golden yellow color with a very malty nose .  it is very drinkable but a little light in body .

s - smells like most beers from a green bottle . not good .  the head is a generous 3 '' of slightly yellow , foamy , craterous head . it has excellent retention and leaves plenty of spidery lace on the glass . a picturesque beer .  aroma- light alc . smell , tons of clove ( well for me @ least ) maple is right on the nose , sweet potato , pumpkin . i do n't know if the beer is barrel aged but i get hints of oak and maybe sherry . a very drinkable fall brew , for a 10 % plus brew .

not much smell but a little malt . tastes of smooth malt . extremely drinkable . i would love to see this on cask .  body is the color of marmalade , and frantic streams of carbonation can be seen supporting and replenishing the excellent retention .  smooth porter richness nicely balanced with light hops m : a bit thin for my taste but fits with the balance and delicacy of the flavor d : balanced flavors and delicate mouthfeel make this a very drinkable porter ; i definitely want another

s - burnt/roasted malts , dry fruits , chocolate , a whiff of an open field . t - toasty , malty , cocoa powder , bit of coffee , and a little sweetness .  a - pitch black , one finger light brown head , nice lacing .  i had a bottle of this at the church street deli and pub in swansboro , nc . the straw smell of the beer which is one possibility for pilsner really stands out and is more enjoyable than many pilsners . there is almost a light fruity sweetness about the flavor . i would probably call this a `` straightforward '' beer , but there are enough tantalizing things going on in the nose and the flavor to keep you sniffing-sipping , sniffing-sipping . i am not typically a pilsner drinker and i found this one to be quite enjoyable . this sight lists it as an american blonde , and while i wo n't get cantankerous as i do n't have a bottle in front of me , i swear it said `` pilsner '' somewhere on the label . it would n't be the first time i got tricked by a label though .

smells unexceptional with a pretty bland nose that has a wet burnt malt smell to it .  1pt 0.9 oz bottle poured into weihenstephaner glass a : very dark brown almost black , with a big tan colored head . wonderful lacing s : great smells here .  the dark fruit and roasted malts really come out in the taste , bit of marshmellow as well but it has a rather average mouthfeel and the ash flavor i detected in the smell just lingers a bit too much .

s : slightly disappointing aroma . actually it smells a lot like a heineken .  superior head retention & lacing s : bready with wet grain , grassy hops as well t : grassyness , crackery & lemony notes up front .  m- actually a little thinner than i would prefer o- really good , surprising beer .

3.0 s : caramel , toasty , and nutty malts . not bad , just a bit too weak . the nose turned out to be deceptive . 4.0 d : a good beer masquerading as a bad one . the appearance offers not much to look at while the aroma barely shows up at the party .  appearance - black body with about 2 inches of medium tan head that offers a very nice lacing .  i would like a bit more carbonation to match the style better .

as it warms the smell becomes more integrated . unique and awesome aroma . t - taste is great - strong hazlenut/wallnut flavor , but well blended with roasty malts and some chocolate sweetness .  poured beautifully pale orange cloudy with a great two finger head which has slowly fallen into a nice lacing over the top .  12oz bottle with `` best by '' date of 3/30/05 , i tasted on 7/29/05 . aroma is citrous and very nice . bitterness is low , but fits very well with the malt profile . althought this bottle may have degraded somewhat by age , i 'm guessing fresh from the keg this would really be something special .

of course it lacked most any noticable quality beer flavors but just as well nothing tasted bad to note either . its basically the same as coors and miller lights , which i have no real trouble drinking either . of the 3 macro lights i 'd rank this one slighty less than coors and about equal to miller .  this pours a black body with ruby highlights with a huge billowy tan head that leaves chunks of lacing .  fairly light and chalky in the mouth , adequate carbonation . just a bit watery feeling to me , still at about a medium body .

smell is of dark fruit , raisin , plum leather , dark cherry and belgian yeast . not a bad brew but pretty one dimensional and slightly bland from a brewery of their caliber .  i had a higher expectation of this beer being a stout drinker and all .  watery iced tea body with some carbonation .

the nose is like the black lager -- i swear , ballpoint pen ink and manure , plus a sour twang and a grassy undertone . the taste is quite different from the aroma and conflicts with it .  the head was tan , retained beautifully as a cap and left sheets of thick lacing .  m : medium body , medium carbonation , extremely oily in texture , it literally coats your tongue leaving a somewhat sticky finish .

smells of ... i hate to say it ... but cat piss ... with a bit oh honey .  a- pours a booming three-fingered white head atop a dark amber beer into a tulip . effervescence aplenty ! great head retention and thick lacing .  mouthfeel : medium , oddly very neutral .

a- dark purple color , non-trasparent , thin light purple head that faded to a thin ring around the glass s- light malts , grains , mild hops , hint of blueberries t- sour , blueberries , tangy , syrup , fizzy , grainy sugar , slightly sweet finish m- light/medium body , medium/heavy carbonation , strongly resembles soda d- not worth buying when i first poured this beer into a glass i thought i had somehow bought grape soda ( but i can get past the look ) . the auroma is not too bad at all but i really do n't know where they were going for on the flavor . by far the worst blueberry beer i 've ever encountered .  a - appearance was by far the high point of this beer ... very beautiful ! perfect in this respect .  medium-light bodied , a bit spritzy ( somewhat soda-like ) , and not quite creamy . lightly warming from the abv .

s- resiny hops , light grainy backbone . d- this is certainly my favorite new belgium beer thus far .  25 appearance : poured an opaque , golden , yellow with a very impressive and thick head that just sat and sat and sat . excellent lacing followed , covering a good 50 % of the opposite side of the glass .  fairly full with a decent body , but does feel a bit watery for a 7.5 % drop . slick , i would say , but a bit thinner than i would like given the flavours .

smell - none other than the glorious pacman yeast is the dominant aroma here , and not much else . although pacman yeast is one of my favorite things to smell in a beer , i ca n't give it higher than 3 because it lacks other wonderful aromas . taste - light sweetness from the malt balanced out by a crisp , citrusy hop kick for the finish .  great job with carbonation and a meringue-like head . golden body is soothing in appearance , translucent , but hazy if you pitch the trub into the glass from the bottle bottom .  m : thinner and not as heavy as i would have assumed from the appearance and smell , still leaning toward a medium feel however . very pleasant . d : the thinner than expected mouth feel and very smooth taste make this a very session-able porter .

not much nose to speak of.. just a whisp of roast in the back of the throat . very roasty malty taste with hints of expresso on the back of the tongue . a solid dry stout.. the only area it was lacking was in the nose .  appearance is damn amazing , has lots of floating bubbles and does stay fresh along time after pourn into chimay cup .  m- light and watery - not much body at all d- smooth finish i recommend this one on taste alone .

pours a nice red/copper color with meium head that leaves some great lacing , the aroma is almost non existant with a slight powdered sugar smell.the tast is pretty complex malty sweet with a tast of candied sugar as the backbone alcihol is prevalent in the finish wich is nice and warming.a real nice malty beer , very impressed .  first thing is the absolute massive duvel-esque head that forms with even the softest pour . it 's really quite beautiful floating atop the cloudy peach body of this brew and though it does dissipate in time , it still leaves a huge dimple filled marshmallow island and sporadic lacing everywhere and for the duration of the session .  yes , burnt , they did n't just roast , they turned the malts almost into charcoal . i ca n't say i really like this burnt aftertaste . it is too bad , because it could otherwise potentially be a very nice beer . the burnt flavor overpowers the hops , so i ca n't say anything about them .

served just a touch cold the aroma is relatively dull . instead , we get what i assume australian grown noble hops with their slightly citrusy , tropical notes .  has a beauitiful mahogany color that 's just dark enough to only be able to see silhouettes on the other side of the glass . the reddish white head is creamy and fluffy and rubs itself all up on the sides of the glass .  i 've been just over a year now getting to know all different kinds of beers , so with this being my first official review please bare with me . the smell was probably what the minimum should be for a good pils . i very much enjoyed the crisp hoppy tast which lingered in my mouth for a bit . i would say that being one who tends to lean towards the darker and more bitter , i was pleasantly suprised and do intend on purchasing prima in the futer .

the smells alittle on the light side with some hops , sweet malt , and bread yeast .  body is a deep , clear gold . great looking beer !  mouth feel is sharp and crisp with an average carbonation level . overall , a good appearance and aroma , but the dryness hurts the feel a little .

nose shows lots of roasted malt with plenty of chocolate notes . simple but nice , that chocolate character is amazing . very similar flavours , nice and light with little roasty bitterness .  a- pours a deep , dark brownish hue with a nice , 2 finger frothy head .  m : decently carbonated and has a little bite .

i did n't pick up much in the way of smell , to be honest . tastes of brown sugar and maybe a little dates or molasses .  the archetypal stout color ebony , the head planetary in size , creamy texture and the lace fine sticky sheets to cling to the glass , a nice light chocolate color for both .  mouthfeel is a bit heavy and thick , leaves your mouth a bit syrupy .

light aroma with some spice & phenols .  this beer pours a dark polished brown color ... like deep dark wood flooring . two fingers of off-tan foam that laces evenly and soft .  the only dissapointment was that it was deffinitely thinner on the tongue than the pour led me to believe .

nice , solid brown body with a one-finger off-white head ... hardly opaque , with the faintest light at the glass 's bottom ... light , almost nonexitstent aroma -- some malts , but otherwise nondescript -- on purpose ? mellow , softly nestling effervescent in the teeth ... presence is substantial ... chewy , definitely nutty ... surprsingly 33 ibus as the hops are not up front ... pleasantly flavorful with a malty breath late ... `` pacman yeast '' ?  appearance : a gorgeous , clear golden hue , with a big , frothy , foamy head , and possibly the stickiest lacing i 've ever seen . scatters the light beautifully - just stunning .  taste : starts with a sweetness that is cut by the carbonation . mouth : smooth carbonation not harsh drink : its malty start and earthy bitterness makes this beer more enjoyable the flavor from the finish and the start mix quite well .

pretty mild on the nose , some faint caramel and grassy/citrus notes .  stellar tan head atop a dark body . lots of retention and lacing .  finish is dry and clean . body is light , waifish , bubbly . acidity is a little much on the back of the throat ; unpleasant bite . decent beer ; mild complexity and somewhat challenging .

s - chocolatey goodness ... no booze in the nose despite the 11 % . nothing hugely complex or mind boggling , but a wonderful example of the style .  a : slightly cloudy , light orange/peach color . thick , fluffy head with great retention .  the mouthfeel initially struck me as too thin for a bock , and so i recommend letting it warm up some .

when i was pouring the beer , even before directly smelling the beer i could pick up some sweet amber malts . when i followed this up with an actual sniff the beer smelled quite light , with some light malts and some chocolate flavors .  looks great ! s : it smells ... like a pilsner ?  mouthfeel : light to medium , but i swallowed as quick as possible to stop the overload .

smell- dark fruit and yeast , not much of either . very pleasant . mouthfeel- light , smooth carbomation and a very creamy bodied .  great retention and spectacular lacing . hazu and enticing . awesome .  feel is light-medium bodied , a bit watery and low on carbonation .

consumed 3/19/11 appearance : cloudy golden yellow/orange , starts off with a nice head , retains some nice lacing smell : rather uninteresting - some wheat funk , some subtle fruity esters taste : wheat malts , some fruits in the background including citrus and banana , an interesting creaminess , something resembling nuts - tastes very simple , clean , and incredibly unoffensive - not an exciting beer , but an amazing summer beer mouthfeel : light to medium body , very smooth , very effervescent carbonation overall : extremely drinkable , but not bold in any way to be honest , this is one of my favorite american pale wheat ales .  poured from its 16.9oz bottle into my snifter a crisp clean amber color with an incredibly thick off-white head that had tons of bubbles in it and held together very well .  light bodied , a bit thin , with a clove-like wheat-ness and a tingly orange peel backdrop . i do not like buying any wheat beer without a freshness date on it but ayingers ' are great no matter . this weizen is nothing to snub , however , as it is an enjoyable beer anytime of the season !

slight hoppiness to the nose with a mild sweetness .  a-this looks awesome , it is a dark hazy red looking like a thick deep color of blood , seriously it does , i did n't even realize the name when i thought it looked like blood . the head is a dark tan , almost a woody brown . it is thick and creamy , tight , with huge retention and a thick lace that pretty much coats everything it touches s-bready malts are strong up front and have a real presence .  mouthfeel is thin to medium bodied with plenty of carbonation .

i love the smell ! the nose is sweet almost in a hard candy type of way . the attack is smooth and easy with the hops casually presentint itself in the flavor . its worth drinking for sure , but man , that nose steals the show .  it had a great pour from the can and it looked great . a nice head that lasted and almost pitch black .  the waimea brewing company sits on an incredible piece of property on the southern end of kaua'i and is worth searching out after exploring the waimea canyon area . i came in parched and wanted to save my taste buds for a tasty-looking ipa the bartender was pouring so i started with a thirst quenching cane fire red . the red pours with a generous inch-tall creamy eggshell-colored head that dissipates to an eighth-of-an-inch with incredible lacing . cane fire red throws a malty nose with surprising yeast notes . on first sip , the crystal malts come to the forefront and are followed by a spicy hop finish . this beer is dangerously quaffable and just the ticket after a day spent in the island sun .

got some of this on a whim . great golden color . i figured there would have been a reddish hue but did n't really notice any . nice hint of cherrys with a hint of the malty nirvana to come . great taste not a strong cherry overtone like i expected good malt taste . good mouthfeel again this is a great session beer . great session beer its on the rotation in my beer fridge  a-very dark and cloudy amber with a good amount of light tan head that stays , along with lacing .  it was crisp and refreshing , with hints of earthy clove and allspice.. similar notes on the nose . very clean flavors overall , and highly drinkable . i would highly recommend , as it seems this beer is the best of it 's style .

s - primarily a combination of roasted and smoked flavors on the nose . perhaps the trifecta is rounded out with some hints of coffee . t - starts off light with some acidic notes combined with a hair of bitterness .  pours a dark , dark brown with reddish highlights . combined with the the textbook lacing , i must say this beer looks perfect .  mouthfeel : a little thin then what i prefer for the style , but that does add to its drinkability .

s- no smell really to speak of , maybe a little nutty t-absolutely surprised , this tasted fantastic . nutty , not really bitter in my opinion so it was a bit of surprise from the style .  great look to it .  m - medium bodied but very thin and watery overall , even for a cask pull .

smells of coffee heaven , with big dark roast notes . it 's a solid coffee stout .  appearance - beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel is on the light side and i sort of wished for a more solid feel but it 's still good .
aroma is light grain , some hops .  it poured a very dark color with nice head and had a good roasted smell .  the mouthfeel is a bit harsh and overcarbonated .

as the pint is lifted , the aroma grabs your nose and twists it into a question mark as it tries to sort out what lurks below . the smoke is subdued , though , about a third of the intensity of a traditional deutsch rauchbier , allowing the rich malty aroma to come through on its own merits . hop aromas are minimal .  ) a : pours golden orange with a massive 3 finger head , white and extremely tight with great retention .  it has a slightly flat mouthfeel in the beginning but this seems to diminish as the beer warms .

aroma rather weak as well , i detect malt with a sweet citrus background , but that 's about it .  bottle into pint glass : a : beautiful medium-to-dark brown hazy body with good , creamy head . great , thick cap .  the alcohol starts to peep through on the finish but is in check m : the body on the finish is a little thin for my liking but the carbonation is pleasant and tingling d : this is very very drinkable for the abv

the nose is very nice . aromas of spiced carrot cake and a hint of caramel are what i pick up , and oh yeah that 's good .  vernon sampled to keep me warm during sunday 's st. patrick 's day parade pours a deep dark brown/black that was fairly opaque with a bit of reddish highlights . had a thick off-white head that lasted forever and left beautiful lacing down my plastic imperial pint .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with carbonation being high .

that 's a compliment . crisp and clean as a dark beer can be , but all that without sacrificing the full taste and body of a dark , dark beer . mmmm . i learned to drink beer on kstritzer , and i learned to love beer with klsch and this beer falls right in the middle of the two . mmmm lecker !  i love a brown ale that 's solid , dark brown . it tells me it 's a serious dark beer without being guinness .  its major drawback is that it seems to lack a thing called flavour . now light beer is bound to have some downsides , but why bother to drink any alcohol if this is what you get . a have run out of positives for crappy beer i am afraid .

taste is hoppy , reminds me of an english ipa . good strong matly backbone with some light hops .  strtebeker stark-bier produces large amounts of milk chocolaty head that forms together into sticky clumps.. the body is pitch black , with only a slight hint of amber hues penetrating through the base of my beer glass .  t - hot taste slides into apricots and almost melts back to the hop taste on the back end m - some lingering meld of both tastes , but nothing spectacular d - i could drink this all day !

not much aroma . the taste is great with some hoppy bitterness in the middle .  this brew pours a cloudy blood red color . the head is large is flufy and off-white . the lacing is long lasting and thorough .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and is slightly watery .

pours a normal color , copper with little or no head , but the smell is atrocious , i literally gagged . what am i getting myself into i thought , it smells like mildew and foot cheese , with some kind of wierd fruit in it , i dont know what to say .  pours a dark brown colour with thick tan head .  m/d : a medium body with a high amount of carbonation . thin and watery .

smell- a very soft matly smell . taste- it has a rostaed almost like carmael taste to it . very good i could drink this all day long .  a-very dark brown with a nice thick tan head s-malty , creamy , some hops and some roasted chocolate smell .  m - easily he goes down giving a scrape along the way at the roof of my mouth and outsides of my tongue . ~ i like this brew .

the smell is subdued , but pleasant . caramel and wood are right up-front .  great head with strong bubbles and thick lacing . one of the best looking amber hued red ales i 've had .  it does have a crisp flavor and mouthfeel to it . lucayan lager if you can find it .
smell is hoppy and steamy ? !  a- black as they come with a great creamy brown head .  mouthfeel : very smooth , but a little more carbonation than i would like to see .

the beer hints of malt and partial alcohol ( smells like a nice macro lager to be blunt ) .  appearance is outstanding . dried sugary fruit seems to be the most dominant of smells .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied and kind of watery .

a - hazy , redish-amber , thick , light tan head , creamy , lace is already sticking to the sides s - big typical barleywine smell , not much left for hop aroma , but clean , with thick carmel malt , nutty , lucious , really good t - more of that straight ahead , nutty carmel , dense maltiness , not much hop flavour , bitterness is med , though the alcohol accentuates it in the finish , lingering , nutty , bready aftertaste , though the alcohol is somewhat in the way m - medium body is just about right , smooth , somewhat creamy , alcohol burn seems a little much ( this is an aged bottle ) d - a very solid barleywine , just a little too much alcohol flavour and burn for my liking the alcohol presence really detracts from what is otherwise an outstanding brew .  apperance : the dreadnaught is an amber orange , and reminds me of leaves in the fall . a beautiful beer just to look at .  thin body , light carbonation .

nose is a bit herbal , almost earthy , alongside a raw-grain-like super-pale malt note .  pours opaque black with a cappuccino head that you could stand a match in , and which leaves chunks of lace and sheets of foam .  this brew is just a little too carbonated for the style , and not as smooth as most british brands .

375 ml green champagne bottle with cork , cage and foil presentation ; bottled february 1 , 2008 . its surprisingly mild aroma contributes lemons , malt and a dash of funk .  poured into a pilsner glass , it 's the darkest ale i 've seen yet .  medium to thick body , spirited level of carbonation , sweet bubbly mouthfeel . that said , i would have like it a bit lighter on the carbonation .

unfortunately , i could n't smell much , but i could definately taste .  big thick white head . good head retention . excellent lacing , a thick sheet of lace was left behind on the side of the glass .  mouthfeel : surprisingly lighter body than i expected ... the beer version of a meringue ? the lighter body makes it a bit easier to have more of this than a similar stout .

the beer was extremely heavy on the nose with raspberries . my wife and i both mentioned that as much as the smell might excite the senses , the taste equally disappoints .  it poured a hazy light golden color with an amazingly fluffy head that stayed and stayed .  mouthfeel is competent . worse than corona .

s - very clean and dry . ca n't separate overall sour note into distinct cherry or sour ale aromas , but the combined effcet is strong indeed .  a : copper brown , fluffy cream head with great lacing .  mouthfeel is a little thin which is my only complaint but other than that this beer is great .

mmmm ... dms . smells like the water you discard after you boil veggies . some herbal hops sneak in as well as some pale malts . a decent hop kick starts out before its overtaken by some pale malts and a slightly bitter/herbal finish .  awesome looking beer that compliments the season .  a-fingers worth of off-white/eggshell head , clear light brown color with some hues of orange , some light lacing throughout the glass s-unfortunately i am getting over a cold so my nose isnt going to be up to snub , from what i can gather though , the citra and falconer hops seem to jump right out , a lot of citrrus and tropical fruit characteristics come out in the nose , also some resinous pine , and bready malts t-really nice balance of flavors here , starts out with dry and malty , that signature grainy , earthy half acre flavor here , it then moves to the citrus flavors highlighted by a very nice grapefruit character m-a little thin , but not crazy watery , has good carbonation that comes off almost grainy d-really liked it , it didnt blow me away like the first time i drank daisy cutter , but this is another solid addition to half acre 's arsenal , hopefully we will see this become a seasonal or even a year round

the aroma is a bit bitter , and a bit of coffee , but the wife says `` still smells like beer to me ! decent aroma , but nothing great , it seems to diminish the longer the beer is in the glass . a good mass-produced stout .  poured mostly opaque black with red edges and a huge tan head and nice lacing .  a roasted and smoky taste at first with a watery finish . a light bubbly body makes this brown very drinkable .

overall fairly light aroma . though the nose was a bit light , the beers taste was intense and enjoyed .  a beautiful dark copper tone , with perfect head in my opinion .  served out of a can , which i was glad to see more breweries moving towards cans . not sure when the coconut is added to the brew , but i might guess at the end to give it the sweetness , but this would require filtering to make sure no yeast went to work on the new sugar . this beer goes for $ 14+ a 4 pack on the island , but it is quite good .

smell : faint yet odd fruity alcohol aroma , clean is where it is at .  light brown color and crystal clear . an absolutely beautiful pour .  m - the feel starts smooth and moves consistently toward an aftertaste with some disruptive character .

this barleywine pours a hazed orange color , with little heading . in the smell i pick up some rye , hops , and some dark fruit .  pours opaque black color with a nice 2 finger very dense dark tan head with great retention , that reduces to a fairly thick lacing cap that lasts .  m : very light and delicate mouthfeel . lighter body than i prefer , but it does not bother me whatsoever , all things considered . very slick , almost oily mouthfeel .

a : pours a dark black color , decent sized head with good lacing down the glass s : smell is very roasty , chocolate and espresso scents are abundant t : nice sweet milk chocolate up front , roasted malts along with a slight espresso flavor .  this is a perfect looking porter thanks to its 3 head of tan foam ; it just sits there , looking like a dollop of whipped cream .  like a watery summit almost . m= high carbonation and overall pretty average .

s- loved the floral , rich aroma . it really excites your senses and prepares you for the richness of its flavor t- not my cup of tea ... .but it does have a wonderful , rich and complex taste .  it looks great due to being bottle conidtioned , and the head diminishes very slowly leaving dense lacing .  m : the carbonation level is acceptable ( albeit perhaps a tad high ) , but i am at a loss as to the `` double cream '' nature of the beer .

bomber picked up at the lcbo ; no date . fantastic aroma , plenty of pumpkin , spices and gingerbread . yep , it smells like pie . very smooth , and very drinkable despite the abv .  poured black with a mostly lasting light brown frothy head with excellent lacing .  the first sip reveals an average body with little carbonation that is gentle and caresses my palate .

smelled great . a citrusy hop bomb in the nose . went to my head just smelling it . poerful hop smell , comes in apparently at over 70 ibus .  the beer pours darker than the inside of a cow ! head is colossal , creamy ; the lace sticky thick sheets that cling mightily to the glass , both are a nice chocolate color .  m-a bit thin for the style with more of a harsh carb bite than i typically find in a stout . overall , the mouthfeel is very , very average .

upon smelling , i get a minor hop presence with a slight aroma of wild grass .  the typical stubborn head that comes with the style is here- one that forces you to wait ; and admire the rocky billows of foam that slowly sink to reveal magnificent spiderweb lacing and active carbonation .  hopping is present , but totally overmatched by latex . this sucks . the body is decent enough , clocking in at a sturdy medium .

dark as coffee . taste with hints of coffee and cocoa ( basically a classic stout ) . really this did n't standout above most stouts in flavor but i thought the texture was very nice .  great lakes edmund fitzgerald porter is a dark brown ale with a red-orange hue and a beige head that has some oily bubbles on it . it fades to a leathery film and leaves nice lacing on the glass .  very nice m- this is what i do n't like ... the body is really thin .

smell - somewhat thin on the nose , but i smell some brown sugar and raisins/figs prominently . taste - figs/apples jump out at you , with a slightly sour note , and brown sugar and cinnamon are there as well .  thanks to chris for this fresh growler ... pours a nice clear gold with a huge head and incredibly lacing ... the aroma is a little muted buts its super fresh grassy hops , really nice ... the taste is more grassy hops , a touch of alcohol but hidden well for 9 % .  m - ok mouthfeel but it feels a tad over carbonated which slightly reduces the overall experience .

attractive lacing s- colorful , textured bouquet t- roasted grains , barley and caramel m- nice texture , crisp and clean d- 9/10 .  pours spectacularly with the widget . super creamy , with a pretty , bright white head .  crispy , mouth watering . tastes good & is n't watery or light . medium to heavy body .

the head is a wonderful ( not ) light pink , however . some lacing the scent is ... gross . rodenbach , say it is n't so .  appearance - poured a 7 oz bottle of thick syrupy black stout into a tulip ( heh , it works ... ) beautiful red toned tan head with lacing .  medium-light body with moderately-high carbonation .

aroma was very weak on this particular brew but smell of sweet malt and dark fruits . kinda of the oposite of the smell and very welcome .  a : beautiful . deep brown color , like brown leather . huge huge head thats just offwhite and stays with the beer for a while .  m/d : a medium body that is over carbonated for my tastes .

faint aromatics . dark malt , subdued hops , nothing sticks out . nice one .  pours dark amber , huge head , huge lace ( glass empty , still full of lace ) , a little cloudy , alot of yeast left in bottle , awesome .  could use a bit more carbonation in my opinion ... but the body is light enough that it works as it is .

aromas of dark fruits , prune , plum , raisin w/ clove and nutmeg spices in the middle , and a touch of earthy hops on the backside . same as the nose , but with the hop bitterness and alcohol bite overshadowing the malts too much .  a : looks just like the picture , pours very nice , lacing is good and is retained throughout the drink . beautiful color , very impressed , like looking at it a lot .  this one remindes me of rich black coffie and hops mixed . this one is an almost black amber/brown brew that is big and malty . the mouthfeeal is heavy , almost like liquid bread . this one is realy good thank hevans for good bock i wish that this one was avalable all year long but i will get more in spring

the smell is faint but i get a definite hops and a slight smoked scent .  a : pours a beautiful hazy dark amber/brown color . a two finger head forms and sticks around .  m : the sweetness of the honey is a bit too much at times , even though it tastes great . the low bitterness makes the beer a bit unbalanced , and gives you more of a smooth feel than a crisp feel . it 's a bit like drinking lemonade , easy to drink and very sweet .

smells of sweet caramel alcohol , not really all that pleasant . good roasted malt flavors .  appearance - pitch black with a fluffy head in different brown colors that leaves a lot of lacing .  the taste undergoes a similiar transformation , but dark chocolate mostly holds court with roasted malt , with a surprising hop element circling around the periphery . not much body to it , but a nice balance and an easy drinker .

i even like wild blue , even though that tastes like grape soda instead of beer . it does n't even taste like cider . but it tasted awful at first !  damn , black with a dark brown tight head with lots of bubbles .  m : light and corbonated d : very drinkable pumpkin ale that is not overdone at all .

vanilla and molasses richness . slight whiff of cinnamon and roastedness . kinda reminds me of xmas fruitcake .  it produced a very nice rocky top head ... i mean very nice and it lasted the entire beer . great looking beer in my opinion .  the first thing i notice is the light body this porter has . too low in my opinion . carbonation is appropriate .

the aroma of the beer was almost pungent and i could really smell the alcohol .  color was a deep blackish brown with the most amazing head . head was light tan , frothy , thinish but thick and foamy , was n't bubbly , just a solid murky , thick creamy-like froth , the lace was in huge patches of the same look .  a little thin on the palate with hop oils and average carbonation .

aroma was a light hoppiness , grass , and absolutely no citrus .  very nice appearance , absolutely fantastic .  is lighter than it appears and taste . i have to say that i am partial on the review since i got a whole 1/2 barrel keg for ... uh , free ! at first i thought this kind of tasted like a `` fat tire light '' if there was such a thing .

smells faintly of fresh pilsner malt , but the smell is very light .  dark black body with a brown head that falls to a full brown patch .  medium bodied with a medium amount of carbonation . ends sticky .

some dark fruits , smokey aroma , molasses or caramel . while the nose was tough to pick up , everything else was great .  nice shapely imperial pint , creamy off-white head that takes up the top 1/2 inch of the glass . below is a midnight black liquid through which no light passes .  on tap at the brewery 07-10-09 . pours a beautiful dark brown with nice tan head . great looking beer with a really unique aroma dominated with chocolate and orange . would have love to tasted this blind as the aromas were a bit confusing to the senses . pretty well balanced with a nice bitter chocolate finish . my notes are also saying that there was a nice woody aroma and touch of dry wood in the taste , though i 'm not sure how that came about .

s- malty smell , light hops . nothing that really jumped out at me .  pours with a black as night body topped by a thick foamy lasting brown head with a good amount of lacing .  mouthfeel is a little thin for my taste , but overall a very interesting beer with lots of distinct fruity characters .

very cloudy , and thick . its smell is almost like a lager smell . very light and sort of honey smell .  this brew is black at night with a beautifully cascading light brown fat , thick pillow of a head that dissipates to a layer three fingers tall that i 'm fairly certain could rest a 2-lb weight on it without sinking .  mouthfeel : medium body , sticky , sweet , and carbonated .

s - a smell of an old brown ale , and that is something i do n't wan na smell . t - gorgeous ! fantastic ! & different i called the style winter warmer because that 's what the bottle mentions . very excellent done .  this beer has some pretty amazing head retention .  taste : bit thin , bit oh water . mf : thin drinkable ? : yes , very much so

aroma- has a huge pumpkin aroma from the beginning and light spices in the background . what i like most about the aroma of this one is that the pumpkin was so huge ! flavor- has nice spice and then finally pumpkin but very light with both of them . very sweet also and malty . not sure its in my top 5 of pumpkin brews ( except for the aroma ) . its still very good for the style !  exceptionally pale cloudy yellow colored beer with a billowy snow-white head . an extremely powerful head forming beer it almost over flowed the top of the glass . looks exactly like .  m : the carbonation gets in the way of the flavour too much sometimes in this one , but not bad for a bsda , medium-bodied , smooth .

drank this brew both on tap in a bottle and lem me tell , on tap is the way to go . in a bottle you do n't ' get much of the semi sweet aftertaste , it 's more of just a regular ol ' beer . this is a very easy beer to sip and enjoy or gulp down . great beer on tap , alright in a bottle .  russell 's ip'eh pours a bright ruby red with a fluffy head that lingers nicely .  rich aqueous body with virtually no carbonation ( i wonder if that 's intentional ? ) , but this beer pulls it off like few could . as drinkable as such a rich beer could be , though arguably a carbonation presence would improve things .

does this unibroue beer dish the fruity whiffs of heaven , or does it douse the evil hell-fire with a dull taste of dastard dandies ? the money-maker is without a doubt the smell with this beer . give it a swirl and bask in the granny apple goodness of ephemere . apples . all day . no way near as pronounced as the smell , but definitely memorable in it 's appley goodness . has a refreshing brisk bite to it as well . if you like beer and do n't like apples , then you may want to skip it . if you do n't like beer but like apples , this could the beer for you . but if you do n't like beer or apples then ... go eat a pear , ya fruit .  it is beautiful . i 'm still amazed by the red in the head and lacing . i love that . waste of a lot of grain , if you ask me .  smooth medium plus mouthfeel , though it is a little thin compared to expectations for an imperial stout .

not much hop aroma coming at me , smells sweet .  pours a huge head with lacing that will never die . nice dark brown color .  m : the body is thin and slightly watery with a low to moderate carbonation .

s = typical belgian funky yeast . not much else .  a hard pour produces a large billowy cream colored head that leaves tons of lacing and looks very sticky .  am impressed m- lightly carbonated , not much bubble coming through , although perhaps not as thick as i was expecting from the type and abv .

s : some hops , and a smell reminiscent of wet earth . not unpleasant . overall a very nice if not spectacular beer .  beautiful crimson body with thin pure white head .  recommended by shady at the waterhuis in ghent , thanks . appearance was chestnut brown with a medium tan head and slight lacing . smell was of freshly cut hay and light spice . taste was hoppier than most browns , a good balance of bitter and sweet . very good choice , quite enjoyable and unique .

very nice . the taste was nice because the hops came through initially but it was a surprisingly balanced pale . the nose prepared me for a near ipa style , but it was nice to have the balance between the hops and the malt .  exceptional lacing and the head stays throughout . fantastic look . as is the words of ed bassmaster ... '' would you just look at it !  only complaint is that it has a little thin feel to it .

aroma is rather mild piney hops with hints of citrus . taste is bitter piney hops with a surprisingly sweet malty backbone .  beer looks great . it looks extremely refreshing and inviting .  m-is sort of thin , much more than i would expect . d-is very nice .
