there were hints of orange on the nose and some clove/corriander spices , not much on the nose .  from the beginning , it has the perfect color for an imperial stout , with a deep , dark opaque black/brown color and a fluffy mocha-colored cap .  first thing i notice upon tasting is again the carbonation , there 's way to much fizz , seems to be overpowering some of the beer flavor . body is on the lighter side of medium .

i love truffles , but this is a little overpowering on the nose for my taste .  bottle from half time poured a clear dark brown nearly black with a lasting brown head .  while average enough , the mouthfeel ca n't save this sinking ship worth a damn , it 's doomed from it 's key structural deficiencies .

aroma : like most imp stouts , but it smells a bit more candied . wow is it smooth . taste : ~15 minutes out of the fridge : damn .  poured hhazy brown color with a huge frothy light brown head that was lasting and produced excellent lacing .  moderate carbonation does help to give some body however .

smell was subtle with some hops and sweetness . taste was superb , hoppy and malty , great balance , nice warming feeling .  forms a beautiful , dark-tan head that rests on an essentially black body . almost two fingers worth of creamy , foamy head off the first pour . looks exceptional for a porter .  a lovely seasonal offering from our pals in jp . readily available on draught , which is a grand thing . a clear dark amber pour with a fluffy but not bubbly off-white/beige-yellow head with nice lace retention throughout . the aroma offers a spiced caramel malt as does the taste , although with a fine & not overwhelmingly nice hop floral bitterness . very drinkable . very flavorful without gimicky sweet 'flavors . '

beer made popular by huge advertising campaigns , this is just macro swill .  a clear , copper/orange with a full 2 inch off-white fluffy head with remarkable lacing all the way down the glass to the last sip .  mouthfeel is slightly diluted and flat but the overall feel and enjoyable nature leads to a quite drinkable brew .

s : slight boozy smell but sweet and light hop notes . t : a good bittering brown with that american touch .  billowing head grows ever skyward above liquid shining like light copper penny ... heavy malts and a hint of soy sauce in the nose , a bit sweet heavy beery flavor , a profile of multi grain artisan bread , with some american macro lager brew qualities to it as well .  mouthfeel was super dry , yet still drinkable enough .

ok so its not a rare micro but this beer has got to be the official `` ol reliable . not much of a smell . if you try hard you get a whiff of roasted malt but thats with a big effort . tastes nice and roasty with a minor hop bite at the end .  pours a nice , crystal clear , deep gold with a compact white head that rises articulately above the rim . it has good head retention and once if finally recedes it leave some nice lacing . tons of tiny bubbles race to the surface , a mighty tasty looking brew .  mouthfeel was average .

produces some nice lacing too . the aroma is dull , as only some soft citrus is detectable . this would be a nice hot summer day brew , very refreshing and very drinkable .  inky darkness and a sticky lacing create a picture perfect design on my glassware .  m- i 'd like a bit more body . carbonation is good .

clear , straw yellow with a small white head . fairly mild aroma . touch of citrus and bread . nice balance , perhaps a bit more hop/citrus than a kolsch should have , but still very mild . citrus/lemon , touch of sweet flavor , bread .  a - dark . real dark , with a huge creamy head that sticks everywhere .  carbonation a tad light .

s- nice sweet malts up front , a little bit of hops and a touch of cinnamon . nothing too complex here . t- the malt really shines through here like in the nose .  bottled 24 sep 08 pours chestnut with flecks of orange when held to the light ; plus 3 fingers of fluffy tan head . superior head retention & lacing s ; big fat toffee as the swing top whooshes open , plus leafy hops , apricot & plums t : leafy hops , coca-cola , brown bread , & dryness up front .  on the palate the beer feels light and thing , and a subtle malt flavor yields to a building , albeit , not overpowering bitterness that is highly drinkable but nothing special .

it has a sweet aroma of juniper berries and a host of herbs that my nose ca n't identify .  this pours a nice golden straw color with a bright white fluffy billowing two finger head that settles down to a rocky covering with rings and patches of lace . after a quick swirl , the head seems to boil up from below and replenish its self .  mouthfeel- decent carbonation on the front of the palate . fairly light and slight watery mouthfeel . drinkability- very high .

watery , weak , metallic . having just read the preview of the kolsch style , this one fits the bill . i have never liked any beers of this style , but this one does the trick .  big and fluffy cappuccino colored head with some serious retention and loads of lace . just a beautiful looking beer .  m=medium bodied , a bit watery in the aftertaste which brings it down a little bit .

goes down very easy . has a rich caramel-like flavor and an almost roasted aftertaste .  this brew pours an opaque black colored body with a large creamy head .  the body is decent , but a bit thin and over carbonated .

on tap at the brew pub ... pours a medium gold orange , light tan head good retention and lacing ... the aroma is phenomenal , by far the best smelling citra beer i 've had . a great mix of really fresh and sweet oranges and grapefruits .  a wonderfully colored beer : dark brown body that 's nearly black , but a beautiful shade of crimson glows as light filters through the edges .  some carbonation .

light malt odor . some noble hop in the nose and not too aggressive . mmmm ... a nice tasting brown .  25.4 oz bottle served in la chouffe tulip . appearance - beautiful ruby , amber color with a thick , bubbly , creamy tan head that leaves thick lacing all over the sides of the glass .  the cinnamon is left lingering afterwards and really helps to cut the sweetness . dr- pretty .sweet , not sure if i could do a whole pint . ov- find myself comparing this to belgian red and liking this more

s- light crisp smell , it could be a little stronger to be better . t- nice and light , flowery side flavor with a slight crispy hop taste thats extremely refreshing .  a - pours a luscious black with a dense head . it looks exactly the way a stout should .  unfortunately , the mouthfeel is pretty thin , although the carbonation is decent .

i have to admit that i do n't get much from the nose- just roasted malt with a little bit of smoke .  appearance - this pours an appealing straw gold with a bright white cap . some nice lace down the glass .  light and thin mouth feel ... medium carbonation .

a balanced perfect example of a american ipa . goes down fast , very refreshing. , .. my wife 's fave ( by far ) ipa - so we get it a lot .  a good amount of both head and lace remains .  pretty light mouthfeel .

the scent was mostly roasted coffee .  a - just beautiful with a deep black hue , a hint of light around the edges and a big , creamy head .  m : really light bodied with a bit of carbonation , the only not awful thing about this beer .

smell had no complexity and no distinc odors but pleasant . very good taste with bitter finish ; also not complex but very nice .  a : the appearance of this brew is very alluring as it shines a gorgeous orange .  m : medium in body , pretty dry .

pours a cloudy , raw golden straw with a medium head that bubbles down to a thin pure white layer . my nose is a little stuffed , but from what i can make out , a wonderful battle between slightly floral lemongrass , malt , and mildly bitter hops .  this is about the best presentation of any doppelbock i 've ever seen . it produces a little over three fingers thick of rocky tan head , which peaks about a half an inch over the top of my stein -- great lacing . the body is dark ruby red in color , and is light enough to allow light to easily shine through , in order to show off its clear body .  the beers appearance is average , lacks in color to be above average ( looked a little watery to be honest ) . the taste is great , smooth , hoppy , fruity all i expected and more . this is a very drinkable beer in fact i killed a 4 pack when trying it for the first time ... .great job dfh .

cheers to rmalinowski4 for sending this my way review adapted from notes taken 11/13/11 appearance : this is the most red beer i 've ever seen , ever - it 's a rich , dark red - off-white , kind of pink head , keeps a bubbly cap - minimal lacing , especially as it warms smell : borderline disturbing , but also good - so , so much cherry - like a bowl of cherries floating in cherry juice topped with cherry jam and flavored cough syrup - more or less no hint of malt , just cherries - a touch of sour , too - kind of scary , unpleasant until i actually tasted the beer taste : absolutely ridiculous - so much cherry - kind of reminds me of a cherry popsicle - tons of cherry , but the overall taste is better than just the cherry flavor - tastes like carbonated cherry juice , maybe a carbonated cherry pie , utterly no hint of alcohol - it 's kind of a stretch to call this beer - a little tart - sweet , but not excessively so for half a 750ml mouthfeel : medium body , crisp carbonation , juicy , sticky cherry juice overall : is this beer ? the smell is a little intimidating , but the flavor is excellent .  appearance : very respectable murky peach , topped with a perfect head well woven honeycombs and plenty of effervescence .  poured from bottle , this fruity concoction from the smith master wields an incredible fruit aroma of pure fresh raspberry . minimal to no head , dark red in the glass . this fine example really pulls off the definition of a fruit beer , with authentic fresh flavors of pure , tart raspberry . lively and fresh acidic profile with pure rasp-o-goodness with a slightly bitter finish . excellent , well done genuine offering .

way overcarbonated ... aroma is of dark roasted malts with a slight sourness .  tall frothy tan head that does not want to go anywhere . large chunks of lace stick to the glass . color is a deep dark brown that is almost black .  a little bit over-sizzling on the feel is a drawback , it detracts from the fact that it 's otherwise velvety smooth .

not much smell , perhaps a faint yeast and beeriness . taste just as nondescript : pretty one-dimensional astringent beer with just the memory of wheat and yeast .  wow , dark black body from pour , with a woody smoke brown head that sits nicely . this is exactly what an imperial stout should look like . beautiful complexion .  mouthfeel is near average , a bit more body and flavor concentration would be welcome .

a- coca-cola colored . with a thick brown-grey almost ash like mousse of a head . s- smokey sweet malt . a little metallic . d- very good .  pours with a three finger , thick light tan head that fades slowly and leaving a good lace . deep clear amber color .  m - tons of carbonation , to a fault .

s : light nose on this . oatmeal is the main aroma . coffee and chocolate are very very light .  it looked fantastic ! it was a cloudy amber color with a thick frothy head . there was tremendous head retension and excellent lacing .  light orange color ... awesome aroma ... just like fresh pumpkin pie out of the oven ... big cinnamon element ... the taste is more subtle than the nose ... nice pumkin flavor also strong cinnamon and some nutmeg ... mouthfeel is light and slightly watery.. decent pumpkin ... i 'd prefer to see it bigger in body with a little more assertive pumpkin taste..still pretty decent overall and a solid seasonal offering .

it smells vaguely like the aforementioned vegetable soup , with a little bit of a malt smell .  huge chunks of sticky head stands over two inches . great retention leaves cotton balls of lace on the glass .  a bit light in body , perhaps somewhat thin .

s : there is n't a spice smell at all . the room instantly fills up with a unique belgian beer scent . there is a yeasty smell to the beer but not overpowering . d : this is very drinkable .  bornem triple 12 oz bottle soft pour in a tulip glass unknown bottling ( fl 29cd 15:12 ) , beatified 12/06 poured a hazy straw yellow with a huge white fluffy rocky fully lasting head with excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is pretty average for this sort of beer .

smell : some mild roasted malts and chocolate were noticeable , but somewhat light from what i expected .  just beautiful . black and sludgy with a thin tanned brown head that could be rebuilt on command with a swirl of the glass . super slippery lacing ( as i expect on a ba brew ) .  mouthfeel : delicate to no carbonation but the beer feels pretty foamy and creamy , which is n't bad but does n't quite mes overall : i think that this beer is pretty good despite the weird mouthfeel .

roasted malts , espresso , and a touch of yeast on the nose , with very minimal ( `` no '' ) hop presence .  this beer looks amazing . s : some citrusy hop notes but mainly a lot of fruit .  taste - wheaty and yeasty , with typical yeast derived spiciness mouthfeel - light body , but not watery . a little more oomph in the body would have been nice . more carbonation would have been good .

wonderful smell . caramel , toffee and a bit of fig . the aroma was awesome , but it went a little downhill from there .  a - pours a bright clean gold with a thick white top .  bland appearence and no lace . i do n't have a lot to say about this beer except maybe a glass of water would have been a better idea.very bland in every feature.that being said it 's not revolting but there are a thousand beers out there of this sort . update a few minutes later : i really resent this beer .

the smell in my opinion is average for an ipa . i tried this one with some hot wings , and they seemed to compliment eachother . overall i enjoyed this brew .  pours a cloudy straw/yellow with a ton of carbonation and a giant white foamy head that leaves fantastic lacing.i hardly ever give 5 's for appearance , but this is a special beer .  extremely mild , even for an english style , however it had an interesting coffee finish , which i do n't think i 've ever found in a nut brown before . particularly curious , since the malts were not all that roasted . hmm .

smell : i do n't get much in the way of smell . i detect a slight citrus smell , which seems to be in line with many of the other reviewers it may be because of my allergies though i 'm not going to put much weight into that . finishes clean . drinkability : this is best thing about this beer . damn .  ) dollop of whipped cream-like head ! it just will not go away , and the belgian lace is top-shelf ! the bier itself is a dark-golden , orangey color , with some cloudiness ( a smidge of yeast may have crept into the goblet ... ) .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and slightly watery .
smell is weak . some coffee , sweet and malty , bit roasty .  pours opaque with a massive tan head .  m- mouthfeel is fairly thick for a macro and very fizzy .

aroma , not as intense as most ipas , grainy with a floral hop bouquet . worth a try for sure but not one of the top-tier ipas .  two inch , fluffy white head with incredible retention which leaves a solid amount of lacing down the glass . one of the best looking gueuzes ive seen .  poor carbonation , mostly foam .
smell is nothing great . looks are good .  dense frothy head on top with great belgian lacing .  4 m : a little flat .

nice smell - rich , sweet hazelnut , as advertised .  terrific retention and some soft lacing . gorgeous beer , plain and simple .  this beer almost goes over the top with spices - but holds back just enough . cinnamon and nutmeg blast out of the malt - like they stuffed a mincemeat pie into the bottle . must be brewed by little elves at the north pole . one bottle at a sitting is all i care for of this beer , but this is a great change of pace - ho ho ho !

it has a dark golden color with a very nice unfiltered haze . smell is the only lacking part of this beer . i can smell some sweet caramel malts and some dark raisin-like fruits . one of the most well-balanced saisons i 've ever had that also maintains a lot of good tastes in it .  a - very fluffy , white , pillow head that formed a plateau in the middle . 2 fingers with good retention and excellent lacing .  m : very bubbly if there is one knock on this beer i would say it is overcarbonated .

s : mild citrus hop aroma . t : lovely malt flavor , biscuity , with some subtle fruit notes and a nice hop tang at the end .  sofie a 5 cloudy dull yellow with an enormous merangue head , excellent retention .  taste : a true witch 's brew of vegetables , raspberry punch , and a thin maltiness . finishes tart and watery . mild carbonation .
aromas are banana and a weird perfume smell .  decent retention with tons of lacing on the glass .  slightly dry in the mouth .

a : see-trhu copper to light-drown , little to no head , no lacing s : toasty malt fragrance , little to no aftersmell t : this is a surprisingly tasty beer ... the taste is a milky , carmely flavor with fireroasted butterscotch cream .  this one gets the blue ribbon for most outstanding head . well , its all head ! the color was a slightly hazed pale gold .  even if you have tried other wheat beers this is the one is different . the pale ale influences defiantly show through with a good hop finish . i will drink this seasonal brew again soon and often as soon as they make more !

aroma - weak , roasted malt and an odd metallic tinge that is only noticeable in the first pint ( and disappears along with your taste perception after a session ) . overall - despite having this beer more times than i can remember ( my unenlightened days at uni were spent solely on this ) , i choose to review this pint because it tasted particularly good .  impressive lacing left behind , and really nice retention .  the mouthfeel is maybe a tad thin for my liking , but drinkability is good .

overall this was probably the best beer i had for the night . i did not drink this beer with any food , overall i would say it had a bit of a bite to it . good beer  great off white head is soapy and sticks to the glass really well . good head retention keeps the appearance up for a good amount of time .  mouthfeel - a smooth mouthfeel , a bit on the watery side but crisp .

nose is a bit light , it 's a bit toasty and coffee .  nice two finger head that dissipated quickly leaving behind a thick foamy tan lace .  12 oz twist off states it is in the `` burton style '' poured copper amber ( darker than i expected ) with a small head smells of homebrew with stuck fermentation , residual maltiness and mineral caramel flavors and that same malty residual , no hop finish , no bittering a bad experience and reading the reviews , i was not alone wife poured it out . i struggled through it

excellent clarity although slightly chill hazed . n : predominately orange and lemon citrus . pine aromas also make an appearance with some very subtle caramel malts . t : lemon and pine upfront leading into orange citrus ( navel orange & tangerine ) and light caramel malts .  2011 brewmaster reserve pours a dark chocolate color but black in the glass up to the light . nice solid foamy khaki head with ok retention and nice lacing .  m : heavy for a pale ale , low carb . substantial slick on the finish .

smell is citrus fruits . some rose floral elements . yeast and `` dank '' come through .  12 oz bottle poured into a tulip glass . pours a beautiful fiery red color with two fingers of light orange/tan head that is quite dense and sticks around for the duration . looks great in the glass .  m- the body is a little on the light side .

i literally only tried this beer because of the label . man was i surprised . the smoothness and the color were incredible . i enjoyed it in the bottle but i loved it in a pint glass poured from the bottle . the taste was extremely smooth and not bitter at all . not thick nor over powering by any means .  poured a big , thick head on a very cloudy light amber body . looks great .  you can definitely taste the hops . spicy as expected from typical winter beers . m- as i said , it 's a bit bitter . it 's not a beer you can drink really fast . good beer to have a good steak with .

fresh floral hops on the aroma , citrus , and a bit a booze .  giant rocky chocolate-colored head that soon settles to a good-looking skim of brown bubbles that hangs around for awhile , providing good lacing .  m : this one has a little more carbonation than i like .

s- very tight nose here . some faint dry dark malts , fresh flour , a touch of dark fruit .  pours a rich , deep clear copper with an unbelievably retentive , thick tan head .  mouthfeel : not a lot of body , a little thin .

bittersweet dark chocolate aromas mix with rum , coffee , and a cascade hop edge . palate starts off with sweet cocoa malt , and light ripe fruit .  pours jet black with a huge , cascading brown head .  m - mouthfeel is where this beer is lacking for me .

deeply musty nose with what i assume is the kaffir lime and some yeasty scents . i guess it is n't a bad smell but i feel its a little dank for golden ale and personally do n't care for it .  the beer was dark brown , difficult to see through .  m - reasonably full mouthfeel . average carb level for the style .

~ca n't really smell much , a bit dissapointing , but a classic lager smell , the carmelized malts , and ca n't smell any of the hops , though i 'm sure they 're there .  appearance : dark ruby/ brown , off white two finger head , that left spider-web lacing all the way down .  the color was yeallow hazy 'wheatbeer ' ; and the mouthfeel was light .

assorted berries dominate the nose , principally blackberry .  inky black with a huge head and awesome lacing here . really attractive beer .  it lacks a smoothness because there is too many bubbles on the tongue it takes away some of the nuances away from the flavor . this is a tasty beer and the drinkability could be better if it was n't so overly carbonated .

ok , so it 's not remarkable and it 's low in alcohol - but are n't we missing the point here ? this is not just a stout - it 's `` mother 's milk '' . it 's liquid vitamin b . let 's say you 're feeling a little weak in the knees and tired , hungry , generally frustrated . grill yourself a ribeye ( bloody rare - preferably a chemical free coleman ) and pop a couple of these babies . i love my `` guinie '' cheers .  i do n't think i have any doubt that guinness is a mighty-fine looking beer , with its meringue-like cream topping and black coffee body . i especially enjoy the pad of brown foam that follows the liquid as it is drained from the pint . fine lacing .  m - light in body . carbonation is a big strong for my taste .

the smell was entirely of spice like pumpkin pie , most notable was nutmeg and clove . malt was quite faint , almost no hops , and just a wee bit of ethanol .  a : this porter pours black with ruby highlights and two fingers of mocha colored head . lacing is exceptional . s : roasted malts dominate the nose which is complemented with a subtle sweetness .  it is very carbonated with lots of bubbles coming up throughout . my other major complaint is that the beer itself is a light in feel , i want it a little more robust . overall , this is very good and reminds me a lot of insanely bad elf . a highly drinkable winter ale that packs a great alcohol punch . needs a little tweaking on the feel and to give the aroma some oompf but so close .

smell is subdued , chocolatey malts , with some faint cocoa and caramel .  dark amber-brown with a big , dense tan head .  the body is pretty thin but the feel still comes across as creamy to some extent .

the nose is light and floral with some very slight sweetness among the malt .  this is a beautiful beer . it pours black , though when held up to the light , the edges of the glass are a brilliant ruby .  the mouthfeel is dominated with alcoholic burn , beginning and a the finish .

smell : sour , spicy malt and yeast .  pours a medium gold with three fingers of beautiful , dense white foam . good retention and pretty streaks of lace stick all over the glass . very uncharacteristic for a barleywine .  a - deep copper . light tan head with some of the best lacing i 've seen . s - grassy hops and caramel malts . t - very strong but nicely balanced . strong hop bite with rich coffee like roasted malts . d - very drinkable , but it more of a sippin beer at 10.5 abv .

s : some earthiness , light biscuit , and not much else . t : more earthy notes , a little wet bread , and some faint hoppiness ( goldings ? ) . d : this is quaffability at its finest ; lovely .  pours perfectly with a massive amount of tight forming light tan head , and has a crystal clear dark copper colored body .  mouth seems a hair thin and the carbonation is a bit prickly .

smells ok , i smell soapiness in it though , which is a turn off . has a pepper floating in citrus smell . smells a lot like you 'd expect from the style .  this is also nice looking ruby red ipa . it is well hopped with glorious cascades and has that umistakable smell that screams crisp bitterness . a very drinkable beer for the average hophead .  m - even . not thin , not chewy , not thick ... just average .

smells sour and oaky , pleasant nose taste is a bit weak , confirming an impression i had when i drank this on tap .  a - the giant waft of gunsmoke is the cool precursor to the brilliant appearance of this beer . the four-finger light khaki head is undying ! probably the best retention i 've ever seen ! a plateau forms in the center and ultra-thick lace is left clinging to the sides like mad !  very nice offering and a cut above the perennial lineup from summit . aroma , floral hops and some malt taste is dominated by bitter hops , a nice floral character also , not the ubiquitous grapefruit bomb that most american ipas are . very highly drinkable , overall a welcome release from a local favorite , summit 's special releases are worth giving a try .

incredible beer . s - i do average on every beer . t - pure bliss . wheat and citrus with a smooth feeling . m - pure , not bitter , very over powering .  a light amber-orange brew , with a truly magnificient head that displays some of the finest retention i 've ever seen . loads of thick , patchy lacing grace the glass . impressive .  m : a lot of carbonation , maybe too much but otherwise full bodied with some creaminess .

good smell , just not outstanding .  so dark i did n't realize it was a clear bottle until i started pouring it . big , thick , spongy head looks very substantial .  m - good coating but only a mild tingle on the tongue .

s : hmmm..not much here . mellow , straightforward , creamy wheat with whispers of earthy spices ... probably cloves and something else . subtly nice .  poured black as night , nice thick head , with good retention , smell was malty with roasted , chocolate , notes .  scent is of fresh earthy and grassy hops , not overly powerful but they dominate ... hints of caramel and yeast in the back end . the hops are not overly bitter or flavorful , but the freshness works . the body is medium , although the oily hops contribute more than the malt ... slightly watery . a nice tasting beer which isnt too complex and just lets the fresh hops star .

its hoppy and floral along with a bit of citrus . t- very tasty . its piney and citrusy .  a : pours a ridiculously opaque black with mild brown edges when held to the light . the head is three and a half fingers of dark chocolate cappucino head . head retention is incredible . in fact , it 's as good as i 've ever seen . the amazing head of this beer was undercut by the slightly seltzer feel it had in the mouth .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and dry for my taste , but it is also very drinkable .

s- a bit like stale bread , but there are some good lager-like aromas along with crisp hops and grain .  pours an opaque dark-chocolate brown with a fairly thick and persistent light tan head that leaves some good lacing .  medium-bodied and moderately carbonated , the flavors throw back to the aroma , with a pronounced hoppiness that is balanced well by a base of biscuity grain .

s- does n't really have that strong of a scent , but you can slightly smell some malts . d- very drinkable . overall an extremely good beer .  pours into a pint glass a beautiful redish amber brown color with great clarity and head . the head eventually fades but leaves excellent lacing on the glass . you really could n't ask for a better looking brown ale .  m : a little thin with moderate , prickly carbonation .

s- malt seems to be the boss around here . smells sweet and a bit like red licorice . lots of dimensions to the flavour and mouthfeel .  it poured out beautifully , looking dark and rich like a barleywine with a very nice thick head .  it was a little fizzy , but that was a minor problem .

smelled sweetly of grain . husky hops .  probably the darkest beer ive had , ever . i was startled by the lack of carbonation .  m : sometimes bottles from portsmouth seem to be a little under carbonated . aggressive , peppery carbonation would have been perfect here . some extra carbonation would have put this over the top .

faint chocolate and chili . mostly musky and solvent like ammonia . some decent complexity here , but not particularly appetizing . musky , almost fishy , stale coffee and even fainter chocolate .  this ale pours a beautiful crystal-clear ruby color with an off-white head .  m : a bit watery , though fairly bubbly and lively .

kinda fruity and musty as well . t - nice . reminds me of a cider . it is very sweet however . certainly more drinkable than a biere brut though .  it looked like rich colombian coffee filtering down from a head of whipped chocolate mousse . really beautiful . t - very solid .  finishes a bit dry . too light bodied for the style though .

very little aroma most likely due to age .  poured from the bottle to a reddish orange with off-white head that lingered thru entire glass , and left excellent lacing . the aroma and flavor were okay , but just terribly wrong for this style .  m - thin and crisp , but not watery .

aroma is wonderfully rich . powdery yeast being folded into bread . smells clean and refreshing .  santa cruz ale works dark night oatmeal stout is a dark ruby black ale with a brown sugar colored , gel-topped dense foam that has outstanding retention and lacing .  nice amberish honey color fruity smell great blend of hops , very citrusy and fruity , almost floral type flavoring ( hence the name ) , very crisp taste average mouthfeel , smooth , not to thick , not to light this is by far one of my favorite ipa 's .

epic lacing & near epic head retention s : faint woodyness & even fainter figgyness t : figgyness & leafy hops , & some mineral hops as well up front .  great retention and great lacing .  mouthfeel : a little sharp on the tongue , but goes down smoothely .

smell - not much , some burnt sugar notes and a little malt . no significant hop aroma , which is true to style . a modest diacetyl note , a little roastiness , just a touch of high alcohol flavor . drinkability - a very enjoyable pint .  bubbly bud-yellow but with an awesomely fantastic white head . slight haze adds intrigue .  m : the kinda thin and the lack of carbonation will drop the score for me to average .

this is an interesting take on a belgian ipa and one where the aroma belied the amount of hop bitterness in the taste .  fluffy bubbles well up slowly up and then back down the sides of the glass like a guinness in slow motion . massive brown meringue head crowns a nearly-black ruby-tinted crystal clear beer .  very low level of carbonation .

banana is the dominant aroma , followed by bubblegum , bread shows through . i 'm always keen to look for local beers with limited distribution as they often hide real jewels .  all holdens beers look good and this one is really good looking ; great amber body , clear and rich , the creamy off-white head sticking to the glass like a wet net curtain .  whenever this touched my mouth i got a sensation of flatness . this limited my enjoyment but it was actuallly well carbonated .

aroma is very faint . only a hint of smoke , and burnt grain shine through .  a dark , creamy head that helps to unleash a hypnotic belgian candi sugar smell .  body is on the heavy side of medium and drinkability is good .

aroma is surprisingly minimal , wisps of malt and alcohol .  a - very hazy amber with a huge head that sticks all over the glass , exactly what i [ personally ] want to see in this style .  taste : begins watery and subdued , velvety but light ; hops are light yet floral , finishing crisp yet tangy . overall : very enjoyable overall , i was n't sure what to expect as a result of the aging process , but my expectations were not in line with my actual experience , but that is not a bad thing , lighter character was indicative of age , but i was expecting more complexity from the scent than what i got in the taste .
the aroma is of dirt and diacetyl . t : a much better flavor .  burgundy color , with a full and creamy foam that lasts .  mouthfeel is much thicker than you might expect .

i guess it 's because i had always expected something incredibly intense from such a strange bottle/name combination . i really enjoy a good belgian ale , and this definitely fits the bill . i imagine this is what duvel would want to grow up into some day .  samuel adams 13th hour stout is a very dark brown beer with a thick , creamy , beige head that has awesome retention and lacing .  mouthfeel : this is a little thin somehow .

subdued citrus smells , not much else but my sniffer is off tonight .  after pouring from the nitro can and settling into my pint glass , this beer is jet black with a tan colored creamy head . a wonderful site to behold , exactly as you would expect for this style .  the mouthfeel like most rogue ales to me seemed a little on the thin side .

insane lacing & head retention s : citric & floral hops show up early , but muted t : floral & piney hops , plus biscuitty malt up front .  i still think its a great looking pint , the light head on the dark brew , the lightness eminating from the dark as you set it down after taking a sip . simply one of the best heads ever , which lends a beautiful look to the whole thing . taste is good , very presentable to someone not familiar with stouts or a soul that 's intimidated by dark brews , but not something that would make one more familiar with various dark beers throw down thier pants and say hallelujah .  it had a light feel on the palate with medium carbonation . my only gripe is that the mouthfeel was kind of thin based on my preference for the style , but that is just me being picky .

a : rich , deep amber ; unremarkable head retention ; good lacing s : not a lot -- esters , floral , citrus ; pretty mild t : i love the taste of this beer .  a=dark black color , pours nice with a thick head that seems to stay around .  the mouthfeel was a bit thinner than i would have hoped .

aroma is n't bad . some fruit and sours .  pours out as dense and lightless as a black hole , tall dense chunky beige head that slowly settles .  feel is good but could be better , a little thin for my tastes , but i like thicker beers .

very musty overall . the nicer elements of the smell are , unfortunately , overwhelmed by a resinous , very oaky smell .  a very lively pour leads to a thick cap of off-white foam that 's not in a hurry to leave . served in a gold-rimmed affligem glass i can only describe the appearance as stunning .  had this in a small plastic sample glass at the brewery beer garden in boston . a-off white head , dark walnut body s-candy , citrus , ice cream t-ice cream and floral hops m-medium d-really full of flavor . i would drink it again though if given limited choices .

aroma : hoppy and malty on the nose with a hint of cherry in the nose .  pours golden into my glass with a massive white head that started forming since the first drop . great retention .  mouthfeel : pretty light bodied brew , almost watery .

very aromatic and citrusy . there is something barnyard-like about the smell , and the alcohol taste is overpowering .  pours one and half fingers worth of creamy orange/tan head . this fades to a very nice solid cap of mostly cream with some big bubbles mixed in . very heavy creamy lacing remains on the glass during the sitting .  warming opens the palate up a lot , the malt becomes more prominent and the hops keep coming through , seemingly more balanced than when at a cooler temp . this light ruby barleywine is definatly mild , with a medium-ish body lacking the explosive punch of others in the style . flavors seem to hit targets on the palate rather than coat it with complex flavors .
smell was lacking , only slight yeast and spice .  pours nicely , with a chocolate-tinged head . looks fantastic in a glass -- a dark , reddish-black .  mouf & gt ; easy drinkability & gt ; good .

straw coloured beer ... maybe a hint of brown . s : smells like a bbq pit , thats about it .  the appearance is impeccable if served right - straw golden color , completely clear obviously and with a head that is the right size and has good retention .  bit foamy and dry in the mouth , feels maybe both over-attenuated and over-carbonated .

s - wonderful fresh and `` outdoorsy '' aroma ... grassy hops , hay , grains , slight peppery spice . very crisp , clean , and inviting . d - a superb saison and overall lovely beer . having a great `` moment '' with it on a somewhat warm but breezy early evening on my porch after a day of cleaning .  a : very brilliant copper colored with red-orange hues against the right light . beautifully fluffy creamy mocha colored head that laced from the top of the glass to the bottom .  m - too carbonated , but then again , thats the way most japanese like their beer .

i smell oranges and pine . this is a very hoppy ipa .  full sail imperial stout , brewer 's reserve served at cellar temperature in a stone irs glass ( tulip style ) . appeared true black , no light getting through , with a nice stratified head ; a frothy burnt crme layer overlays bubbly yellow-brown , below which is only darkness . excellent .  medium full feel , but the carbonation came across way too harshly initially .

smell - ok . not the strongest hop smell and not the weakest hop smell . taste - very nice . bitter ! ! !  22oz bottle poured into a frosty 22oz mug seriously beautiful beer -- bright golden orange , medium cloudiness , huge billowing piles of head and unbelievable lacing .  mouthfeel : medium-thick with a little harsh bitterness at the end .

if you love the smell of hops , this is great stuff . brewdog again did it for me . smell is fantastically green herbs hops and grass , also the apricot ( ?  the first pour produced a pillowly blanket of finely packed bubbles an inch thick . beautiful . over time the bubbles die down to about a 1/4 '' but resurface with swirling . the beer itself is a deep , impenetrable brown that lightens a bit at the edges .  tingly mouthfeel brought in the flavor of more hoppy fruit-sweet malt mix .

kind of a faint aroma . wow . that tasted like marijuana .  pours a wonderful looking burnt orange to brown in color with a huge , very creamy , yet frothy tannish colored head ... with excelent head retention . awesome looking solid and sticky lacing all over the glass .  mouthfeel : full to medium body .

s- bright notes of cocoa powder , nuts , toast and fresh leaves . really exciting . t- very different from the nose . it was a bit pricey but i 'm certainly happy to have bought it , not my favorite of the style but tasty and complex none the less .  a : cloudy caramel and light brown . the frothy head is 3 fingers tall and beige in color . there 's a hearty finger of retention for most of the session and a ton of lacing . i love it .  highly carbonated feel to it .

the best way to some it up is that it smelled like a rich budweiser .  big bubbles to the froth . head dissipates slowly and leaves good lacing .  the mouthfeel seems to be a tiny bit weak to me , but this is obviously a forgivable trait for such a fine beer . it 's a little bit creamy and grainy , but the body lacks oomph .

awesome . t : balanced just right .. toasted caramel malts with a touch of cinnamon balanced out with some great resiny pine hops with not much bitterness aftertaste .  a : pours a very thick motor oil pint . produces a light brown lasting frothy head , with bubbles .  d/m : light carbonation but its a really big beer .

a little smell of malt , caramel and a floral note not over powering at all .  it pours a deep black color with four heaping fingers of dark tan head . there is lots and lots of belgian lace on the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel is a bit over carbonated .

the brew is a fizzy yellow drink with a little aroma and only a token head .  i love the bottle , nice swing top , classy looking , and pours perfectly into a nonic glass a deep dark brown color , with a nice sturdy white head .  if any faults to be found i would pick on the body which seemed too light . its easy drinking .

certainly not a bad aroma , but not as powerfull as some of my personal favorites .  starting at the top - screw tops are bad . the clarity was exceptional and the mouthfeel was exceptional for the style ( thin ) .  tasted the hint of caramel-like characteristics which probably contributed to the sweet smells ... enjoyed the strong hops of this brew ... bittersweet comes to mind while tasting this beer ... overall , very enjoyable blend of hops and barley and was informed the aging of this beer contributed to its tasteful experience ... m - not sure what exactly is was which did not sit extremely well here , possibly a little coarse ... d - i would def .

aroma was lacking , made me question if there is any dry hopping going on with this . ample bitterness , brings it in that department , seems to be long boil high alpha acid hops . as good as any other ipa in northern nevada i guess .  bottle from lubire : poured a dark brown color ale with a medium dark foamy head with great retention .  med-full bodied and prickly carb . blvd pale ale used to be so much better before they started brewing for dollars .

s. earthy hop aroma . o no one flavor stands out .  a- very very dark black . almost completly black even when held up tp light . great big creamy 3finger head , only receded slightly staying thick and creamy .  the mouthfeel is a little light , but not horribly so .

smell - a smooth , soft aroma that is entirely pleasant . buttery shortbread , biscuity malt , no detectable bitterness .  it pours a ruby-tinged teak . a solid beige head sits on top and takes its sweet time fading . lots of webs of lace mark your progress as you drink .  ca n't descrbe the mouth feel because of all the spices ! ! !

s : it smells like raisins with some familiar belgian esters . it 's not overly complex . t : it tastes sweet like a mixture of molasses and malt .  the head is really quite amazing , as it stays for quite awhile before gradually dissolving .  smells of brown sugar , mollasses , alcohol , and smoke tastes of sweet tobacco , smoke , pork and whiskey medium light body , light carbonation i would very much recommend having a taste

the aroma is some roasted chocolate scent with the cherry tartness poking through . there is a tiny bit of brett farmhouse funk in the nose but not enough to give itself away casually . especially once tasting it , i would have appreciated a strong upfront aroma . the first sip is a blast of sour cherry over top dark cocoa flavors .  huge billowy beige head atop a clear and golden amber beer . slathers of lather 's thickly on the glass , and the head relaxes some , but stays the whole ride down .  nice balance between the light chewy butterscotch flavor with a mild yet intresting hop finish ( the finish got better in the terms of complexity as a drank more , up front it was a tid un intresting ) .. mouthfeel : avg . nothing wrong with it i suppose , maybe a tad oily .

some citrus pokes through in the nose amongst some mustiness .  this stout pours with a black body topped by medium thick , light brown head with lots of lacing .  m - this part is a bit underperforming , but only relative to the rest of its strengths ; it just does n't have the substantive feel that i want , but it has proper carbonation and relative weight .

the color was a honey gold ; the head was a solid inch to inch and a half ( depending on the pour ) ; the smell was mediocre ; but the taste was outstanding .  picked up a twelve pack of this on sale for ten ninty nine and that is great deal a : the appearance of this beer is a nice golden color with snow white head with lots of bubbles racing to the top s : little sweet malty character with spicy check style hop bitter smell , very nice t : very smooth then taste like sweet biscuts and begins to turn slightyly spicy bitter and finishes very clean .  m : light body , medium carbonation , starts crisp but thickens and becomes creamier toward the finish .

aroma is the least pleasant aspect of an otherwise exceptional beer ( just my humble opinion ) . coffee is front and center , but there 's a subtle sourness in the back that just did n't resonate well with me . dry , but deliciously drinkable .  a - poured a hazy copper colour . good carbonation , two fingers of thick light beige head . great thick rings of lace and a finger of retention . spot on ipa appearance .  mouthfeel : light for the style , high carbonation , sweet , moderately smooth , with a really sweet aftertaste drinkability : this is refreshingly different for a dopplebock .

as far as i can tell , the aroma does not offer a great amount ... a hint of hops , and some dryness , but fairly subdued . the flavor on the otherhand is a veritible explosion of goodness .  not sure how old this bottle is though . a pretty slow pour yeilded me four fingers of beige head so i took a break . when i got back the head faded but left the best looking lace patterns i 've seen that were bumpy resembling a mountain range .  mouth feel seems a bit off .

smell : a little bland . nothing that stands out but really not far off from style . overall : very good but i would have enjoyed more aromatics as it says on the can it was dry-hopped but i know for a pilsener that is not generally a punch in the nose . very good taste and that certainly raises my opinion of it .  served in 12 oz snifter/tulip glass a- big 2 inch mocha or light brown looking head , very frothy , looks like the head of choc milk shake , completely opaque s- wonderful cocoa smell with a lil spice in there that i can tell is not hops f- wow can u say chocolate , very cocoa tasting , very hot spicy finish ... after looking at the bottle i see it is cayene..as the beer warms some notes of oak and vanilla are noticed .  m - somewhat thin , as one might expect .

this beer pours and the skunk arises . taste is medium carbonation with larger taste and is pretty clean tasting despite the skunk smell .  great looking ... deep gold color and a head that lasts with a lace that will be there tomorrow morning .  medium body is a bit light in the finish .

s - not much of a smell as i expected malts and dark fruits and a bit of spice . t - really malty , caramel , with dark fruits , slight raisins , and a really awesome finish that leaves a sweet aftertaste .  appearance is a crystal-clear auburn with a two-finger tan head that sticks to the sides of the mug .  mouthfeel is on the lighter side and sticky on the finish .
soft aromas of lemon , orange and dry wheat .  the beer is a very pretty dark amber color and looks great when held up to a light .  m - feels like a normal ris .

smell is interesting , i smell a slight spicy hop aroma , followed by some strong roasted malt accents .  bottle into a tulip glass the beer was a brilliant ruby red color with two fingers of head just rising above the rim of the glass . the head reduced to one finger of just off-white creaminess and remained throughout the sample leaving impressive lacing . from a visual standpoint - very nice beer .  good drinking for a spiced brew , 100 times better than buffalo bills pumpkin pee . i think this beer is better now that brooklyn brewery has it under its wing .

s- the nose is pretty faint .  a : pours an opaque black with ruby tint when held to the light . has a huge , generous cream-colored head that takes several minutes to recede to any drinkable level , leaving tons of sticky lacing down the glass as i wait . the head never fully vanishes .  i think i might even enjoy just smelling this beer as opposed to drinking it , actually . built on a malty brown ale base , the spices fill this beer out , but all pumpkin ales are inherently unbalanced because of this , imo . you have a great variety of tastes in the same spectrum competing , and there 's just no way to let one win out , even slightly . the finish is great , but there 's just something overwhelming about the initial taste that bugs me . a beer to drink a few times every fall . it 's better than most of the other attempts at pumpkin ale . this is one case where dh 's overattention to detail definitely pays off .

s - the scent is very subtle . there are some sweet hints here but it 's made up mostly of long roasted malt .  i loved the look in the pint glass . not a bad beer , it just does n't do muc hfor me ... but it looks cool .  tasting the beer , there is surprisingly not a strong wheat flavor but enough to really justify it as a wheat ale . only downside , and this is more of a personal note , wheat beers seem to me to have a bit of a grainier ( no pun intended ) fluid taste .

smell of herbs , a grassy smell , or possibly heather flowers .  pours pitch black with two fingers of creamy brown head .  hops are up front . anybody know what kind of hops these are ? thin but decent hint of malt . label claims 5.2 % abv . not excessively hopped but definitely one for the pale ale drinker .

while cold , the smell was very weak . it seemed to have promise , but as the beer warmed the smell started to let out some off flavors alongside the pumpkin .  pours a gorgeous hazy honey-yellow with a nice fluffy head ( 33cl bottle ) .  i took my first sip and was shocked , this tasted totally like an ipa . seemed overly carbonated and gassy . 21st amendment is a great little pub and they have a fine addition to their solid line up with this one .
the nose is yeasty , with faint fruit .  pours with an orange amber body topped by a thick white head with lots of lacing .  as noted , the mouthfeel is both on the thin and flat side .

you can just sit and smell this beer for hours and hours . strong , pine-sap hop nose follows in on the taste , though not as strong as you might expect . i 'm totally lost on the `` 7 types of hops '' ( sounds like some sort of brewery purchasing agent 's investment club to me ) . the `` 4x more hops than our ipa '' is also misleading , since this really makes you expect to get knocked flat on your ass with hops . i had to go re-read charlie pap 's sage advice about hop isomerization after scrathcing my head over the missed expectation . rather than just , `` oh yeah , there 's hops in there , too , '' hops infusion makes a point of deliberating as much loving , meticulous thought to the hops as is commonly obsessed over the grain bill in beer . in my mind , hops infusion succeeds handily in bringing hop recipes to the forefront and introducing me to an entirely new way to appreciate beer .  poured in a pint glass , excellent cascading effect , which concludes with a tall , thick head on the dark golden contents .  mouthfeel : average carbonation level . body is decent .

very clear with a nice round ring of foam atop the brew s_slightly phenolic with a mild banana nose .  it 's stellar . it 's how you expect a base imperial stout too look . pitch black hue , tan head , about an inch of head , that laces nicely .  hhaw : chemical sweetener , one-dimensional brownness , overweight body for the profile .

smells like sweet maple syrup - maybe a touch or coriander thrown in for good measure .  looks amazing and beautiful .  m - very carbonated , almost to a fault . thinner than it appears , and somewhat disappointing .

s : smells of cooked vegetables with hints of sweet malt . sorry , i do n't think this is infected , i just do n't think it smells good .  a . wonderful lacing and a quarter inch head . one sexy beer .  '' the body is a little thin , but for only $ 6 a bomber , this will be a common dessert beer at my house from now .

very , very nice looking . s : lots of bourbon and licorice , some chocolate . a bit too much for me . t : much better than aroma . however , still quite good .  this is one of the best looking beers i 've ever had . it pours well with about an inch high head that slowly lowers into a nice layer of dense foam . the color is a beautiful , dark red with a bit of amber .  m- a bit thin , slight astringency , slight carbonation bite , nice warming in the finish .

not much for a head , i could n't really pick up much of a nose on it . drank great though .  330ml bottle poured into unibroue glass feb11 2010 a a nice hazy orange that has tonnes of bubbles popping up from everywhere and a massive fluffy head that goes nowhere and leaves lots of thick lace . this is a sexy looking beer without doubt s some tropical fruits with a little yeast and sweet grains t i get lots of grainy cereal on top of what i smell perhaps with a little spicy and earthy flavor to go along with it m a little creamy yet somehow light and fluffy at the same time d i thought the 10.5 % on the label was a typo until i stood up and took a step sideways , so ya it may be dangerously drinkable i was surprised by this beer , i do n't think belgian ipa when i drink it but what do i know .  the mouthfeel is a little watery and thin .

2008 bottling appearance : as others have noted , this looks like prune juice , not beer - no carbonation at all smell : the best attribute of this beer , as the lack of carbonation has no impact ; the boozy element hits the nostrils right away , with a little bit of burn ; underneath is the dark fruit ( prune juice , perhaps ) and brandy taste : prune dominated dark fruit , with raisins and molasses , up front ; by mid-palate , they oak and brandy elements rise to the fore and linger after the swallow mouthfeel : medium to full body and flabby , with no carbonation but plenty of warmth drinkability : the flavors are enjoyable but this beer seems to be heading downhill , not only from the lack of carbonation , but from the effects of oxidation ; such a pity that the carbonation issues across so many of the lost abbey beers have compromised the brewery 's reputation but they chose economics over reputation note : i am now drinking the 2009 on 4/1/11 and have gotten over the lack of carbonation and decided just to focus on the flavors . the port-like character of the aroma and the taste is enticing and , while there is some booziness , it has mellowed into a flavorful melange .  beautiful cloudy , deep brown with ruby and caramel highlights . off-white 1 head that gradually fades away to a nice 1/8 cap . tons of lacing very pretty .  poured from a 12oz bottle ( shared with coastiefish ) into a tulip glass a= rich mahogany color with very thin off-white head s= sweet , tiny bit fruity ( fig ) , a little biscuity , alcoholic t= round fig/raisin at the front of the mouth , quickly tapers off to thin , alcoholic sweet malts m= complex ( see 'round ' and 'thin ' comment above ) , very tightly carbonated and dry d= very drinkable as it well balanced and not too `` extreme '' .

a good crisp red . the red color is nice and bright . the mouthfeel is terrific and gives it a terrific drinkablility at an irish pub that you ca n't always get in a guiness . the head is about one inch and has a sweet foamy flavor that belies that rest of the the flavor profile .  poured to a dark , opaque brown with thick tan head and great lacing .  it 's a smaller brewer , but sometimes , big things come in small packages . we enjoyed a growler of this bad boy and it delivered smiles all around . had a good smokey/malty taste mixed with an ever so humble bite of the hops . if i were going to brew an amber , this is what i would go for , espcially for how refreshing it was . try it if you stop by the brewery .

the aroma is lightly sweet and hoppy . the hop aroma and flavors are piney and a bit citrusy .  this beautiful beer fills my .5l munich pils glass perfectly ! deep amber color sparkles like a fine gemstone .  this continues into a palate that i hoped carried a little more density . while a very nice beer i came out with the feeling that some barrel aging would smooth and fill out the midpalate .

s - sweet and malty with a bit of coffee in the nose . the aroma would be the only disapointment for me as there just does n't seem to be much there .  reviewed 10/29/2007 ( bottle ) : pours a huge tan colored head , frothy , and lasting .  a nice beer that is easy to drink , but a little thicker body would be an improvement .

smells a little weak , but not bad . this is a drinkable beer , similar to most euro lagers .  a- gorgeous looking beer : muddy brown , bubbly at first but tempers quickly .  m - thin , carbonation is a bit high , mildly refreshing .

strong malt smell , light hop flavor .  a - very attractive cloudy dark brown color with a substantial foamy off-white head and good lacing .  it has too much carbonation for the style ( a bit over medium ) and has a little watery mouthfeel .

aroma is quite hoppy , prodominatly pine , with grapefruit and a hint of cracked peppercorn . : ( i was pretty excited to taste this after its wonderful appearance and terrific aroma . the lable design is also classy .  a - pours a very nice translucent amber color with a nice 2-finger off white head that left good lacing as it fell .  mouth is heavy and bitter with a cloying finish .

here 's the nitro can perspective on guinness : it suffers in the can . the canned product says that it is pasteurized , which can affect flavor adversely . secondly , when tasted side by side with the beamish nitro can stout , it tastes harsher and less appealing than beamish .  massive white angel-food-cake head billows up and lives forever ; an iceberg of cream sits in the middle with big bubbly arcs all over the glass .  m- im used to some more carbonation from my belgians , thats the only serious complaint i have about this brew .

s- fainter than i expected , roasted oats , a little coffee-ish . t- everything from the nose except much stronger with the addition of some chocolate hints through out . very nicely balanced .  appearance- light amber , maybe a darker peachy color . frothy and creamy looking 1/2 inch head which is super gleaming white .  i think i would have liked this beer even more if it was a bit lighter in mouthfeel .

the smell was very malty with a slight skunk scent to it .  dark brownish red with a huge fluffy tan head that seemed to stay around forever while covering the glass was thick lace rings .  m - the carbonation is starting to weigh on me as i go through the beer .

the nose detects some sweet brown sugar notes , while the palate experiences a well balanced blend of hops and malt , all of which encompassed in a biscuity mouthfeel .  gigantic 3 finger head that lasted forever . sticky lace all over and a puddle of head throughout the beer .  mouthfeel is on par for the style .

it did n't feature much of anything as far as aromas are concerned .  appearance - everything i 'd expect out of a double ipa . dark caramel colored with a head that 's a showstopper , as it foamed up to a good size with a pure white color . thick coating hangs around throughout with a heavy lace .  mf - kind of thin - but i think it 's normal for the style . this one has a stronger flavor but a watery mouthfeel like the other two altbiers i 've tried .

lacing is excellent with layers marking where i drank . s : nose is coarse and grainy with a slight hint of coffee and sugar . t : beginning is warming and oatmeal which develops and sours with hints of coffee . d : highly drinkable , flavor is n't too heavy but is complex enough to keep me intrigued . enjoyable if you 're looking to transition from a maltier palate to something that starts to be hoppy .  very dark brown inn color with a few fingers of beautiful tan foamy bubbly head . very good looking beer .  mouthfeel : bitter drinkability : goes down easy , great aftertaste . this is by far the best american macro lager that i have ever had !

s - not a whole lot released on this one , letting out slightly bitter notes with a pleasant maltiness . t - a simple taste with malt & a nice bitter after aftertaste .  a beautiful dirty-white head develops , at just under an inch in height . nice & frothy , it takes a minute & a half to settle .  not much carbonation , which is strange for anything with hefeweizen yeast .

it has an upfront bitterness to it but then you get some chocolate flavors on the back of the tongue . i 'm not getting much in aroma , but i have a cold so that may well be a factor .  draught - mcganns pub , doolin , co. clare a black , black stout , with a darker head than the standard draught .  not bad at all ... mouthfeel is ok . it feels nice and full on the front , but the finish leaves the beer with a lighter feel to it .

aroma was hop forward with quite a bit of malt to back it up , mainly toffee and caramel .  bottle enjoy before month notched-sep served in a pint glass fantastic appearance . glowing orangey-amber with a two-plus finger tall head of bubbly , light tan foam .  lighter mouth feel and for me extremely drinkable .

malt driven nose , a little old fashion .  this is one of the most beautiful beers i 've ever seen . it looked like what i picture a lothlorien beer would look like ( uh , maybe this should be my last beer of the night ?  m : definately this beer 's shortcoming . little to thin for the bold taste .

not a whole lot here in the smell dept , faint hay .  a 22oz bottle with 62906 stamped on the back of the label . it was a clear light yellow , with a thick white head that lasted forever . impressive lacing .  it 's a little black , a little viscous , a little chocolatey sweet , a little smokey , a little creamy , a little meaty , and a little carbonated .

s - sweet and malty . very faint . d - wow !  poured into a duvel chalice glass.. a : very light coloring , ridiculously large pillow on top that i have rarely seen on any other beer .  the mouthfeel is lighter-medium bodied with a very easy carbonation in the mouth .

not too many aromas present on the taste . tastes great , very creamy with carmel and molasses flavors , slightly malty .  pours pitch black wih a coffee colored head .  rogue ales are easily becoming more present in my inventory.this one is no exception.i expected more malt out of this , but i should of known that the rogue in all of us loves the hops.slightly weak aroma until warmer , a lighter-bodied feel for an ale , but the finish and drinkability makes it great sports beer.looks great in a big , fat mug too.i will consume many .

not much aroma till it warmed a bit , then nice clean malts , slightly sweet smells , with an unusual roast to it that made it lean towards a swartzbier , but not over the top .  a : pours reddish amber color , 2 finger width frothy white head , good lacing down the glass s : strong piney hoppiness , slight yeasty smell .  m : immediately strikes me as having a buttery smoothness . slightly thin in the mouth but satisfying . could use a bit more carbonation .

mmmmm , smells good . real good .  got it home , popped the top , poured into my new belgium globe ... apperance - perfect , dark , rich and cloudy amber color , for an ale this is perfect .  medium light body , a bit thin for an h-w : more like a witbier .

s : strong spices up front including nutmeg and cinnamon . there is some pumpkin to be found along with some sweet malts and a bit of cloves . t : similar to the taste , there is a lot of spice which mask other flavors that are trying to come through . o : this seems like a decent pumpkin offering , but there are many better choices available .  a - beautiful huge fluffy 2 inch light tan head , dies down semi-quickly but leaves quite a bit of foam on the glass on it 's way down . lacing is really just foam so far , but lots of it . guy on the bottle looks like mike mogis .  as for its mouthfeel , it was far thinner than i 'd expected , which might make it more suitable for session drinking than an average stout .

s : not overly aromatic , but some pleasant floral notes notable .  black with thick and creamy tan head - this head held peaks if you whisked it with a utensil - i got ta say that i have never really seen - you could eat this beer with a spoon .  the body is somewhat awkwardly light for the heavy roast and dried fruit notes , but i 'm of two minds about this because it also improves the drinkability .

the smell was rather faint ( i do n't have the greatest nose ) and it did n't impress me as being particularly good or bad . i am a fan of stout to begin with , so my review might be a bit biased in that respect , but i have to say that beamish is hard to beat .  this is certainly a beautiful looking beer . the color is almost perfect deep amber . the head showed excellent retention .  in the mouth it 's got some body , but i 've had better .

s- just can smell a very sweet malt scent .  pours out golden amber and sits a foggy reddish amber-brown in the glass . big billowy off-white head caps the beer . very nice .  mouthfeel is crisp and refreshing . i like this beer , the hops are a little over the top , there is n't much balance there , it 's kinda thin , but good and refreshing .

smell : surprisingly mild . as others have noted , it smells strongly of grain , backed up by a very subtle backbone of cinnamon and clove . taste : fortunately , the taste is much more interesting than the smell . i see this conceptually as a great transitional beer between summer and fall -- it 's got all the brisk drinkability of a summer beer , but with a level of complexity and depth i 'd expect from autumn .  clear golden-orange with generous head and good lacing .  lots of carbonation feels a bit prickly on the tongue .

it does n't really have a smell , just a faint hint of chocolate , but the taste is very smooth , a great roasted taste . very easy to drink if you like the style , i highly reccomend if you 're looking for a cheap stout .  pours a deep and opaque black , like night , thick brown head , nice lacing and great retention , looks pretty badass .  poured from a bottled into a belgian style tulip glass . nice head formation torward the top of the glass . citrus and coriander on the nose . formed tiny ( champagne like ) bubbles that lasted until i was done with this 11.2 oz bottle ( not long ) . nice lace . smooth and well balanced . wonderful golden color . easy to drink . perfect summertime beer .

the aromas are subtle and plain . i 'm picking up some earthy spices and a slight fruitiness .  it looks amazing . no light will pass through this beer very black .  m : thin to medium viscosity , slightly acidic on the palate into the middle but then becoming smooth , with low carbonation .

this gives off soft aromas close to sweet and raw dough , and a dry stick of topps bubble gum . to me this has a unique taste for a tripel .  cloudy yellow , full saison head , which lasts . great appearence , like most saisons .  felt of in the mouth , but was slightly bitter and acidic .

smell : fruity and cheesey . it smelled as though i should have a good cut of cheddar to go with it . oranges , tangerines , orange colored fruit . i felt like this could replace the standard `` lawnmower '' beer . replace that feeling with and beer with a don de dieu , and you 'll smile through the next mouthful of grass clippings  beamish appearance was wonderful . a very dark brown , to black , with good creamy head and good lacing .  mouthfeel : not very thick . lots of carbonation .

after reading reviews on this beer i decided to get one . i thought the can was very plain to start . i poured it into my guinness glass andit was appropriate because the beer turned out to be a lighter colored version of it . this beer is delicious and i regret i only bought one . creamy on the toungue.i just wish the abv was 1 % higher and it would be perfect .  a black pour with a solid brown head .  full bodied , rich , sharp carbonation and pretty hot .

i came across this while stuck in boston during a snow storm , and i was immediately pleased to have found it . i have n't had many reds to compare it to , but i know i liked this one . the flavor was good and well balanced , in line with what i have come to expect from sam adams . it had a clean after taste and a definite drinkability . i did n't want anything else while i was in boston .  apparence : bright red and dark color with a thick dense head .  light-medium bodied with very high carbonation with a prickly mouthfeel .

aroma , not horrible , even get a little agave sweetness .  lots of crater-strewn head that looks rather picturesque . this is a beautiful beer to behold .  m : the light body is thin and dry . carbonation is about right .

s- roasted malt dominates .  ok , on to the dark lord . it poured a small head of dark brown fine to large sized bubbles . it is dark , thick and i mean thick ! 70,000 mile old motor oil thick and black as a black hole in space . all hail the dark lord !  mouthfeel is a bit disappointing .

the smell is a little weak with a spicy and grapefruit scent . their is a light aroma of malt but the hops dominate the scent .  frickin ' a beautiful . i shit you not . dark and rich and black and medium dark head of tiny bubbles that lasts forever . not ridiculously thick and certainly not thin and they really must have worked at this . beautiful .  poured out a nice dark gold hazy beer , moderately carbonated . smells of banana / alcohol esters . a semi sweet beer alcohol is very well hidden.mouthfeel is so so . very drinkable for a tripel , this is the type of beer that could totally sneak up on you .

shoved my nose down into this guy and pulled out roasted espresso bean , cocoa powder , and some hints of hops which i really liked . i was n't really expecting that , made me excited to take a sip . this beer is quite tasty , its not like chocolate , its more like cocoa powder and roasted espresso bean .  appearance this beer looks gorgeous ! its a dark , dark brown in color with some ruby hues and a beautiful head .  very cloying . it just does n't seem like beer or ale or any other above average abv malt beverage ... more like a weak apertif .

the aroma is that if light malt and a piney hop aroma . the hop aroma is not what you would expect at all from a ipa . it is very light compared to most other ipa 's .  poured a glowing golden orange color with huge carbonation and a fluffy white head .  s-hay , rust t-sour , citrus peel , fruit stone , m-medium , somewhat gritty d-nice but not the best in this category . would pair nicely with food . i would drink this beer again .

faint smell , but not a suprise for this type of beer .  pours out to a clear medium amber , forming a tall , quickly expanding and sustained meringue-like white head with excellent retention and solid lacing . good looking beer .  mouth feel is sharp and crisp , with a high carbonation level . overall , good appearance , body , and blend .

smell - very evident belgian yeast aroma , but not a strong aroma otherwise taste - this is not an overpowering beer , but there is great variance in flavors .  goldish copper color with a white head with great retention and lacing .  spices , and a dry carbonated finish with a touch of grassy hops .

some may think im crazy for saying this , but i found it to have the same taste as a very very weak ipa . i 'll probably buy this again sometime , just for the fact that its important to support your locally brewed american , oh wait , i mean belgian beer .  the beer after its disinterment from the 12-ounce brown bottle sets in the glass an atramentous color with a thick creamy chocolate brown head that is modest in size and after its dissolution the lace forms a glutinous sheet that melds with the glass .  mouthfeel is thin and light .

first smell it had the grassy hop scent with a slight smell of caramel .  pours a dirty amber color with a huge yellowish head that fills the entire goblet and leaves cottony cloudlike chunks of lace all over the glass ... completely covered .  mouthfeel - leaves a little to be desired .

overall this beer looks and smells really good , but the taste just doesnt work so well for me .  the head looks simply amazing . the lacing is good .  m : thin viscosity with a low level of carbonation .

the smell is strange . i get a good whiff of some malt but i also get something very tart and maybe medicinal ? not the best nose out there for the style .  it looked great -- poured a deep red with a substantial head , leaving lacing on the glass -- but the smell was nothing special for me , i got some hops but not much more complexity than that .  m : overly carbonated which made the flavour hard to find at times , swirl it a bit before beginning the drink , overall medium-bodied and relatively smooth .

s-not much on the nose , some malts and a hint of hops . its not challenging or complex , just an easy drinking ale .  deep dark brown almost black in color . huge foamy , dark tan head that lasted all the way to the bottom of the glass followed with lace all along the sides .  mouth feel - creamy and slightly astringent overall - this is a good beer , but i prefer the un-oaked unearthly .

smell is very light . some light herbaceous hops and a rather clean malt nose .  pours a 1.5 finger light tan whitish head over a crystal clear dark orange-gold liquid .  m - light to medium bodied . it tasted a little watery for me .

s - malty , hoppy , slightly citrus , with some chocolate at the end . t - smoky , malty , roasted flavor .  three fingerd of light tan head form up slowly , thickly . a nice looking lacy weave around the glass as it recedes .  mouthfeel : medium-light body . medium carbonation .

really nice looking pumpkin ale . smell is a little disappointing to me . it 's got all the typical stuff , pumpkin , brown sugar , cinnamon , nutmeg ... but it 's just really on the weak side for me .  pours chestnut with a big , fluffy , off-white , long lasting head . lots of lacing .  i feel it is a tad thin as are all the lagunitas offerings i 've tried . very good , but with some more body could be fantastic .

it 's slightly fruity , but very clean overall .  a : pitch black with a big , fluffy , dark brown head with great retention . lacing is awesome .  it 's a light bodied and fairly highly carbonated beer that is meant to be served cold , but iunlike typical macro lagers can be enjoyed at 45 -50 degrees .

malty earthy smell . super smooth silky flavor .  pours dark gold with a huge fluffy white head that lasted for a good 15 min .  what a name ! good thing this one lives up to that mouthful . a cloudy ( unfiltered ) straw gold extra special bitter with orange hues . developed a creamy , glass-crawling white head with good retention that left some nice lacing . strong , hoppy aroma with a medium-heavy body . malty bread , apricots , butterscotch , citrus notes . yum . a great example of their extreme series , bold and complex .

aroma - malty and raisiny sweet as expected , but not real intense . drinkability - tasty and dangerous , they are smart to serve this in the smaller 10-ounce goblets .  the head is a pillow of dark cream , awesome head retention -- it does n't dissipate at all .  mouthfeel : the body on this beer is fairly thin .

all in all , it is very pleasing . malt smell is very bready .  in an imperial pint glass it looks deep , deep brown with a cocoa colored head . very impressive head as it was soft but thick and never dissipated .  m : a little thin , nothing remarkable here .

( no concerns there as you definitely want to let the temperature get to 50-55 degrees f. ) s : a little disappointing but safely within the style . light grassy hops with a lemony citrus twang . d : very drinkable .  great milkshakey , frothy eggshell of a head . nice cola color with carbination rising up .  t - rich , nothing really overpowers here , a good balance , alcohol on the back end though , really comes through surprisingly for only a 7 % brew m - alcohol finish , can really feel the burn , strange o - pretty good pumpkin brew for sure , just need to mellow out the alcohol burn on the back end

nose is full of smoked meat -- delicious bacon-y goodness . smells awesome , very powerful . the flavor on it is also very good , though it kind of draws back the smokiness a little ( still pretty smokey ) .  a- i love the look of this beer . laces the glass nicely .  body is a little light for a stout .

the aroma has a lot going on but is very subtle . not like other imperial ipa 's that jump out and grab your nostrels .  5.0 a : this is quite a dark one with pitch black color . two and a half fingers of frothy , creamy light brown head that has good retention to the last 1/2 inch , then refuses to fall any more for several minutes . the appearance is a thing of beauty , with the nose nearly as enchanting .  sweet to start , wheat , a little honey , coriander , oranges , a little ginger ... .feel is nice to start but a very light and watery finish ... easy to drink .

s- smells intense . bourbon mostly , with hints of coffee , chocolate , vanilla , and maltiness . a very nice combination of flavors that keeps me coming back for more . m- the beer is very well balanced . it has a pronounced bourbon flavor , with out being too overboard . it could use a little more time to mellow out , as the 07/08 kbs i 've had are much smoother .  almost pitch black , just a bit of light in the pour . a perfect two fingers of tan head . looks beautiful .  feel was medium-bodied , smooth , and oily . in a word , crap ( spoken with a good scottish brogue accent ) .

a : copper , clear , head with staying power s : pretty much all malt , not getting much hops , less than you would expect from an ipa anyway t : huge malt , lots of toast and caramel , almost to a fault , then plenty of hops to back it up , really great sipper .  pours medium red with orange-plum highlights , tall beige head .  light carbonation .
s - smell is ... odd .  a - pours a solid black , no light or anything other radiation is getting through this brew .  m- a little thin .
