s - slight sweet aromas from the bottle . t - nice sweet dark fruits and boozy finish that warms the stomach .  bottled on 5th week of may pours an effervescent & slightly hazed straw/golden with 3 fingers of fluffed up eggshell-white head . crazy lacing 7 head retention s : lemon & grassy notes t : rich honey malt , a little lemon & white pepper .  after i got over the flatness characteristic to the style , the beer really started to grow on me . each sip i enjoyed the beer more . there really is n't much aftertaste at all as i finish through the beer . i really enjoyed this and might go out of my way to try this again .

paulaner brauerei munchen -- paulaner wiesn bier limited edition ! lacy 1/2 '' white good retention head.clear fizzy bright gold color.sweet bavarian yeast mild noble hop stank front.smooth pale malt delicate butter sweet crisp clean pale caramel fest body.mild hop clean dry end.odd hops ? purchased 2 for $ 12.49 @ seattle fred meyer -- ballard on 9/25/2010  outstanding look to this baby ... . lovely amber color , and a huge , frothy head ! unreal ! head lasted all day , and left great lacing .  lots of hops in the taste , more than expected actually , along with roasted malts , coffee , and hints of bitter chocolate , and carmel . lingering bitterness on the palate . recomended .

s-i am not sure if this was a cause of being in a growler for a couple weeks ( i did n't drink it right away ) , but the aroma was faint although pleasant . floral citrus but just not much of it .  pours slightly cloudy orange amber color with a nice dense 2.5 finger off white head with great retention that reduces to a thick lacing cap that lasts . some very nice lacing coats the glass as you drink as well .  consistency is a bit watery . light carbonation moves the flavors , but not much flavor lingering .
aroma minimal . just a little bready .  a crazy 2 1/2 finger tan head with unbelievable retention and great lacing .  medium body yet very drinkable .

aroma is of some slight brown roasted malts . aroma is less sweet than anticipated .  pours black with a big brown head .  the mouth is nearly overcarbonated , which is kind of common , which lends it to feeling thin .

s- nutty and bready malts . nothing much else .  this beer pours a ruby red color with some brown tints to it . it has a thick fluffy light brown head that fades ever so slowly , leaving a good lacing .  mouthfeel : light-bodied -- a bit too light , i think . very minimal carbonation . i would like it a lot more if it did n't feel so light-bodied and if it were n't so lacking in carbonation , but it 's still one of the better american ipas i 've had .

i would prefer almost any other drink to a corona wihtout lime . first , without lime : nothing impressive about the appearance or smell , but it 's really the awful taste that kills this beer . bitter in an unsophisticated , unappealing sort of way , it makes you wish you paid half the money for something that is better straight out of the box . the lime drowns out the crappy bitterness of corona and gives the beer an enjoyable sour flavor . all in all , lime is undisputably the savior of this otherwise extremely below-average beer .  12oz bottle , bb 3/11/11 pours a very nice 2 finger head that just keeps rising aroma is very roasty , like a porter or stout , at this point carbonation on side of the bottle looks massive .  mouthfeel loses points because the carbonation is too soda-like .

light brown in color with an almost grayish-white hue throughout the beer that looks sort of like when snow when falls on bare earth . the best of the beers i tried while i was the brewer 's alley . it was smooth and easy drinking and went great with my french fries and watching television in the bar .  pours a rich dark brown with a tan creamy head that lingers . after cupping the top of my pint glass and swishing it , i got some faint coffee and alcohol .  this beer has a medium amber color , and creamy but light and airy head . domion has an even , almost wood-like flavor throughout . this beer was *not* to my liking , but you might enjoy it . - backdated tasting : i first reviewed this beer on 01jul03 , this post is based on notes from that review .

i note that it had little to no smell to it besides the normal beer smell . this was kind of a dissapointment i was hoping for a nice roaste malt scent . tasting it took care of that .  this beer looked magnificent in the glass .  smells of thick syrupy caramel and citrusy hops , as well as a faint roasty characteristic . the roasted taste is a lot more prevalent than the smell would suggest , and plays well with the perfect level of hop bitterness . a little lighter-bodied than i feel it should be , but the drinkability is very good .

an off sweet brown sugar aroma with a bit of nutty character and that is with my nose deep in the snifter , odd .  a stunning and brilliantly clear ruby brown lager poured from the bottle into a pint glass . the clarity and color make this beer super inviting .  m : thin and average for the style .

4.0 s : decent aroma with a pleasant biscuity nuttiness . earthy hops and caramel .  stone has some great beers so i figured it is time to try this one ... a : looks awesome . it poured great . super dark with hints of ruby highlights hidden around the edges .  it dries out pretty quickly though , giving the impression of thinness . its a bit spicy , with modest carbonation .

aroma is good but not very belgian ... fruits are big and round , no spiciness detected , and the malt is reminiscent of an english pale ale . no hops in the aroma and the yeast is seemingly mia .  beautiful looking beer .  what balance ? ! this is typically not the style i chase after , but being in switzerland , this was one of the few beers that i could find plenty of . the name sounded nice , so i risked trying a 1l as it would be cheaper in the long run , and i did n't expect this brew to be too offensive . it 's smell was n't rediculous , but the head was big and frothy , yet not long lasting . i would have to say this is a nicely balanced beer that i believe anyone could enjoy . if you are stranded in switzerland and see this brew , give it a try as it is quite tastey . after having another swiss beer , this one gives me hope . i look forward to trying more swiss lagers in the near future .

s - was n't crazy about the nose . had a bit of hop aroma as well as some grainy malt scent , however i also got an off-putting sourness that made me a bit wary of trying this beer . t - luckily , this beer impressed me .  fun to watch and once settled , looks full and rich , with dense pillow of foam atop a black , ruby-edged body .  m - nice carbonation . decent body that 's on the thin side with a respectable structure . short finish .

aromas are too obviously alcoholic , with sweet toffee-like malts and faintly floral hops ( not nearly hoppy enough ! ) failing to enter the foreground . overall , i love it .  a - beautiful brownish red brew , cloudy from the swirls and currents of yeast circling around it 's massive glass . produced a three tip head of froth that stuck around a while . nice lacing .  mouthfeel - medium carbonation , light body .

compared other commercial brews that contain them , this one is much better . spicy , hop flavor , bitterness with a nice balance of malt sweetness .  it 's got a perfect appearance with a very light golden color , excellent clarity and a large white head .  m : light body with moderately prickly carbonation .

caramel malts . not unpleasant but not much going on . taste had biscuity tones with a slight alcohol taste as common in scotch ales .  the smokin ' lager poured a cloudy copper-red with a lot of tiny floating particulates . it had a huge light tan head the had great retention .  this is a great beer for a reasonable cheep price . its one of my personal favorites . it accentuate the taste and sell of the beer and makes it easier to drink b/c without a lime its not as good . i dont think you need to pour it out of the bottle b/c i think the bottle adds something , but either way its still a great beer for eeryday drinking and ecpecially by the pool or beach !

smell is interesting , almost a bitterness like citrus smell but none of that came through in the taste .  bottle in pint glass a - beautiful copper brown with a light caramel colored head that dissipates quickly s - leaves a lot to be desired .  mouthfeel is a tad too sticky but the drinkabilty is excellent .

even brown/black head s - very faint smell , subtle hints of sweetness and bitterness t - extremely complex taste .  pours a two finger head with a huge cascading border . liquid is nearly clear golden copper .  i poured a 12 ounze bottle into a pint glass and immediatly noticed the beautiful color and head . the heaed left much lace which was nice and sticky . there was a stong hop aroma and a strong hop taste . neither was overpowering and both were artfully crafted and mixed . do n't drink and review .

looks damn good . aroma was a little weak , but had nice roasted coffee malt ( mostly roasted/burnt with a hint of coffee ) .  a - poured into a tulip glass . golden to bronze color that pours a high white foam that reminds me of lemon meringue . laces the glass beautifully .  a lot of carbonation overall : i actually really enjoyed this beer .

a : golden amber , coarse weak head s : strongest quality : fairly standard floral , greeny , veg scent t : godawful . the hoppy scents lead you to believe that there will be something *there* : but it 's bland , watery ( i really believe that there is more taste in a miller or bud light ) , absent until the finish -- unfortunately , where what i can only describe as candy-scented plastic , the plastic of tupperware , assaults you .  this beer pours a dark , dark brown color through which almost no light can pass .  m : light bodied with moderately-high carbonation .

aroma is rich bread , fruitiness with dried fruits , metal , wildflowers , and overall very nice . taste is lightly juicy-spicy with light spicy-zesty bitterness just dominating , with light , vague juicy fruitiness , coriander , light bright alcoholic quality , and a faint hint of gin-like character .  really fantastic presentation .  mouthfeel was probably the worst aspect of the beer ( still not terrible though ) . a tad thin for what i want from an impy stout .

appearance is average , but the nose is complex and very pleasing . flavor is not as complex , but nice distinction and balance .  a- absolutely pitch black , thick and syrupy . the head is very thick and brown and settles to a nice covering . the lacing is pretty sweet .  m : pretty moderate carbonation on a medium body .

the smell is just so so . i does n't smell bad , but the it is a little weak . the taste is very pleasant . it is very malty with a hint of coffee .  a- a careful pour from the bottle yielded a 3/4 '' creamy well-retained head with fabulous lacing . the body was a well-carbonated bright light amber . picture perfect !  mf : average . carbonation is pretty good .

something is off with the aroma , the first thought i have is vegetables , i 've had this happen with a few beers ( such as gubna , which is a different style ) , the byproduct to cause this aroma is not unpleasant but it 's just not right for a beer , behind the aroma of green bell peppers is some caramel malt , no real hop aroma to speak of but that is expected for once . things started off wrong with the aroma and just could n't impress with the taste .  this stout had a thick off-white head.the color was an opaque black.solid beige foam lace circled the glass.first taste is of coffee.hints of smoke later follow.creamy mouthfeel but somewhat watery for a stout.slight bitterness with a dry finish.not the best stout , but not the worst.i would drink again .  m : a bit harsh , and difficult to even sip , think champagne all the way .

definitely enjoyed the wake n bake and big hoppy monster , plust the rye pale ale is n't bad . corn taste and nothing too special .  even a day after it was tapped , this nitro pour esb collaboration between sierra & the three penny bros. was exceptional . this was the last keg left of this brew , and it lacked any discernible aromas .  medium to light bodied .

smell- does n't smell like anything but water until its either flat and/or skunked . taste- smooth , though not much to it , your run of the day ab light beer . drinkability- well its a beer in which you can get drunk off of for pretty cheap .  beautiful looking beer .  but , thin and slightly gritty in the mouth . not a bad stout , but lacks the fullness and breadth to be an imperial . an excellent stout overall , and many no doubt will overlook the thinness in deference to its amazing sweetness .

a - reddish brown color with about a 1 finger head s - ca n't really detect anything in the smell , which was weird because of the taste t - absolute taste explosion . so many tastes going on at once . great combo of wheat , caramel , and malts .  this is a great looking pale ale . a vibrant golden color with a large white head that has wonderful retention . a thick cap remains for as long as there is fluid in the glass . of course a lot of lacing is left behind . all beers should look this good .  could use a little more heft in mouthfeel .

i tried this beer at gabf . loved the vw and loved the taster books . s-well there was some burnt aroma rolling off early with a carmel finish .  pours dark brown with a huge dense persistent head .  mouthfeel is a bit soapy .

not a ton going on with the smell to be honest . t : the taste is phenomenal and is really what makes this a great stout .  this beer 's physical appearance is attractive , notably transparent and focused on clarity . gorgeous .  mouthfeel - light smoothness , carbonation is a tad low . average weight .

the planter overflowed with marigold , alyssum , and a small manicured tree . i noted that my beer was not merely gold ; it was marigold . this is a good belching beer . bombay bomber is clear with a faint but hoppy aroma . its lace is formed of large breakaway chunks of head .  poured a very clear copper color with a huge and sticky tan head , tons of lacing and lasts forever .  medium carbonation , very light and crisp with a slight malt taste mixed with a nice strawberry flavor . it 's sweet , but not a bad overpowering sweetness and i think the brew is just the right mix of fruit to give it flavor and still be a good beer . this was very tasty and refreshing , went down easy ( almost too easy as i drank 2 in 15 minutes ) , and is the type of beer i could drink all night when it 's hot outside . overall a good summer beer !

s-smells interestingly of pineapple , some roasted notes and some chocolate notes ... . kind of a weak nose t-i 'm still getting a bit of that pineapple in the taste with chocolate and some very light roasted notes . the mouthfeel is out of this world and if the nose was a little better , i think this would be an amazing beer .  fantastic head retention , and there are sheets of lacing stuck to the glass . ca n't imagine a dunkelweizen looking any better .  m - watery soft in the feel which is surprising when i consider it looks like motor oil in the pour .

nose is sweet candied apples , toffee , fairly rich malt , a touch of sweet rum , and some grain underneath . good and expressive . fairly rich , syrupy palate .  appearance : this poured beautifully with a heavy full head colored orange/tan .  mouthfeel is smooth , but a touch watery and thin .

smell : no noticeable aroma other than a tiny hint of banana .  a- deep dark rich brown . a few shades from black . rich thick fluffy 3 finger head with a careful pour . major layers of lacing .  the carbonation is a little weaker than most weissbiers ; the bubbles are small . the liquid is very smooth and a little thick . a textbook example of a hefeweissen , maybe with a slight reservation for the weak carbonation

smelled very fruity , pears and apple . tasted the same , crisp , fruity and smooth .  a - a great looking beer . leaves flawless lacing on every sip and a continual small white head throughout . i gave similar marks to ommegang 's hennepin , which also had superb head retention and lacing .  m/d - mouthfeel is a bit thin , but that 's not unusual for style .

picked up @ the brewery a- pours a clear deep copper color with about a 1-finger white head . s- trying to pick up something here some light hints of toasted caramel t- sweet at first , caramel malt taste , then finishes like a crisp brown ale m- great mouthfeel starts out smooth and finishes with a nice crisp burnt bite d- very nice , had it with a salmon dinner , and went down nice and smooth , complemented some of the spicy flavors overall a great alt beer , i just wish this stuff was more readily available , but i guess good things are hard to find  pours an absolutely beautiful rub red color . has a huge tan head , and a ot of bubble coming up in my duvel glass . one on the best looking beers i have ever seen .  m - lacks a bit of carbonation for the style .

very nice . taste : malt , but with a strong taste of fish oil .  looks black . light brown head with consistently thin retention & good lacing at the onset . overall , retention is wispy , though there 's a solid wall of lace . very impressive .  the flavor is rather nice sweet roastiness medium feel in the mouth and a little to much carbonation for the style for me .

disappointed by the lack of aroma . sweet malty flavor , with hints of honey and pear , some tartness in the finish . damn good oktoberfest beer .  the beer poured into the octagonal tumbler i chose , clear golden with a very slight amber hue . abundant carbonation .  the mouthfeel is on the light side , but like i said , this is consistent with it being a wonderful session beer .

s - not a lot going on aroma wise . slightly grassy and grainy , with a touch of pine and wood .  what a fantastic looking stout .  the mouthfeel could be said to be a little thin , but it 's not a big issue , but the beer is definitely too carbonated for the style . lackluster mouthfeel aside , this beer drinks nowhere near 13 % .

s. no strong smell at all . t. very wonderful . layers of mocha , chocolate malt , cocoa powder and grains .  massive four finger white head is foamy and tight with unbelievable retention . carbonation is very visible and very steady .  mouthfeel seemed a little lighter than i imagined after the beer was in the glass . maybe it was a lack of carbonation or something but it seemed like nothing was there , a little watered down but still average .

the rochefort 10 pours dark brown into the chalice , forming a 1/2 inch off-white head that leaves whisps of lacing along the surface of the glass the beer has a nose of belgian yeast and caramel malt . there is also an oily/alcohol smell that can barely be detected .  this beer poured the most beautiful old gold i have ever seen , with a petit ' white head .  on the other hand , it does a great job of capturing the `` black india pale ale , '' what with the paper-thin mouthfeel and big bitterness .

okay seriously , this sounds wicked awesome and unique . s. maple granola , not strong though , just peaking through . the maple is present as a side note , adding a woodsy aroma . oats are similar in that they are a faint whiff of morning oatmeal . totally disappointed . d. just unremarkable .  pours a four finger light brown head that fades slowly leaving a good lace . nice clear deep mahogany color .  m : considerable carbonation , medium body , and bitter ending .

s : a lot of caramel malt , some piney and light citrus hops . caramel character is very candy-like . not much to look at and the alcohol is a little too apparent , but it 's still nice .  appearance- just a tad cloudy amber-orange colored pour . creamy as hell looking sterling white head of about 3/4 inches . a nice layer of head remains constant throughout the whole beer .  m. mouthfeel is actually slightly refreshing and similar to a seltzer .

possibly due to a significant amount of hops for an ipa . s - malty bready aroma .  poured into an imperial pint glass , did the cascading thing , forming a huge , thick , frothy , slightly off-white head , which had amazing staying power , as expected for a nitro can .  a couple sips of this and i 'm done . it drinks sticky and dry and leaves that godforsaken after taste behind .

aroma is very light and soft ; clean , crisp , and rounded with a pale grassy , whole grain maltyness that would seem like what a pilsner should smell like . just not very aromatic in any fashion . a nearly perfect pils .  exceptional presentation with a beautiful champagne bottle . the beer poured amber with a creamy and long lasting white head . perfect appearance .  bland overall , but what is there is n't particularly pleasant . dirty malt flavor with very light bitterness and not very good at all .

as much i tried , i could n't smell much anything .  i love my darker beers , and i am definately going to love the rest of the sam smith 's range . the head just is n't disappearing and the beer is as black as sin .  mouthfeel was on the thin side , but the flavor was a riot of spices - nutmeg , cinnamon , pine and clove along with dried fruit - plum and raisin as well as chocolate !

not for the faint of heart . this sucker 's strong . a really dark coffee flavor with a distinct boozy back end . i enjoyed it a lot but do n't think i could do more than maybe one more bottle . the texture was a nice , thick , oily creaminess and it poured with a hefty head . pretty much hit that nail on the head .  i got a huge pillow white head over a nice clear straw colored beer . beautiful . the head slowly fades in places , leaving rock-like protrusions and lovely lace clinging to the side of the glass .  the body is moderately full , the carbonation is kind of hard to predict , but is a little low .

smell of roasted malts , some chocolate and a faint toasted wood scent .  a - pours a hazy golden straw with a 2 finger mounded head with outstanding retention . big cliffs of frothy lacing left behind .  mouthfeel : creamy with medium body , but the bottle i 'm drinking is a little flat .

s - mild roasted barley noticeable , but not much more .  creamy head ( a bit thin , but due to a very full pour ) , recedes to thin but constant creamy layer . amazing curtain of lacing all down the glass .  body is a little light .

very good lacing & above average head retention s : slight breadyness t : caramel & toast up front .  mild aroma in a black body with an energetic head of light brown fine bubbles . near the top of the head below the beer line a continuous flow of small bubbles can be observed .  smelled of raspberries of course , but with a nice yeasty undertone . taste was very sweet , like raspberry pop . we had this as a before-dinner drink , and everyone was pretty happy with it . my mother ca n't believe it 's actually beer . i recommend as a dessert beer or a beer to give people who do n't think they like beer .

smell : rather bland but a slight citrus smell , more specifically lemon taste : mildly sweet taste similar to many beers of this style but lacking any strong spice .  sinebrychoff- porter a- black , plain and simple , jet black . looks like a rootbeer float sorta .  it was a very refreshing beer , but due to the fairly high carbonation would be difficult for me to drink more than a few .

there was really no aroma involved at all .  light orange color with a beautiful , authentically belgian , well lasting foam .  once it hits your mouth , the carbonation in it kind of picks at your cheeks . that 's why i marked it down a bit on mouthfeel .

nothing to note here with the aroma . the best thing i can say about this beer is that it 's nicely balanced and very easy to drink . i guzzled three of these in no time .  poured black with a huge two finger light tan head . fantastic head retention with tons of sticky lacing coating the glass after the head diminished some . a beautiful beer . incredible aromas from this beer .  feel is a little astringent from the depth of dark malts used .

not much in the nose , slight aroma of fruits and some alcohol is detectable .  a solid 2 fingers of buttery foam formed slowly on top of the body . the color of this offering is pretty amazing ... slightly hazy amber with a dense ruby center and lighter golden edges . the head had great retention and really clings to the glass well . starting off great ! !  mouthfeel-medium low body , medium low carbonation . if i had one complaint about this beer , it would be that the carbonation could be a little bit higher ( or more towards effervescent ) .

s- quite bad . first time i 've had a belgian beer smell like a heineken . and acutally , its worse . this beer may be better in a non-tulip glass , because that way you wo n't catch so much of that crap smell .  appearance- an almost overwhelming head that just barely exploded oput of the glass upon the first pour . great , and thick head retention . great deep amber , almost rust related color . awesome bubbling combined with what i would the slide fade lacing .  the mouthfeel is a little watery .

this thing smells like a 3muskateer dunked into a hot chocolate ... unbelievably sweet smell . alcohol becomes more apparent as i sit with this , however the smooth , roasty , dark chocolate flavors really win , i can taste a candy bar with each sip , really cool actually .  pours super black .  dryness & oakyness , vanilla , a touch of caramel in the finish mf : chewy , low carbonation , richer with each sip & warming as well drinks great for the style & abv , not as good as ba boris , but nice .

smells lightly fruity , with some notes of roasted malts .  anyway ... pours a burnt amber color with a few centimeters head into my scotch glass ... looks perfect ! not too much not too little .  m : a nice fullness to this beer .

s - kind of sweet and maybe malty but the smell was very weak and hard to distinguish . m - very smooth with medium carbonation d - i started off worried about this one after pouring it and giving it a good smell . nothing too impressive until it actually hit my tongue .  a : thick , white , creamy head . definitely get guinness if it 's between guinness and a watery american macrobrew . if it 's between guinness and another stout , go for the other stout .  impressively , no heat . fantastic feel .

aroma is very much an american hops extravaganza -- extraordinary blend of citrus and pine . flavor is on the big side for an apa , strong malt balanced with hop bitterness . caramel and biscuits in the flavor as well .  the beer poured a rich amber with a nice tan head , the presentation left you saying now that 's what a beer should look like .  m : medium-weight , ultra-creamy texture , the carbonation is plentiful and helps cleanse the palate for a perfect finish . exceptional .

some resinous hops and fruity plum notes hang in the background . t - sweet caramel and lightly burnt toast up front with a little bit of warm alcohol and hop bitterness . the aroma is exceptional ; complex and well balanced with all of the classic barleywine notes touched upon . this is a very nice example of the style ; it would be nice to see sam adams make this a regular yearly offering .  a - near black . gigantic , thick creamy head that stays for some time . lots of cling lace that would need a chisel to remove .  mouthfeel is extremely robust and creamy . amazingly sort and delicate , almost velvety ... in this aspect , the beer is perfect .

this is the first of the chimay line i 've tried , and i reccomend trying some of the lower strength beers first because i 'm sure the alcohol flavor wo n't be as prevalant .  scored this on a move today . cascading brown pour leaves an opaque black beer and creamy white head in it 's wake .  m- very smooth , silky texture makes this beer go down almost too easy o- overall this is a very good beer , a delicious flavor and smooth mouthfeel make this beer very drinkable without any of the heaviness that usually accompany a beer of this abv .

s- delicious smelling , rum soaked raisins , vanilla bean , toffee and chocolate , and then some more melted chocolate .  urthel hop-it served in new belgium globe glass a : pours clear pale gold with big , meringue-like head that shows great retention and leaves wonderful brussels lacing .  hops , fruity esters and warm alcohol spice up the biscuit flavor m- very fine carbonation and a relatively light body make for a perfect mouthfeel .
the nose is one of the most gorgeous i 've ever smelled- apricots and flowers .  poured black with a brown head .  mouthfeel is very crisp and very clean and bright .

s - beautiful mix of roasted malt , munich malt and hops . it is , however , a nicely balanced munich oktoberfest . sweet caramel up front which dries slightly and has a nice hop character .  very dark black pour with somewhat sweet but pleasing aroma of roasted malt with overtones of chocolate .  wonderfully thick and viscous in mouthfeel , slick with a subtly prickly carbonation teasing the tongue .

smells strong of apricot . very strong , but delicious . the wet dank hops definately come through .  pours a dark reddish brown topped by a sticky , off-white head and nice , sticky lacing .  mouthfeel is fantastic , and the beer looks amazing , but the taste and drinkability could be better .

smells fresh and fantastic . taste was bitter hops , caramel , malt , melon and some pine . not as complex as the aroma , but still very tasty . vibrant , bitter finish .  the darkest brown you could imagine .  the mouth feel is spot on baby , full , grainy , just like fresh bread . nice .

popping the cap yields an absolutely intoxicating citrus scent - some tart apple , grapefruit , and maybe some peach .  beer is super dark and a swirl around the glass reveals a very viscous beer . one of the most visualy beautiful beers i 've seen .  m : the mouthful is excellent . the beer is so smooth and rich .

i smelt pineapple like the post claimed , but my girlfriend got a wiff of apple .  a - super clear light amber/golden color with a thick foamy , ice-cream-like head that has great retention s - pungent , piney american hop aroma ( amarillo ?  the mouthfeel is exceptional - thick enough with soft carbonation it just feels super rich .

smell -- bourbon , vanilla , charred oak , chocolate malt , coffee with cream , and dark fruit . truly wish i could get an air freshener that smells like this . taste -- milk chocolate , bourbon , rich vanilla , oak sugars , brown sugar , licorice , anise , prune , tobacco , and a gentle coffee-like roast flavor .  ebony is the color on the pour , my idea of how all beer should look . the size of the head is medium frothy in texture and light chocolate in color as it erodes a fine covering of lace is formed to conceal the glass .  medium to full bodied , with gentle , small bubbled carbonation . a very mild , smooth mouthfeel , yet robust and strong . extremely clean , particularly for an american brewed beer .

the heady aroma is dominated by brandied fruit - dark , rich , and spicy . these rich and mellow elements are tempered by an alcohol ( reminiscent of cognac ) zing - the result is deliciously bittersweet . allagash grand cru is a beautiful beer in every respect - the perfect accompaniment to a cold winter eve ...  a very dark beer for a brown ale , almost opaque in appearance , but very appealing to the sense of sight . inviting and intriguing from an optical standpoint , the rest of the journey through this beer adventure does n't exaclty measure up to the auspicious start , though it does n't fail to satisfy completely .  mouth : this beer is very smooth yet unexpectedly strong flavored ( compared to the relatively weak smell ) . it embodies the mouth with earthy , raspberry flavors and a very compelling bitterness that hints of wood smoke upon swallowing . also , surprising for a cask ale , there is a touch of carbonation that tickles the bottom of the tongue if given a chance to rest there .

018 a - pours a bright golden color , quite cloudy , one inch fluffy white head , not much retention or lacing s - great aroma , lots of barnyard funk and sour lemon , very earthy , light acetic character , aroma is closer to the character of a traditional belgian lambic than most of the american wild ales i 've tried t - strong tongue ripping lemon sourness and barnyard funk up front , lighter acetic/vinegar notes on the midpalate with the funk and sourness leaving rather quickly , as great as this is initially , the finish is really truncated and disappointing , really my only knock on the beer , finish does extend a bit when the beer warms up , but it 's still rather short , alcohol is well-hidden , pretty dry overall m - medium-bodied , with moderate to lower carbonation , not much alcohol warming , dry finish d - pretty drinkable for the style , the sourness and funk are intense ( up front , at least ) , but they are n't overly harsh on the palate , the smell and taste are interesting and sufficiently complex , alcohol not an issue really good sour overall that would be exceptional if not for the short finish .  the beer is a dark umber brown , topped with a creamy almond colored head . that 's some great head retention in my book . lots of lace on the glass , leaving rings all the way down .  t/m : the taste is a citrus , grapefruit hop dominance , but the mouthfeel is as creamy as a glass of milk . a very interesting brew that works out very well .

smells of roasted barley and a hint of sweet.from the name , i thought it would be pretty hoppy .  pours a light ruby brown with a big creamy off white head that retains well and laces the glass .  the mouthfeel is remarkably creamy and silky with a low carbonation .

aroma is excellent . behind some lemon and sourness i almost get a west-coast ipa - apricot , grapefruit , orange , tangerine , maybe a bit of pine .  a : pours a lovely crystal clear rich red . a great 3 '' tan head forms instantly and the lacing clings tenaciously throughout . really nice , i wish more beers poured this nicely .  m : full-bodied with perfect , low-moderate carbonation ; sublime mouthfeel on this beer ; viscous ; smooth .

s : very , very nice . milk chocolate , bourbon , malted milk balls , sweet cream . perfectly complex for the style . the bourbon scent was amazing . the distinct chocolate flavor was real nice . overall , real nice .  this beer looked black at first , but held to the light , its a super dark , clear burgundy .  the carbonation is perfect giving this beer a creamy texture .

aroma is somewhat weak -- hints of chocolate with an odd hop scent that gives it a almost `` watery '' nose .  it is very light gold color and a giant head rose to the top of the glass . very well carbonated and effervescent .  mouthfeel/drinkability- clearly the highlight of this beer 's attributes , the mouthfeel is perfection . responsive , slick , smooth , and very much alive , it showcases the finish better than any other beer in any category from recent memory .

very malty aroma hit me as soon as i popped the top on this bad boy . the wonderful malty smell hits you fallowed by a light hops .  appearance : clear with a deep golden color . plenty of white head . good head retention .  the taste and feel to me are perfect . not super thick , but still able to coat and linger . a well balanced flavor not too sweet or bitter , and carbonation that lasts to the bottom .

appearance - yellowish orange clear beer with nice head and retention smell - a superb scent !  bottle ( room temp july 2005 release ) : poured a pitch-black color stout with a bid foamy dark brown head with pretty good retention .  the mouthfeel is excellent , and feels fuller than its weight suggests with a delightful slickness - great lakes always seem to nail the mouthfeel category .

very little remaining carbonation but the cork is sweet smelling and there is no leakage around the cork , it looks new . smell is intense ! almost bloody your nose intense . it is a shame but the flavor does not match the amazing aroma . mouthfeel is diluted by the alcohol content and lack of carbonation .  trying to pour this it is an intensely head forming beer it is a clear dark brown colored ale i observe . an impervious black colored beer in the glass with a dark brown head .  mouthfeel is delightfully deep and rich , round and full , slurpaliciously smooth .

not as complex as the nose , nor as inviting , but still quite enjoyable . covers the mouth thickly and lingers .  a - looks great . big tan two finger head that leaves great lacing as i drink .  m- medium to full body with a nice creamy carbonation . d- a pretty good stout , alcohol was a little too hot but the feel of the beer was really nice .

malt is very subdued and its wonderful . t- piney hops , very resinous . o- excellent smelling , decent tasting , okay mouth feel .  pours a five finger cream head that fades slowly leaving a very good lace .  m - this one feels zingy and electric on the tongue , and the hoppy aftertaste is really nice . wow ! d - this could become a summer staple in my beer fridge .

the aroma was nice . spicy , yeasty , doughy and sweet .  pours a golden , honey with solid twofinger head . excellent retention and lacing .  m : excellent mouthfeel , dry , substantial , crisp , perfect really . the mouthfeel pushes this beer into fantastic treat territory .

a : pours light brown with a bit of a white head that disappears quickly s : amazing aroma . piney , grassy , earthy hops all mixed with a smoky , peppery sort of spice , as well as a malty , caramel sweetness . insane aroma .  i love the cascade effect from the nitro and the head that it leaves .  finishes like a sherry or port , really dry , fruitty ( apples ) & boozy mf : rich , subtlely carbonated as it should be drinks pretty well considering the heft .

the cork came out with a loud `` pop '' here we go ! this poured nicely with a beautiful nose as i poured it and could smell the raisons , figs or prunes from several inches away .  body is a hazy gold , with an amazing rush of co2 . head is thick , white , and meringue-like . head retention is amazing . that thick head never smaller than 3/8 inch .  mouthfeel is very full bodied and chewy which suits it well .

it smells delicious . remeniscent of pte , but i dont want to try and compare directly . this beer has some really enjoyable qualities .  straight up black with a huge dark brown foamy head that cascades when it forms . excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is rich and velvety , just superb . i have n't had a porter like this in a long time - rich and roasty , a pleasure to savor .

the smell is what hop heads live for . it 's full of citris , piney and spicey hops . not much malt , just smooth high end hop flavors dancing throughout your nose . taste starts out wiht some caramel and hop notes , then turns into a blindingly bitter hop blast .  22-ounce bomber i 've walked by without buying probably hundreds of times , poured into a pint willi glass yields an inky ebony body capped with a thick mocha head with ivory swirls around the rocky bubbles in a shock of foam that retains great and leaves fat rings of lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is as full as can be , with a massively creamy feel up front that coats the back of the palate . thick , sweet , and gooey , this is the rare feel here that 's up there some of the best imperial stouts .

smells fruity and hoppy , like fresh peaches dipped in raw honey . very yummy smells . tastes refreshingly light with a mealy malt backbone and a hint of bitterness that fades back to gentle malts on the finish .  this witbier is an attractive summer quencher like most , however , the spices are a bit too strong for my liking .  mouthfeel is on the thicker side and slightly creamy , the carbonation is relatively low giving it a very nice mouthfeel for the style .

this has a really great aroma . t : very sweet , with a good bourbon character ( and very slight vanilla ) , molasses , grape juice and champagne , orange peel and orange extract hops character ... this is good but i have to dock some points for the cloying sweetness .  3f white foamy head that hangs out for quite some time . beautiful carbonation streaming up the sides of the chalice ( especially attractive in the sunlight !  f : excellent carbonation and very creamy .

wonderful , classic belgian yeast aromas . i 'm thinking green apples and something else .  wychwood hobgoblin is a very clear , reddish brown ale with a creamy , dense , yellow-beige head that has outstanding retention and leaves thick sheets of lacing on the glass . it looks perfect !  very thick mouthfeel right where i want my ris .

wonderful aroma ! t -wonderfully balanced , definitely all about the bourbon .  very black beer poured from a nitro-tap into a pint glass at o'donovans irish pub it minneapolis , mn . bubbles started at the bottom and slowly rose in a cascade to form a thick creamy white foam head at the top .  m : thick , creamy , considerable carbonation . 9.6 % abv plus the thick mouthfeel make this a beer to be consumed slowly .

very nice . some yeasty scents , some light malt , but that 's it . wow . this is good , although the ipa factor is far far in the background .  dark brown with garnet highlights .  very smooth , full body starts out sweet , moves towards a dull bitter , then gets sweet again at the end overall impression and drinkability are very good .

the bourbon was clearly superior to me , and i believe that was the consensus among the group as well ... the aroma on the bourbon is awesome , dominates the brandy , vanilla , wood , dark brown sugar ... the taste is alcoholic bourbon vanilla , but it still works . tons of prune graham crackers which are awesome on the aroma and taste . a little sweet right but in time will be unreal .  a : small tan head over an exceptionally dark black/brown and ruby-hued beer ; head retains wonderfully and leaves webs of lace on the glass .  full bodied with minimal carbonation .

aroma : a lot of malts . caramel and toffee stick out the most . smells sticky . taste : much like the nose , but i taste cardboard flavors out of it .  thanks to brian44556 for sending me this one ... a-dark brown , almost black with a nice thick dark tan colored head s-really thick scent of chocolate covered cocoa beans .  otherwise the malt is good , and the hops come out and play a little under the light fruity taste , gives it a little complexity m - this is the real star here , super smooth and slightly tingly from the carbonation , very very nice d - this is definitely worth the money , would recommend as a stepping stone for someone who was n't sure about ipa .

smell : this is easily one of the best smelling beers that i have had ever .  a - dark brown with a boisterous medium brown head . this stout has the look of a winner .  the mouthfeel is full with tongue tingling and a hint of syrupy , but not in an unpleasant way .

aroma is fruity with citrusy hops , a suggestion of apricots , and cologne .  batch 266 the beer pours black and completely opaque with a huge cocoa tan head that stays around very well and leaves a ton of lacing .  nice rich lush mouthfeel .

the nose is a wonderful balance of strong clove and wheat aromas . spicy with some banana and honey in the back . wow ! the taste starts off malty but then quickly changes to some clove , some bite from the carbonation , then a biscuity finish with some suggestion of bitter hop .  the pour starts out out black on top and light on bottem but u can watch it come together to this great deep amber with a 1/2 inch head that never leaves and leaves some great lacing.aroma is of highly roast malts with a nice intertwined roasty flavor with some light hoppiness coming from the pale mixed in.very drinkable and definently tasty just a great beer .  m. i do not notice the over-carbonation of other reviewers , all i can focus on is this silky mouthfeel , its amazing . it does coat the mouth a little bit , what i do it jsut drink more of the beer then , leading nicely into the next section ... d. oh yeah , getting this one again . with that silky mouthfeel , i would gladly accept many waves of this ruby-black ambrosia .

sure enough , smells like a chardonnay ; some tame lemon , yeast , wet oak , and crabapple .  bomber poured into my large gulden draak tulip , wolaver 's farmhouse ale is a hazy darker gold with a very large and super tight and creamy white head that is painfully long lasting , very rocky on the settle , leaving heavy hunks of foamy lace . very impressive !  great luscious creamy mouthfeel .

piney , simecoe , chinook , centennial hops dominate the nose.malt ? ! ? ! ? ! ? what is that ? some sweet taste from the malts but the rest is all hop goodness.the bitterness hits you after you swallow.its ohh soo good.as the beer warms up the sweetness really starts to show .  it pours black . not inky black like some others but dark enough . the amazing part is that you can see the bubbles rise from the bottom of the glass to the top ! head retention is pretty good not that i care .  mf= nice heavy feeling on the tongue . coats the tongue and throat with a thick layer of hop oil leaving a wonderful alcoholic warmth behind .

s corn grit and sweet cereal adjuncts and some musty notes t a tiny bit of alcohol and sweet malt upfront .  ) a- poured carefully into a tulip glass with a hand-high rocky white head , which was well retained and slowly gave way to some incredible lacing . the body was a bright yellow featuring abundant visible carbonation . d- a pleasure to look at , smells wonderful , and super-tasty ... very very drinkable until the 8.1 % abv gets you !  it 's quite smooth and creamy in the mouth with a full body and a very fine-bubbled , natural carbonation from bottle-conditioning .

not a whole lot going on the smell department . pick up some caramell and malts .  from the bottle . poured black with with deep mahogany edges with a brown head with lots of lacing .  the mouthfeel is very fluffy , dry , and fruity . exceptional .

i say stinky because it smells like old musty grain and alcohol .  a - a beautiful golden-orange color with a one-finger head and good retention s - smells of citrus and hops t - citrus up front .  mouthfeel - 5.0 simply luxurious . the low , fine carbonation , coupled with a thick , heavy feel over the tongue makes this beer silky smooth . a - 4.0 , s - 4.0 , t - 4.5 , m - 5.0 , d - 4.0 .

the aroma is a heady mix of milk chocolate , oak , roasted malt , vanilla and floral hops . carbonation is light and very smooth . this is one excellent imperial stout . its got plenty of oak flavor and tonnes of hops .  bottle into a tulip glass a- pours a beautiful hazy pale golden color with an incredible four finger rocky , pillowy head that leaves lots of chunky lacing . perfect looking belgian-style beer .  boddingtons pours super smooth and creamy with 2 fingers of head . no complexity , but oh so smooth . a great beer if you 're looking for a thirst quencher that 's incredibly smooth , consistent in flavor and easy to drink , then boddingtons is for you .

poured into a large tulip glass a clear deep golden with a large blooming white head that took forever to subside.multiple layers of lace left behind.wow what awesome aromas , there is an american twist to this beer no doubt , floral and citric hops all over the place , its perfect as far as iam concerned.dry on the palate with grassy herbal hop notes , light spiced phenols but they dont play a big role.this is quenching and bone dry , i really like it.if all beers of this style were like this i would be a convert , the american craftmanship to the belgian strong pale style in this beer shows thru with great left coast hop flavors.the alcohol lends a little sweetness but its held in check pretty well .  a deep light brown with hints of amber . nice sized head lasts a while . longer .  creamy to the point of being syrupy , carbonation is perfect at a smooth moderate level .

a+ aroma leads to an ok taste , but not bad at all .  gorgeous beer . sailor 's delight sunset red , with a persistent head that 's getting in the way of my immediately enjoying this beer . carbonation slow-rolls to the top like a well-fished spinnerbait .  this is perfect imo .

the nose demonstrates some complexity through a roasty , hot cocoa-like character . additionally , there are nutty undertones evident in the aroma and taste .  color is a deep red with a fluffy off-white head . possibly the most beautiful beer i 've ever seen . i held it up to the light and looked through the red color for quite awhile .  really very nice m - this is what a stout like this should feel like . full bodied with moderate carbonation .

s : excellent aroma of pine , citrus , and a hint of lemon .  appearance - dark brown stout , very opaque , little head formation , head laciness is beautiful . looks rich .  m - nice and creamy , whole lot of body .

the head lasts quite a while and leaves a nice lacing s - beautiful , lemons , pepper , yeast , very floral with a bit of grass and maybe a little honey .  pours beautiful . poured hard several times , a beautiful dense head will form over the pils .  the mouthfeel is undoubtedly the greatest aspect of this beer , with its full , creamy feel , which provides a luxurious decadence .

poured in a pint glass deep autumn clear pour medium head with lacing aroma = pumpkin pie starts off with a smooth malt then with finishes with all the pumpkin pie spices ( nutmeg , vanilla , cin , brown sugar ) simply a delicious pumpkin ale smooth creamy body , crisp yet smooth carbonation very drinkable yet potent . at 8 % , it can catch up to you quickly . one of the best pumpkin ales i have had this year ...  labeled `` batch 12 , 2007 '' poured into tulip clear ruby color . lots of off-white head that slowly recedes but pretty much stays around . lovely lacing . wonderful to look at .  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

the nose is absolutely fantastic , i do n't think i could ask for anything more . rich milk chocolate , fresh brewed coffee , and smooth bourbon each jump out of the glass , no aroma dominating , but all of them quite pungent .  tumbler pours a strikingly beautiful deep burnished bronze-brown with a thick fluffy head atop ... i gave this one a perfect appearance score because it looks exactly the way i want a fall brew to appear ... deep and dark and warm looking ... toasted malts and a hint of cocoa or chocolate in the background ... .  mouthfeel is quite thick and creamy . awesome .

loads of lacing . fruit bomb on the nose . lots of fresh hops , citrus rinds , sweet pineapple candy , unripe watermelon , fresh mango , and ripe peach . the taste is much like the nose , albiet a tad less intense . similiar to a hopped up west coast ipa that i brewed recently with more of a rich , sweet cereal-esque malt backbone full of barley , rye , wheat , and oats . easy drinking yet full of flavor .  this looks amazing . s : hershey 's .  the mouthfeel is really right on .

smells absolutely glorious . a toasty , yeasty smell , like fresh baking bread .  this beer 's strength is its appearance . it looks every part the ideal ipa . clingy head , bubbly , retaining lacing , very very inviting .  in the middle there is a dry briney sort of flavor with just the slightest hint of salt , which just tingles on the tongue because of the delightful carbonation . this beer is delitefully light bodied with a zesty sort of carbonation that just feels great on the pallate .

lots of corn notes with an over-sweet vanilla aroma and an odd cough syrup note at the back . slight bready notes as well - just full of those insipid grain lager notes i despise .  the appearance is great ( my sister even pointed it out and she knows nothing about beer ) with the nice red color and tons of lacing .  there 's some hints of vinegar in the background that , surprisingly , seems to fit right in with everything ealse going on in this beer.. mouthfeel/drinkabilty ; the mouthfeel on this one maybe the fullest , and mostly velvety of any beer that i 've ever had . between the raspberries , chocolate , nuts and very full mouthfeel , this is like drinking a chocolate raspberry cake with a some walnuts or pecans sprinkled on top .

the smell is all chocolate with just a touch of coffee and it smells as if it would be sweet chocolate and the overall taste reflects this sweetness though not coyingly so .  pours a slightly hazy gold color with a one-finger white head . the head recedes into a medium-sized layer on top leaving great lacing .  extreme smoothness and finishes malty sweet .

s - freakin ' massive nose of various fruits . colder , it was a ripe strawberry . just a huge nose . t - in the bottle , i could n't really put my finger on it , and i ca n't on tap either . d - a beguiling , complicated beer that is difficult to pinpoint .  a vehement pour into a snifter creates a haughty 3 finger head that floats atop a jet black body . cocoa colored lacing adheres thickly to the glass .  mouthfeel and drinkability are superb . could drink many of these , nice to see fff does something besides the in-your-face brews we always hear about .

smell this has a humongous nose . the dark , roasted malts are evenly mixed with some strong coffee grounds that are burnt to a crisp . taste the nose finds its way nicely into the taste . the chocolate came out strong on the tongue making this a very complex stout . mouthfeel this is medium-bodied and creamy with some good , strong bitterness .  appearance was superb , yellow , light orange color with an enormous amount of carbonation and a thick , pasty and rocky head that just does n't settle .  nice weight , carbonation , and roundness in the mouth .

s : heavy chocolate with nice marschino cherry notes . brandy and dark chocolate brownies .  appearance - beautiful . just what you 'd want in a golden clear lager . really nice head and lacing .  the mouthfeel is extraordinary , easily the thickest beer i have ever had , and it helps bring down the almost excessively intense roast character .

there is no doubt you are face to face with a pale ale , but it smells mostly like lemons .  the lacing is very nice . very defined rings grasp my glass .  mouthfeel is awesome . feels so full and thick , especially upon first sip .

just wonderful aroma as i remember from out of the bottle ( t ) - just like the smell .  pitch black with a huge dense creamy brown head .  mourhfeel is full and creamy , one of the best in an american stout i have had yet . carbonation is spot on and makes the beer smooth and thick , chewy and creamy ... .excellent .

the smell was a beautiful tart , sour , cherry smell combined with funky , barnyard , wild yeast aromas . not overly tart , but just the right balance . the mouthfeel was smooth yet crisp with medium body and strong carbonation .  pours an exceptional dark brown/ruby color with a huge tan head that last all the way down and a great cligning lace as well .  perfect . o : while this was a tasty beer , i have such high regard for the brewery that anything that does n't blow me away really disappoints me .

very nice smelling beer , i might even go so far as to call it great .  the beer 's got a pitch black body with a huge two and a half finger dark brown head . some visible bubbles in the glass coming up from the bottom of the beer , and excellent lacings to boot .  mouthfeel is excellent !

so i 'm trusting that they do n't make two dunkels with 5.5 % abv and do n't list one on their website -- perhaps they changed the name or label or something to that effect . the aroma is nearly non-existant but is of must and malt . it 's not a very complex smell by any means , but the flavor hardly follows suit .  pours pitch black and completely opaque without even the faintest hint of lighter color when held to a light source . two finger thick frothy dark chocolate coffee colored head with excellent retention , only slowly fading into a thick lasting cap .  wow , what a jazzy mouthfeel ! very crispy , peppery yeast , dry ... amazing effect in the feel , very earthy and exciting . sometimes the feel can be energy , and this one delivers it in spades .

s : firm medium dark chocolate , hint of roast and coffee . t : muddled baker 's chocolate with some brown sugar play .  pours inky black with a rather thin dark caramel colored head of fine bubbles . rather thick body but i 've seen more syrupy . leaves good lacing .  quite excellent . d - the lower bitterness and abv makes this extremely drinkable for a dipa .

has an extremely unique aroma kind of earthy and fruity almost like real homemade apple cider you know the dark brown stuff .  matilda pours a lovely orange amber color that glows nicely when held up to a light source . it is just slightly cloudy with an amazing frothy white head that leaves killer lace .  m : luxurious and creamy , the carbonation is spot on .

it smells fresh , refreshing in fact , like a lemon candy mixed with some juicy fruit . i could smell this all day , just wonderful . appearance : bright clear gold ( it cellared in my fridge for a long while ) with a thin white cover and trim that laces . flavor : the wonderful smell dies off a bit in the taste . one of the best smelling beers ive found . ill watch for a chance to try this again .  this beer pours a incredibly brilliant , deep , true red .  big and chewy with a very smooth , creamy finish .

they followed , just recently , with a `` stubbified '' brick lager yellow label . yellow is light in colour , light in nose , but surprisingly creamy at first taste -- one wonders if brick has borrowed from its parent sleeman 's cream ale for this note . another thing it is , though , is *very* drinkable ; this is a beer for chewing and swallowing , a beer that one never seems to tire of ( or one , at least , that this one never tired of last night ; - ) all things considered , a very fine beer that comes in a cute bottle with an adorable , low-and-wide , corrugated cardboard case .  a : opaque black with a slight reddish brown on the edges of the glass every now and then while drinking . half a finger of head with some nice lacing .  m- wonderfully creamy with just the right amount of carbonation .

smell : probably the highlight of this brew : a big , bright , rounded fruit aroma that roils round the nostrils and beckons one closer . taste : jagged and unmodulated : a throaty rash of booze with dark fruits up front , sweet , sweet , sweet ; rolls back , leaving a bubbly fizzing sensation along the tongue . carbonation is spiky but awkward , emphasizing the finish , and not the start , like a dying star . drinkability : more sport than leisure , this one lacks the hop snap and malt range that would make it a pensively pleasurable sipper , but it 's fun and loud .  a - pours a very dark brown , almost opaque , with a nice red hue on the edges . solid thumb of mocha coloured head with incredible retention and settles into a smooth mountainous terrain . fantastic ! the appearance is fantastic with look , scent and mothfeel all contributing the a fabulous experience .  thick and chewy mouthfeel . this is a pretty solid stout .

smell : void of just about all aromas . very faint fruity flowery hops . disappointing .  looks great , deep ruby color and a massive head that leaves the glass looking almost destroyed .  m : thick , very full body , so tar-like it 's almost oily , light roasted acidity , modest carbonation .

smells kinda like a malt liquor , not very impressive , but not bad . taste surprised me with a good , brown malt palate .  the solid black beer was buried in a mountain of shaving cream . i got two inches of head for every one inch of beer , and it wasnt even thinking about going away .  mouth is very nice , very smooth with sour feeling and a very good level of carbonation .

there 's some really nice lacing down the glass as i drink . smell - plenty of american hops in the nose , with grapefruit up front and pine and pineapple following closely behind .  best looking beer i 've had in a while .  and this was a grave mistake , as this beer is truly excellent . i noticed the mouthfeel before the flavor : the bottle conditioning mj pointed out on the label made this beer velvety smooth .

incredibly rich , old , and amazing . oxidation gone beautifully right . delicious , but a little overly musty compared to the incredible nose . m : flat , obviously , but with nice heft and moderate stickiness . o : i love it when a weird old beer turns out to be fantastic . i 'm sure some bottles of this are awful , but this one was a treat .  a- this stout is absolutely gorgeous ! deep , coffee color with a great tan head . brilliant lacing that lasts until the glass is empty .  the mouthfeel is awesome . smooth , check .

it had a big smoky , coffee nose along with a dark chocolate sweetness . this beer struck a clever balance between a dry stout and a milk stout . thanks , good dog , laugh all you want .  poured into a weizen glass appearance- clear golden color with a large , stubborn fluffy white head . this beer just looks phenomenal . smell- lemon , fresh cut grass , semi musty dank cellar , the sage as stated on the bottle is very present , a hint of wheat .  mouthfeel is excellent ... nice and full . the feel in the mouth is thick , and the flavors really linger in the mouth .
the smell is rich , nutty and a little roasted .  huge carbonation creates a dense chunky head that rises in a column above the rim of the glass .  mouthfeel is excellent .

aroma pure , fresh strawberries , especially before swirling . it really does smell like fresh cut strawberries that are about to be scooped onto a piece of angle food cake .  pours an opague black with a light brown heading that is very sticky and soapy looking . odd for a stout . exceptional lacing and heading stay throughout the tasting .  mouthfeel is really lift and crisp .

it is very delightful . taste : this tastes like peaches mixed with champagne .  2011 vintage . looks hazy amber , great lacing and very inviting smells subdued , slight hop aroma which is surprising considering what this beast tastes like tastes like honey , flowers , citrus and has slight ethanol in the background due to the high abv .  excellent body .

smell : a definite blast of raspberries in the nose . this is so much better than what i had heard from other people at this point . for a 2007 , this smells like raspberries just picked off the bush .  it has amazing lace and head that just stick around . the body is a bronze transparent color with a lot of small bubbles .  really creamy on the mouthfeel with soft carbonation . solid stout , not quite one of the best but good .

very nice aroma on this beer . flavor reminds me of extremely naughty goose in that it has a roasted marshmallow-like sweetness which is delicious . i 'm usually not a huge fan of brown ales , but this is simply outstanding .  a re-review pours out a beautiful black colour with cascading tan head ... ..slight roasted malt in the nose with a little of the metallic notes of the can too .  nice and thick on the palate as well ; chewy , chocolate-like , malt sugars stick a bit to the palate , though this beer is in no way heavy . wow , i just checked out the alcohol on this ; this beer drinks way bigger than it is , not because of the alcohol ( which is quite hidden ) , but because of the concentrated malt flavors .

the smell is exeptional , honey indeed and the fruity hops make this a feast for the nose .  love the silver can with the simple one color black print .  thick mouth feel , chewy with almost zero carbonation .

nose was great , but the rest was just pretty good .  a : very very dark brown in color with almost no light shining through . great retention and very nice lacing .  one of the smoothest barley wines i 've had , and especially for 12 % , it 's fantastic .

the aroma was extremely strong of raspberry 's with a mild sweet yeast and a light bread malt scent .  appearance - luminescent pale gold with sudsy white head . clarity is excellent . i ofeten think of these beers as having a more rustic appearance but what a beautiful beer .  full mouthfeel , with a medium heavy carbonation and some syrup afterfeel .

appearance : a dark copper color , with little head smell : sweet , apples , smells so good , like a sweet apple cider . wow , this is great . very sweet and tart at the same time .  poured into a thick glass mug . pours almost pitch black with an off white , cream color head .  mouthfeel is among the creamiest i 've ever had from a bottle , ever .

s : absolutely astounding cocoa smell . that 's amazing . the best cocoa smell i 've had in a beer to date . that is absolutely excellent . tiny dry espresso finish . o : this is hands down the best `` chocolate beer '' i 've ever had . absolutely amazing . would recommend to anyone .  produced a huge fluffy pure white colored head with a ridiculous retention behind it . plenty of lacing left behind as it finally started to dissipate .  feel is relatively full bodied and incredibly smooth and drinkable . this is one damn fine beer .

the nose is spectacular , full of spice and tangy of pine , very strong and inviting . this is a fantastic beer , although it is slightly paler than it should be , making me wonder if it might not be better labeled as an ipa . either way , it was delicious .  appearance : the body is a deep brown color that can only be seen through at the bottom . the head is about three fingers tall that has great retention and superb sticky lacing .  the mouthfeel and carbonation are also excellent , as is common in most sam adams ales .

the nose is absolutely wonderful , dank with grapefruit , pineapple , and orange aromas . forget ipas , this bad boy is more pungent than some imperial ipas that i 've had .  sparkling , foamy lace is really nice to look at .  mouthfeel is stunning . this is so light and smooth , and yet the finish is long and nearly endless .

decent ale with cider hints . the pour is clear yellow that hazes up a bit , promising some interesting quality . lackluster in appearance leads to such in aroma & flavor . mild grains & toasted malts prevail with minimal hops to the nose , while the flavor is a clean , crisp grain-with apple cider malt taste .  a : this is a really good looking beer , if for no other reason than it 's ruby red color , it 's nice head retention , and its uniqueness -- not many other beers have color like this .  mouthfeel is one of the creamiest i 've come across in a long while . moderate in weight .

straight copper , pillowy eggshell shaded head that fades kinda quickly , smells like fresh hop flowers . i love it . there 's citrus in there as well and some sweetish malts when the head dies down a bit . it 's mighty tasty , just not as potent as the aroma . nice and crisp , light to more a medium body .  appearance : amber with hints of brown . solid head of nicely shaped large bubbles . good retentive head .  the mouthfeel was spectacular ! pretty damn full bodied for a porter , and oh so lush and creamy .

s : the aroma is a heavy , ramped up coriander , honey and subtle tartness . t : the most significant change in this beer from the regular saison is an increased tartness .  pours jet black with a persistent squatty , thick tan head .  body is thin with low carbonation . overall a unique stout , very flavorful and with great mouthfeel .

as soon as i popped the top i could smell the delightful stank that i feel every saison should have . the aroma really knocked me down .  this beer pours nutty brown with about a half inch of off white head which recedes leaving a thin layer . there is lots of very nice lacing . very pretty beer .  one of the thickest beer i have ever tasted , equal to the thickest , this is milkshake thick . quite an interesting beer but way to thick to drink in quantity .

s - yeast and hop dominate , not that prominent t - up front some nice hop flavours with some vanilla ice cream type flavours that follow .  poured with smallish burnt sugar colored head that mostly subsided and no lace .  great mouthfeel .

finally i got the gift set of the 3 bottles of chimay and the goblet . s - the smell hits you as soon as you open the bottle . sweetness balanced with malty bready goodness . it smells juicy . t - sweet and carmelly balanced well with maltyness .  275 ml bottle , 2001 vintage , brewed when i was a senior in high school , a : pours a dark brown with a light head that does n't last too long .  m - thick , full bodied with medium to low carbonation which lends to a very smooth beer .

smell : what a strong and wonderful scent this beer gives off ! the smell is sweet , chocolately , and mildly robust .  appearance : poured a slightly cloudy brown color , with moderate visible carbonation . half-finger bubbly head that diminishes immediately . no lacing .  t/mf : super clean and carbonation so tightly packed on the tongue it feels almost creamy , solid sweet grassy apple and dextrose like opening with a slight hop twang in the middle with a protracted finish with a good deal of hop oil running down the center of its tongue , the malt bitterness is there as well and the finish is quite long and just a bit nutty , everything is very nicely balanced and the mouthfeel is exceptional . d : pretty nice pils , well balanced and sexy mouthfeel , the only knock here is the rather bland appearance .

very herbal aromas sage and some sweetness . the aromas are fantastic it was just a little too salty in places to make me really want another one .  appearance : deep brown showing ruby amber with backlight . tan head collapsed pretty quickly into a clumpy cover .  very thick and creamy mouthfeel with a perfect amount of carbonation .

this is tough to review cuz it tastes like a nice hoppy ipa and yet i cant really taste any apricot other than sugarry texture on the mouthfeel . it does have a fabulous smell which i am now giving a 5 . seems like it would be a great one for the peanut butter combo that is so good with hoppy ipas  pours a hazy lemon honey gold with a thin white head that dissipates to lacing and then to nothing .  mouthfeel is quite clean with just a touch of metallic tang .

decent lacing s : i 'm catching alot of tropical fruit with a strong floral hop presence , getting some pine and a very sweet malt background . very sensual ... i want to take this beer behind the jr. high and get it pregnant ! it 's very complex , but the sweetness of this beer is shining through more so than the hops for sure . o : i 'm impressed . this is a great , very complex , iipa . it is probably the sweetest iipa that i have ever had but i think that the balance that the hops bring at the backend make this a great beer .  a : a dark black body with ruby highlights and a couple of fingers of tan head . retention is poor and it quickly recedes to a quarter-inch film on top .  full-bodied for sure with light carbonation .

bell 's two hearted ale really impress me . lovely scent of pine and grapefruit w/ a hint of malt and florals in the back ground .  bottle poured into my darkness glass ... pours a dark oily and thick black . hardly any head is discouraging ... the aroma is lighter than the original version , a lot of the `` hotness '' of the bourbon is numbed which is actually pretty nice .  bold , velvety texture -- magnificent .

nose is decent . very tart smelling with strong notes of funk and yeast .  poured a golden/straw color , with a wisp of foam across the top , but nothing substantial . for a lighter beer , i really enjoyed this one . the menu noted that this tasty brew had won two silver medals at the gabf , and one bronze medal at the world beer cup .  the mouthfeel is excellent and imo is what really makes the beer .

the smell makes me think of my grandmother pulling a fine pumpkin pie out of the oven in her old lakehouse . damn the silly bjcp judge who informed me they are tasteless gourds .  fresh floral and hoppy aroma , maybe some maltiness in the background , but it was not very pronounced . flavour is spicy bitter upfront followed by malty fruitiness ( mostly citrus ) . i really enjoyed the excellent bittery aftertaste . great beer , classic esb .  the mouthfeel was so smooth and creamy , amazing texture that added so much to this beer .

smell : wonderfully sweet-smelling aroma of bourbon and all of its compulsory , accompanying notes of vanilla , brown sugar , and charry oak .  a - it looks a lot like a cola or root beer ; very short-lived fizzy head , quite thin , and i see soda bubbles clinging to the side of the tulip .  silky smooth all the way through .

little formations and foam sculptures acquiesce on-top of the meringue . the main fragrance of this beer - you 're going to be shocked - is hops . nice and piney , this beer seems to pinpoint the varying aspects of hops in a more multidimensional way than most beers do . i get citrus here ; the classic grapefruit and papaya . while i majorly appreciated the diversity of hop-flavor in this beer , i could not help but feel that it is almost an exact clone of rogue 's santa . goes down fairly well , and quite the grab at $ 3 a bomber .  pours just a slighly hazey copper color with good carbonation but missing some froth and foam from the pour and afterwards .  it was incredibly viscous without being cloying and the finish was amazing .

overall , good appearance , great aroma , and good body .  it seems to be at least partially based on the bock style . though few liquor stores in the united states seem to carry xingu , it is nonetheless a worthy find , and definitely a beer that i would buy again !  mouthfeel : rich , velvety mouthfeel . just coats the mouth so wonderfully . overall : bold flavorful taste , velvety smooth , and a very good beer overall .

i think the hops are normally a bit extreme . i personally only recommend stone beer 's in general if you love hops to death .  a- poured from the bottle with a thin brown head which quickly evaporated to nothing ... no haze layer , no collar , no lacing . the body was a filtered opaque super-dark brown color , which exhibited no visible carbonation .  the mouthfeel is the best in the business and incredibly smooth .

first whiff was not good , nothing but euro skunk instead of the standard dopplebock aromas ( look 'em up ) . this would be an above average brew , if not for the euro yeast and resulting skunk .  poured a nice brown with rich creamy head . however , the head quickly left and lacing was minimal .  incredibly smooth and heavy mouthfeel .

pours a deep brown with red highlights and a tall tan rocky head that fades to lacing , the aroma is n't awe inspiring but a good bit of malt and a bit of spiciness of some sort .  a : pours dark black with not head whatsoever .  m : right about perfect for the style ( or nearly any style ) .

the smell on this one was amazing ! i could smell it right away as i began to pour . lots of hops on the nose , and sweetly so . a little bit of fruit in there ( apricots ? well balanced . great carbonation level and nice weight for the style .  a - pour is a light orange color . minimal lacing , and a thin white foam that is not retained .  m : rich full creamy body and very moderate carbonation .

atoms is vibrant , full of chocolate , marzipan , coffee , toast , and mint . great aroma but it does n't follow through in flavor .  a : red , and very hazy . like , much , much too hazy .  in the mouth , it is velvety soft and smooth with a dry finish and a medium to full body ... a bit of plato .

smell has an immensely pleasing wet hay funk wafting off of it with a hint of the grains and touch of spice .  appearance is rather bland , copperish yellow with no notable head or lacing .  mouthfeel - nice and creamy full mouthfeel .

not much to smell because of the nitro head .  dark golden hue with a massive frothy white head ; decent retention and patchy lacing , for not the head , one would be reminded of a simple draught bud pour .  mouth is wonderful , as creamy as you could hope .

smells like banana bread , and i 'm loving that !  a - motor-oil black with subtle carbonation action that pushes up a modest cappuccino foam head that subsides to a film after about a minute or so . not much for lacing , but then again this style always has trouble in this area .  nice carbonation o - it looks great and has fantastic mouthfeel , i just wish more of the barrel character came out or even more of the citrus ... just a bit one sided .

i love the smell of this beer . buttered biscuit aroma with some caramel sweetness underneath . grassy english hops round out the smell . nice blending of flavors . not really that bitter for an english bitter , but i liked it nonetheless .  a : comes in a small tulip , pitch black in body , with a half finger of dark mocha head . retention is decent , with a couple of spots of lace . nothing exceptional . the tulip was a perfect pour size , but i wanted several more , and if i were n't driving i 'd have gotten them .  thick mouthfeel , viscous and sugary .

really not much of an aroma . lovely taste .  a - pours brownish cola , some cascading bubbles around the side , not much head .  mouthfeel is superb - medium thickness with an amazing finely bubbled carbonation that tickles the tongue .

pop this cork and the first thing that hits you is the incredible aromas of real cherries , not the 'cherry pie ' aromas of some beers .  poured a dark blackish brown with a tight bubbly tan head that quickly disappears leaving only a few bubbles and a small amount of sticking .  m : the mouthfeel is pretty much perfect for this one .

very good . beer is thin and moderately acidic .  not close to any craft beer that most beer snobs enjoy but a very drinkable beer on a hot day . yes it is not going to win any awards for best beer , but i think bud got this beer right and killed off miller chill . great beer for none beer drinkers , and those who just want something different from all those heavy micros .  the taste is a mild roasted malt flavour with a hint of coffee and the mouthfeel is a lovely creamy texture that coats your mouth .

huge resinous citrus , grapefruit , tropical and floral aromas burst up at you . sweet malt backbone with candied accents . the hop oils are so bright it is like inhaling the perfume of a fresh handful of cones . i think i still might like hopslam a bit better , but in the interim this is quite tasty .  very clear color for a wheat beer , must be filtered , as it is crystal clear with a very small fast fading head . there is actually no head shortly after the pour .  m : mouthfeel is great . chewy and tasty , yet finishes dry and begs for you to drink more !

s very nice . white bread malt character overlaid with bright pine and highlights of orange zest . o an ambivalent brew with a great nose but a real let down for me on the actual flavor and mouthfeel .  a : pours a clear golden orange , with a smooth one finger white head that dissipates quickly and leaves little lacing .  soft and creamy texture , medium body and almost no carbonation . really nailed this .
