big nose of fresh hops and exotic spices , pineapple mint and lemon basil . still , this is a great american ipa and well worth the sample .  clear , dark amber color . thin white head that quickly collars but paints some impressive lace regardless .  the maltiness is chewy with some lingering sweetness , but it dries out towards the finish thanks to a touch of bitterness , alcohol warming , and some oakiness . this is an extremely well balanced strong , full bodied brew that offers a plethora of rich & creamy characters to the beer lover .

wonderfully dark with an excellent smoked aroma , reminicient of a great rauchbier . the head was creamy , but not overly large . overalla great quaff .  pale straw color topped by a two finger eggshell white head . it 's pretty much completely transparent making me believe that maybe they overfiltered it .  mouthfeel - very smooth , agreeable carbonation level , slightly heavy , right on for the style .

very nice ! ! !  great beer , tastes very fresh . a- average s- very fresh with the strong hints of kitchen spices thyme and sage taste- same as smell , the thyme and sage come through strong , but add freshness and structure more than i anticipated m- light and smoothe d- i could go all night  almost creamy . a perfect level of carbonation .

perfect blend of bready malts , lager yeast traits and subtle flowery hops on the nose . i love this aroma . it 's got some poundcake aromas as well without seeming overly sweet .  this was a mainstay in hawaii & still a nice beer regardles of where you find it pours amber to copper with a 2 fingers white head . no head retention , some lacing s : fruitty & piney , with floral hops sneaking in as well big fruittyness & bready notes up front , piney & citrus hops follow up .  the thickest mouthfeel i 've ever had - always has been and i still wait for the day something thicker comes along .

the aroma was thick with piney hops and nothing else . sadly this crazy flavor combination was pretty gross .  3.0 a : mildly hazed orange brown color . one finger of frothy beige head that falls rapidly and leaves no lacing .  mouth feel : it has a thick , rich and luxurious feel in the mouth . there is a light bite on the lip and tongue . the carbonation starts out strong but dissipates quickly improving the lush feel of the beer .
s- great smell . citrus mostly with some really nice sweet tropical fruit notes .  a : deep amber hue , very little lacing .  mouthfeel- outstanding mouthfeel .

heady and powerful , this smells wonderful . taste : bourbon present as well as apples , banana chips , spices and brown sugar . overall : i know fred intends for all his beers to be underm carbonated but i feel it held this beer back from being truly great .  pours much lighter than i expected , more a deep brown than a brown-black , and still letting light pass through rather easily . head is yellowish beige , large-bubbled and frothy where agitated , but otherwise forming a thin film .  m : another incredible aspect .

on the first taste the beer seems malty sweet and perhaps slightly metallic , and little more . as it warms up and progresses strong flavors of cherry and subtle flavors of vanilla and raisin appear . needs more hops , or some other source of bitterness to fill it out .  hazy golden colour , moderate creamy head .  m : the beer feels so good in the mouth .

this one smells just divine . im initially greeted by crisp a fruity ( cascade ? very nice . the flavor consists of the same caramel and dinner roll malty base but its a little less impressive than the smell .  bright light orange color with a small collar of white foam .  i love the mouthfeel , this one coats the inside of your cheeks and lingers on the pallet , while the sweetness fades and leaves the hop bitterness behind .

s - caramel and chocolate aroma . t - light malted milk balls , i am stunned at how rich this beer smells yet how weak the flavor is . i want to try this again , b/c the aroma was just so great , i have to just imagine that my can or my palate was off .  this pours a dark cherry red color with no head .  lush and extremely creamy on the palate . super fine carbonation structure ; uncious and smooth , velvety even . the booze becomes a bit burdening , as is expected with the high abv .

big distinct aroma of citrusy hops hits you first , orange , tangerine , a mlange of tropical fruits , flowery , followed by a sweet smelling malt , the hops last thru out the pour . world class bouquet . crisp hop dominated entry on the palate , distinctly citrusy hops , orange/lemon/pineapple , followed by a wonderfully balanced medium malt , the hops never release their grip , thank you troegs . the hop oils cling to your tongue and will not let go ! this is an incredibly delicious ipa ! seems perfect at about 50 degrees or so .  this poured a clear copper color with no head .  m - mouthfeel is perfect . silky smooth bubbles and full bodied texture .

s - most nutty amazing smell thick aromas including some coffee and caramel t - clean and clear and then the nut follows .  a : crisp and clear golden amber ... the glass was poured quite high , so the head spilled over the rim of the glass , and did n't leave much behind . a thin little collar remains behind .  very creamy feel with medium carbonation and body .

the aroma is fantastic with this one .  poured a 12 oz can into a pint glass ( i 've had the bottled version too , but this review is of the canned version ) appearance : nice gold color , just the slight bit cloudy , one-finger head that is just off white , good carbonation smell : traditional ipa smell , pretty floral but not too complex taste : nice malt presence at first but then the hops take over , good amount of hops mouthfeel : medium bodied with a reasonably dry finish overall : this is a solid ipa , it 's not 100 % like a west coast ipa , there is a good malt presence and there is a bit of pine taste in it , but also very citrusy .  a big creamy malt character washes over the tip of your tongue . silky , creamy , yummy . my friend dave said this was one of the best barleywines he has had in a while .

smell : ok , i think i 've nailed it : fresh cut lumber . yes , this beer smells like sawdust , home depot , and all the good memories you have from your days with a circular saw .  2 finger white head , with great retention that really took a while to fizzle down . not much for laceing though . average appearance , very rich golden copper though .  the mouthfeel is particularly noteworthy , and every swig leaves a viscous coating of robust barley goodness on the tongue .

t - taste was unfortunately unable to live up to the aroma , but was very nice . citrus , mainly grapefruit , and pine is obvious from the start and finishes with an oaky flavor , leaving a somewhat lingering bitterness . d - very refreshing . could easily have a second although the high abv ( 7 % ) would keep me from having more than that . overall , this is a very nice imperial ipa .  poured into pint glass with a small head that split after a little bit.looks okay.alot of citrus hop aroma in the nose , a little bit of biscuity sweetness.nice balance between the citrus/piney hops and malt sweetness.very clean finish mouthfeel is medium bodied , very easy drinking.really nice fall release that strays from the pumpkin ale/oktoberfest norm .  very good stout .

the smell is n't very strong . i wonder if maybe i got a bad bottle because i remember this smelling much better before . when i stick my nose way in there , i smell a little burned caramel , and i like to pretend i smell raisins too ... and now my nose is all wet .  appearance : pours a nearly opaque brown body with a cascading 3 finger toffee colored head than recedes to nothing in less than a minute .  incredibly smooth taste , silky transition from sweet to bitter . feel is silk as mentioned earlier , pure bliss .

a banana explosion in your nose ... a few later , shy chocolate aroma will grew up.slightly caramel malt notes too .  poured in to a weizen glass . pours a tarnished gold color and is for the most part clear . just a touch of haze . modest frothy head for a bavarian style hefe , not the massive foam head i expected , even on a aggressive pour . i suppose the absence of the massive head even makes it more so ? at the brewpub they serve this in a pint glass with virtually no head .  the mouthfeel is heavy , yet very smooth . much more full of a body as compared to any other amber ale .

nose is outright amazing with roasty malts , and some bacon bits like aromas too from all the roast . nice beer .  a nice medium colored golden beer . small white head only one quater of an inch stayed a while .  amazing texture ! full bodied , creamy and smooth as silk !

aroma is nearly non-existent and lies more with malt than and refreshing or interesting am . hops .  head fades fast into bubbly soapy top . when you drink it , you can tell this is a little different than a lot of strawberry blondes out there . it is not as candy like as other strawberry blondes . i liked the fact that it was n't simply strawberry .  mouthfeel is full and round .

she smells really good . she doesnt taste bad either .  pours a muddy brown color , cloudy , and with a faint head .  m : the mouthfeel is nothing short of silken : smooth carbonation , light body , and a clean finish . d : a solid , downright archetypal example of the english pale ale , but only really distinguished by its exceptional mouthfeel .

s : smoke all the way , barbeque , unique and outstanding smoked wood nose . d : as with the marzen this is a crazy experience .  pours pitch black with a razor thin head after a hard pour . little more than a thin rim of bubbles after a few seconds . after some swirling , a half finger of coffee colored head appears , only to dissipate within a couple seconds .  m : the mouthfeel is complex , deep with myriad bold flavors . the interplay of the raspberry and oak is superb .

luxurious white foam caps off the beer that takes several minutes to dissipate leaving some lacing . smell is heavy on the banana ( almost bubble gum ) with a solid wheat and a mild citrusy zest , little clove . medium body is rounded out by just enough yeast to make it full-tasting without being too rich .  orange , cloudy , with no head , just the many eyes . a warm biscuit assaults the nostrils with feathery grace .  it 's crazy how thick and creamy it is with almost no carbonation to speak of .

the wonderful smells coming out of my glass included a boat load of raisins , dates and xo brandy .  appearance : pours a very pale gold color , with a small white head that stays for a while and leaves a good lace .  m - smooth as silk , medium-full body . clean , not cloying at all .
the aroma is deep , unique and crazy . the oak aging certainly plays front and center .  a - mid-brown in colour and murky . minimal lacing .  mouthfeel has a fantastic thick body .

picked up the second to last bottle from henningshead bomb a- pours a deep deep black , motor oil , deep brown head , heavy lacing on the edges s- smell pretty amazing , heavy like chocolate , tobacco , lots of oak , malts alll up in the bitch . t- very deep chocolate , marshmallow , burnt coffee , very robust , also a bit of bitterness from the hops at the very in . o- not my kind of imperial stout , but a very well crafted one , there are not random tangents and i can respect the brewery , being its my first .  appears thin with a tiny head that quickly fades . dark brown , looks like coffee .  mouthfeel is near perfect . rich , full bodied , but it politely excuses itself from your palate and doesnt linger over long .

smell is amazing . yeast , hops , spice , apples , lemon and nutmeg all come out for me . that gives way to a wonderful finish that really saves this beer .  poured into a tulip . pours a hazy light orange color with just a layer of foam that dissapears about as soon as it forms .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , the hops just attack and stay on your pallet .

smells absolutely delicious : sweet and malty with a lot of vanilla caramel and milk chocolate on the nose along with bourbon-soaked dates . so excited to try this .  it looks extremely heavy and sludgy in the glass .  this one was balanced and mild overall , the creaminess of the mouthfeel was the most incredible thing about it .

the aromas are amazing . it smells very malty , similar to that of a barley wine , or if you have ever smelled malt extract , that is what this beer smells like .  pours ruby with a large fading head .  a - nice full head ; great lacing along the rim ; color a bit off ; it seems almost orange , two-toned s - excellent hops and florals ; a hint of something stale however t - hops are not overpowering ; nice malty flavor throughout m - the carbonation was surprisingly excellent ; wonderful effervescence on every mouthful d - overall i would say that this beer is not an every day , sit down at the pub , beer .

this is a fantastic smelling beer . oaky barrel wood is pretty pronounced in the flavor , as well as some rotting logs from what seems to me to be brett .  drinking it from the brown bottle , i could n't tell much about the appearance , so i 'll leave that for others to comment on . chocolaty and full of flavor ( roasted flavor ) it felt great in my mouth and went down very easily - too easily ?  velvety ... nice . the mouthfeel really helps this beer out and even saves it .

typical stout look , but above average head size & retention , along with sheets of lacing sticking to the glass for at least the first 3/4 of the beer . smell is less exhilarating , weak tones of coffee , toast , chocolate .  a : pours with a bright white bubbly head that struggles to get up to 1 finger . the body is pale golden straw , clear and very light in color . super thin sheets of lace with tattered ends . nothing particularly great about the appearance but , given the style , nothing exciting was expected .  mouthfeel is wonderful . chewy , sweet up front , sugary , filling out the palate , with a viscous wheat body , and mild tart notes with smoothness running down the tongue with a semi dry finish .

eight hours after opening bourbon barrel fourth dementia ( 2011 ) i 'm still reeling from the aroma . oh yeah , and bourbon . in fact , it 's extremely good . and the thick body solidifies this as a dessert old ale if there ever was one . it 's the best smelling velvet you will ever open from a bottle .  above average lacing & a trace of head retention s : cream , cocoa & coffee , plus grinds , fades a bit a the end , pus a touch of booze t : roasty malt , cocoa , chicory , along with dryness & dark chcolate up front .  the medium body leans on full but is in no way sweet or sticky . it 's very smooth and creamy yet a nice balance is made from ash and roasty bitterness .
s : intense phenols , pretty much overwhelming .  hazy copper color with a thin white head .  m : full-bodied and creamy , with low-moderate carbonation , and some alcohol warmth in the throat .

the head starts out at about 3/4 '' and whittled down to a light skin on the beer . the smell is amazing ! there are so many different aromas that definitely work together . there is the initial hop aroma of citrus and pine but mixes very well with the slight coffee and chocolate from the dark malts .  a - little to no head . no lacing .  perfectly carbonated and has a texture that is just right .

very narcotic aroma of lively beans and intensity . a pleasing tart of cocoa sweetness transitions slightly medicinal in a good way with respect to the world wide potency .  pours a slightly hazy gold with a small white head which leaves minimal lacing .  m- medium full , and quite creamy in the mouthfeel . carbonation is very unintrusive , but works wonders making this beer full , but light at the same time . o- exceptional drinkability , especially as it warms up .

taste : the flavors do n't do the aroma justice . it smells huge but drinks easy .  750ml into a tulip . pours an uninspired murky dark walnut , minor tan head was slow to recede , minor lacing .  m - stellar mouthfeel , definitely a slick feel but not oily like some overly-hopped ipa .

bitter hop and alcohol odour . nice head at first , firm and white , small bubbles .  served in a bells tulip glass , no head at all ( also too cold ) . murky dishwater look about it .  the mouthfeel is easily the highlight of this beer . body is absolutely perfect , full and creamy without getting too big for for its britches and approaching imperial level viscosity .

potent , sticky icky hop buds . intense dry-hopping leads to a fantastic nose on this one . t- this thing is a hop grenade . d- not for the faint of heart , and kind of a shitty price ( $ 6 ) but very good . good stuff .  a small amount of head formed and then dwindled to nothing but a ring around the glass .  big boned , with refined carbonation . nice lagery smoothness on the palate . sugary sweet .

totally excited about this awesome looking bottle . a : a light straw color with a nice white head . s : slightly sweet , slightly malty , but really there is not a whole lot to the smell . t : taste follows the scent .  330 ml bottle a -- poured a dark ruby color and settled a dark , murky , i guess plumb color . half finger of bright white head that went away as quick as i poured it .  mouthfeel is excellent , smooth as butter .

aroma has citrus , nice light malt , lots of breadiness -- - more than i 've ever smelled in a beer -- - and some hops . bursting with rich malt and light fruitiness . just enough hops to keep it from being cloying -- - leave it to a german-style brewer to avoid the over-hopping which characterizes so many american microbrews . quite drinkable .  very dark opaque color with brief head .  mouthfeel is truly exceptional . thick and full-bodied ... well carbonated .

the aroma was a delicious blend of floral and fruit elements highlighted by the hibiscus ; almost like a scented candle . the flavors were also very enjoyable , a blend of strawberry , pomegranate , wheat , lychee and a hint of alcohol heat .  a : dark brown , almost black body , with a thin , creamy tan head ; mostly lasting , but no lacing .  this is a full bodied brew with a smooth , creamy feel to the mouth . it has a modest and enjoyable level of carbonation . very good feel about this brew and well made across the board .

there is n't much of a smell , some malt nose and a memory of hazelnut . very drinkable , like my mouth is a magnet for this beer . a good nutty , malty , very drinkable beer , that does n't look very appealing .  very hazy dull copper color..nice off white head and sticky lacing . very surprised by the lack of clarity here .  texture is syrupy , thick , wonderful on that front .
smell : the nose is grainy with a bit of caramel malt .  came from the tap a light amber color with a thin white head .  cream , creamy mouthfeel .

suggestions of fresh , moist pipe tobacco , candied plums , and rum soaked raisinbread caress the nose . swirling and time release gentle wafts of dark chocolate and a kiss of herbal hops . absolutely seductive aromawise . in flavor , upfront is a toothsome mlange of unrefined brown sugar , dried dates and concentrated caramel . a notch more viscosity would have bolstered the hefty malt backbone aptly . turns lightly nutty late , with hints of carmelized almond leading into the sweet , yet thin and immaculately clean finish . superbly crafted and really a quintessential eisbock .  pours an ink black but unlike the straight zhukov , there is a small tan head .  mouthfeel is silky-smooth and beautiful . this is the beer 's greatest asset .

the smell is amazing , mocha caramel and hints of dark ghiradelli chocolates . nice to look at and warming on those chilly days , but a true stout will make you crave it all times of the year , this was not one of them .  pours a hazy pinkish , orange color thick with noticeable sediment . not a very big head and does not leave much lacing .  mouth is medium bodied heavy , awesome carbonation and an amazing blend of fruits and hops that sting the tongue .

a- citrusy grapefruit and orange hop aroma along with a slightly fruity and sweet malt aroma . upon opening the bottle delicious aromas filled the air , this is a great beer that you can just enjoy from aroma . t- much like the aroma hoppy goodness takes control , citrus fruits .  pours a decent 1 finger head that quickly dissipates and leaves little retention behind . nice cloudy yellow color .  the mouthfeel is wonderfully soft and smooth , syrupy and full , just enough fizz to cut the sugary fruit .

the menu says that this beer is `` brewed with 500 pounds of fresh watermelon . '' the beer was n't as fruity in taste as i expected it to be -- it has a typical wheat beer taste going down and finishes with a mild watermelon taste . this is a very drinkable summer beer .  upon first site i have to say that it looks fairly average . really it has a much darker side than many ipa 's - this is a ruddy brown color .  mouthfeel : very thick , almost chewy beer . this is a very good combination as well and makes for a very unique drinking experience .

this is the first beer in a long long time that i can remember smelling so good from all the way across the room from my pint glass , the nose really carries that far ! heady scents of pineapple / mango , pine resin , and roasted malts as if from a porter mingle together in a combo that really makes me salivate for some reason . tastes of all the things promised by the nose and also some interesting interplay between a sweet caramel malt tone that plays hide and seek with a roasted more bitter malt , finish is relatively straightforward bittering ... overall a fantastically well-executed bipa .  the beer pours a murky brown color with a cream-colored head .  m : perfect carbonation / smoothness to this brew .

simply delicious and maybe worthy of session drinking . pop the cap off one of these bottled babies and you are instantly engulfed in floral/herbal/hop aromas . at first sip it is a refreshing / light to medium pilsner body that encourages you to gulp a little more confidently untill a few mouthfuls later you are in a caught up in the aroma all the while never minding it .  received this in the ales of scotland gift pack , this poured a bright yellow , with little head and no lacing .  perfect for winter in the northwest.. and not too spicy like a lot of other winter ales but also warming .

s : chocolaty , toffee , malty , roasted espresso . t : slightly hoppy at first , very malty and chocolaty , towards the finish with a chocolate sweetness left behind .  a : this is one black stout ! this is blacker than satan 's armpit . not much head to speak of , just a slight brown ring . the anise and very slight vanilla add enough other complexities to keep zhukov from being one-note with all the dark chocolate . this stout sets the bar so high and i ca n't wait for it to come out again .  the mouthfeel is right where it should be .

this one was a bit of a letdown ... i was all set for a full-on nw american hops extravaganza but instead i got what i think was british hops ( fuggles ) . it was nicely carbonated and smelt good enough , though .  this beer poured a cloudy orange/yellow with a thick head which quickly dissipated .  in fact , it 's extremely good . and the thick body solidifies this as a dessert old ale if there ever was one .

carved in the west-coast `` in love with grapefruit '' mold there are a bunch of strange hints bubbling under the hop attack nose . marshmellows . reminds me of lagunitas ipa . all of those hops somehow gave this beer the most marshmellow taste i 've ever experienced , which was not pleasant .  poured a slightly cloudy amber with a thin dark tan head that quickly became a tan ring around the glass .  this baby also shines on the mouthfeel .

the nose is like a raspberry popsicles . this is the best smelling beer ever ! it tastes like it smells .  very little spots of lacing are left around the glass .  imho : a good representation of the style ; good balance , very sweet with a great mouthfeel .

not much head retention or lacing s : sourness , hay & barnyard in this , just intensifies as this warms t : lemon tartness , green apple sourness & a bit of hay up front . finishes with puckery tartness , oaky dryness , a bit of balsamic vinegar acidity & sooo much sourness mf : light/medium bodied with slight carbonation & much dryness drinks very easy , always happy to try anything from these guys , i think i prefer these heavier & darker for optimal effect , none of the rr sours are slouches though .  appearance- the color is no surprise for an imperial stout : a deep red tinted brown . there is almost no head , though there is fairly nice lacing which lingers for a few seconds on the side of the glass .  truly exceptional creaminess . overall this was a refreshing take on the style with exceptional mouthfeel .

no smell to speak of . tastes rather run-of-the-mill but does n't have any aftertaste to speak of .  nothing special about how it looked ... poured a clear golden yellow with a nice white head .  what a great body on this beer ! velvety smooth with a medium thickness and a superb carbonation level that adds to the experience .

intoxicating and exceptional . chocolate-y , with rosewatery alcohol fumes .  this pours out a dark but translucent brown with a meager head that quickly disappears .  a uniquely creamy and smooth mouthfeel really stands out to me . medium to full bodied . a nice , bitter , warming finish .

really , really good . the flavour does n't live up to the amazing highs of the aroma with the flavour lacking a bit of depth . very good and it works well here .  12oz . brown bottle . a : pours a shiny golden color with a thin white head which leaves nice sticky lacing .  this beer has an unnatural smoothness to it .
smell- real strong blueberry aroma , notice right away when pouring .  average , low orange color . no real head and a low carbonation level .  thick and smooth moutfeel and mildly carbonated .

the aroma is of straight up hops . it smells as though i will be eating hops , it makes me a little afraid for what it will taste like . surprisingly the taste is not as hoppy as the smell lets on .  beer poured a nice straw color with minimal head .  this is velvety smooth , and absolutely perfect . overall : a fantastic extra from a fantastic ba .

smell is somewhat unpleasant with grain and malt undertones .  on tap at the brewpub , served in a pils flute , blitzen is a clear gold with only some wispy , white skim .  m : the feel is full bodied and oily ... perfect for an imperial stout .

aroma is deeply of hearty grains , very impressive here . taste exhibits the malt depth quickly upfront , and quickly gives way to ample crisp hoppiness .  a muddy brown beer with thin head . the haze no yeast , probably a chill haze .  m- low carbonation and amazingly creamy d - i 've always thought that drinking guiness was like drinking a loaf of bread -- a can makes a good dinner and this is still the same
perfect scent , just as a wit should be .  pours a hazy transparent gold with a fluffy white head .  the mouthfeel is rich and thick without ever being sticky .

slight hay/grass aroam with ahint of bakery , but really nothing to speak of .  mojo ipa is a hazy golden ale with a frothy white head that fades quickly and leaves good lacing .  taste has bitter chocolate with a hoppy clean finish ; mouthfeel is exceptional and creamy .

wonderful aroma . t : very nutty with caramel flavors . lots of malt complexity . brown malt ? i enjoyed it .  i was lucky enough to pick up a couple of bottles of this , and while expecting an average euro pils , i was very surprised ... i could actually taste fresh hop bitterness ! must of been right off the boat ... very tasty , one of the best i have tried .  m : i think this may be the best aspect of it , just a wonderful body .

smells incredible , smells a lot of grapes , not so much grapefruit but grapes and citrus .  poured from a 12 oz bottle , no date a - pours a light , slightly hazy yellow-orange with a thin , one finger white head . retention settles to a thin layer ; sticky lacing s - after the pour the initial nose was very floral , but as it sits a more piney cascade presence makes itself known .  thick smooth mouthfeel and mildly carbonated . the creamy smoothness is more apparent and delightful now .

bananas , sweet sugars , hops , excellent . this is a very good tasting beer , but there is a touch too much water in the mouthfeel and a touch too much soapy residue left on the tongue afterwards .  all in all , this is a very refreshing summer brew . extremely light and smooth , perfect for a hot summer 's day , just as the bottle suggests . in addition , i also find the cartoon on the bottle amusing .  mouthfeel is perfect , with a light body and a crisp finish that ends semi-dry thanks to a vigorous carbonation level .

smells amazing . t : you guessed it , hazelnut .  the tan quarter inch head withdrew to no head at all very quickly . the still body had a very dark brunette color . as the beer swirled in the glass , it left a weak lacing .  m : medium-full bodied and silky smooth . this is one of the creamiest , smoothest beers i 've ever had and is an absolute joy .

aroma had notes of cherries and chocolate with a little bit of coffee . jah va stout is a very nice stout .  it was served to me with a small , sticky head .  m : thick but clean in the mouth , almost oily , with a warming alcohol effect down the throat . light carbonation balances the thickness of this brew quite perfectly . d : hmm , i do n't think this beer gets all the credit it deserves .

s - rice , wheat , and other hay/ farm smelling adjuncts .  a : pours a murky brown with two fingers of tan head that recedes into a foamy ring with little lacing .  there 's nothing , i repeat ... nothing bad about the mouthfeel on this one . rich yet dry and even clean for something so huge . full finish gives off a little oatmeal chocolate chip sweetness .

aroma is thin and distant..slight hint of green apples and dark spoiling fruits . there is a spritzy , grainy wet finish with suggestions of nuts . nice , although an extreme stretch to compare it to a traditional flemish brown ale .  this is velvety black beer with a thin tan head that has lots of little odd white blotches in it . very drinkable for this style .  this beer is absolutely in the mouth , and the complexity -- the way the bourbon and hops almost spar with one another across the tongue -- is simply beautiful . just when you think there 's too much here for the alcohol to show through , it warms your mouth and very much adds to the experience .

i almost ca n't smell anything . there are some malt notes here , maybe a few hops , but not much .  a : pours a dark brown , almost black . a small beige head forms and leaves some light lace behind .  this beer has a nice full body and a crisp carbonation .

s ) really nice on the nose as well , great whiff of yummy juicy west coast citric hops with a firm honey malt base . very neutral overall flavor , a few peeks of hops and malt , but it 's like a perfect balance that mutes each flavor .  good solid dunkel . poured with a small to medium tan head that quickly subsides and a tiny bit of lace .  mouthfeel is full , thick , viscous , sticky , and hardly carbonated . this is absolutely delicious , but the sweetness really gets to be a bit much .

aroma is great . roasty . i think i could just sit and smell this one all night .  poured from 12oz bottle into pilsner glass a- bright/clear yellow orange , foamy white head fades to about a finger s- apricot of course ... some citrus , perfumy t- like dried apricots from bulk section of super market ( which i love ) , and citrus and ends with a slight honey/ artificial sweetness , nutty finish m- lots of carbonation , medium bodied , crisp , very sweet and refreshing d- great , goes down smooth and easy , pleasant fruity aftertaste , not too expensive , a beer to buy again and again !  mouthfeel on this beer is damn near perfection in glass .

poured in ellipse glass at the bullfrog a : thin head ; light orangish brown ; a bit , but only , of lacing s : grapefruit , pear , hops in delicious quantities ; very inviting t : belgian-style ipa , quite yummy ; uses u.s. hops called calypso , which tend to be on the lighter , piney side ; pear and apple overtones come through m : slightly dead a really nice beer .  pours a oily peach tea with a pinky of white head . drinks fine , a very confused belgian golden imo . & probably as cheap or cheaper here as it would be in that heavily taxed country .  m- thick body , almost barrel aged type of thickness . i thought that this was brilliant about this beer . this is probably the best thing about this beer .

the scent seems almost bang on , along with a touch of coffee aroma . a great smelling brew . t + m : just like the aroma for the most half , with 'added chocolate chips ' the sweet tooth loves it , though i suppose under some circumstances , it could be come a little cloying .  a - dark clear brown , quickly fading head s - yum ... dark roasted nuts ... t - right along with the smell , a delicious dark roasted nut , almost stout type taste .  really smooth and velvety with just the right amount of carbonation .

this is what it is . this is probably the first beer you snuck as a kid . it 's at every high school party and in every frat house . it a house hold name . this is a average beer for a good price . that it 's been around for years does n't mean it 's not worth drinking . just because it is from one of the big boys of brewing do n't mean it 's not worth a review  355ml bottle poured into pint glass 9/10/11 a clear dark copper with lots of little bubbles but not much for head or lace s a fruity nut bar with some hard toffee a little herbal hops and plenty of sweet malty goodness , fairly earthy and right on for the style t what i smell but a little leafy tea bag and some booze , not quite as nice as the smell but still pretty darn good m medium bodied with a sweet after taste that lingers o pretty solid marzen that 's working well with this chilly fall weather and the turkey dinner making me fatter i did n't even realize this was in the mixed pack i picked up but i 'm happy its in there .  o : very good eye appeal and remarkable mouthfeel .

skunkiness and honey followed by a faint nickel nose . slight floral hops in there for good measure .  this is a good beer from summit , not great but this one would be a great 12 pack buying refrigerator beer . it is not as red as it is copper brown .  m-creamy , rich and wonderful . d-dangerously good . so smooth , a little filling but it goes down well . wow , what a fantastic beer .

hop aroma erupted from the bottle like few others . in the mean time i 'll check to make sure i have the word `` hop '' in every sentence ... .  just enough to seem refreshing . appearance - copperish , straw color .  the best part of this eer by far is the mouthfeel and drinkability . nearly flawless , the only problem is that i want to drink it faster than my wallet permits .

smells perfect ; exactly how a pumpkin beer should in my opinion . d - a really good pumpkin ale . i thought it smelled amazing , but wish the taste was a little sweeter as opposed to spicey .  it has a dark reddish/brown color covered with a thin cap of tiny bubbles .  the great flavor is held up with an excellent body and mouthfeel .

a very heady , spicy , warming , yet also very cool and calming , aroma profile . after the first few sips , the aftertaste was n't as acrid , but it was still pretty obtrusive .  pours a slightly cloudy deep amber pale ale .  mouthfeel is thick and lush . wonderful overall , a great scotch ale .

omg this was skunked . first smell from 5 ft away said skunked , last smell before i finished the beer said skunked . pepe lephew level skunked . i found this beer to be a fairly good epa that had been slowly destroyed by light leaving it to be a skunked heap .  vintage bottle 1998 , sampled january 2005 this beer pours with only a wispy pale head , it is a hazy dark amber color .  excellent mouthfeel .
i feel dizzy just smelling this , and not from the alcohol .  decent retention and poor lacing .  mouthfeel is perfect . the weight of this beer is phenomenal .

that should n't take away from the dreat hop taste and smell that this beer has . nice cascade aroma to say the least . the look is good , not great , not too much lacing at all .  appearance : hazy straw golden as you 'd expect , but a very thin and weak head .  i love the full mouthfeel on the speedway stout .

lovely . taste is a letdown . the appealing citrus smell so lively in the aroma is gone as it crosses the tongue .  on tap at cbc in cambridge . pours a syrupy copper red with no head .  m - outstanding ! the smoothest , creamiest brew i have ever consumed , goes down like liquid silk . d - i would come back to this one purely for the mouthfeel , never had anything like it .

'' the head on top was a thin layer on top , and it had a light brown , iced-tea color .  mouthfeel is great ! lots of carbonation and it very crisp and refreshing .

a - pours quite black with a one-finger mocha head that quickly diminishes , retention around the edge only , no much lacing s - the aroma is the highlight , like a vanilla latte with four or five shots of espresso and some caramel thrown in as well , they hit the creme brulee notes very well , really fantastic aroma t - bitter coffee burst up front the quickly turns into a sweet and sour vanilla and caramel flavor , lingering light coffee bitterness and a strange lactic sourness , i 'm not sure if there is an infection issue with these bottles , but i tried this on tap at last years winter solstice and in the bottle ( same batch ) soon thereafter , and there was no sourness , my previous tastings were much more enjoyable , i 'm giving this a 3 versus a lower score because i know how great it was before the sourness developed m - full-bodied , moderate to low carbonation , fairly sweet and sour finish with only light bitterness , some alcohol warming d - the sourness is rather awkward and really limits the drinkability , the alcohol is pretty well hidden pretty disappointed with this bottle , as my previous tastings of this beer were fantastic .  poured a 2 finger light tan head with good retention . thin , inconsistent lacing .  this has such a beautifully smooth mouthfeel with a perfect amount of carbonation zing .

the aroma is amazing- a wonderfully fresh coriander and thyme smell with underlying lemon . unusual and very interesting .  dennis : typical unibroue here , fizzy , great dark fruity taste and an alcohol kick that sneaks up on you . jen said it best below , but what i enjoyed most was the slight alcohol bitter kick at the end that i got on the exhale . they seem to have an overall air of similarity in all of their brews , not that it is a bad one , but it gets boring . this one offers a nice blend of citrus fruits , orange and lemon accompanied with a slight banana , clove , apple and pepper punch . nice fun little bubbles dance on your tongue to make this fairly easy and fun to drink . definitely worth a try ; it is both a typical and unique unibroue .  m - nice small carbonation , very soft and smooth .

i love the aroma its very enticing . taste is chocolate and roasted malts , faint scotch and ash . great smelling and tasting brew . i would have liked the body a bit thicker , but great just the same .  this beer pours a murky orange-amber color . the head is a half inch in height , and recedes quickly into minimal lacing .  fucking incredible amount of creaminess . good carbonation .

fairly sweet and a bit stale , really .  on to the beer , this ipa was a bit of a letdown appearance wise . the head vanished quick and lace was minimal .  m : perfection . my words simply ca n't do justice to the body of this beer .

nice floral and apricot odor , followed by a very hoppy taste with a citrus finish . the smell almost overpowers the flavor , but the floral hops dominate the taste , almost too much yet this beer still has a very good flavor and balance .  very cloudy dark orange body with pretty good lacing and a small but stable head . the only bad thing about this beer is the haze .  this drinks exceptional , no way this is 10 % ? ? medium on the body , sugary and tart , bold hops with bitter finish , very creamy and smooth .

wow as a i pour this all i can say is it smells phenomenal . i ca n't wait to drink this one . smells incredible . citrusy hop notes mingle with some tropical hints and a mango like sweetness . really this is how a dipa should smell . overall this is a fantastic beer . i love the aroma on this one and the flavor makes it a top notch dipa .  500 ml bottle in a snifter a : black , shallow tight tan head .  the beer has an exceptional mouthfeel , and is just luscious .

this thing smells amazing . huge caramel and vanilla aromas upfront that let just a bit of the roasted malt and cocoa flavors sneak in .  a - a burnt orange color with a nice yellow hue in the light . there is a very strong white head and a good amount of carbination/ s - a great front end of citrus , deep fruits , nuttyness and pepper that is mellowed out by a strong armoma of bourbon and vanilla smoothness .  the carbonation was enough to give it life but not bite your tongue . fantastic beer .
