the scent is munich malt sweetness with prominent chocolate and caramel aroma , bread crust and nut-like qualities , all indicating that munich dunkel has been used as base beer for this one . the very subtle ham-like smoke show up when it comes to flavor , but remains shy nonetheless .  poured a golden straw into a tulip glass , with 2 fingers of billowy head that fairly quickly dissipates ( at least in my glass , there is still some on top of my wife 's ) . one of the better saisons that i 've had the opportunity to try- especially given the mediocre farmhouse ale 's i had at the clips of faith festival the day before yesterday .  mouthfeel is great . this one stands out in the mouthfeel department for dipa 's .

the smell is not good . it smells like any macro you 've had . thankfully my nose does not work particularly well . crisp moutfeel with a sweet nose and a bitter , and somewhat dry , finish .  a : clear yellow with some gold undertones . a highly carbonated head initially , but dies very quickly . needs a bit fluffy look to it .  ale best enjoyed before 01/09/06 printed on the top label 09id 12:50 big burst of air at open plus a bit of foam from the top appearance dark red , slightly opaque body ; rising carbonation from the basement ; massive cloudlike , off-white head ; lace is modest smell with a bit of a cold the nose is a bit blocked but ill do my best ; yeast , date , raisin , candy sweetness , spice , sour apple , some bread crust and a touch of alcohol taste again , excuse the slighty blocked nose ; yeasty ; apple and a bit of the spice and candy ; a bit of hops at the end mouthfeel big full feel ; a carpet of carbonation rolls into the mouth ; nice crisp carbonation and dry enough for a nice close drinkability for such a big feel , the palate is cleaned nicely at the end corsendonk hits the dubbel as good as ichiro . what a pleasant experience .

s- metallic note first , with some dark yet creamy chocolate , roasted malt , off vegetable smell ( brussel sprout/cabbage ) worsens as it warms t- malt is very subdued in the beginning but there is a creaminess changing to a strong hop bitterness coming through in the finish and heat of the alcohol lingers strongly on the back of the tongue .  thin soapy head on an amber to light copper beer . rich caramel and toasted nuts , with a slight hop aroma in the smell . caramel and slight roasted character in the malt , slight hop grassiness , very clean yeast character , with a pleasant bitterness at the end . slightly undercarbonated , but very smooth , for the style , this was slightly heavy ... a very clean and malty apa , that dose n't revolve around hop aroma and bitterness .  the body is outstanding , better than any abt from belgium i 've had , decadent creaminess and perfectly mouth-filling .

great scent . all hazelnuts at first and then you can smell some hops and malt .  22oz bomber ... an increasingly distant remnant/reminder of 'summer ' 2010 ... this beer pours a medium orange-amber colour , with many a floatie , and one finger of foamy , bubbly off-white head , which leaves some nice cavernous lace around the glass as it dissipates .  the mouthfeel is epic , the perfect feel .

some chocolate aromas and a slight alcoholic aroma which is surprising based on the % 4.8 abv . the alcohol aroma does not translate to the flavor at all . the aroma was much better than the flavor .  appearance : dark brown with slight haze . thick and aggressive head at pour which dwindles to a granular film ; present until finish .  great , bubbly mouthfeel that compliments the other traits of the beer ; keeps the sweetness from being cloying and offers it a dry finish .

smell : rich caramel , citrus , and apple cider . good blend of sweets and spices .  bottle : poured a bright orangey color ale with a very light foamy head with no retention and some lacing .  thick , creamy , viscous liquid that was milky , chocolatey and roasty . big on taste , and big on feel . nice .

appearance : nice amber color with apparent carbonation out of the tap smell : fantastic ! very aromatic and floral + citrus taste : i am a hophead so i will just say that i really enjoyed the hop flavor that gave all that the smell promised it would . could have been a little more thick , but overall very enjoyable . overall thoughts : i really dug this beer , it was aromatic and smacked me in the face a bit ( which i like ) .  pours pale burnt orange with a lot of floaters .  m : this mouthfeel is out of this world . extremely creamy and very very smooth . although the alcohol is present in the nose it is very well hidden in the taste and mouthfeel .

up to the nose , it released a nive fruity smell including pineapple , peach , and mango .  batch 2-2009 pours a foggy , cloudy orange with a fair , jet white head and some no lacing . it 's not all that to look at .  m - perfect . low carbonation and high viscosity .

more fruit when it 's cooler : a really pineapple-y citrus tartness , then more resin and spice as it warms . alcohol comes through but it 's unobtrusive . taste follows up nicely on the aroma , with an aggressive hop bitterness balanced by a slight malt syrup and liquored-up piney character .  a- totally opaque orange pour . highly carbonated . has the feel of there being pulp in the beer .  it has a nice thick feel that i do not often find in wheat beers , and leaves a pleasant and satisfying aftertaste .

s : fruity and bready : heavy on the yeast , crisp apples ( love that in particular ) , bananas , sugar , alcohol . as the beer warmed , it smelled like a fresh apple cider , too ... lovely spices like cinnamon , cloves , cardamom . huge fan of the smells . a very multi-layered experience . t : tastes of sweet yeastiness , burnt sugar , darker tones of the apple , touch of alcohol . d : what can i say ? big fan of the fruity smells . makes me think of a nice fall day .  i had this on tap at the brewery and liked it so much i brought home some growlers . i 'm a huge skeptic of magic hat , but this was suggested to me because of my lucky kay affinity . some iipa 's i drink are way too overpowering and very hard to drink . a wonderful concoction that i hope magic hat keeps around .  d : another excellent brooklyn brewery creation that cuts down the style boundary between hefe and wit with style and tons of flavor with an excellent mouthfeel .

poured into my new arrogant bastard pint glass ... this pours an extremely murky reddish brown with virtually no head ... a small one if any ... extremely murky.. looks very much like a cask ale to me which should be an awesome thing ... the aroma on this is just lovely ... absolutely one of the best smelling brews ever ... the woody oakiness mingled with the raisin-like fruitiness and sweet maltiness work perfectly here ... this beer is loaded with character and complexities in the aroma category..someone said something about christmas pudding and they nailed it ... this would make an excellent christmas ale ... there 's a spiciness here that reminds me of spice cake and a sweetness like the boiled custard that goes over it ... magnificent ... perhaps the most pronounced oakiness of any oak aged brew i 've ever had ... this is just a magnificently crafted beer ... the deep sweet malty aspects along with that dark fruitiness has this one making me love it ... its a perfect sipping beer to relax on my patio and watch the hickory chips work their magic on my chickens ... the vanilla and oak and sweetness mingle together perfectly ... hints of booziness here and there ... very very nice ... could i see myself ordering one of these in a smoky english pub ?  light color hued for an ipa - almost a straw/gold color .  hits the tongue with an almost velvety texture with little carbonation .

s : faint aroma of biscuit and toasted malt . t : the taste makes up for the lack of nose . o : very enjoyable copper ale .  this is one of the first true competitors for the rauchbier urbock by aecht schlenkerla i have ever tasted . the tatse is not as punchy smokey but rather more subtle and multilayered . there is a slightly more prevalent sweetness which i like and this is very well balanced by the smokiness . the mouthfeel and drinkability are very good !  mouthfeel is velvety smooth , and drinkability is great .

a : pours pitch black , little to no head with some lacing , appears to be thinner than some impy stouts , but is still quite dark s : big notes of vanilla up front along with bourbon and oak , these notes meld flawlessly with smooth dark chocolate , everything smells like it is in perfect balance and there is no pronounced booziness like i often find in barrel aged beers .  poured in to a pint glass a very fizzy orange color , with a quick to fade white heading .  mouthfeel is full and creamy with dead on carbonation .

i really like double ipas , but compared to stone 's ruination or russian river 's pliny the elder , i ca n't say that reaper ale 's sleighor dipa is in the same league . smell is the best characteristic of this beer ; heavy citrus and piney notes ( yummy ! overall , i enjoyed this beer , but would not have more than one on any given occassion .  i 'm quite surprised by the scores here , this was the best beer of the day at mth ... pours a dark straw lightly clear ... the aroma is a really nice combo of wet grassy hops , immediately reminds me a stronger daisy cutter , nice but one-noted .  m : the label on this beer says its a smooth dark ale ... they arent lying about how smooth this beer is..very nice ! this is a great beer ... was a little bit hesitant to get it cause i do n't really like imperial stouts..its very far from that , a very tasty brew .

the smell is pretty skunky and could be compared to stagnant pool water .  a - pours a very dark mahogany with a modest tan head that has decent retention . lacing is very light , but there .  the mouthfeel is awesome too because it has that thicker rich like malt taste that you 'd get in well crafted higher alcohol beers .

the smell is faint . there is a little bit of hoppy citrus there , and less malt .  a : pours a golden color , not much head at all . tastes almost like a pilsner only a shade darker in the color . i know its called bayern amber , but if it was a blind taste test i would almost put it in a pisner or some other category .  m-medium creamy carbonation with a spicy finish .

it does have a nice raspberry aroma and , it is n't a bad looking beer , but it tasted like a sweet raspberry soda .  a - hazy dark brown/red body that lets very little light shine through . the head is a creamy khaki color and pretty minimal . just some small edging and weak lacing .  m- unbelievably smooth and creamy with a bit of a alcohol-hop bite at the end . very nice .

look : the beer pours a golden-yellow color with a huge white head smell : malts , grain , grass and light flowery hops .  i found this to be an easy drinking ipa , but the name big hop is a misnomer -- the beer is very crisp , but not very hoppy . if youre expecting something bitter , than you would be disappointed with this brew . this was my beer of choice for a short while , because of its drinkability , however .  mouthfeel is amazing with this beer .

very nice lacing . aroma is a bright bouquet of various apples , tart and sweet . beautiful front flavor and finish is semi dry and very clean .  a : this beer poured a cloudy orange/golden color . not really much to look at .  mf : perfect coarseness and dryness for the style .

the smell is also incredible , hoppy , grapefruity , and slightly of honey . after tasting it the sweet and honey odors are much more present and dominate the smell , making it not as great , but when i first smelled it before tasting it was incredible . the taste is good and for the 21 % abv the alcohol is surprisingly masked .  poured from a bottle into a duvel tulip a- pours a dark , murky , pond water looking shade of orangeish brown with a one finger , very frothy offwhite head . very nice head , but the beer itself looks disgusting , so i 'm splitting the difference s- it 's an interesting aroma , partly of citrus and partly of grass ... .i like it , but i ca n't get as much of it as i want due to the size of my glass .  the mouthfeel hit me as exceptional , as the start was crisp and the finish was lightly crisp and smooth on the tongue . the spices last long on the tongue after swallowing .

smells of lush tropical fruit , grapefruit and pineapple predominate . darn good beer here .  light brown with orange/copper highlights . no lace .  mouthfeel/overall : mouthfeel is awesome . full bodied , with mild , low carbonation the produces a lush , velvety mouthfeel .

very nice aroma . t : similar to the aroma , there are some slight belgian sweet notes at first with hints of light fruits and bubblegum . there 's a nice combination of sweet and funky , and it smells wonderful . i 'd like the bpa aspects to shine through a bit more in the flavor and to have a drier body , but still it 's a cheap alternative to the likes of orval .  tiny , tan tinged head that does n't leave much covering . peach , mango , papaya and some skunk weed on the nose . these are immediately beaten down by an extreme bitterness that completely dries out the mouth and leaves some burning alcohol flavors in the mouth .  dark fruit , malt and the zesty yeast combine to flavor the beer , it is rich and full bodied yet not heavy on the tongue .

in the aroma , a faint hop and some wheat like notes . nice mellow hop , with a nice wheat hint , although the nose is lacking .  poured into a czech pilsner glass , premium verum shows a yellow gold body ; transparent .  mouthfeel - very smooth feel , subdued carbonation , right on .

short version : decent ale with great hop smell but lacking in hop flavor/bitterness . first nose was strong on hops .  darker than i was expecting . a ridiculous punch of simcoe hop flavor . somewhat on the verge of becoming an imperial amber ale ( la nugget nectar ) or a lighter american barley wine than a double ipa .  the mouthfeel is the best part of this drink .

not much hop aroma - smells malty and faintly alcoholic . it 's an ok beer , but an ipa that costs around $ 9 for a sixer should have some hop aroma , imo .  a- a bright copper with very little head and lace for a dipa .  mouthfeel is amazingly thick and rich .

a big fluffy white head with some visible carbonation smells of pine and citrus . the scent is much like their standard ipa just more intense . this one lets you know its gon na get you . the taste is much the same , just in great excess . i enjoy hoppy ipas but this one is just too much .  appearance is a cloudy dark amber/brown wit a nice whitish head , but not the black the label hinted at .  mouthfeel is creamy and rich , but sits lightly . almost ... fluffy , with a bit of a refreshing tang at the finish with moderate even mild bitterness .

good stuff in the smell - fudge , chocolate syrup , and roasted coffee .  12oz bottle into a pint glass a : pours a reddish mahogany with a khaki head that fades to a thick ring and leaves no lacing on the glass .  lovely soft caressing bottle-conditioned mouthfeel .

smell is wonderful ; the cherry aroma is very pronounced . this is the best smelling beer i have had so far . taste and mouthfeel are excellent .  appearance very dark ruby black with visible carbonation and no head .  the mouthfeel is where this beer shines the most ... oh so creamy and full-bodied . just magnificent .

s-5.0 : smells sooo delicious . chocolate , molasses , salt , cookies , figs , oatmeal , and some perfectly muted hops .  when poured from the swing-top bottle into my sniffer glass , it showed a dull gold/amber color with a white head .  m : crisp and bubbly carbonation make the drink a pleasure in your mouth .

spotty lacing left all over the glass . s - very strong tropical hop aroma . hops are certainly the center of this one . pineapple is the primary fruit that comes through in the nose but i alos pick up a little mango and a light candy sweetness . t - candied pineaplle and other assorted tropical notes . very hop forward without being a tongue buckling hop punch .  amber color , almost red , slightly veiled . the head is decent , with some little bubbles , average compactness .  the body is fantastic . it is -- just as the name says -- like cream : slick , glassy and wonderful .

smells of strong citrus , you can definintely tell there are a lot of american variety aroma hops .  poured from a bottle into a tulip . beer is black and has nearly no head at all .  mouthfeel is the best part of this beer . the beer glides onto the tongue and sits firmly , with just enough carbonation to bring fizziness to both the tongue and the roof of the mouth . easy to swallow .

smell- one of the best scents from a stout i have set my nose upon . huge hit of burnt coffee grounds , plus some dark chocolate and cigarette smoke smell .  a little on the red side for a brown ale , but that 's ok , we do n't drink color . good foam hugging the glass and a nice aroma of mollases and alcohol .  mouthfeel is full and creamy , the ease of drinking this is quite astonishing for 12 % abv but the plastic is holding it back a bit . fantastic stout overall , although i 'm not sure it measures up with the top tier .

i tried this beer in a restaurant that i had been looking forward to trying for some time . the barmaid was having a bit of a time getting a good pour ( turned out it was her first night on the job ) we were patient , and our patience was , eventually rewarded . i thought this beer was very good . most reviews do n't seem to agree so i 'm guessing that the fact that my beers were drawn from the tap makes all the difference .  pours a fairly clear , dingy brown with a thin off white head on top . poor retention and no lacing .  m - creamy goodness !

smell and taste are strong cocoa powder , vanilla extract , mild roasted coffee beans , table cream , and bitter chocolate . bourbon on the nose , not apparent in the flavour . a gorgeous beer , one of my personal favourites .  amber with a thin white head that fades quickly .  a fantastically smooth and creamy mouthfeel that leaves you begging for another pint .

belgian yeast gives this beer a truly delicious smell . aromas of green apples and white grape juice really make this beer mouth-watering .  bottle poured into a glass a : amber color with a small whitish head that fades rapidly ; poor head retention ( better head retention is standard for this style ) but good lacing .  the mouthfeel is very , very nice . not too thick , not too thin and with the fine carbonation that you 'd want from champagne .

the nose knows : this pumpkin beer smells better than it tastes , hence the perfect 5 . rich pumpkin , not overpowering , with nutmeg and cinny thrown into the mix . the smell improves as this beer warms , as you drink it , stick your nose into your glass- the pumpkin presents itself boldly . tongueland : little thin , not lingering , which is a good thing .  date : 26 january 2011 glass : standard 10oz snifter type : 12fl oz snifter poured aggressively , 2-finger head holds firm for a while , color is red-orange , lacing is a little runny .  it had a great amount of body nd flavor while not feeling too heavy .

the smell was amazing ... .like an orange life savor ... .very good !  poured a darkish amber into my tulip glass - little head , not much retention .  slick and full in the mouth with a perfect crisp level of carbonation .

pours a dark red/brown hue , huge brownish head , smell is faint , not very aromatic , beautiful lacing ensues .  against my better judgement picked up the summer 2011 discovery pack at the lcbo . has a toque hanging off the 'k ' in the beer name . pours yellow and fizzy . good head retention .  the mouthfeel is amazing for this beer , considering the style and the alcohol content .

much like the piiti porter in appearance , this one takes on a new life in aroma with the onslaught of coffee you get from the aroma . i enjoy the aroma/flavors of coffee just as much as the next guy , but this might have been a bit too much . i applaud them for making this , because i really did enjoy it , but just tone down the coffee a little .  color is a fabulous copper amber brown . unfortunately , the head is very small and short-lived . almost no lacing .  mouthfeel : very full and creamy .

either way , it 's pretty awesome . also slight vanilla notes .  is a clear , amber-brown with not much carbonation or head .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy and with huge grapefruit flavors , followed by pine and then resin . beautifully balanced .

fantastic . maybe a bit caramelly , too . just wonderful . the taste is bourbon dominated , but that 's about it . a very nice offering .  appearance : murky medium-brown . thin beige head that dissipated quickly .  the mouthfeel , i am guessing due to the aging , is nearly perfect . just a hint of spiciness on the palate leaves this fairly dry and wonderfully smooth .

poured from a 12 oz bottle , no date , but has one of the bell 's funky batch codes ... a - pours about as black as black gets , with a generous roasted marshmallow colored head . s - hints of bitter chocolate , roasted malts ... earthy aroma . i do n't want to say the nose is thin , but i found myself wanting more from it . t & m - full bodied , creamy .  a - deep brown around edges , black in center . thin off white head , sticky but nothing special .  m- very smooth with a good carbonation level . excellent .

a wonderful aroma . overall i wish the taste lived up to the phenomenal smell of this beer , but it 's still quite good .  liberty ale is a hazy golden ale with small particles floating in it .  very full bodied and mouth feel complex and nice tastes all around very drinkable stout with nice hop balance

smells awful . i swear to god i can pick up a hint of limburger cheese and that 's about the last odor you want coming from your beer . those terrible aromas are detected in the flavor also but there 's a also a sweet grainy element that improves this whole experience ever so slightly .  appearance : looks pink coming out of the bottle but amber in the glass . fast fading head knocks off a point .  really big , rich mouthfeel . thick and chewy with a smooth carbonation , which suits the decadence of the flavour well . in fact , this is one of the most perfectly matched mouthfeels i 've come across , so top marks for goose island !

s - this smells like pure vanilla , with some butterscotch aroma in there as well .  pours a dark brown with a light khaki head that is fast fading but comes back with a nice swirl . typical fresh pineapple ipa nose and not any `` brown '' character if you smelled it blind .  exceptionally creamy mouthfeel , a bit airy though .

s ) superb late hop nose . citrus , pine with good malt . almost identical in aroma to marmelade on toast . tingly , slightly astringent , yet quite crisp finish .  a - pours a deep brownish mahogany color . a one finger , off white head that has sub par retention , there is no lacing which is not very consistent with this style .  m : very good body given the low abv .

s - very rich and powerful aroma . fruits and flowers with some honey in the front and the powerful aftershock of alcohol in the back . the aroma of this beer is something special !  easily the best beer in the flying dog mix pack ... still not saying much . the taste is hop bitter , but nondescript . there 's a slightly off-putting pilsner-esque bitter taste on the back end of each sip .  it 's rich and smooth , a touch creamy -- flawless mouthfeel .

really , quite good . m- this would be the real up side of another year .  amber in color , but doesnt have the tradional amber/red ale aroma . has a great creamy texture that goes down smooth . apperance was weak except for some lacing .  mouthfeel is creamy and smooth and aftertaste is creamy dark semi-sweet chocolate and alcohol . yummy !

yeasty notes of flowers and bubble gum in the aroma . the taste is fairly dry at firsts and sweetens up midway through with bits of vanilla , bubble gum , and lemon grass .  a dark shade of amber with brown hues inside . the active , tan colored head ... gone fast ? i really enjoy the zin-like aspects to this one , dry-leafy and some dark wheat in a subtle way .  the mouthfeel is the best part of this beer .

a : pours a very dark brown with absolutely no head s : there was a good dark fruit aroma along with some sourness t : vinegar sour throughout the bottle .  bottle into a pint , it 's a deep golden color with about a finger of white foam . it 's pretty solid .  mouthfeel : smooth and body-warming right from the start .

smell- the nose is bright with german hops , then a cereal-like and sweet adjunct nose completely takes over .  pours a murky golden brown . decent amount of fluffy white head that dissipated quickly but left a nice lacing .  no alcohol warmth comes through ... m - thick and creamy with a moderate amount of carbonation . this one is deliously viscous ... d - really enjoyed these .
smell is fantastic , tons of vanilla with some chocolate .  not much carbonation after an aggressive pour into a tulip glass .  4.5/5 mouthfeel - smooth almost has a chewiness . exceptional .

its cheap price and drinkability have truely enabled its nick name `` fratty natty '' . if the price was not so low no one would buy this product .  appearance-muddy golden brown color and somewhat hazy . a bit lighter than i 'd expect . moderate sticky white head with good lacing .  real big , nice an simple mf/o : super viscous , super smooth , creamy , and velvety . the best feel to a beer that i 've ever experienced .

wonderful raspberry aroma . my kids kept walking by and commenting on how nice it smelled . the raspberry was not overpowering nor sickly sweet .  a - little head , with no lacing , but still a good looking beer . good light golden lager color . usually the same price as busch light , and far better !  very little carbonation .

the smell is awesome ! citrus and fairly aggressive hops over pale malts . love it . the taste is also quite good , it comes on very strong with the citrus at first , with a bit of floral , slightly aggressive hops moving in .  pours an efferevescent dark ruby red/mahogany with a 4 fingers head that drops off quick . no head retention or lacing s : slight peppery/yeasty nose up front , then alcohol & oaky/sherry notes as it warms .  mouthfeel - this beer is perfectly smooth . i am very impressed with the texture and flow of this naturally carbonated new glarus brew .

lots of hops with an equally strong , rich malt profile . clear that up a bit and the visual appeal will match the amazing aroma and flavor .  this beer pours a dark brown color .  m : medium viscosity , very smooth on the palate with perfect acidity , and with low carbonation .

smell is a little soft , not much going on there .  got this bottle from mike , thank you poured into a tulip glass at 51 degrees . appearance : there was a two finger head that quickly dissipated . the clarity of the beer is hazy .  wonderfully coats the mouth and the tongue .

aroma is intense with a tart raspberry sting and belgian chocolate complimenting each perfectly . a little liquer like kick in the end finishes the smell . taste does n't quite live up to aroma . a bit too chocolately and the raspberries seem a bit muddled .  a - poured a very dark amber . tan head quickly dissipated .  mouthfeel - very smooth brew , big-bodied with a velvet touch .

very very fruity , phenolic smell . spicy , but not as much as n'ice chouffe .  pours a dark brown , the slightest trace of a tan head rises and fades into a thin ring around the edge of the glass , little to no lacing .  m : hands down..the best mouthfeel i 've had with any beer . perfect !

in damned good nature . smell : mellowness of the 3rd degree ... hop bitterness entwining grapefruit and lactic-acid playfulness . taste : its looks like a scottish ale , smells like an ipa , but tastes like a very deserving quad ... rambunctiously fluffy and just right -- has a certain appreciated barleywine sensation , but jsut about everything does , seemingly . uncanny goofiness .  drank from my stella tulip a - pours a slightly hazy golden copper colour , with an off white head that reduces quickly to a film .  medium bodied , extremely smooth velvety mouthfeel .

pretty nice .  orangeish brown in color , with a persistent white ring and very fine bubbles across the top of the beer .  black as can be with as nice looking thick tan head.. the head almost looks reddish like many other imperial stouts.smells of burnt coffee , some chocolate and ripe fruit.taste and mouthfeel are topnotch . this brew feels like silk in my mouth .
piney , hoppy nose . flavor is grapefruit some sweetness , hoppy ; piney finish .  pours a murky caramel in color with an off white head .  m - very easy drinking . excellent carbonation .

amazing aroma . t - rich toasted marshmallowy malt , sweet toffee , fruit , molasses , a touch of bitterness blends in and evens things out .  pours a murky and hazy yellow in color . nice head on top .  excellant mouthfeel once again .

t - the initial hit is definitely honey and grape then it follows with the grain which is very pleasant and interesting . m - the mouthfeel is quite smooth for a 8 % abv beer d - i feel that the beer is very drinkable contrary to what has been said here so far , but different strokes for different folks .  sierra nevada pale ale is a pretty clear and pretty lively golden ale with a thin white film that leaves good lacing .  m- very smooth , silky and full . nice higher carbonation towards the finish .
anyway , the nose is excellent . a refreshing sweet and tart whiff of lemon , and subtle wheat/grain .  a - pours a light gold , minimal head , minimal lace .  lovely mouthfeel

the aroma is wonderful - smells almost like a lambic or flanders red to me . beyond all that , there 's a bitter aftertaste that is absolutely brutal , especially considering the style .  reviewed 1/14/2007 ( 750ml bottle ) : pours a cloudy brownish/dark tannish color , light brown medium sized head .  on the middle palate , this beer really shows off how big it is , coating my whole mouth while chocolate notes come through . as mentioned , this is a big oily coating beer with lighter carbonation .

very nice copper colored with 2 fingers of sticky white fome.piney/grassy hop attack on the nose is excellent . bursting with tangy citrus hop flavor , with some sweet malt flavor to back it up .  appearance - orange , straight up . smell - bourbon right off , quickly fades . bubblegum in the middle and nuts on the end . nice pairing beer .  overall , the flavor is very mild , for a craft beer in general and a barleywine in particular , and i 'll admit that 's not normally a plus for me , but i love the rich , creamy mouthfeel and the boozy finish .

s - orange peel , lemon , sour apple , vinegar come together to give a gorgeous nose to this . t - sour apple and lemon hit right away with intense sour flavors .  as with all lambic and gueuze i opened the bottle outside , as i 'm smarter than the beer . it pours a very murky orange , with what initially is a nice several fingers of foam , but is gone in seconds , leaving not even a ring . what 's left looks like a tequila sunrise .  the body is huge and luxurious with a silky , creamy mouthfeel and oil , mouth-coating texture . very rich and decadent .

smell has that distinct lager smell , slightly skunky .  dark brown , almost black color with some light shining through , no head and no lacing .  palate is extremely creamy body , soft ripe fruit & cheese , tart apples , light hops , and again just very creamy & smooth .

bottled 30 nov 2005 pour an effervescent & semi-hazed ( clears pretty quick ) peach with 2 fingers of sand colored head . above average lacing & head retention s : sourness , horse blanket & apple cider in abundance t : much tartness , lemons , dryness .  this looked like a hefe . it was even cloudier than a lot of hefes . it was served to me with a large soapy head . the grainy sediment floating around probably masks the sweetness giving this a `` husky '' quality .  nice mouthfeel and great body to it along with quite a flavor punch to your taste buds .

aroma is of fudgy chocolate brownies , crme brulee , creamed coffee , and a little sherry . the taste is shorter and thinner than expected , but still good . overall , this was enjoyable . i think this is more of an imperial stout with some slight barleywine characteristics .  review # 2 a : nice copper/ruby blend of color . the carbonation is not lost on this , foamy white head with a decent lacing filling the snifter . seek this one out if you are a barleywine fan .  i feel this beer really shines in its feel . it 's highly carbonated , but still feels rich and syrupy .

beautiful aroma of pine and citrus throughout with a nice caramel sweetness . the aroma seemed much more amazing than the actual taste but nothing to complain about .  12oz bottle , capped and corked apperance : minimal head retention , but a nice foamy lace . color is a cloudy peach and golden yellow .  one of the fullest bodied beers i have ever had . very creamy and delicious .

aroma was exotic . chocolate , vanilla , wood , i asked if it was a brandy barrel in there , but alas , no , but damn if it did n't smell that beauty of sweet brandy .  pours a medium amber color , with a thin , 1/2 finger head that dissolves immediately . no ring , and no lacing .  anxiously i lift the glass and pour into my mouth , very smooth , very think and velvety . i taste roasted chocolate , i taste sugar , i taste lots of alcohol , and some hairspray ? ? best winter beer out there best stout i 've had so far .

very clean smelling , very simple imo t-raspberry at the forefront followed by a nice slight bitterness to balance the taste out .  picked up this lovely from bb8189 poured from a 12oz brown bottle into my surly pub glass . off the pour it appear flat , but then out of left field a solid 1 '' head forms up . light brown in color , is the head , quickly receding to leave a thin coating and thicker collar of retention .  first sip reveals a silky smooth beer with fine slightly tingly carbonation .

s : oh it smells god awful . smells like a skunk pissed in a natural ice supply .  the head fades slowly into a frothy mess before dissipating into nothing .  the mouthfeel is full and thick with an exciting combination of carbonation that gives this a superb texture .

roasted coffee aroma with hints of chocolate and caramel .  poured into a goblet , revealing light and cloudy yellow body under a little bit of white , lively head . looking decent .  m - creamy and thick . this one is as smooth as velvet the whole way through the bottle .

the smell however , is quite amazing . huge hits of vanilla , coconut , and bourbon . very good stuff .  a : clear medium-amber body with a thin , faint , ephemeral off-white head ; decent lacing . let 's hope the lack of a real head promises more intense hoppiness to come .  m - right up there with the best i 've sampled in this regard , rich/thick/velvety beer . chewy and smooth .

aromas were a fantastic mix of fruit contexts and hops . i smelled grapes to an almost wine-level alcohol punch .  appearance & gt ; beautiful ruby brown . pours with a big , large bubble , golden head that dissipates in a short spell . the beer is a bit lackluster in liveliness , but my fingers are crossed .  m -- extremely smooth ; excellent balance of thick and thin .

smells fantastic . strong scent of raspberries .  we also think the juniper berries and is much more stressed than other st. feuillien .  the mouthfeel is the crown jewel of this beer . light with just a hint of carbonation . simply marvelous .

smell : very flavorful and welcoming that carries warm potent notes of the flavors in the beer : chocolate , coffee , mocha , and hops . appearance : very , very dark with basically no head .  12 oz bottle poured into a snifter fridge temp 2008 appearance : pours a dark , opaque brown color with a 1/2 '' tan head . it is short-lived and leaves barely and lace behind .  beautiful mouthfeel , thick , smooth , velvety , love it .

the aromas are incredible some of the best i have experienced in an ipa and the first time i can truly say i grabbed an orange note in a brew . medium mouthfeel but the carbonation was a little lacking i think i chock that up to the growler this is a very drinkable ipa more on the sweet side of the balance but close to being perfect . a true recommend in my book .  a - hazy rusty red brown with an off white head .  it has a creamy full body and excellent drinkability .

the smell was pleasurable , but very subtile with roasted malt and carmel . the odor of some kind of fruit hidden in the back .  a dipa will a set of nuts but very drinkable . somewhere in the middle of small batch 471 ( lighter ) and the lagunitas kill ugly radio ( strong ) .  m : creamy with a very smooth carbonation , tiny bubbles . and what a beautiful body .

very good .  pours a murky gold with an insane pillowy head that i had to eat with a spoon before i could finish my pour smell - all i pick up is apples taste is sweet spiced apples and light grain this beer has perfect mouthfeel - light crisp and creamy with very active carbonation drinkability is almost perfect - had to take off .5 because all the carbonation made me burb too much overall this is a great summer/fall brew .  mouthfeel- super velvety smooth ! drinkability- the mouthfeel alone make this brew worth trying .

the smell and taste are just an explosion of citric fruits and strong , fresh hops . most ipas start tasting very similar after a while but this is truely unique . i 've got the thing at least three feet from my nose right now and it is all i can smell . the hops and citrus are very strong , but surprisingly not overwhelming . very drinkable for 10 % abv . wow ! !  the first i 've seen abita do in bomber - impressive look with the gator snapping out of the weeds ... pour is deep golden yellow . rather large white head . provided some decent lacing as consumed .  m : great mouthfeel , carbonation is flawless . i 'm floored by how good this feels .

awesome . t : like i ate some hay .  clarity is obscured somewhat by chill haze and perhaps a little sediment ( though i left the bulk of it in the bottom of the bottle in large pieces ) .  m : the best mouthfeel in any beer i have ever had . so smooth and with a perfect body .

schnozzle is greeted by sweet malt , then blam , hops all flowery and spicy , citrus like in its crispness , clean , a bodement of things to come .  a - served with no head . dark , almost opaque red color .  super smooth mouthfeel , awesome , carbonation is light but tingly and perfect for the beer , just right .

nose- the hop aroma is very pleasant , and impressively potent with all the alcohol present in the nose . the fact that there is a hop aroma in there is impressive . taste- here 's the alcohol .  purchased from huckleberry markets in spokane a : beer pours a golden color , slightly hazy with some sediment and 1/4 '' white head that quickly dissipated .  lovely inviting texture with perfect carb .

unfortunately , the aroma was slightly dull and dead . still , damn good even though i could tell it was n't as good as the fresher victorian pints , and was n't even close to the cask .  it pours a bit thin for a dipa .  perfect balance and the mouthfeel is amazing . i want to chug it at times .

aroma is slightly faint , with some yeast spice and some clove . drink is great and very easy to put away .  a - poured into a wine glass . it formed a thin white head that receded to almost nothing fairly quickly . the color is somewhere between brown and amber . there is not much if any lacing .  amazing mouthfeel and good smell but the flavor falls the test of complexity .

s - brings the typical banana scent of weihenstephan yeasts t - floral essence with typical banana taste of weihenstephan yeasts m - it 's a weihenstephan weisse ... .  a- a murky , leathery brown liquid with just the tiniest bit of head to speak of- a thin ring around the edge with a few splotches on the surface . very syrupy looking when swirled .  amazing mouthfeel - smooth as silk with medium-full body and seamless carbonation .

smell- amazing smells coming from this one , you have a nice fruity scent on the one hand with a sweet toffee on the other , followed by the usual bready malt smells . taste- just like the smells you get a nice fruity sensation with that sweet toffee coming through , appearances from the bready malts and a very small flavour of hops thrown in there . overall- easily the best offering from railway city brewing co. this award winning ale hits home on all fronts , the smells are just out of this world good , and the taste comes through just like the smell fruity and sweet , looks great , tastes great , with a great carbonation on it as well .  22 oz bomber pours a very nearly black color with very little brown foam , even with an aggressive pour .  thick , silky , smooth ... coats the mouth .

very clear s : probably the strongest citrus nose i have ever encountere- this thing is like grapefruit rind , piney hops , and sweet malt . wow .  pours a deep ruddy brown without much of a head at all .  me likey this dubbel very much ! full , smooth , mild-mannered , and malty body texture . appropriately low in hops , alcohol causes some warming -- yet it blends in well with the flavor .

minimal streaks of soapy white lacing crisp citrus and earthy hop aroma . nice caramel malt backbone .  a - thin powdery sediment floats in the otherwise clear goldenrod-colored brew . a loose off-white head has ok retention but does n't leave much lace as it lowers .  mouthfeel is outstanding : creamy with a volume-adding carbonation , medium-bodied .

incredibly sweet on the nose . raspberry puree .  a : very clear amber , does n't look particularly exciting except for the lovely foamy head .  first sip reveals a smooth silky body and mild carbonation that is almost non-existant .

some spice , but mostly the candy smell . some slight pumpkin , but seemed rather artificial . taste : first was a pungent artificial pumpkin pie taste . after a few more sips , it started to become extremely overpowering .  a - color is a medium to dark brown and is cloudy or turbid looking . the head was slight after the pour and faded away to nothing shortly thereafter .  smooth , creamy mouthfeel that roles over the tongue with ease .

aroma is bursting with fresh apricot goodness . the apricot is n't as strong as in the aroma but it pairs itself wonderfully with the husky flavor from the grains . but it does n't come off really as a flaw since it 's going with the apricot flavor . because it 's an apricot beer ? i see a ton of c- 's out there but i 'd like to see a better apricot beer out there .  surprisingly cloudy orange yellow color .  the mouthfeel gets a 5 ... it is so creamy and smooth in the mouth with incredibly soft perfect carbonation .

the appearance is nothing out of the ordinary but the nose , as the previous reviewer had noted , is like being lost in a giant field of hops . a smooth sweetness mingles with the strong and fresh , but not overpowering at all , hop flavor . another outstanding offering from this so far , ca n't miss brewery .  appearance - cloudy yellow , effervencneance and a one-finger head that quickly dissipates .  m - chewy and delicious . moderate carbonation .

delicious . t : bready , rye bready .  generally i find brown ales to be a wide ranging crowd pleaser , but not usually worth recommending . the color and head where more or less what i 'd expect in a non-bottle conditioned craft beer . it 's been said nicely already - `` very nice beer when you want something nutty and rich and brown and a bit strong !  a very nice mouthfeel rounds things out . just the right amount of carbonation adds to the pleasing sensation .

smell : citrus is dominant here as expected . a little bit spicy , i guess from the grains of paradise ? this was made for a nice relaxing evening of baseball .  appearance : clear brown in color with a short 1/2 head . the head falls quickly .  love the feel to this brew .

s : wow , this beer smells great , one of the best smelling beers i have ever had . as soon as i smelled it i knew i would like this beer . t : this beer tastes very good , right up there with some of the best in this category .  this beer is an excellent example of what a light beer should taste like . in my opinion , the lighter , clean taste makes the beer much more drinkable . in a perfect world , this beer would replace amstel light as the standard high end light beer .  the finish is huge and takes forever , the huge body coating the whole mouth with the perfect amount of carbonation .

solid aroma , but a bit on the weak side for a dipa . d : the smell was promising , but nothing else draws me in .  a-golden yellow with a thin white veil for a head that left zero lace .  mf : good carbonation , full body , viscous , sticky and chewy with hints of alcohol . near perfect .

ta : you smell the cocoa , the taste does n't carry quite the same punch , but it 's still very good . mf : like a stout - soft , rounded edges .  appearance is like that of an amber ale , no head really .  mouthfeel is velvety and cream at the same time . medium weight and somewhat thick the microfine carbonation breaks it up into a quenching and warming brew for a cold and damp night .

great bittering , flavor and aroma hops . not as much aroma as a moylans hopsickle but much more bitterness and flavor .  looks : murky . there 's no head here save a teeny tan ring .  mouthfeel - perfect consistency , it had lager-level lightness of body without being watery ; a definite pleasure to roll around in my mouth .

smells amazing ! grass , pine , grapefruit , orange , lemon peel . almost perfect carbonation and finishes nice and clean .  this double ipa poured a clear copper color with no head .  sits in the mouth well extremely creamy porter that was very enjoyable .

this beer 's got one helluva nose . thick roasted malts , chocolate , char , vanilla bean , burnt malts , black coffee ... a thing of beauty . very pronounced aroma . the flavors are n't as bold as the aromas were , but they 're nice nonetheless . good stuff .  pours dark brown with a large fading head .  m : smooth and pleasant , creamy but not thick . just great . d : goes down easily .

the aroma is mild , grain , grass , anda hint of sulfur .  a - looks like a general brown ale , i had a small pour so ca n't say much about the head but it was present in appropriate form .  mouthfeel is pure silk with just enough carbonation to prick the tongue .

very faint roasted aroma , with a very slight coffee bean base .  drank from my duvel tulip glass a - pours a slightly hazey golden colour witha white head thad disappears real quick .  mouthfeel : creamy , and perfectly carbonated .

s : exquisite aroma , full of floral notes . scent of good wine .  poured into a pint glass at 54 degrees appearance : a deep dark black color . there is a quarter inch finger head that is dark tan . the head has no retention to it .  mouthfeel : thick , creamy , and smooth . almost like drinking a smoothie . drinkability : an exceptional stout .

hands down , you win , as of today i 've rated over 420 beers on this site , and this is the freshest hop nose i have ever smelled without using a randall . extremely floral and a tad citrusy . much more like a fresh bouquet of flowers , but if you 're a home brewer you 'll know this smell . it 's like opening up a fresh bag of whole leaf hops and taking a huge whiff . very nice and very different from you typical hop monster . taste is medium bodied with a smooth very even citrus bitterness . the flavors never really separate , but just mash together in a very nice hop balance . this is really a fantastically unique beer from a bottle .  good clarity with almost no lacing .  m - slick and viscous , with a rich , full body . very nice .

aroma was absolutely pecanless . it is actually pretty fruity .  a : pours a slightly hazy light gold with a finger of white head that quickly recedes into a thin ring with little lacing .  it finishes with a grassy hops note that stands up to the big malts and adds a wonderful balance .

has a slight citrus smell but is dominated by grassy hops , not pleasant smelling hops either .  a nice golden body , bright and clear . short , white head that fizzles out quickly . leaves a clump of bubbles and light lacing .  the namesake for this porter is very fitting , perfect actually .

smell here is hands down the best i 've ever smelled in a beer . earthy , sweet , flowery , fruity , very intriguing , makes me want to drink it . a bit sweet , very flowery and earthy , very natural feel . mouthfeel is very bubbly , too carbonated to go with the rest of this beer . if it had been a bit less carbonated , i would have liked this alot more , as it would have been very reminscent of a sweet stout .  pretty darn average .  mouthfeel is top notch - full on the palate , but finishes extremely clean .

immediately upon opening this beer the blueberry overtone is present . the smell , as aforementioned , is strong like blueberries . the taste is decent , to be quite honest it tastes like drinking blueberry pancakes , although admittedly it is not what i would consider a 'sweet ' beer , considering it is a fruity beer .  the colour is black ; the low head is pale brown .  mouthfeel is nice and thick , and perfectly carbonated for what it is .

s - strong floral aromas , hops are very prevalent but does not imply bitterness t - initial flavors are very strong and bitter hops .  a_pours black , jet black with a smallish coffee hued head . this diminishes quickly and settles into a small brown cap . lacing is non existant . despite the lack of head there is a good carbonation which cuts through the liquid which could be construed as cloying otherwise .  the body is full . the fullest , most oiled up voluptuous body you can imagine . very light carbonation .

smells ridiculous . vanilla/oak barrel overpowering .  appearance : despite all 6 attempts , i ca n't even rough pour a decent head into this beer . i get a thin rim that rapidly dissappears . the beer is not flat , but there 's no head ( this is not my glass , its happened six times to this beer , and none to any other beers ) . the color is a nice , clear , dark amber .  this makes the second founder 's beer i 've found with this creamy mouthfeel .

overall a fantastic smelling beer now they need to match the taste to it .  sampled may 2007 labeled as organic ipa , and certainly not anything like a british lower hop spectrumed ipa ( i think the organic ipa needs to be broken out as a separate entry here ) very well carbonated ; the beer pours with a four-finger thick , lightly tan colored head . the beer is an almost clear , pale reddish , full copper color . very well hopped with notes of loud grapefruit , fresh cut tangelos and candied citrus fruit . the second pour produces a five-finger thick head ; this is definitely way over carbonated , but the good thing is that the foaming and the pour effectively degas this brew . this is definitely an enjoyable ipa ; smooth , fruity , yet still well balanced for an ipa .  moderately carbonated , slightly sticky . there is a great warming feel to this .
the nose on the other hand is very nice if not different .  pours a clear yellow brew .  m - full bodied and creamy texture on the palate .

s. tons of warming booziness and a strong apricot and tangerine fruitiness . it is amazing how much this smells like fresh fruit . this is a really good beer that i knew almost nothing about until i opened it .  a : light bronze colour , and small head that leaves rather quickly . not very carbonated s : it has a fruity and hoppy smell to it .  t- super balanced across the board . m- very balanced . d- delicious .

the aroma is intensely rich . notes of caramel and burnt/smokiness dominate with light fruit notes including plum , raisin , coconut . the rich aroma was the greatest aspect . i would recommend seving it cool , not cold .  goose island 's hex nut brown ale tasted like a classic brown ale . it was clear , maybe a bit light in color . it 's low abv makes it an easy drink .  m - this is what i want . incredibly thick and full bodied . just an amazing velvet feeling beer .

great stout smells all around . this is still quite a nice beer and incredibly full flavored .  edel pils pours a crystal-clear golden color , with surprisingly little head or lacing .  just enough acidity . incredibly soft malt base , rediculously soft carbonation .

the smell was that of a skunked pilsner . the skunk overpowered the hop and alcohol notes .  hazy golden to amber in color , with a thin head that dissipates rapidly .  the mouthfeel is very full and creamy , which i appreciate .

awful taste . smells like wine more than beer . mouthfeel is nice for a few seconds but after a while it starts to `` eat away '' at your mouth with it acidic complex . after reading some reviews and admiring the fantastic packaging , i can say that i am disappointed . practically undrinkable .  appearance - cloudy yellow with a small head .  little carbonation . this is excellent .

simply awesome aromas of thick toffee , burnt brown sugar , and milk chocolate . finishes quite clean . drinkability is large - with more flavor than the avg aba , but low alcohol level , this is a winner .  pale and cloudy , as expected . head disappeared quickly .  the mouthfeel is phenomenal , with high carbonation and light to medium body relative to its strength .

a very bread nose greets you with each sip . a mild hop bitterness is noticed .  kaiser curmudgeon occupies somewhere between burnt orange and mahogany in the color spectrum . there 's a bit of bone tinted foam sitting on top of the beer , but once it fades it leaves no evidence that it was there .  wonderful body and drinkability , both due to the cask pour .

i was a little disappointed with the taste of this after the great smell . m : probably the weakest point of this beer in my opinion .  nice light in color .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it has just the right amount of sourness to bitterness ratio to balance it out .

smells strawberry fruity and bourbon oaky during the pour . to the nose , rich strawberry vanilla , licorice , playful oak , bourbon char , sweet caramel , cherry , clean alcohol , pineapple , lavender , and more . wow , just amazing , i hope the flavor is a match . beneath alot of tannin , i get some raisin and some basil ( may sound awful , but it actually fits pretty well ) .  poured out a dark brown with a half of finger of tan head ... no real lacing .  m : fantastically smooth .

grass and summer days mix with the flowery hop smell to give the perfect ipa smell . taste : less sharp than expected by the smell .  a : clear bright red body with an inch of bubbly pink foam that quickly disappears completely . ok , but slightly better retention would have been nice - that head was beautiful for the few seconds it lasted !  mouthfeel is so creamy and smooth with just the right amount of carbonation .

aromatic and a delight to the smell . was a little put off by the amount of head that the ale put into the glass .  12 oz bottle pours a very dark black body with a small khaki head that quickly falls away . just a spot or two of patchy lace .  thick and creamy , really a great feel that i was n't expecting with the hop bite of this cascadian .

immediately recalls the feeling of sniffing fresh creme brulee . aromatics suggest some sort of strange starbucks concocction with caramel , exotic flavored coffee , and french vanilla . smooth in the nose like smelling a fresh crepe before it 's filled . strikes me as a bit `` engineered '' -- but good . one of the most unique and impressively creative beers i 've ever tried .  clearish deep garnet brown color , head on this one was milky and washing out fairly quickly .  the mouthfeel is wonderfully smooth enhancing the overall experience .

the smell is my favorite part of this beer . it has great notes of pine and citrus , as well as fresh grass . the taste is quite good with a fair amount of hoppiness with significant malty sweetness . overall , this is a very good beer .  the beer pours a deep amber , forming a very thin bubbly head that fades very slowly .  mf : very smooth with rich flavors and a creamy texture . medium carbonation .

s - wonderful aroma of milk chocolate , leather , smoke and just a little licorice . just awesome ! t - roasty and sweet taste .  golden , apple juice-ish color with a thin , fizzy head that 's in a hurry to get somewhere , leaving only a small slick of bubbles behind . very solid beer , extremely easy to drink .  full bodied and pretty sweet which really smooths everything out .

s - wow . dank and resinous hops are here to party . t - very nice candied fruit sweet notes , nice hop complexity . this is obviously a very hop centric brew . it 's an odd combo . d - this one is an ass kicker , it will sneak up on you .  nice nice smell , and besides the lack of lacing , the look of this brew is great !  m-thick and chewy . just lovely . d-one more please !

one of the most complex and interesting saisons i have ever had . very fresh and lively both in aroma and in taste . really a beautiful beer .  3.0 a : pours a slightly hazed radiant yellow brown .  m-extremely full bodied , thick and chewy , syrupy and coats the mouth , moderate carbonation , rather crisp finish and even slightly dry . one of the biggest bodies i 've had in any kind of ipa .

an amazing aroma . t- biscuit malt is more present as well as some citrus notes such as pink grapefruit and lemon zest . o- extremely drinkable with a great aroma . the only issue i had was that it was a little less complex in the taste and a little malty , but a fantastic dipa that can compete with the best .  poured from 12 oz bottle into tulip glass . pours a chocolate brown with almost no head . appears to have low carbonation .  on the palate the body is simply creamy & full , with enough zippy carbonation to keep it interesting . finish is creamy soft and rather sweet .

s : very doggy . wow , very very doggy . i ca n't dive too far into the taste due to the awful smell .  pours an inky black , nearly opaque colour with a 1/4 inch of head , even off a hard pour . the minimal head recedes quickly and leaves just a little wet lace . not much in the way of retention , just a few bubbles .  excellent mouthfeel from this bottle-conditioned brew .

s - very coffee rich nose that truly smells like cold but fresh-brewed coffee . lots of roasted malts behind with a bold aroma and some mocha . an absolute delight to smell . t - tons of coffee flavor is all over the place with a well-balanced roasty bitterness with a light chocolate and cream background .  pours a muddy amber brown with a fizzy but thick white head that recedes to lace on the outside of the glass .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , creamy and pleasant on the tongue , lips and cheek .

the cherry vanilla aroma is very strong and appealing . the characteristic chocolate and roasted aromas are also present , but they play a supporting role to the cherry vanilla . i stuck my nose into this one too much for being in public , but it had a great smell . the cherry vanilla character also comes through very strongly in the taste . it adds a strong sweetness that for the first few sips was really good , but it started to drag down my palate after awhile .  poured into a stiffer appearance : dark brown with reddish hues , not as dark as i was expecting , with virtually zero head even with a vigorous pour .  mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with a brilliantly smooth texture and a clean finish .

this one reminds me of an ipa i tasted in boise , id from a taphandle labeled in masking tape and sharpie magic marker .  served to me in a branded pseudo-pint a : yellow golden ale with near excellent clarity . single finger of bone white foam falls over several moments to a sheet of the same . no lacing .  the mouthfeel is amazingly thick .

s : outrageously tasty smell . smells of fresh hops just picked from the vine .  a : beer is a very cloudy deep copper/orange color . very little off-white head , maybe a finger at most all froth .  the mouthfeel on this beer is what really impressed me .

clear . smell : amazing ! the first whiff is a standard ale , but then you catch cinnamon , allspice , and a hint of brown sugar . if you like pumpkin pie , you 'll love to smell of this beer . taste : crisp , intial hops , cinnamon and pumpkin , and a little bit of caramel and malt in the background . as it warms , this beer gets a bit less pleasant ; the pumpkin flavors recede and it starts to taste more like an `` off '' ale . nevertheless , a nice fall seasonal and a fine tribute to my favorite dessert .  the waitress only said it was dark . i could drink this beer all day !  m : homerun . double-cream indeed ! thick foamy effervescence that when swished around leaves a wonderful long-lingering , slightly bitter `` roasted '' aftertaste .

nosewise this beer is an a+ . incredibly deep , dank hop aroma that smells less of grapefruit than gooey-ripe heirloom cherries ... just as rich as a rain-soaked hop farm on processing day . at first i did n't believe these were amarillos at work , and i 'm still not sure , but there 's a ton of citrus lurking in its thinly biting way .  a - deep chestnut brown with a fluffy , sand-colored head . retention is mediocre , and lacing is sporadic but cohesive in the spots where it does form .  m - creamy and luxurious . the bite is done through alcohol rather than carbonation .

the smell is amazing , caramel , toffee and vanilla . tomme could easily sell this as a perfume to beer geeks . note ... do not fret if you can not get your hands on this beer , while i really liked it , i found it to be very similar to a standard as .  appearance : pours hazy golden with a small , quickly dissipating white head that leaves behind no lace .  this is definitely an exceptional mouthfeel for an ris .

rich , silky chocolate with fresh coffee . overall , this porter really surprised me . the aroma is unbelievable and i just wish the taste packed a huge punch that the aroma did . it is really good and i am glad i had a chance to try it .  taste is a great balance between the malt and hops with a slight spiciness , color is a cloudy light amber .  a great silky , creamy moutfeel . excellent .

smells like sculpin junior . taste is bready , like corn bread almost , not much sweet malt notes . very dry finish and very clean .  from a stubby 341 ml . capped bottled , 2005 vintage , number 2106 . poured a light caramel , fresh , raw apple cider brown with a fizzy , bubbly head that quickly settled into fine lacing . a good barley wine in a unusually shaped bottle , i 'm trying to remember , but i think years ago , when i was a really young , small child , my father use to drink hamm 's and old style from bottles like this .  the mouthfeel is wonderful - smooth and silky , bordering on syrupy .

the smell on this is amazing ! off the top of my head i do n't think i have ever rated a iipa perfect on smell . this one can not be improved . no gumminess is evident at all .  picked this up at macadoodles in jane , mo pours ebony with much effervescence and a pinky fluffed up mocha colored head . average head retention & lacing s : plums , tobacco notes & figgyness , & boozey cherries t : follows the nose , some molasses , cherries , dryness & earthy hop bitterness & hints of carob up front .  great mouthfeel in particular .

the smell is just awesome . dark fruits such as plums and raisins , figs , brown sugar , woody vanilla and earthy chocolate . man , it 's just awesome . taste does not quite live up to the smell . it is an odd wood , which i ca n't quite describe . it almost reminds me of really old hops , in that it is bitter , but a bit fruity .  bottle from a 6-pack i just purchased , poured into a tumbler glass ... - dark clear copper.. almost a solid amber colored ale.. quick fizzing white head down to a micro thin ring and some dusting ... - nice zesty hop forward smell.. grassy earthy herbal.. some citrus , lemon , sweet caramel and roasty sweet malts , ... - citrusy bitter hoppy goodness.. impressed.. some earthy grassy notes ... sweet malty notes without being too sweet and syrupy .  creamy mouthfeel , very interesting , with a perfect amount of carbonation and feeling not unlike a fudge bar that melts in the mouth .

very low aroma-simply smells like `` beer '' .  the beer pours a darkish tawny amber color with very little head retention and lacing .  has a bit of a sweet aftertaste m : smooth like silk , not sticky or heavy , really nice d : could drink this all night due to the bitter bite in the beginning followed by a sweeter smooth mouthfeel overall : it was a great beer that my roommate picked up as a random pick .

used a pyramid dpa draught glass , because i wanted to do a head-to-head vs. their replacement ale : 5 barrel . i usually use a boddingtons for hoppy ales because it concentrates hoppiness perfectly to my liking . i am not certain if that is why the nose was too bland for my liking or not . ) nonetheless , i felt there was very little in the nose to fortify that there was a pale ale underneath . typically i love complex brews , but what i did not enjoy was the flatness of the appearance and aroma . it did not come across as complex -- only incomplete .  poured a hazy light orange/gold color with a thin white lacing covering the top . the head did n't stick around long or leave much for lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy . the aftertaste is extremely clean ; not sticky , dry or anything bad .

s : roasted malts and barley . t : a very watered-down taste of roasted malts .  another first impression whoa ! its head was a very white color . it has a very light orange color with yeast particles floating in it .  m : perfect , silky smooth , very light carbonation gives a great feel on the tongue , viscous and full-bodied , oily .

amazing . t : starts with a gigantic coconut sweetness . pretty rich stuff .  pours a hazy peach color with a thin whispy head that recedes faster than my hairline .  m : perfect . medium , creamy carbonation on a medium/full body .

smells rather mundane . not much to speak of here , moving along to the taste .  not all that impressive looking though . the pour is brown with some red hues , and a quickly fading soapy tan head .  beautiful . d : great in so many ways , but just a little too hot on the finish to be truly drinkable .

some fruit on the nose ( citrus and slight grapes ) along with maybe some slight coriander or nutmeg .  a nice reddish orange color that was a little cloudy with sediment .  on the first sip , the first thing noticed is the smooth , creamy texture . nice body on this one .

thick and rich and just an amazing smell . t -- very sweet tasting and the fruits have held up extremely well in this . very port like . o -- thrilled to have had this . heavy , rich , sweet and excellent . held up very well for it 's age .  whirlwind pours a somewhat hazy , pale yellow color . it has little head and no lacing .  the mouthfeel has an almost perfect extra virgin olive oil and buttery finish to it .

750ml bottle # 58l rich aroma is both sweet and tart . the nose on this is absolutely stunning . pours a very attractive cloudy peachy/rose color with a thin , but tight bright white head . flavor is vibrant , fresh and perhaps a little young . medium bodied , excellent carbonation with a vibrant , clean finish .  had alot of lacing but not much of a head . the color is a clear straw yellow . very average apperance with not much going on there .  m - full bodied . almost a syrupy feel to it . it 's rich , creamy , and my favorite aspect of this beer .

it 's a lovely smell , and not just for the great memories of dinners with dad . very nice . mouthfeel is good- hearty , somewhat thick liquid , with a high tight carbonation that is n't oo oppressive .  this is a very tasty beer , but its appearance is nothing special in my opinion . it has a very nice white head , but is very light and its not once you get to the 90 and 120 minute ipa 's where you see the darker color .  mouthfeel reminded me of monk 's cafe on steroids , pretty full and seems to swell and invade every corner of the mouth .

absolutly awesome . when you open the bottle and smell , it seems like the bourbon will over-power everything else , but once poured , all these aromas meld very well . t- just like the smell , but with more a burnt chocolate flavor and the additions of plums , cherries , and molasses .  the abv is higher than i expected , because this beer is exceptionally drinkable , and you can enjoy several without feeling bloated . 2 of the 4 beers definitely surprised me ( the other being the backdraft brown ) .  almost limited carbonation lends to the slick feel .

i smell coffee and chocolate . its not overwhelming , but determinable .  golden/bronze hue , not much murkiness at all . lots of hops and a hint of citrus ( i 'm getting grapefruit ) on the nose . a good session ipa .  thick chewy mouthfeel with fine carbonation .

aromas of strong jalepeno and other hot peppers . very expressive chile pepper aroma and flavor are enticing , but the extreme heat makes it challanging to drink .  a : an amateur pour captured the yeast slug in this beer , producing a cloudy amber body that glows slightly reddish against the light . the head is surprisingly flaccid for a beer that contains brett ; it 's half a finger at best , with short retention , no lacing , and a very thin collar .  exceptional mouthfeel , but the high alcohol is too present in the taste to make this an easy-drinking beer .

s - amazing , i finally get the whole grapefruit aroma . i always pretended i knew what people meant , but this is amazing . t - very malty , hops are subtler than i thought/hoped .  this beer pours a very light golden yellow color , with a thin white head . the head fades fast , leaving pretty much no lace .  superb mouth feel , a full sensory experience . the after taste is delicious , tongue coating , coffee , full bodied .

damn , the smell is n't good at all ... surely not inviting ... more strange but not in a good way . i get some chocolate and licorice with something else that make the smell bad .  appearance is a hazy , dark brown ... not overly appealing really .  the body is perhaps the best part of this beer . feels full bodied with a nice smooth , soft texture . perfect . some truely remarkable parts to this beer .

a wonderful rich chocolately oatmeal stout with a truly exceptional `` full-bodied feeling '' aroma . love it . yum .  brew was presented in a standard pint glass with not much of a head , had some faint froth on top but was very light and lead to only a slight amount of lacing at the top .  feel ( 5/5 ) very effervescent on the tip of the tongue in the initial taste ( almost reminiscent of the more carbonated belgian ales , like duvel in this respect ) . this transitions to a wonderful fullness as it washes to the back of the mouth .

phenomenal nose -- not much different than sumpin ' sumpin ' with bountiful pineapple and mango fruitiness bursting forth .  a - nice think pour to a golden body .  m - the feel is extremely smooth . i am very impressed by the silk feel of this brew .

smells sweet and floral ( bit strange/unique for a `` wee heavy '' ) .  a very light gold with a decent white head which left minimal lacing .  m : awesome mouthfeel , thanks to the cask conditioning .

really beautiful . flavor is slightly sour , malty , caramel , sugar , a bit of prune . overall a good taste , but a great aroma .  the head is fizzy at first but recedes quickly into nothing , with no lacing left behind .  m : thick , viscous and chewy ; one of the creamiest mouthfeels i 've ever encountered . yes .

aroma blossoms with freshly-lit rich tobacco and dark chocolate . ) ... i know i 'm a sucker for raspberry stouts , and usually i like them thick and sluggish . this one is both complex and oddly refreshing . what a unique , accomplished winner from one of my new ( and way too far away ) brewpubs . recommfgended .  picked up a bottle of this after reading the hilarious brown suggah story . pours deep yellow with a fluffy white head that is gone before you know it .  the mouthfeel on this beer is excellent , with a perfect crispness that accentuates the bitterness of the hopping .

probably one of the best smelling and inviting aromas in a beer i have ever smelled . the flavor pretty much followed the nose only some of the flavors were much stronger than the others .  poured a fairly light , golden color with a bit of 'haze '' .  mouthfeel is thick and chewy , wonderfully creamy and velvety . overall impression : excellent imperial stout .

on cask @ the blind tiger ... 1/19/09 pours a cloudy , hazy , bubble-less blond color . wow the smell is exploding with citrus and pine . excellent cask beer , would love to try this on tap or the bottle .  pours a rich , deep mahogany with barely half a finger of head , no lacing and only moderate retention .  smooth creamy mouthfeel and very drinkable , especially at 5 % .

this coffee-chocolate stout provides an aroma that is exceptional . mudhouse coffee & tea company also of springfield , mo .  this brew , served at room temp of course , poured a hazy caramel color with a small , inconsistent head that reminded me of a soda . solid !  my favorite aspect of this beer was it 's creamy smooth mouthfeel .

s- the one downside of this brew was the almost lack of definable aroma . hints ( subtle ) of hops , grapefruit , but it was an effort to put words to the very limited smells . t- good medium hoppy edge , slight malt , but the finish has a sharper bitter twinge .  had the first batch of this since witch 's hat opened the day after christmas . appearance is cloudy and is not particularly appealing . i thought the smoked beer taste would be ruined for me after these bad experiences but the 1908 is an excellent brew .  it 's not too heavy , nor syrupy , just perfect with an appropriate amount of carbonation .

smell is glorious , all english style ales should smell like this . seriously , the beer 's gone and i keep sniffing the glass and the empty bottle , its that good . hints of bread dough and alcohol , among others .  pours crystal clear orangish golden amber color with 1-2 fingers of a fairly foamy head with decent retention that reduces to a thin lacing cap . not much lacing clinging to the glass .  the spices sit on the tongue and create a festive atmosphere in the mouth .

rich , malty flavor lingers long after you finish . lighyt on the tongue and keeps its fizz , does n't flatten out immediately . it has a high abv for some but i like it as a session beer .  pours out black with a thin tan head that quickly disappears . it has good carbonation , but little retention and lacing .  drinkability and overall : the only thing that makes this any more drinkable than the average beer is that incredible mouthfeel .

huge bready and yeasty aroma . very spicy smelling , plenty of black pepper . amazing , complex combination of olfactory delights . flavor is a less intense interpretation of the smell . bready and yeasty with black pepper and citrus . dry , clean finish .  a- a light copper to orange color . about a one finger head that disappeared quickly and not great lacing . in short , this smells like fresh pumpkin pie .  smell - bittery and hop-ish taste - the bitter taste of irish stouts , very well done , but much better from tap mouthfeel - exceptional is perfect . it 's creamy and amazingly smooth .
strong , delicious smelling dark chocolate aroma .  pours a dark orange with a little white head .  m : very good balance of carbonation and stickiness . perfect !

the color was typical of a pale ale , mostly sunny with some haze , and the hops were very fragrant with a lemongrass note . if hops are your thing this is definitely a pale ale for you .  a : orangey color , opaque , like the traditional unfiltered yeast was also mixed with some tropicana pure premium , or something . not sure i was a fan of the appearance . t : the traditional banana of the hefe is replaced by an orange citrus , but the cloves are still there , just like they should be . the hops come through strong at the end , making it almost like a pale wheat ale , but with a ton more character .  mouthfeel is just phenomenal , as this one has a smoothness all its own to go with a creamy , thick texture of oil .

delicious . taste & gt ; excellent .  a - clear on the pour , it 's totally black in the glass , worthy of the awesome name . a low tan head has little retention and a little lace .  m - the feel is full and rich like an amazing glass of red wine . this has such a rich velvety texture ; amazing .

smells like bacon on a campfire .  a= this beer pours a murky , cloudy , unattractive looking brown color . the head is huge and beautiful upon pouring , but quickly reduces to 1/4 inch . s= this beer smells fantastic !  perfect . absolutely perfect .

smell is almost nonexistent .  pours a fairly clear redish amber . little to no head , no lacing .  m-on the low side of medium carb the beer is very full and creamy with no detectable oiliness . the texture is possibly the best i have had in an ipa , and although not bitter enough to satisfy true hop heads , the flavor is very interesting and pleasant , and the aroma complex .

caramel and hints of milk chocolate are here as well in the aroma . one really needs to close their eyes when they take in the scent.. the appearance throws the mind off and this radiates aromas more suited to a darker , redder quad-style beer . big mango and other tropical fruit sensations like pineapple are infused into the belgian candi sugar profile . for a quad , this beer is pretty enjoyable , different , and surprisingly drinkable ( note : drinkable , that is , for quad lovers like me ) . this beer succeeds and has renewed my faith in this experimental brewery from flanders . 750ml worth of this rich liquid is too much imho for one person .  no head . lots of sediment .  the carbonation , while lacking in the glass , is perfect on the palate . the mouthful is fantastic .

aroma is pungent , citrusy hops . i usually would n't give a perfect aroma score to a hoppy beer without much of an herbal balance , but the strong , complex fruitiness deserves a 5 . i think the fruity hop profile could have given this more depth , but it 's hard to please the palate after the aroma is so great .  it pours a golden hue and cloudy ( unfiltered ? ) . decent lacing .  i can tell by the haze and head that this one is gon na have some exceptional mouthfeel due to some protein action . very full bodied .

s- strong coffee smell , finishes off with a slight semi sweet chocolate smell . on smell alone i have to say this is the best smelling stout i 've ever had the pleasure of inhaling .  poured a hazy pail orange/yellow color with a thin white head ; slightly foggy but transparent enough to see through it .  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a perfect punt of carbonation .
