i am literally overwhelmed , this beer smells awful . sorry sn . this one smells horrendous though .  absolutely no head at all- some froth develops as it pours , but disappears immediately . looks fine , but not a lot to say about it .  m - slight carbonation , smooth and silky d - i would n't suggest this beer to anyone really , glad i tried it for trying sake but it is not very drinkable .

i smelled the `` skunk skank '' as soon as i opened it . tastes much better than it smells ( but it smells pretty bad ! ) mouthfeel is above average . overall drinkable , but the skunk smell dropped this a good 1/2 a point .  33 cl bottle poured into a goblet , saison 1900 is murky dark gold with lots of lots of unappealing sediment in static suspension .  mouthfeel : medium mouthfeel and very smooth .

smell is espresso , some day-old coffee , a wee bit of chocolate and some spicy hops .  pours a slightly cloudy golden yellow color with a half finger white head that immediately fades without any lacing .  creamy , soft medium body and very light , prickly carbonation .

there was an earthy aroma but not much else .  the beer looks like a hefe , kinda -- the cloudy yellow body throws up a pretty good head , but that quickly settles down into a standard pale ale-like , 1/4 inch collar .  full bodied with moderate , fine carbonation .

the nose is immensely roasty , and filled with coffee , chocolate , and a bit of sweet caramel . this was a horrible beer , perhaps a bad bottle , but certainly a drain pour .  12oz bottle well within its ' best by date , served in a tulip . a - very hazy burnt orange in color , letting just enough light through to show that i was n't careful enough with the sediment from the bottom of the bottle .  m & d : very soft in carbonation , light-bodied , but the flavour shows too much impacts of the pear-ish sourness .

i like the bell 's two hearted ale and when i spotted a single case of bell 's hopslam in my neighborhood beer distributor , i had to purchase the case served into a shaker pint glass . s : the most amazing aspect of this beer is the smell . i detect a mix of grapefruit , orange and pineapple aromas . t : for a beer whose label declares it to be a `` biting , bitter , tongue bruiser '' , it has a nice sweet malt backbone . notes : this is a pricy beer , but a must try for any hop head .  poured a rich amber color with no visible head .  mouthfeel : light bodied and crisp with moderate carbonation .

s : very faint aroma of lager yeast . maybe a bit of caramel/chocolatey sweetness , but really not much to smell . t : the weak smell belies a very flavorful dark lager .  appearance : light copper color , thick initial head , dissipates in a fair amount of time , nice lacing . smell : hops up front , malt plays a very small role in the background .  the body is n't half-bad , a soft , creamy medium with prickly carbonation that matches the cherries , whose tartness grips the sides of the tongue between sips . perhaps these are n't the right cherries for this beer .

wow has a great mix of smells i ca n't exactly place , but some citrus and hop and malt -- yum ! the flavor is much like the smell -- a delightful mix of many different tastes , and in the end it 's very good . very glad i tried it . i 'm not usually an amber fan but stone came up with something original and delicious .  pours hazy red/brown with an off white head .  a- hazy golden with minimal head and zero lacing s- astringent citrus with sweet malt t- very quick bitterness but the malt comes in too fast to distinguish any type of hop flavor m- by far the best part of this beer . the high ibu is noticeable on the tongue .

a : deep honey , amber in color . also , some tropical fruity hops . good nose . t : mostly follows smells .  poured into a pint glass a clear golden yellow with a one finger head that dissipated quickly leaving little to no lacing - i was anticipating it to be a lot stickier and retain itself ... oh well .  but then the flavor ... ..sweet and roasty at first , enjoyable medium body and carbonation , and then the aftertaste !

not a whole lot to the aroma , just some toasted malts , bit of fruit . delightfully toasty , and kind of bready . at under five percent , this is a very drinkable , smooth and satisfying beer . though perhaps not as fresh , snappy or bitter as some of the other dsseldorf alts ( many of which are n't really distributed in de ) , frankenheim alt is still a very good example of the style , and it 's readily available in german supermarkets .  on tap at the nook in huntsville , al a : a very dark brown color with a very small tan head that quickly recedes to nothing .  m - medium body , ample carbonation , finishes dry .
first whiff of this was somewhat skunky .  the color was a really cloudy , extra-hazy honey-golden shade .  very drying , nice carbonation .

s : smelled like a winter festive smell with cinnamon and nutmeg spices with dried raisin and citrus aromas working in the mix . after airing out for a while it had an alcoholic bread pudding taste which went well with the festive winter smells . m/d : alcoholic feel all the down the throat but kinda bland on the tongue .  this one poured a hazy , straw color . nice white head , lacing and carbonation .  m : medium and creamy . d : this has a kick-in-the-head hoppiness .

s-chocolate , coffee , and toasted malts with a pleasant hop presence at 55 ibus . this is maybe the best smelling porter i have encountered .  pours a mostly clear copper with a slightly off-white head of foam . the head quickly drops to a coating on the surface , with some lacing . years ago , everybody used this yeast . if you are looking for a pale ale as a pounder , this could be it . i suppose there are some who would n't like the yeast character , but i kind of like it .  mouthfeel is full bodied and thick ; really syrupy , hot with alcohol , chewy , with decent carbonation .

i think it cost something like $ 14 . 5/5 s : lemongrass , honeydew , flowers , and some herbs . 4/5 t : a bit of a let down from the smell .  appearance- pale tawny with some nice haze , this scottish gruit shows massive carbonation in the glass ... the head recedes quickly to nothing at all , but the concentration of color is quite attractive .  lively carbonation . mouthfeel is full . finish is clean and smooth .

the aroma opens with what smells like centennial hops , fruity with a hint of mango and pineapple , followed by vanilla , cherries , apple juice , and when swirled , a little sour milk . it 's hard to put my finger on it , but the malt is definitely sour and the bitterness has a chemical/metallic component to it that is very peculiar . hrmmm , this is a weird beer . this one is nothing to get excited about , and i 'm definitely not inclined to buy another .  anyways , let 's move on and get to this beer : it 's a pale straw color , that pours a nice head , but shrinks considerably after a minute .  mouthfeel is well carbonated and medium bodied .

s - toasty and not as sweet smelling at other dubbels i 've had . some roasted coffee notes in the nose that are unusual for this style .  a : literally looks like apple juice or urine ... but in a good way ... and i know that sounds weird .  feels raw and boozy , needs more taste and less hootch . mouthfeel - nicely smooth and creamy , leaves a pleasant residual to help fight off that alcohol burn .

very pleasant nose . t - alcohol is pronounced ; it 's almost astringent and a tad sour .  the beer pours up a dark mahogany , with a head that dissipates quickly .  m. the mouthfeel is a nice smooth creamy feel that finishes off with a nice dry feel .

smells heavily of citrusy hops , lemon and some pine all well remaining somewhat sweet . syrupy herbal hops , pineapple and toffee on the forefront with some serious alcohol warmth in the aftertase .  appearance : the usual - dark black opaque body , brown creamy head that quickly dissipated . some lacing , but not an exceptional amount .  it has a full body , lightly-syrupy-turning lightly-dry texture , and low carbonation .

aroma was very sprucey , notes of licorice and molasses , some pine , no hop or malt aromas.a good spicey aroma nice and pleasing .  appearance is a cloudy brown with a decent head .  mouthfeel is fine , crisp and medium bodied .

s : smelly ; pale malt and barely any hops . not the strong point here .  ok , so this is my first review and i 'm fairly new to the quality beer market ( having been a bud light chugger for years ) . now that i have tried the winter cheer ale , i am a huge spanish peaks brewing fan . this beer was a like heaven on my tongue when having it last night . although i drank from the bottle , i 'm looking forward to pouring a glass next time .  mouthfeel is pretty good for the style though .

in my amateur opinion i found the aroma lacking . i wanted to smell those cascade hops .  a - pours a bright pale , a little thin looking , and no head to be noticed .  body & mouthfeel was nice but the flavor killed it for me .

above average head retention & lacing s : plummy & figgy notes merge with oakyness & a whisper of vanilla , the strength of this beer is the aroma , plus much peattyness t : follows the nose along with brown sugar & molasses , plus iron & leafy hops . finishes dry , smokey & fruitty with nice charred grain notes mf : fairly smooth , medium bodied , starts to become almost prickly as this warms , but also becomes a bit sticky nice drinkability , easily one of the best bottled beers i 've had out of britain in the last 12-18 months & a top flight example of this style on the upper edge of abv , yum  maduro pours an intensely cloudy deep brown . to say the light tan colored cap is able to gather itself to two fingers in height would be stretching the truth , and there 's barely any lacing left behind to speak of .  m : the body is medium with a lively carbonation and a crisp , lightly bitter finish . this is probably the best part about this beer .
smells like your typical hefe .  appearance - deep amber color , minimal head that dissipates into a film .  taste is watered down and a bit corny but not offensive , mouthfeel is light and crisp .

minimal head retention & lacing s : peppery & chile notes , smells like a beer of this ilk should ! chile spice/slight heat & faint smokeyness tries to fight through sweetness .  a - it pours a deep black hue , and is capped with minimal froth .  the chewy mouthfeel will keep you around to finish the pint you ordered , but i doubt you 'll want another .

a : poured a melted jolly rancher orange-red ... . more on the orange side come to think of it . s : malty , biscuit-like , with a slight bit of crisp hoppiness . it delivers a fair amount of aroma , but not too much .  color was a deep brown with little head ( did n't notice much lacing ) , so there was nothing exceptional about the appearance .  mouthfeel is smooth and moderate-to-thin in body . an amazing first half , with a terrible second half .
the aroma is quite nice , although not overly pungent or strong .  l : pours a gauloises bruin deep brown , with nearly no head .  no complaints , perfect wino beer . tecattteee

fantastic aroma with yeast and fruitness being the dominant characteristics . the flavor is kinda strange .  pours out a light amber , small head with next to no lace .  md thick mouthfeel and strong carbonation .

smell : the smell was very malty , with a stong taste of toffy , cholcate , and coffee .  the reddish amber double bock had a thin head , but lots of malt in the nose .  mouthfeel : the body is on the thicker side with tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

awesome . the taste was almost as complex as the aroma . malty and delicious .  poured from a 12oz bottle into an imperial nonic pint glass ; beer thanks to cardsmith a : you can immediately tell the bottle-conditioning from the yeast sediment that trickles into the glass as you pour ; fairly thin-looking ruby-red/copper/amber color , very sparkly , decent head and very minor lacing .  m - good coating with a tingle on the sides.of the tongue and top of mouth .
smells of slight hoppyness and belgian candy sugar .  copper/orange color , murky haze . one finger bubbly head that very quickly faded .  m : medium body with nice , full carbonation .

the lightish brown color is awesome and clearer than i thought a darker beer could be . i smell the hops , almost as much as the imperial i had from sam adams . i have to say i will try another dogfish but not the 90 minute ipa again .  a : pours like a normal stout would , builds a light brown head that fades quickly .  mouthfeel it has a nice full body and medium-low carbonation .

the aroma was very yeasty , with some malt and candy tones .  poured a inch head that was in a hurry for the sky . minimal retention & not much lacing of which to speak .  mouthfeel is quite good , low carbonation means it 's super creamy .

this may be the second fruit beer that i have ever liked . smell & gt ; bananas , hops and burnt sugar . excellent taste & gt ; bitter start , hop punch , smoothes out with a resiny hang ... but all the while there is an overlying ( and not overpowering ) layer of fresh baked banana bread . i think it 's grand . mouf & gt ; just okay drinkability & gt ; sure !  pours a light orange color , small head to it , small amount of lacing .  i think if you put this brew inside a bud light bottle the ratings would go from a b+ to a d. nice mouthfeel , though .

s : the smell was really nice and pleasant . it began with a little sweetness then a sharp expresso .  poured to a hazy reddish-orange with thin off-white hhead that lingered well and left good lacing along the glass .  m - thick . oh god , is it thick ! carbonation is surprisingly high . it is a little bit refreshing , but it also leaves a residue in your mouth .

smells is completely dominated by the odor of fresh ground ginger and an every so slight maltiness . taste is very mild maltiness with a subtle layer of ginger followed by a touch of hops , very underwhelming .  thanks to geuzelover for this aged sample , bottle reads- 1/22/2004 cloudy orange color with very little head ( maybe to due age of this sample ) .  m : silky smooth , low carbonation with a slight alcohol burn .

smells malty , citrusy , smokey with a hoppy background .  paradoxically , i suspect what makes me like it could lead those who like belgian ales to dislike it . it pours a very thin , loose white head which dissipates almost immediately , and a rich gold color representative of the style .  medium-full body with a smooth low-mid carbonation .

a nice nose of hoppy zest and bakery fresh bread with a little butter melting on top .  dark , muddy brown with a large tan head .  aroma is grapefruit , thick and gooey bready malt and magic hat buttery yeast . taste is equally alright but nowhere near worthy of the promised hop onslaught . grapefruit and agave hops with hearty malt balance . the real ale feel of this beer is enhanced by prickly hop resin . never has 100 ibus seemed so small .

toss in some brown sugar as well ... love the aroma . t-more acidic than expected ... not as richly flavorful as the nose leads you to expect ... .sure the dark fruits and brown sugar characteristics are there but the taste takes on a little more acidic feel ... call it a sour yeasty note if you 'd prefer ... it is not overwhelming at all but is definitely a part of the taste . personally i think it really adds a nice dimension to this ( and an unexpected one from the aroma ) m-medium bodied ... yeasty feel ... d-very enjoyable ... pretty complex and well worth trying .  i 'd had this in a bottle before and liked it , so figured i 'd try it on tap at the rogue in portland .  it 's a struggle for me to judge this beer as obviously a lot of craft went into it 's production , and yet i have to acknowledge that it makes me want to vomit . i will qualify all of this by saying that i hate eggs because i can not bare the sulphurous stink that i experience when they are cooked in any form . it get 's easier with each swallow but to me this tastes like someone is pouring a skunky heineken down my throat just after i 've had a swig of a very nice brew .

the aroma is about what you expect from a porter . i get notes of chocolate and roasted malt with not too much else coming through . the flavor is not as good as the aroma . i get some cocoa and roasted malt notes but there is also a sour cream/sour milk note that does n't go with the rest of flavors .  not sure how old my bottle was . there was absolutely no head and slight oxidation on the nose , but neither fact bothered me a lot .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with plenty of carbonation .

some yeasty haze and patchy lace initially . s : sweet and spicy phenolic character . t : a lemony sweetness that was at times cloying . wheaty with clove and hop spice on the finish .  poured into a duvel tulip . inky black , only the faintest chestnut hues around the edges . leaves a thin head that quickly recedes into nothingness , leaving neither a ring nor more than a few flecks of lacing .  it had a good body , not too thin , with a bit of carbonation .

copper color , almost hazy with little carbonation and little head to speak of , little lacing s : a flat , malty aroma t : light carbonation near the end with a malty aftertaste , tastes more like a light belgian than anything else m : light to medium body with low carbonation and a rather smooth drink d : not a bad beer , though seemingly mis-classified as a vienna lager .  pretty light in color for a pale ale . it 's a hazy golden . decent head with good clinging ability .  the mouthfeel is full and creamy . all in all , it just seems like an average barleywine/dipa..

yeah , sweet , dark , maybe some milky coffee on there as well , pretty pleasant . taste is a bit thin , some pleasant roastiness on there .  i dont know the exact name other than blueberry.but i do know it was damn good.it had a fruity candylike taste with hops and blueberries.i absolutely loved the taste of a hopped blueberry ( wheat ) .it was so much differnt than the hopless other fruit beers.it added a spicy zest to it.it was very crisp but lacked in any head.the blueberry flavor was real and not fake.wasnt watered down and was just wonderful .  m : mouthfeel is crisp and carbonated ; refreshing .

i felt that despite the strength of the hop flavours and aroma the balance was beautiful . i kept wanting to smell the beer again before every sip .  pours a lighter red , almost oragnish color , with an almost non-existent head .  m - medium-full body , lower carbonation , a slightly grainy texture , with light residual stickiness .

there is definately a strong smell of raspberries . it tastes like it smells -- very strongly of raspberries .  a : straw-golden . good head that dissipates quickly and does n't lace much . low carbonation s : very floral bouquet with hints of biscuits and honey .  mouth : oily and thick . very good . taste : hazelnuts . after a few sips , i got used to it , and it settled down to a good stout but , i could n't get the thought out of my mind , it was suntan lotion . spicy , peppery finish .

the strong , apricot flavor described in the earlier batch seems to have gone by the wayside ( first poster actually described a candied apricot flavor ) . the scent of apricots and grain is mild but present . fantastic .  this ale was a very clear red/garnet color . lots of big bubbles rising up .  feels pretty full .

first i have to say that i 'm a big fan of omm brews . now you serious beer guys are n't going to like this , but in the spirit of keeping the gravity , i cut this ale with keystone ice rather than flush it . i 'll stick with the ommegang abbey ale . like i said earlier , i ca n't disagree with the myriad of excellent reviews of this offering from ommegang , if this style suits your taste . but if , like me , you were introduced to ommegang through their abbey ale or wheat ... whit ... weiss , whatever you choose to call it , the hennepin is a different beast .  a wispy head and no lacing develops during the session .  medium body with a little astringency for cleanliness . leaves you with a good flavor and a touch of weight on the aftertaste . this is a complex and beguiling brew that every time i think i have it figured out , i am thrown a change-up .

it 's basically a spiced wheat ale , with orange zest , lemon zest , coriander and peppercorn . none of these come through in any dramatic fashion , aside from a little citrus-ey coriander , but it is interesting , regardless of my aversion to spice and fruit beers .  pours a slightlty hazed straw/bronze with 2+ fingers of eggshell white head , a bit of a foamer/gusher . above average head retention & average lacing s : lemony & peppery notes .  mouthfeel is nice , gently prickly and medium-light body .

a quick burst of pine aroma when the bottle first opens , disappears oddly quick , and leaves a perfume note that while not repulsive is not especially inviting or enticing . taste begins with a quick sweet note down the middle of the tongue before bitter and flowery hops overrun everything . the odd perfume/floral aroma trait shows up in the finish and refuses to go away quietly . its almost orangy citrus but takes a bad wrong turn .  a rather aggressive pour still leaves this beer flat-with absolutely no head .  medium bodied with good carbonation .

very drinkable , i can drink these 24/7 . a nice refreshing , easy to drink and pleasant enough beer to consume all night and get drunk off of . ) so , at least there are no cheap adjuncts made in this and tastes a lot better than others of the lager styles . outstanding ! !  poured ~1 finger of head . not overly impressive .  light body and easygoing feel when cold .

to me it had a fruity , citrusy aroma to it .  poured a 1 '' head which dissipated to a trace . although not technically a stout it reminds me of stout in most ways . so after my grand tour of 6 different weihenstephaner 's i 'd say heffeweisen and vitus were my favorites , korbinian came 3rd .  for such a warm & wintery smelling/tasting beer , the sensation is awfully sharp & has a prickly & active mouthfeel . interesting .

pours an excellent dark black into my glass with a very pleasant bourbon smell . as the beer warms up it starts to smell almost citrusy , like grapefruit .  it probably would have not been easy to get a different color , but i would have preferred more red to it just for aesthetics sake . = ) head : light white , dissipated quickly in the plastic sample cup .  mouthfeel is smooth .

a deep , rich and very nice smell . the first sip , in particular , was a real let down after a really enjoyable aroma . however , there were times when i found it to be very nice .  appearance : hazed orange colour shows the rawness of the brew , decent lacing gives snap and it dissipates .  mouthfeel - about right for the style ... the style being a flavored american wheat beer and not a witbier , as listed of course .

a bit earthy but overall very quiet . taste was hop flavors , pungent , organic .  hazy raw sienna yellow in color .  the flavor is very light , watered down even . m : light in body , creamy in texture , smooth finish . its not bad , better than i had expected , but compared to your typical micro-brewed porter , its pretty average .

smell : it was n't pleasant to me at all , but it was n't disgusting .  i had this beer poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a murky , maybe chill haze , with only a little ring of white head and not much lacing ... s : smells about right for an english-style barleywine , which this is most certainly attempting to be .  mouthfeel : light to moderate carbonation , smooth with a lightly dry finish .

very pleasant , and surprisingly robust for such a light beer .  a- a bit lacking appearance wise . not much head to speak of , and what there is dissolves into a film . no real lacing either . nice dark amber color though .  it 's not bad , necessarily , it 's just totally wrong for the style . that said , the mouthfeel is smooth , thick and rich , and the 6.3 % abv is nicely concealed .

the smell is very , very nice . it 's very funky , more funky than normal . there 's a bit of oxidized , sour smell , but a nice full funk .  a - clear macro lager pale yellow hue with a big three finger head that leaves quite a bit of foamy lace on the glass .  its light-medium and creamy with mild carbonation .

the smell is faint ; it takes some time to locate the aroma . no hops to be found here .  mixed bubble head with low retention and low lace .  a little too spicy for my liking m- thick , with a malty character . goes down smooth d- a little tough to handle all the spice .

s - smells of sweet malt , candied sugar , and banana . pleasant aroma . t - the sweetness from the noise is huge in the flavor .  bomber poured into an oversized tulip . a : pours a clear pumpkin orange with a thin white head . no lacing .  smooth and light bodied .

water yellow in color , smells of slight grains and water ( no smell ) .  a - pours copper-gold with 1 finger of off-white head . dissipates moderately fast and leaves no lacing .  mf : thick body , somewhat syrupy , very low carbonation , nice for the style d : very thick and and hearty , a bit hot on the booze , could use some age , .

aroma is of mild sweet caramel malts along with some grains . nothing real flashy to report here .  the beer pours a deep chocolate , almost black in colour with an off-white head that has little retention . indeed , it looks unremarkable .  it comes is sweet , with a medium body , and the bitterness really does clash a bit too much with it . not bad , i especially like the smooth mouthfeel , but i think that aftertaste is going to stick with me for a while .

dry , grassy aroma with some fruity apricot nectar hints .  poured with a slight head and a tiny bit a lace . color is n't copper , but a slightly hazy light to medium amber .  medium bodied with good carbonation .
smells really nice with strong cocoa scents .  pours dark murky brown with a red tint .  mouthfeel : pretty nice actually . soft , nicely carbed .

s : molasses , dark chocolate , campfire smoke , and a touch of oak . t : oddly fruity on the first taste with a burnt oak character .  beige head , decent , quite compact , not very persistent .  beer coated my mouth very uniformly with a honey taste in the front of my mouth and bitter taste in the back like a barelywine . the flavor alcohol is the only quality that counts against this beer .

the first impression of the smell is wine-like , muscat grapes , grappa of raisin . good marsala , and maybe liquorice ( more evident in the taste ) .  i first started to notice this beer when the red lobster that i worked at started offering it on tap . it reminded me of harpoon summer beer .  alcohol is strong and a bit rough with a potent orange , passion fruit , and sour berry edge riding the edges of my tongue . mild carbonation and thick dextrinous mouthfeel that evaporates in the end in a pleasing way .
nose - lots of chocolate and roasted malt in the nose along with some alcohol .  poured with a nice off-white head and some lace . color is a medium hazy amber .  mouthfeel is quite good .
the aroma was fruity with chocolate and dark fruits and an alcohol bite .  but hardly any head formed at all , very disappointing .  it is highly carbonated .

it 's black ( or nearly black ) with a delicious looking head that coats the sides of the glass with its frothy goodness . smell : chocolate and more chocolate .  the coloring is reddish-brown with a soda-pop head that fizzes out like a cola .  mouthfeel : crisp and clean .

s : caramel malt . a sweet scent . t : sweet .  a very clean beer . appearance is somewhat of an initial turnoff ... a bit murky which is expected for a beer of this type .  m : very tingly on a very full body .

good smell , but subdued : pineapple , apple , banana , menthol , rubbing alcohol , slightly buttery shortbread . tastes of ripe golden delicious apple , pineapple , yeast , alcohol .  the look of this brew is nothing special . very little head , although , it does have a nice deep amber color .  medium mouthfeel works fine .

smells of raspberries and very little else .  referred to as `` extra '' on the label and courtesy of ba rblwthacoz . pours insanely murky mahogany , with tons of flaked particulates being churned up as the carbonation gets settled in . a half inch head of beige settled to a solid skim coat with some brown discoloration from sediment rising to the surface . decent lacework throughout the glass . aside from the horrible amount of dregs this beer is quite complex and refreshing ... as long as you like sours !  lots of carbonation , medium body ... very drinkable very nice mouth feeling .

a rich and overpowering acetone aroma .  the beer is a golden copper in color , with an unimpressive head . well , i guess i can understand that a 9 % abv , but i do like a little head with my beer .  m : light-bodied with moderate carbonation . clean finish .

s : some roasted malts up front followed by sweet , creamy chocolate . slight hop aroma on the finish as well .  pours a hazy golden color with a quickly fading head .  i hate to review this brew cuz i love columbus brewing . decent carbonation and some lace . ok if you like fruity beers . the only thing is it says it has a nice hop finish ... nah . hot a hop in the lot .

smell is very raw alcohol and some roasted malt and raisin presence . tase is very tart and bitter , slightly fruit and somewhat cloying .  bottle , '09 vintage , a : pours type black with a minimal if any type of head . not a great start , but it 'd change my mind . but it 's not flat at all .  the mouthfeel was great though , oily , hoppy , slick on the tongue .

smells delicious ; smells of pumpkin pie and has a nice spicy earthy hop aroma mixed in to the overall aroma . flavors of pumpkin , nutmeg and caramel slowly melt into a delicious concoction . it sits around 9 % but drinks very , very smooth . nice seasonal !  poured a deep , deep brown with a small head that fades .  mouthfeel - like most porters it has a nice smooth feel . actually impressed with the feel of this porter considering taste .

a : poured a orange gold color with good carbonation and a nice white head caps it off s : all over the place , pine , citrus mainly t : harsh .  i loved this pumpkin ale . i thought it was the very best of all of the pumpkin ales i drank this season . it smelled great -- lots of spice and just enough pumpkin -- not a beery pumpkin pie like the o'fallon pumpkin ale that was just overpowering with pumpkin and spice .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with creamy carbonation .

pretty good nose , considering the other categories . quite a package . the palate however seems a touch odd .  head is decent initially , but faded before i could measure it . i can create some lacing with a big stirring of the glass.. it has a nicecloudy amber/brown color .  m : best part of the beer , light-bodied , light carbonation , pretty nice .

it was cloyingly sweet . good nose . strong vanilla , very strong caramelized notes give way to noticeable alcohol on the back end .  pours somewhat hazed & effervescent amber with 2 fingers of cream colored head . average head retention & minimal lacing s : caramel , breadyness , fruittyness & grainyness t : bready with toffee & honey notes up front .  full bodied and carbonated well .

watery , but barleywine aroma , likely needs considerable ageing .  looks very average .  mouthfeel was light and fluffy on the palate with a fine , spritzy , lively carbonation . practically champagne-like .

s : sweet caramel , dates , nuts , alcohol , cotton candy fruity esters , christmas cake t : plenty of sweet caramel , raspberry bud candy , dates , raisins , christmas cake , nuts , alcohol , brown sugar & cider , modest bitterness , alcohol is noticable .  slightly murky deep maroon color with thick , but rapidly flattening khaki head .  looks beautiful in its golden splendor , smells too estery and one dimensional , metallic finish , nice mouthfeel and i may or may not finish it .

the color was between amber and straw , with just a hint of haze . s : very subtle , not strong pumpkin or spice . if the label did n't say otherwise , i 'd swear i was smelling a wheat beer rather than an ale . t : ok , now i sense the pumpkin ( 1st ) and spice ( 2nd ) , with a bready malt and hops making an appearance as it finishes going down .  a : pours with a small off-white head that disappears quickly . relatively speaking , the body is a dark shade of amber orange . lacing is spare to none .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

s-slight floral hops , earthy , some roasted malt . overall , meh ... t-sweet citrus as it hits the tongue , then sugared malt , then hops , some alcohol in the finish . what it lacks in smell , it makes up for everywhere else .  poured into a pint glass age of this beer is unknown pours a dark brown with a one inch head aroma-smells almost like bread pudding with raisins-perplexing taste-it says `` mild stout '' on the label so i am somewhat taken aback with the initial taste .  mouthfeel : crisp and tingly . this is where i think it stands out as just another average wheat ale .

it looked like pink grapefruit juice , a favorite of mine . very pink , cloudy , like i said , grapefruit juice . nose was salty , like the breeze blowing in off the atlantic , underlain with a tomato-like tang . frankly , mr. shankly , my mouth actually began to water . it reminded me of the fantail on days when we could not dump trash and garbage and the sharks would troll behind us , hoping that we would chum the waters for them , having built up a smell that would fall a redwood .  murky brown body w/ a touch of a halo and a couple lazy bubbles coming up from the bottom .  m : fairly thick , sticky , and medium carbonation .
nice yeasty fruity aroma .  nice light brown color with bascally no head .  the mouthfeel was pretty pleasant though , smooth , ( unfiltered ) .

smell : sweet malt with hints of chocolate and burnt caramel . the slight smell of alcohol his hidden beneath as per the style .  pours a murky reddish/iced-tea color , tiny tan head fades out very quickly , spotty lacing on the glass , and lots of tiny floaties in the beer . on the lighter side of full-bodied , lots of lingering hop kick , and some mouth-coating/warming alcohol spiciness .  body and carbonation are good .

smells like more of a raspberry ale than a porter . it does smell good , but not like a porter in much of any way .  a a very pale golden yellow , with barely noticeable wheat haziness . no yeast sediment in the bottom like wheat counterpart and fantastic beer easy street wheat ; what a bummer . new `` belgium '' should make belgian wheat beers -- and that means mucky stuff in the bottom of the glass that makes wheats worth drinking in the first place . brief 1-finger head whittles away to small wispy puffs . the sort of faceless but tasty summer beer for all day sipping .  m ) lively carbonation , smooth but strong . refreshing .

aroma is very chocolaty ... a semi-sweet and roasted chocolate smell is very noticeable with some floral hoppiness in the background .  pours a very , very dark brown color . appears black until held up to the light . no head at all , though there are some very slight legs .  light-medium body and moderate carbonation .

it a neat beer with an unusual flavor and feel . its unusual and drinkable but a little sweet to drink all the time . i would try other beers from this brewery to see if they are as intriguing .  appearance- poured a honey yet slightly amber hue with a spritzy two-finger head . the head has very little retention but leaves a minor foam with a dash of lacing .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with a creamy carbonation - probably one of the better features of the beer .

smell - nicy malty and chocolatey smell .  gold with a touch of orange and a tight ivory colored head which drops to a skim . verify little lace .  just a poor finish . a solid mouthfeel for the style .

smell : citrus and floral , something i do n't get in english bitters . confused a bit , but smells nice ; floral , citrus , some sweet malt .  p : clear , golden body . no head , save for a small ring .  mouthfeel : the thing that 's done correctly with this brew , as it 's full , creamy , and has enough carbonation to make me crave the other wheat flavors and aromas that are too obfuscated by the boysenberry flavors and aromas .

s- smells nice with big , upfront aromas of wheat , yeast , orange peel , coriander . the smell is alluring , but what follows is a let-down .  there was a bit of an off white head that dropped off quickly .  mouthfeel is very full , carmelly throat coating with an alcohol burn following .

it reminds me a bit of a cherry lambic in appearance . the nose is pretty unappetizing -- it smells of sour rice and some asian fruit that is obscure to my american palate , but that i 've smelled before ( at the world of coke exhibit in atlanta , believe it or not ) .  poured into my large st. feuillien goblet , rose cassis ( 2005 ) is a ruddy cider color , very murky , with an off-white head that settles to a long lasting skim but leaving almost no lace . the sediment was well compacted , and while it looked hazy , there was no sediment at the bottom of the glass , which i sipped slowly .  i suppose that could be the hops , since i 'm getting no other hop scent at all . pear flavors are more pronounced , some wheat , and some herbal sensations .

very compelling aroma . the mouthfeel is pretty full bodied with smooth creamy textures alongside carbonation zing .  pours reddish brown with no real head .  mouth feel is smooth and clean , with a low carbonation level .

enjoyable . taste is almost sour , with tons of the clove that was evident in the smell . overall , started promising , but did n't deliver .  muddy looking like a good scotch ale . i love a good scotch ale so hopefully thats a good sign . not much for head , but great lacing left over on the glass .  mouthfeel is spot on , maybe a bit heavier and not quite as ethereal as some others , but good . if you have n't tried the style and want to see what its all about , save your money for the deus or the malhuer brut .

s : roasted munich malts and noble hops . the hops , very german in their scent , are more forward than i 've typically experienced with bocks . t : quite average , almost bland .  poured from a 12 oz bottle into a tulip glass . a - pours an almost pitch black with a twinge of light tinting it a crystal clear brown . head is thin and dissipates quickly , no foam collar , but sporadic dots of lacing to cling to the side of the glass .  creamy medium-full body with very light , tingly carbonation . full and heavy in the mouth .

typical lager appearance . s - cereal grains , light malt , and some light piney hops . nothing too special here . d - not too bad as far as adjunct lagers go . nothing i 'll be going out of my way to drink in the future , but i get the feeling this wo n't be the last i see of calgary .  a - it 's a light looking beer but has a bit of amber tint to it s - smell is subtle definitely lagery and very good t - the taste was just as the smell was , quite subtle but so smooth and easy to drink m - it was great , i did n't get that funky corn thing going on as i do with most lagers d - i could probably drink a whole 6 pack within a few hours , and that 's saying a lot for me because beer fills me up a lot .  upfront its smooth with a thicker creamy mouthfeel and moderate carbonation .

s : floral , green -- like smelling wet twigs . tea-like . piney . it 's very , very hoppy on the nose . which is fine ; smelling does n't cost anything , and i like it .  pours a dark brown color with a thick , foamy tan head . a goodly amount of what are presumably yeast bits are floating around in my glass , even without me agitating the bottom of the bottle .  light bodied , smooth and refreshing .

s : a very pleasant light cherry aroma with a light malt overtop it . yummy smelling .  its cloudy , yellow-gold body is capped by a short head of white foam that dissipates readily and leaves just some spotty lace about the glass ( dirty glass , perhaps ? ) .  nice light body and sparkly carbonation .

nicely balanced aroma , with toasty and doughy malt , a bit of caramel , fruity and earthy hops , citrusy . i had more hope after getting a good smell , but things just did n't come together .  although it was a bit cloudy , i think that was due more to the fact that i had just received the shipment and i should have given it more time to settle .  mouthfeel is good , slick and medium bodied , but drinkability is rough as this one just did n't do it for me at all !

wow , the aroma is truly amazing ! subtle for its complexity . you have to stick around and give it a chance , but it doesnt exactly have to twist your arm , either . it really is an arrogant bastard . good beer .  served in a pint glass , very dark with no head .  t_very rich fudge is the best way to describe this . m_a bit viscous with a light but hard carbonation . works well here .

uninspiring . aromas are agreeable : grapefruit hops , caramel , wood and vanilla .  a : pours a dark ruby red color . a small tan forms , but recedes in an instant .  the mouthfeel is nice , thicker than many beers without being syrupy .

very pungent . mouthfeel- much thinner than expected.. the alcohol is very present ... drinkability- i was in the mood for a dark , creamy stout , and this beer failed to deliver .  poured from a 22 ounce bomber into a british pub glass , perhaps a bit too cold at pour . forms a 1 inch head that fades into an espresso cap very quickly .  as the malt bill is substantial , this beer has a nice heavy body . the carbonation is moderate , and overall it has a nice feel .

what a wonderful blueberry aroma this beer has ! it looks like a typical ale , and has virtually no head .  i came across this delectable treat at the mercury lounge in goleta , california . i think the best trait this porter has is the exceptional balance between ingredients . a true porter that doesn & # 8217 ; t try to be a stout . unfortunately the lighting was horrible at the mercury so i can & # 8217 ; t comment on the appearance other than the unique bottles are quite an interesting sight .  light body , medium to high carbonation has a very nice mouth cleansing feel , the highlight of this beer .

the nose on this beer is pretty nice . caramel , toffee maltiness and piney , grassy hops are both very noticeable .  appearance-half finger white head ; light yellow ; cloudy smell- grainy with a hint of spice taste- malted wheat ; grainy ; crisp ; refreshing mouthfeel- light body ; good carbonation drinkability- easily sessionable beer & gt ; i will definitely get this again .  m : quite a big body with a creamy texture . the mouthfeel is really good , but for some reason it does n't go very well with the flavors .
aroma has hints of roast and some plum-like fruitiness .  served in a nonic pint glass , the beer pours black with about a half inch tan head .  mouthfeel is light with good carbonation .

this is really a tale of two beers , the smell is really godawful , but the taste is subtle and kinda tasty . as far as overall drinkability , i had to put it somewhere in the middle as that nose is really bad .  big thanks to russ for bringing this to compare to the wooden hell at our tasting ... this looks just like wh , a light watery brown not much head to speak off ... this takes a huge turn at aroma and taste , while it is nice its now where in the league of wh .  3/5 m : medium/full body , warm and smooth going down . 4/5 d : too sweet for me to have more than 12 oz .

s : somewhat skunked but has a definite malt smell . seems like there 's something in the smell that reminds me of canned vegetables , but i really ca n't put a finger on it .  an orange/copper colored beer with a slight haze . has a small white head that disappears quickly.the aroma is sweet and spicy with hints of nutmeg and cinnamon .  md body and strong carbonation .

while popping the top there was a cheap beer smell , once poured it had almost no aroma . the taste is definitely better than bud . definitely a step up from a macro beer , but for the price i could have had 6 bottles or a couple bombers of a really good beer .  murky brown with a tan head .  still average overall . mouthfeel/overall : light bodied with pleasant carbonation . pretty smooth drinking and not overcarbonated .

the aroma is of faint caramel with a hint of barnyard . the over-carbonated head really gets in the way of the aroma . the taste is of a sour brown ale . i actually like the taste quite a bit , and if the aroma was n't so hidden by foam i could really get into this beer .  appearance : opaque orange , very thin lacing and soapy bubbles . you 'd get a bit of head on it only after significant swirling . for something that 's been sitting a while in the cellar , it 's nothing unusual .  i got this bottle from a friend who went to the brewery in michigan . i do n't know if this bottle was stored poorly or something but ipa is the last impression i got from this beer . smells of deep caramel , candi sugar , some sweet citrus hops are barely there and theres some hints of biscuit and chocolate . this already smells like a dubble belgian ale and it taste even more like one . it 's exceptionally sweet , almost like a mild ipa that was aged for far to long . it 's got caramel and raisen notes along with some prune and apple . there 's a little hint of hops but you honestly have to search for it . i really think travel took a heafty toll on this beer .

s. spiced bread and sweet malt .  picking up the summer shandy was a most welcome surprise . as a major fan of leinie 's sunset wheat , it was hard to imagine that they could put out a beer to trump it , but the shandy comes close . initially , the shandy is reminiscent of a standard american wheat ale , but slowly , the lemonade flavor builds on the pallet to a crescendo , and thus , presenting its full-body of flavor . there 's no debate on this wheat ale , no lemon necessary , the lemonade brewed into this beer is a shandy and all one should need .  mouthfeel is about right ; it 's not bone dry and spritzy , but not thick and chewy , either .

aroma is very good with a nice scent of vanilla and hints of malt . color is a bright amber/brown with good carbonation and a nice head . although it is a very good flavored brew its a piss poor excuses for a stout .  appearance - small white head atop a golden slightly hazy body . head dissipates fairly rapidly . little to no lacing . grapefruit punch recedes into a green apple like sourness .  medium body , low carbonation .

fruity esters are noticed upon smelling . somewhat dry in flavor , hints of fruitiness and acidity .  a : pours a dark reddish brown color . a small white cap of foam forms , and leaves hardly any lace .  very nice mouthfeel , which is immediately hit with a taste of the bubblegum yeast , followed up with notes of clove , chai , and maybe some cinnamon .

smell is malt , alcohol , and fresh oranges .  pours a murky mud color with no head whatsoever . no lacing present , the beer actually looks kind of dead with the exception of tiny bubbles around the edges of the glass indicating a trace of carbonation . the color is attractive despite the murky pond water appearance , there is a deep mahogony color with a tinge of tawny gold around the edges .  4.0 m : medium body . good moderate carbonation with a pleasant creaminess .

i 've only had a few barleywines and this is my first old ale to date . smell : smoky , malty with alcohol being the prominent smell .  a- pours a deep amber color , with a 1-finger head that disipates moderately quickly leaving no lacing .  the mouthfeel is good , not too light and not overly heavy either .

s - nice soft woody hop character .  1 finger being head with bulky collar retention . honestly , it looks like a stirred up mud puddle .  feels light and clean with a nice density . big bubbles in the carbonation stay locked in and add a lot of life to this one .

shame ... s : strong aroma 's here of raisins , espresso beans , dark chocolate and a bit of nuttiness t : raisins , dark fruits , espresso beans and nothing else really . d : besides the smell , i found this beer to be very poor . i would n't spend money on this again , nor have i even enjoy the beer .  pretty much copying my marron acidifie review here because the beers are so damn similar . dark reddish-brown topped by a thin head . carbonation is low and the body is cloudy and opaque .  m - solid coating with a medium amount i 'd tingle on sides and under tongue .

the smell was non-existent . maybe got a bit of malt and floral notes , but almost nothing . not offensive , just ... nothing . a good pitcher beer , and one i 'll probably get again .  a - a light yellow , very pale looking appearance for an ipa .  moutfeel is nice and crisp due to a decent amount of carbonation .

poured into nonic pint glass a - brown-black in color , no head whatsoever s - big roasty flavor . coffee notes , a little vanilla t - malt , no hops as expected .  a- poured a dark copper-red/brown , somewhere between an ipa and an amber . no head , just a small trace of a halo . no lacing , no nothing . fine body , no head .  m- light and bubbly with a little creaminess it feels good in the mouth with crisp carbonation . d- without the skunk this would be a nice beer , it feels good in the mouth and smells and looks like most lagers , but that skunk flavor is a killer .

appearance : i was very excited on the first pour since it lived up to it 's exceptionally dark and bold image smell : typical ris smell but more to the hoppy/nutty side taste : way too alcoholic for my tastes . there 's actually a very good stout behind all that alcohol though .  sampled on 5-18-07 best before 10-2-07 pours a very pale , semi-cloudy yellow with a quickly fading head and decent lacing .  carbonation is all but absent , the aroma is too faint to appreciate , and it loses suds early . its one redeeming feature is its fully textured mouthfeel .

s : smells nice , fruity , slightly hoppy , a little earthy t : pretty plain tasting in comparison to the smell , malty , earthy , a slight bitterness at the end .  3.0 a : lightly hazed dark yellow/light orange color . just a half finger of frothy white head that fell quickly and left no lacing .  m - smooth , thin , extremely refreshing .

good detention , not much lacing s- a lot going on here . fruity hops are followed by bigtime vanilla from the oak , and some banana . initial hops hit is nice , but then the sweet vanilla and wood comes in leaving a bad aftertaste for me .  a - pours a hazy straw color with big head with little retention and some spotty lacing down the glass .  m ) i actually thought it had a very nice mouthfeel .

nose is assertive milked , semi-sweet coffee , roasted grain and rich sweet dark chocolate - very nice nose . mouthfeel is thin and watery and with no body .  a ) nice copper color . about 1/2 inch of white head , not much retention , a little bit of sporadic lacing .  mouthfeel is pleasant : medium bodied , smooth and lightly carbonated .

aroma has some dark ripened fruit notes hints of cherry/raisin notes . alcohol plays a pretty big factor in the nose here , i can really smell the booze in this one .  pours a clear copper brown , topped with a one finger kahki head , no lacing and the head faded quickly .  m- full body . high carbonation .

nose is inviting with floral and citric notes . malt is noticed with some faintly carmel/bready aromas .  rusty golden nectar pours into clean glassware , a quickly expanding snow colored head forms nicely at the top , pleasant variation in bubble size , head fades in a hurry leaving a very thin layer of white on top , lacing is poor to mediocre , i 've stumbled into the cellar of some british cider brewer from the turn of the century , the lovely nostalgia inducing scent of apples consumes my nostrils .  mouthfeel : does have good mouthfeel .

a- very cloudy , shit floaten around not the biggest fan , yellow color s- citrus t- i like the lemon grass and the orange isnt over done . better then the geniric belgum wheats that flood the market m-cant get overe the particals clinging to my throat .  i was n't too terribly impressed with its appearance . a fairly aggressive pour with a good bit of distance between the bottle and the glass yielded a very meager head . what foam was there , vanished in about 20 seconds .  it has a medium body and nice carbonation considering .

aroma is big-time citrus hops and a generous dosage of granny smith apple . smells innocent enough .  bajuvator pours a dark brown , lighter than a cola , and it leaves a thin tan head on top .  this light bodied beer has a creaminess that is hidden in the appearance and aroma , however it does feel pretty good in my mouth .

seriously , i had high hopes for this one when i poured it and took in the nice chocate and coffee aroma , but it tasted like someone had dissolved a charcoal brickette in it .  a : cloudy yellow . pour out 2/3 and then swirl the rest for a decent head , otherwise you wo n't have any .  medium bodied with a soft , creamy mouthfeel .

s : i detected malt and bread aromas . an overall complex aroma for such a light beer . t : a malty start that gave way to sweet fruit.remindes me of a cider .  appearance - there was n't much to look at , thus the 3.0 on the appearance score . completely black , very little head to speak of , largely due to the lack of carbonation . in retrospect ... this beer was almost impressively black .  taste & mouthfeel - first things that come through are a smooth malt , followed by a piney hop bitterness . a crisp refreshing taste , ends nicely in a sweet smooth finish .

smells of rich and overly sweet barley , candied sugar and toffe notes with a hint of vanilla . good but i doubt i 'll age another one .  appearance : burnt orange in colour with a thin creamy head .  m : it was nicely carbonated and i enjoyed the feeling of this in my mouth .

great nose but after that not much great about it .  had the beer sampler with one each helles , hefe-weizen and dunkel . sample size was.1l from the tap in a straight sided glass . ( looked like a juice glass ) . cloudy copper colored beer with half a finger of head that dissipated last of the three beers that were served .  medium to full bodied , tingly and warming .

this is labatt 's answer to rickard 's red . but the beer has almost no smell which , come to think of it , is not necessarily a bad thing given that it 's from labatt 's .  pours a standard brown ale brown with a small white crown .  m - good carbonation , fairly large amount of bubbles .

p- grape and gourmet in va beach . s- roasted caramel malt .  pours a dark hued brown with really no head to speak of and light carbonation .  the body is light and not too watery , but the hop bitterness is further accentuated by the resins in the feel . the carbonation is nice and light though , as a cask should be .

fragrance ( from citrus oil ) is just like say , hoegaarden ... .but the taste is more `` drinkable '' ( a very low ibu rating ) .  drank from my duvel tulip a - pours the classic oily ebony colour with a tanned large bubbled head that fades away after two minutes or so to a film .  m : a medium mouthfeel . the feel is the best part to this beer , there is a nice smoothness to it .

the aroma is very potent . i 'm wondering just how much nutmeg and allspice are in this thing . the taste does n't quite live up to the aroma . there is n't a lot of taste to it . it is n't disgusting , it 's just lacking .  it poured a watery light amber , very translucent with a frothy white head . it 's very drinkable because it 's a very solid beer but this bottle at least disappointed me a little bit .  01.14.10 at city beer store a : was surprised by the light copper color ; for some reason , i remember this beer being lighter s : wet-sock kind of of funk t : kind of a metallic , alcoholic finish m : really nice carbonation d : not my favorite , but then again , not my favorite style .

smell - it has a sweet fruitiness in the scent that does n't overtake the robust malt aroma .  poured a slightly hazy pale gold with a quickly dissipating head .  the taste up front is somwhat sweet with a carbonation presence providing plenty of creamy thicker mouthfeel without all that carbonation sting to the toung .

pours with a big ole head , and lacing is fine too ... smell is similar to heineken , some call it skunky- i call it skunkarific ! ... a basic beer , but it seems to do the job ... for the price , a real bargain !  jet black in color . smallish head that hardly left any lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel is just below medium with average carbonation and very subtle alcohol warming towards the end of the glass .

we thought that this was going to be a sweeter , rounded saison due to the explanation that this was to be a saison noir . this really reminds me of orval , but not for the right reasons .  it pours a very dark brown but the head is disapointing with poor retention .  m : fair body , pleasant carbonation d : doubt i 'll finish this - there 's other stuff i 'd rather drink now

the nose is chalk full of warm caramel and vanilla malt aromas . a little nutty smelling . smells really smooth and appealing .  pours dark copper with ruby tints and a small but persistent off-white head .  m - mild coating with a high amount of tingle . tingle around the body of the tongue and behind the bottom lip .

the aroma consists of wheaty tange , lemmon , and a musty note . a nice tarte flavor that takes this nice clean wheat beer and makes it so refreshing it would be perfect to drink on a sweltering hot day .  pours a cool copper with a hint of a redish tint , with alot of think lacy head that stuck around all the way down . i consider this a nice big mouthfell that would be very drinkable at any time especailly on a nice cool nice with the feet proped up after a hard days work .  mouthfeel is good . forgettable ris here .

dark amber , mostly translucent but not see-thru , small cream head s - huge banana esters , a little nutty bread t - like the smell , plus some hops .  the beer poured a hazy pale orange color and made a 1 finger fizzy white head that dissipated to just a thin white ring in under 3o seconds . a moderate amount of lacing is left on the glass after each sip .  mouthfeel is good , maybe a bit over carbonated but still smooth .

s : munich malt , very toffee-like . nice sugary , baked goods notes .  a_pours from the can almost black , the true nature of it being brown is only revealed when held up to the light . some lace clings , but not much . a mild sweetness creeps unto the tongue after this initial wave . this can make for a good session stout that does not overwhelm your taste buds like a stronger stout .  good moderate carbonation .

tons of hops , but lots of malt to back it up . pine and citrus hops are the most pronounced . the malt is all caramel smelling . t- wow ... brutal . very intense and in your face . the alcohol is very strong , and almost overpowering . d- ugh . the alcohol is way too strong and the oak made that nasty medicinal taste that sort of reminded me of cough syrup .  poured a cloudy rusty tan . bout a finger of head . smelled strongly of piney citrus .  however , the carbonation is good and the beer is thick and full-bodied ... maybe even a bit too much for an ipa , but not bad .

light straw color with not as much yeast haze as i was expecting , the wispy white foam head is substantial . is this an american hefe or a german one ? bananas and vanilla pudding in this one . light noble hop breadiness . does not taste as good as it smells . yeast does not pop out as much as expected . i like most flying dog brews .  true black in colour , the foaming tan head fell away very quickly to just a weak collar and a wispy scum .  m - light and crisp . high carbonation .

smell : best part of this beer . sweet cirtus aromas . pepto bismol . overall : while it smells appetizing , the taste is artificial .  much appreciated 330 ml poured into a ccb snifter a -- poured a cola color and settled a murky brownish black . short lived half finger that was light brown color that went to film . decent head retention but also quickly fades away leaving bits of a soapy lacing on the sides of the glass .  m- very creamy texture , surprisingly light ( but not *too* light ) body .

very , very well blended smelling . hints of lemon and mild cherry on the back . very good . t : wow , this is a bit of a disappointment at first .  appearance- a beautiful cloudy yellow orange color . a disappointingly lackluster head with little sign of carbonation , but damn that 's one pretty color .  mouth- i like the feel on this beer a lot . it 's very sweet and creamy but not at all like a double stout . something new and it was probably better fresh .

the aroma was very strong , with hints of alcohol , lots of malts , fruit .  a - cloudy , milky yellow with a small head and no lacing .  the beer has a creamy and smooth body , but that delivers in an awkward way with the flavors this beer has .

aroma starts out with a blast of sulfur/rotten eggs and copper . clearly some sort of infection here . bretty notes and wine are the foremost aromas underneath the lingering sulfur .  dark copper brown with a slight haze .  m : medium bodied with decent carbonation .

s - somewhat sweet smelling with caramel , cloves , almost like a trail mix smell ... not too bad and left me ready to experience great flavor .  pours a medium gold with a pretty standard head that leaves ok lacing .  app - copper , carbonated head of minimal size and dissipating rapidly smell - hoppy , piney taste - a little hoppy bite but a more than overwhelming caramel biscuity malt taste that i guess balances the offering but not when there are so few hops to begin with.. mouthfeel - kind of cool and different on this one , kind of coats the mouth in a silky fashion overall - not too big on this malty aftertaste , etc . the carbonation is more than i prefer

i would say that enjoyed the citrus and corriander aromas and flavor nothing else really came through in this one . for once upon a time i drank this a celis grand cru ( when it was brewed in texas ) only for a few months way back when .  poured a light clear golden.sudsy head that diminished but left broken lace all the way through .  when you swallow it , the hops hit ... and to be honest i did n't like 'em . mouthfeel 's fine and i 'm sure if you like the flavor profile this would be a fine brew .

aroma is an intriguing mix of yeast , malt , spice , caramel , and a bit of leather .  no head and teeny bit of lacing .  last night i brewed a big ipa , and as tradition dictates - `` drink what ya brew . '' upon opening the beer and taking a sniff i was a little disappointed . where are the hops ? maybe a bit of floral notes , but that could be the yeast . first sip and i get the bitterness of the hops , but not as much flavor as i 'd like . if this were labeled as a pale ale , i would have given it much higher marks . however , as an ipa , it just does n't hack it .

( s ) - spices of nutmeg , cinnamon , allspice , clove , and apples , very cider-like . not as pleasant as the smell was offering . the pale ale aspect and the spices added really conflict with each other in a way that i am not a fan of .  served in a snifter at the source a solid black color with no head at all even if coaxed .  the flavor was just a bit too harsh , which is odd becuase to the palate it is a beer that has a pleasant feel to the mouth .

robust hop aroma with a well balanced flavor .  2010 vintage , so it 'll likely be a bit flat . pours a dark , inky black with obviously low carbonation , thick and syrupy with a very thin mocha ring and swirl of haze . big , delicious aromas of dark malt , molasses , chocolate , raisins , and some booze .  a bit of hoppy bitterness , but otherwise not much ... not really my thing m + d : rather smooth , semi-creamy mouthfeel - one of the better aspects to this .

the aroma is quite rich and enticing , the type of aroma i would expect to find on an imperial stout not a porter . i get sweet fruity notes of burnt raisins as well as some nice rich chocolate notes . this is a really nice malty porter , there is not much in the way of hop notes , just a mix of sweet and dark malt notes .  being that it 's from bmc , it 's a stab at a rare style from them and it 's actually pretty good and refreshing .  however , it goes down smoothly and the carbonation is just right .

s - some sweet tart cherry , but in general the scent is underwhelming and almost vacant .  a= pours a nice hazy orange color with a small head on it that holds almost no retention or lacing on the glass . the color of the beer is pretty nice but the head is off .  mouf & gt ; good . easy .

the aroma has a mild sweet citrus aroma with a hint of peppercorns .  dark auburn color , clearish but really more translucent , little head , no lacing .  i do like the syrupy mouthfeel , but it does n't compensate for the taste of alcohol .

the aroma is quite nice ... it has a typical american wheat ale nose of cracked wheat , crackers , pale malt grain husk , but overlaid by a dusty sour fruitiness akin to raspberries .  clear amber beer . no bubbling . thin , off-white hea ... hey , where 'd the head go ? very dry . brown shugga could take some getting used to , but i think i could really like this stuff .  mouthfeel is hot and crisp . very interesting , and it worked for this particular beer .

aroma of buttery toffee , super malty , and that 's about it . not much going on with the taste . there are some very interesting notes on the finish , but they seem to disappear so quickly i ca n't define or enjoy them . i do n't think it 's very smokey as others have suggested , and alcohol lingers in my throat and breath .  appearance while looking for some sort of freshness date , i noticed that this bottle had a ton of chunky sediment that was starting to get stirred up . i carefully poured and got a hazy pale honey colored beer with lots of suspended chunks . its almost uneven and just does n't look good . the head was short and there is no lacing .  medium mouthfeel .

) great aroma upon agitating the beer . nice crisp hoppy smell .  pours a very cloudy orange , looks like iced tea . almost no head and no lace due to cask .  m : medium smooth body with just the right amount of carbonation . this is the beers best aspect .

the aroma reminds me of a sweet porter .  on to the beer : it pours like fizzy , straw colored water into my weizen glass with zero head .  the flavor profile replicates the nose fairly closely , but is clearly dominated by the molasses and prunes , as well as the dry sherry and more wood . the finish is fairly dry and sherry filled in this otherwise moderately sweet , full flavored beer . drinkability is where this beer really falls apart , and in fact i was unable to finish even the 8 ounce wine glass serving i received at the g & g . while not hot , the beer is heavy and a bit tiring on the palate , and it was just a chore to get this beer down given the sweetness , wood and sherry flavors .

12 oz bottle poured into imperial pint glass a : very golden amber with large fluffy , creamy white head , awesome lace , leaves a ring every sip , a little light but good looking s : nice aroma , nice piney/fruity/citrus all hitting together , very pleasant and aromatic , slight hint of sweetness from malt , a tad bready and a tad caramel t : now that i 've smelled and tasted it , the hops are very similar to dale 's pale ale , has that same fruitiness with a little pine note too , however it starts tasting of alcohol in the finish , does n't have a very `` deep '' flavor profile , but its good , has a little biscuity malt to balance , but the finish just is n't super pleasant m : starts just about medium body , but gets kind of slick feeling as that alcohol hits d : ok , all in all not bad , but not close to the best ipa notes : like i hinted at , its not a bad beer , but its not even top 10 ipa 's that i 've tried .  more or less a typical pils as far as i am concerned . not really bad but nothing really stood out either .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and medium carbonated .

aroma is interesting . my first thought was that it was almost like a high quality golden tequila , but no , it 's sweeter and fruitier , but there is something in there- wood smoke like i remember from the bad old days when i liked that other stuff . quite a disappointment after the decent interesting aroma . no spices , no complexity , no pepper , weak fruit .  poured from a 12 ounce bottle into a tulip glass , a bit off fridge temperature . a : pours light brown into the glass , with a very pretty ruby luminescence when held to light . the lack of any lasting head is disappointing for the style .  m : medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation . keeps good with the style o : stays within style guidelines for some of the aspects like appearance and mouthfeel , but really lacks the flavor and bitterness that is usually present .

scent is the typical floral assault that one would expect from an ipa . taste continues the flavour , but that 's it .  poured a bright orange with lots and lots and lots and lots and lots and lots and lots and lots of sediment .  carbonation is light & fine . feels creamy without being heavy .

perhaps i am just not use to a lambic quite like this one . s : sour cherries and yeast not much else but what would you expect from a lambic .  the head was one finger and pure white , left no lacing and did not retain at all .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with good carbonation .

very thin head s - sweet aroma . smell of raisins or dates t - sweet - instant caramel , raisin flavor .  reviewed 12/28/2007 ( sampler @ oggi 's pizza and brewery , peoria , az ) : pours a non-cloudy radiant yellow colored body , with a small white colored head .  m. medium to full bodied with decent carbonation . coats the mouth decent , definitely all that sweet malt .

sweet smelling and fruity . apricots .  when poured into a pint glass there is an unexpectedly large head which dissipates quickly , leaving lacing more pronounced than other cheap beers . the color is an unimpressive light yellow , there is no smell , and the taste is watery yet drinkable .  brewed in honor / sacrifice to mother nature after floods in the area around the brewery . good lacing . maybe some slight floral hops but i 'm really reaching . hides the abv incredibly well . light and smooth , caramel malt sweetness in the main , hops very subdued again . a bit of oomph from the malt in the finish , but this could nearly pass for an ordinary bitter . as it warms the finish has a bit more yeast character than it should really . would like a bit more hop character ( no surprise there ) to match the dominant malt but certainly an easy drinker .

saaz , pale malt , and light-struck hop aromas . sweet pale malt upfront ... followed by an explosion of saaz flavor !  bottle given to me by my brother in-law who appreciates good beer but also buys cheap stuff regularly . he drinks it like soda pop . a - nothing special although it has a little more color than some macros . head faded to a thin ring in minutes . good everyday beer but not quite up to pbr ... pretty close , but not quite there . decent picnic beer and a good alternative to bud or coors .  aroma was very complex , spicy , pungent . flavor was just a mass of confusion . sasion ? triple ? wtf ? the reason this `` triple is so hard to nail down is absolutely flabbergasting . the brewer was very proud to tell us that 9 different strains of yeast were use to ferment this concoction . why 9 ? what was there about each that he hoped to add to his beer ? the real answer is that for a triple , you triple the malt bill .

not too much in the smell , just a bit of spice . taste is pretty good . a very enjoyable , easy drinking beer .  pours a more clear than hazey or cloudy , muted sunshine . not a lot of bubbles or head for a tripel . a little lacing slinks off the glass slowly .  the infection has n't totally killed the other flavors quite yet and there are still some bourbon notes that save the beer mouthfeel : medium body with medium to low carbonation overall : i really want to try this one when it is not infected .

aroma is a little sweet and fruity , but not too robust . great , super-grapefruity hop flavor along with a just barely noticable sweet maltiness .  a - pours a cloudy pale orange with a dismal looking white head . no lacing .  nice clean mouthfeel , with just the right amount of carbonation .

aroma : sour wet socks drenched in caramel . not appealing . a good beer , though not a good represenation of the style .  had a slight off-white glass ring for a head , over a hazy golden-yellow body . there was negligible lace , and not enough carbonation visible .  despite the lack of carbonation , the feel is good for the style , quite smooth and silky .

i 'm pretty sure that the only cream ale i 've ever had was genessee and that was back in ohh i 'd say about '89 and i did n't know a whole heck of alot about beer back then so.. i guess this will be a new experience . s- not much of an aroma , just hints of cereal grains and grasses , maybe corn husk , and a touch of vanilla and something like cassia . i 'm rather impressed .  opens with a complete lack of carbonation pours a hazed caramel with a modest amount of tan head . some floaties , trace amounts of lacing & head retention s : sourness & tartness ; vinegar & leather , a bit of horse blanket as this warms t : follows the nose , peaches & plums hidden underneath , along with much oaky dryness , some vanilla hides there as well .  good mouthfeel .

some notes of musty , aged leather.. like a baseball glove you keep in the basement . what a huge disappointment flavorwise , mostly based upon the uniquely intense nose . other : no aftertaste save a slight generic kahlua leftover .  wacko poured an almost orange color , with a very small head that went away quickly .  m : thick and chewy body .
s- some grain and alcohol , the main aroma is of corn and husk .  poured dark yellow with a quickly disappointing head .  mf- a nice medium bodied beer that has good carbonation level .

nose is heavy on the apricots , fresh and crisp , sweet with the start sweet and the malt profile decent , the top fair to middling in feel .  appearance : pours a translucent golden-brownish color . the head is thin and fizzy and dissipates quickly leaving no lacing .  nothing overly sticks out .. m : lighter side of medium body , high carbonation , crisp clean feel .

rather low aroma . hoppy but not much else going on . the lack of aroma does nothing to knock it down .  dead head , with zero lacing .  goes beyond anything recognized as beer , anywhere ... no , it 's closer to port , and should be consumed as such . thick on the tongue at first , then mild , still with a sweet , treacly coating that trickles down the throat .

looks like any b/m/c lager . a pleasantly dry-sweet combo of the only slightly sweet apricot and the heavy , wit ( belgian wit style ) wheat . apricot is marginally too sweet , but salvaged by a sourness that prevents this from becoming undrinkable . the wheat is good .  poured into a tulip snifter . pours a somewhat cloudy gold . the head was initially about one finger of white foam , but it fizzed away into nothingness in almost record time . no lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is thick and fairly creamy , not bad at all .

smell was fruity , spicey , and malty , but more with the fruits .  appearance : i believe that the can is quite the looker , but the beer color itself is an avergage light yellow . it has a head that quickly fades into a white ring . smell : it has an average smell of weak corn flakes . drinkability : a quite drinkable near beer also i have to say , it goes down smooth , and has a weak aftertaste to it that allows the flavor to be savored .  nice body , its just not balanced or enjoyable to drink .

s -- -roast and chocolate malt . t -- -rich mocha and roast with balanced bitterness .  i did n't think that i 'd like it ( probably because of the bad experience with the first one ) it pours out a rather pale gold , looking a bit like regular bud . i 'd suggest a switch to a brown bottle to help prevent skunking .  m - nice carbonation , creaminess .

its a lighter looking pale , and its pretty floral , and aromatic . i guess you could call this a session beer , but by my standards i dont like its low alcohol content . its light , and refreshing , and tastes like a mix between a citrusy tangerine , and apricots .  no stickiness in the lace that is left . not much in the smell , but it is a bit maltier and bit more noticeable than , say , a typical michelob . taste is a bit sweeter and maltier than the 'typical ' macro . the rice is fairly prominent . a baby step up from the 'typical ' macro like bud .  long aftertaste as the sweetness lingers quite a while . medium-heavy in body .

the smell was very complex . it had elements of citrus , alcohol , and other things . the taste was similar , except for the overbearing taste of an old musty house with moth balls .  it pours with a golden body topped by a thin white head with little lace .  mouthfeel is light , crisp and on the smooth side with high , fizzy carbonation , a very light body and decent drinkability .

i can almost taste the watery goodness that is foreshadows ... s : smells like muted frat house basement and cheap grain and/or cattle feed .  poured into a ccb tulip . a : this is one awful looking beer . runny mud puddle brown color .  good carbonation .

a sweet malt aroma permeated the nose with hints of spice and banana .  appearance is quite bad , cloudy chestnut brown with basically no head , and the little there was faded almost instantaneously .  mouthfeel : just interesting enough to make me want to drink another in 5 years .

the aroma was of peaches . okay , good on both accounts .  it poured a translucent brown that was somehow still brilliantly colored . there was very little visible head .  the finish was clean , mouthfeel was crisp .

nearly white head ( if it can be called that , i get no head retention from this foam ) s // roasted barley and chocolate and coffee like roasted flavors strongly present , and a malty sweetness joined with caramel and maybe brown sugar or maple . a bit of citrus hops present , counterbalancing an otherwise malty nose . t // barley and maple syrup provide an adequate sweetness with a drier , roasted and burnt flavor . d // this is pretty hard to finish .  my illuminator came entirely devoid of head , it trailed no lace , and its sullen body lacked fullness despite a complete lack of carbonation .  mouthfeel : light crisp from start to finish .
