a : larger than desired head of white merengue topping ( i stole that from a previous review because it 's the best description ) s : spicy scent with mild hop and malt scent . more yeasty as with the saisons .  a - pours a straw yellow with a white one finger head that dissipates very quickly no lacing .  m : soft , nicely carbonated , fairly substantial . nice .

a : yellow/orange with small rising bubbles ; slightly cloudy , short lived white head s : citrus and sweet t : initial burst of tang , not quite orange in flavor ; reminds me of tang , giving way to a faint suggestion of plastic ; does not taste like beer m : enough carbonation to bite at the top of the mouth , but very thin on the pallate ; leaves quickly d : pleasing if you want a thin tasting beer that suggests citrus , but not enough carbonation or interest to motivate a repeat the `` orange '' flavor simply does n't taste natural , and there are absolutely no other `` beer '' elements involved in the taste ( hops , barley , yeast , etc .  full ruby red . pratically no head , and anyway , it is quickly falling to zero .  m : medium-light mouthfeel .

pleasant citric , floral aroma that 's cut with a biscuity , grain malt character .  a : pours a translucent yellow amber with a small amount of white head . not much retains , leaving nearly no lacing .  medium bodied with good carbonation and a nice malt flavor to compliment the banana flavors .

nice herbal , slightly fruity ( think melon ) smell with a nice pepper kick at the end .  a : it looked like yellow sprite .  pleasant carbonation and smoothness , soft sweet and slightly bready aftertaste .

would i still say that it 's one dimensional - low on the body and malt flavors , wicked bitter and one dimensional ? i mean , hey , it 's wicked bitter and one dimensional - and i like bitter beers .  from a 12 oz bottle pours a relatively light and unattractive yellow .  fell is slick and full bodied .

smells of yeasts , apples and pineapples .  blackbeary wheat is very pale with a small white head that vanishes quickly . it looks like a heineken !  m - well carbonated , probably the most enjoyable part of the beer , other than the looks .

bottle purchased for $ 6 at daveco in thornton , co. a - pours a clear , medium copper-red with a small , dense , off-white head s - can smell it from 3 feet away . molasses , toffee , and a ( relatively ) light earthiness . kinda cloying . m - just shy of chewable d - having trouble with this bottle definitely a new and interesting experience , but i 've no intention to try this beer again .  green glass bottle ( .33cl ) with a classic pressure cap served into a la chouffe tulip in gouda , holland . a : one finger head of poor thickness , no cream , and poor retention .  the mouthfeel is pretty solid . medium bodied , decent carbonation , moderately sticky .

it 's smells like a good lawnmower beer .  milk stout 's appearance is its worst feature . the hint of red , however , is not a good development as it causes the stout to look watered down when in rests on the table .  t- citrus , mild bite , little hops , with a warming alcohol feel and a sweet aftertaste . m- full with very nice carbination .

s - an espresso bean and burnt malt aroma with a powerful chocolatey sweetness underneath .  a - dingy yellow like a good hefe weizen should be .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a firm feel to the carbonation and an all around smooth feel for 6 % .

hop smell is strong but light , floral and lemony with a slight savory undercurrent .  clear straw yellow color . no head , decent carbonation .  light in body and carbonation level . smooth , crisp , and refreshing - exactly what you 'd expect from a blonde ale .

initial smell is of a dark chocolate bar , second smell is a little dark fruit , and more chocolate bar ! no real taste of alcohol is present which make this a dangerous dessert beer .  the beer pours out a golden straw color but without any head .  the feel is bright and fizzy , with a moderately full feel .

s- smelled like the outside of my favorite bakery around 6am . yeasty ... bread ... my sniffer is a bit clogged this evening ... so i 'm not catching the fruit/citrus aromas others indicated ( this may influence the taste as well ) . t- pretty much went with the smell . kind of tasted like drinking a slice of light wheat bread .  served on draught into a stella artois pint glass in ibiza , spain . a : pours a one finger head of poor cream but fair thickness and retention . colour is a clear yellow .  carbonation drops to the bottom in a cloudy haze that clarifies as the head settles thickly atop . reminds me of fundip poweder candy . ingredients list scots pine and spruce sprigs and this is a pine ale but i question the wholesomeness of the ingredients .

nice bitterness , good color and lacing and lots of malt flavor and aroma . but the burning alcohol dominated everything else .  pours a fizzy yellow color with not much head .  body is a creamy medium .

s : sweeter aroma , lightly spiced wheat toast . t : fruity hopping with a tinge of lemon twang , mild caramel .  color is thin yellow with a thin , thin head and only the rumor of lacing .  m- full body with low carbonation .

nose has a rich grain sweetness ; hops pleasant aromatic , citrus like crispness , start has a decent grain presence , hops underpowered , and with the alcohol certainly present , top is fair to middling in feel .  appearance - clear light amber with almost no head .  i had to check the bottle to note it 's 12 % abv . it is smooth though for being such a big beer . those guys at dfh know what they are doing with big beers , but i am thinking maybe those 10,000 gallon palo santo tanks they built are past their usefulness . i really am grateful a great ba was kind enough to send this to me and in no way want this review to reflect on doublesimcoe 's generosity . also , american brown ale . maybe american strong ale is a better fit for this brew .

not a boldly presented aroma but what comes through is quite nice . tastes like a sour beer that gets stomped by malt and has some degree of bitterness also lingering around .  color : cloudy/opac light amber with a white foamy top with big bubbles that stays forever .  took a little swig at first , assessing the carbonation . very bubbly , which i like . felt really smooth in my mouth .

the smell is nice and roasty .  the body is pale yellow , essentially clear but with a few stray flocs swimming about . the taste is blas and nondescript with no lace and no real character .  m : well carbonated , medium bodied , and has smooth finish .

sweet , almost apple like in aroma , light hints of wheat , fresh , crisp and clean to the senses , with the start sweet , top is light in feel .  appearance is this orange color . does n't really look too appetizing .  m : a medium body with a low/medium carbonation d : i really wanted to like this beer ... .
it smelled good , to me at least .  ugly cloudy amber color .  mouthfeel : medium body with tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

this layered beer comes out of the bottle quite nicely . this b & t produces a tannish , khaki head . toasty malts dominate the fragrance and taste . slightly biscuity .  12 fl oz bottle served in a pilsner glass , reviewed live : a - pours a transparent golden/orange color . the head is 1.5 fingers and dissipates quickly and leaves no lacing .  m : crisp and a little smooth , light-to-medium body , medium carbonation , finish is clean .

s : great tangerine smell . there is a malt smell that is not strong .  drank it straight out of the 40oz so there was no head or lacing to be seen s= typical piss smell of a cheap beer t= nothing special at all .  there are some citrusy hops and the slightest medical brett presence . kiwi pineapple and lemon from the hops , bit a biting bitter hop tang mid-palette . ov- another miss by mikkeller . there are aspects that are intriguing but to put this ridiculous level of hops with candi sugar , a bruiser abv and brett ? it 's like dumping jalapenos on a raspberry chocolate torte . if you happen to purchase one of these , sit on it for 3 years in hopes that the hops fade and brett blossoms .

( s ) clove , cinnamon , some nutmeg and definitely decent pumpkin .  very cloudy , almost muddy . the slightly off-white head features large bubbles that fade quickly , leaving a thin film of incomplete foam .  the mouthfeel was pretty good , it went down rather smooth .

aromas of citus hops , grapefruit , light malt sweetness .  i gave a low score for appearance not for the green color of the beer , but because the head disappeared right away , completely . the green beer with the head was interesting and appealing ... without the foam , not so much .  this has a medium body and medium to high carbonation .

had this one over at christopher 's in porter sq . s- nothing too special or inviting . kind of metallic . t- overwhelmingly bitter .  appearance : clear yellow . slight orange hue to it . it has only the slightest bit of haze to it . if i saw this on tap at a restaurant i would definitely order this over any cheap american lagers .  i enjoyed the carbonation the most as the mouthfeel made this really refreshing and light .

smell : a very progressive aroma that alternated yeasty bread , spice , alcohol vapors and caramel malt .  2 finger head that fades incredibly quickly to leave no trace of lacing or head .  overall : medium bodied with a smooth mouthfeel , this porter is better paired with food rather than drank as a session beer . minimal carbonation holds back its potential .

s : smells like a tripel , with some malts , fruits , and candy sugar/bubble gum `` belgian '' smell .  not what i expected in a german beer , a very light offering and sweeter than anticipated ... .and lacking in carbonation . appearance is very disappointing but the taste and mouthfeel is rewarding .  m - nice carbonation balances out the beer , medium bodied .

dayton , oh alefest : this was a very bitter beer in my opinion which is not to my liking.the appearance consisted of a small sized tan head that contained fine sized bubbles.the body of this beer was clear and uncarbonated with a yellow-gold hue.the nose was hoppy along with a heavy bitter flavor.this is a medium bodied beer .  a : a very pale golden yellow color with minimal white head .  a - one inch off-white creamy and fluffy head ; light copper/bronze colored ; clear appearance with visible carbonation ; small patches of lacing s - floral , herbal , and perfume-like aroma of hops ; butterscotch lingers in the background t - very floral , perfume-like taste up front that reminds me of bubble gum ; diacetyl buttery flavor is also noticeable beyond the floral/perfume characteristics ; taste becomes more leafy and vegetable-like at the end of the taste with diacetyl still present - this taste lingers on the palate ; somewhat bitter towards the end of the taste m - light to medium bodied ; moderate carbonation ; fairly smooth mouthfeel that 's a little dry in the finish o - i 'm not sure of the last time i had an english ipa , but maybe i 'm just not a fan of this style .

s - very aromatic . had a very big earthy smell of grains/hops .  red-orange color , goes flat fairly quickly .  m. fairly thick with restrained carbonation . d. a bit thicker and lighter ( in terms of hops ) than i 'd like in an apa .
smell : what a nice , full nose on this stout .  bottle , a : pours goldenrod with a mild soapy head , spots of lace , pallid .  mouthfeel is creamy and full , with large bubbled carbonation .

smell is predominatly a spiced cracked peppercorn hoppieness with sweet malty aromas coming through . fresh baked bread-sourdough bagget , floral hops , apples , sharp cheddar . some very mild alcahol fumieness .  transparent mellow gold in body with absolutely no head to share the glass . bland and boring looking .  mouthfeel : light-medium bodied with lots of carbonation that works for this beer .

smell : the smell is fruity and spicy , with a suprising amount of yeast and wood notes . it 's pretty , and smells nice , but goes downhill from there .  poured gold with little carbonation and a very thin fizzly head that disappeared within seconds . no lacing was left . nothing offensive - relatively clean for style . a touch of salt emerged as the drink progressed .  off the pour , this doesnt look like a pale ale i 've ever had . it resembles a beer poured in a non beer bar that makes a point to not place any head on the beer . taste is filled with unfermented honey , biscuits , straw , light earthy hops bittering mildly with a lemon lime zest to the flavor . hop bitters come long after the swallow on the linger and contain a touch of rind and plenty of amarillo aspirin flavor . i still dont understand how this is a pale ale . a bodacious pils with ale yeast maybe ...

aromas : sweet malt , lots of graininess , some floral hop notes , bit of sourness . some chardonnay .  poured from growler . head , retention , and lacing are dismal .  mouthfeel is medium , with medium carbonation creating a creamy texture .

s - slightly boozy . touch of whiskey-like aromas and lots of roasted smells .  2.0 a : murky orangish color . not really any head going on and thus no lacing .  has a thick malty backbone with a bitter finish m- smooth mouthfeel .

nose is full and reasonably complex and without the stuck band aid notes common in domestic 'dubbels ' . yeast notes remain subtle but present but are never truly endearing . flavor is sweet and with potent caramel notes .  the only real difference i could tell with this beer is that it is very drinkable . every other aspect in this brew is pretty bland average .  the softness of the honey comes through in the middle . th creamy textue is captured in theabout thirty seconds after the sip . it slowly shows that faint dollop of cream .

s - muted dry hops and rich malt . grapefruit and a bit of pine on the nose . t - spicy and sweet . d - great esb .  poured from the can , clear yellow color with a small and vanishing white head .  nicely carbonated , at least .

s : at first a clean floral hoppy aroma . a nice balance of pale malts with some fruity aromas .  it 's super clear yellow complete with fizzy white head .  i capped this one to save the nice carbonation and in the hopes that i would drink it later to get the value of the bottle .

somewhat subdued but very pleasant . t - the taste is really throwing me off .  opaque clay mud color . an ugly duckling quite frankly .  a clear medium honey small head leaves quickly slight soapy lacing s slight malt vert subtle smell t medium malt bitter slight tinny finish but not bad claen in end m medium body nice mouth good carb d first spanish not tiring - a nice beer to get in 6 pack form when visiting europe .

smell- strong pineapple , very juicy and refreshing . a slight medicinal smell .  pours a pale yellow color with a tinge of orange , very clear which is odd for a saison , you 'd expect at least some haze to it , hardly any head and no lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel has good carbonation and light body .

the aroma was alright , the head bubbles , kind of hid it , but what i got from it with a slightly fruity hop and rust mixture , it was in a clean glass .  as i poured this beer into the glass it looked a little pale to me . as i drank the beer it tasted just as bland . i never got a strong enough taste with the 4 that i drank to have anything bad to say about it other than just that : it was flavorless .  m - medium body and low carbonation .

s- smells of cooked pumpkin and mild spices ( cinnamon , nutmeg and allspice ) ... slightly sweet with nothing that overtly reminds me of hops nor malt . i actually like the aroma . it gives me the impression of pumpkin pie without any cloying sweetness or overpowering spice ... t- a mild flavor overall comprised of some weak pale malt notes , mild cooked pumpkin flavors , and some barely perceptible non-descript spiciness .  heres my experience : appearance - cloudy , pale orange . watery looking . not very appealing . huge foam mass erupts upon pouring , despite the beer being well chilled , gently handled prior to opening , and trickled as slowly as is humanly possible down the side of the glass . i meant relentless meringue .  crisp carbonation .

s : not much here . i was a bit disappointed at first because the smell was unimpressive . t : a nice mix of the c hops .  the pour was a strange orange that looked dull in some lights , and down right toxic in others .  m - the feel is smooth , soft and easy . ~ white it smells and feels the part , the flavor holds the most weight here and unfortunately i ca n't say its something i 'll every purchase again , nor will i recommend this beverage to a friend .

smell is very fruity , but i 'm having a hard time identifying the fruit .  ..pour left no head , clear yellow , that is actually deeper than most of the brews in this vain . in the final analyses , i 'd have to say , better than a lot of cheap stuff , and no worse than the big 3 !  do n't really feel like writing a full review for guinness ... 1 . ) because everybody knows what it tastes like and 2 . ) i 'm only gon na drink it on st. patrick 's day anyway because it sucks !

a-murky deep brown , no light passes through it when i hold it up to the light , not much in terms of head retention , there is a slight off-white ring around the edges of the glass s-raisins , dark fruit , figs , honey , booze t-raisins again , vanilla , weird sweetness with a tart/sour twang , flavor isnt remotely appealing m-pretty light actually , smooth , no alcohol bite , little carbonation d-not a fan of this , outside of the nose , nothing really stuck out about this beer  a - golden honey colored body - i aggressively poured a one finger white head that was gone by the time i turned around from disposing of the can . no lacing and pretty clear .  it 's really smooth and i appreciate the level of authentic bourbon present in the nose . and it is n't the bourbon that is overpowering , it 's the abv of the beer itself . it just drinks really , really boozy .

not much smell here , a little sweet malty aroma is about it and no sense of chocolate .  nothing special about this beer though other than its name in my opinion . fun to drink , but it will leave you wanting your comfort beer . the taste is crisp but a tad bitter in the after taste . the apperance is bland .  if you hold your nose its actally not a bad beer , the mouthfeel is solid , the taste is n't bad ... the only problem is it stinks .

appearance : golden color with good head retention smell : nice strong piney aromas taste : lopsided to the hops side .  appearance - no carbonation , no head , beer was yellow with a touch of orange taste - sweet malts with banana with a slightly unbalanced bitterness .  mouthfeel/overall : mouthfeel is pretty good .

it has a faint , fruity , sweet smell . ( it smells better than it tastes ) the initial taste is sweet , but has a somewhat dry bitter finish .  one of the better light beers . but that 's like saying one of the more polished turds right ? a darker appearance , preppy aroma .  full bodied with appropriate carbonation .

$ 11.99 750ml from the beer store , southampton . big billowing off-whitehead . nose is big pine , shots of grapefruit , and maybe a pinch of sulfur . big bitter builds and builds and finally overdoes in the aftertaste . could use some fruity complexity , too one dimensional . these guys are new , should take this back to the drawing board . and have a back-up name for the brewery once marvel comics hears of them .  it poured golden yellow with medium activity and no head . i came close to not reviewing this beer . i really questioned how this beer could be so far off from the traditional style , especially coming from spaten .  mouthfeel is medium , smooth and soft . not great but a decent dubbel .

great smell and look but low marks on everything else .  ) a clear dark orange , tinted red . zero head .  medium mouthfeel .

appearance : very cloudy , reddish-brown ( iced tea look ) , with a thin head smell : very nice coffee smell , hint of malt ( not sure i 'd know this is a beer from the flavor , vs a coffee drink ) mouthfeel : slightly thicker than your typical amber ale , but definitely not a porter - very nice .  purple tinged cranberry color with thin pinkish head .  the mouthfeel is a bit creamy yet light at the same time .

unfortunately this beer smells better than it tastes , it is poorly balanced .  no lacing or foam either . looks very watery and plain . taste - despite its poor appearance and lack of smell , i enjoy the taste alot .  definite bandaids .

smells of tart fruits , sweet berries , a big kick of belgian-style yeast and some light bready malts .  a : nothing great here , pale yellow , decent carbonation .  m : medium body with a heavy carbonation . a mild creamy finish .

there is a light but raw earthiness to the aroma and it is complimented by scents of new leather . t : more than less , a direct translation from the nose .  this beer poured with literally no head .  the mouthfeel was medium thick with a creamy nitro-like feel .

s - sweetly floral , i 'm getting a kick out of the perfumey heather . i enjoy the aroma more than the taste .  has a clear almost straw color with the average rocky head .  m : creamy and full bodied . nothing harsh about it d : meh .

smells of strongly molasses and alcohol . i 'm worried that it may be too sweet , but we 've all smelled a thomas hardy 's and still loved it .  i rather liked this ipa and i 'm not an ipa fan . great head , good flavor , it seemed a bit cloudy , and there was sediment at the bottom of the glass when i was done , but that really just added a little charm to it , but for regular coors light drinkers it might be a little off putting , so if i 'm making my domestic beer drinking friends drink it i 'll do so in a dark pub .  nice , full body with good carbonation .

pretty fair , unexciting aroma for a bpa .  with a hard pour into my pilsner glass it builds about 1/2 a finger of head that quickly disappears . the beer is orangeish amber hue with slight cloudiness to the beer . a little lighter in color than i would expect .  smooth mouthfeel .

s - it had a good fruity aroma , but i could n't really smell the apricot nor the hops . i could sense the sweetness but it was very faint .  piss yellow in color , no head , no lacing , no retention .  m : probably the best part of this beer to me is the texture . while the sweetness is off putting to the taste , the round sugary syrupy feel to it is nice .

the smell was good .  zero head retention or lacing s : bready with with caramel & some peppery notes t : caramel , herbal hops , & peppery rye notes up front .  medium light body with controlled carbonation .

s - sweet roasty malts and added coffee .  not too impressed with this one - maybe on a beach looking at bathing beauties in scotland .  m : on the full end of medium with a low to medium carbonation .

s : scent is nice ... caramel and pineapple .  it was a bit hazy due to some floating particles . the head was white , low , foamy with poor retention ( lot of lacing thought ) .  feels good in the mouth with a decent carbination for a dark beer .

aromas are sweet sherry wine and alcohol with a vague woody character . very muted vanilla and chocolate . not nearly as sweet as the aroma suggests . a dash of cooking sherry .  bell 's pale ale poured a golden color , with a smaller head .  m : not to thick , not to thin , the right amount of carbonation as well . probably the best part of this beer d : the more i drink it the more it makes me think of old coffee , i will not be getting this beer again .

the smell was very characteristic of a stout , chocolate and malts ... roasted of course . in addition there was a very sweet berry smell to it , as the name would suggest .  pours pale yellow with a bright white head that quickly disappears .  carbonation is creamy but the beer itself is incredibly light and goes down smooth .

s- pine nut and citrus . t- dry and muted nice pine hoppiness .  bottle- color of pale bright yellow , with a big bubbled white head subtle nose of grass , skunk , slight skunk , slight oats , metallic , and sour taste of sour lemon grass , slight malt , grass , and some lime/lemon - body is dry , acidic , and with medium high carbonation aftertaste of grass , lime zest , other citrus , and maybe yeast  the mouthfeel was good balance body and bitterness .

pours a clear copper color nice off white head that leaves some lace behind . aroma is light on malt a little grainy , where are the cascade hops they advertise , damn it if you say your using cascade put more then a pinch in . the hops i do get are grassy or is it just the grainy malt . taste is like the aroma but the malt is better actual hints of caramel .  having said that ... it looks fine for style , so there is n't much to say . it 's part of what makes a macro a macro . however , the head is very fizzy and recedes really quickly ( down to nothing without ever taking a drink and in less than 1 minute ) .  mouthfeel is actually kinda impressive . best part of the beer .
the aroma is almost sweet and very fruity , with notes of berries , orange peel and wheat .  pours a little flat and generally looks like muddy water .  mouthfeel is silky smooth but not too heavy .

nose predominantly hoppy and piney with a trace of grain alcohol .  somehow , it 's gotten worse . a : clear golden color with a thin head that fades really quickly . s : more like a pumpkin bread aroma than pumpkin pie . a hint of pumpkin , but the beer is thin and watery and has a pretty awful yeast and bread flavor that it seems like all of these kennebunkport beers have . somehow , it is n't the worst of kennebunkport 's beers , but that does n't mean it 's any good . a : clear golden color with a small white head .  m : nice feel . feels good .

well , it 's a cheap light beer . i almost swear there is no alcohol in it ... either that or my tolerance is through the roof since i am used to drinking for flavorful beers with an abv content of 7-8 % + ( i think mgd64 is only 4 % at most ) anyway , worth taking a dive into if your looking for a cheap light beer to stock the fridge with .  pours an extremely clear golden colour , way too clear for a hefe , and with a huge wedge of lemon i forgot to ask them not to add .  surprisingly , this has a great mouthfeel . lighter carbonation than your cheap macro swill means it is easy on the old tastebuds .

sweet nos , with caramel malts , toffee and some tropical fruit . good amount of floral hops as well .  pours a golden amber color with virtually no head into a weizen glass .  good mouthfeel , fizzy but not foamy .

the nose was promising .  it has a purple like body with a slightly red hue . the head and lace were kind of a purple/fuchsia color but both were thin . sort of like the cheap schnapps that you buy in a european train station .  no mention of `` ipa '' . big sorachi ace presence dominates the flavor profile . so much so that the hop oils coat the tongue heavier with every quaff . halfway through the pint my palate was fatigued by the intense lime peel/citrus bitterness . hop bitterness overtook the rice and malt and held their presence to a minimum . this was my first experience with sorachi ace hops . this beer is out of balance and too hoppy to thoroughly enjoy .

a : dark opaque hue , passes no light at all , foamy brown head , decent lacing s : mild roasted dark malts , pecans t : dark roasted malts , nutty , hearty , black bread m : decent carbonation , medium to full bodied , hearty , mildly bitter overall , a really good black ale with a full hearty , nutty taste .  dark , dark brown , but not black , slightly see through , minimal head fades quickly , no lace . looks like a glass of flat coke .  mouthfeel is very carbonated , nice and refreshing .

hoppy sweet grapefruit & orange scents with detectable awl-kee-hawl esters , which was not surprising considering the 6.4 % abv .  appearance - transparent yellow .  once you swallow , it feel like the beer evaporates in your mouth , very smooth .

unusual , very nice . atypical taste for the style as well . mediocre as a saison but nice as something else unique cheers jd  pours a clouded straw gold with no head .  m : nice , medium body , perfect carbonation .

from the brewers of guinness , there ca n't be much wrong with this drink . the only surprise with this irish ale is that the odor of the drink is almost non-existant . the flavor can best be described as delicious , lighter in flavor than most beers of this color and at only 4.5 % alcohol you can go ahead and put a couple of these back .  on draft at the soiled dove in denver , co . i ca n't name one redeeming quality of it except that it 's watered down and easy to drink if you 're in the mood for something bland that wo n't fill you up . might as well just drink a bud or coors .  the mentholipus becomes strong in the aftertaste and my belly is warm from either pepper or alcohol burn . thick body is making it hard for me to finish the bottle .

zero lacing or head retention s : vanilla & caramel in copious quantities t : starts out with a lot of vanilla , then caramel up front .  pours out light , pale straw and sits a foggy light gold in the glass with a miniscule white head that is gone sooner than it appears .  m. medium body with high carbonation .

not much lacing but i am betting on the bar not cleaning the glassware properly s-slighlt pine smells maybe some bready malt t-grapefruity piney hops abound throughout . good sweey malt character provides swwetness and hints of dried fruits . the fresh hops are really nice i just wish they factored more into the smell  pours a mostly clear copper-gold with a weak head even on a hard , hard pour .  m : mouthfeel was fine . medium carbonated , medium thickness .

nice enough .  a : dark amber ; no head , no threads , no lacing -- you might think it dead !  given its high ibus and abv , this is not meant for easy drinking .

banana and clove are very fleeting . i was pretty excited about the initial big banana pudding smell , but things just kind of died after that .  ' opened up with a slight hiss , but poured a flat opaque orange with some browner and copper tinges - no head , no lace .  the gouden carolus triple ( it says triple on the label , not tripel ) frankly smells awful , sour yeastiness combining with a potent alcohol character to create a nasty odor . '' but it always is that bad , like ketchup , vinegar , and everclear mixed together . there 's a bit of unpleasantness , but there 's also your typical tripel breadiness . the aftertaste moves from the breadiness of the initial flavor into actual bread -- it literally tastes just i just ate a slice . it looks and feels like a good tripel , tastes like a slightly off tripel , and smells like bear shit .

the aroma is sweet , slightly roasted , chocolate ( hot chocolate ) and some coffee and honey . overall , an interesting beer , albeit one dimensional .  pours a very murky and watery brown with absolutely zero head .  lighter bodied for the belgium beers and surprisingly light for the 7.5 % . the carbonation is good giving a creamy body here , a touch too carbonated but very acceptable all things considered .

22oz bottle poured into my half acre pint glass ... pours an incredibly thick and hazy pale orange with just a one finger light tan head that leaves a bit of lacing behind ... smells wonderfully of sweet and juicy tropical fruit , pineapple and mango come to mind . juicy , i know juicy is not a smell , but it just smells , well , juicy ... tastes as the smell led on , juicy and fruity , tropical and sweet up front . sticky and resinous finish , very good ... would love if this one was canned along side the regular daisy cutter ...  the beer pours a your typical macro light yellow with a fizzy white head that dissipates quickly leaving very little lacing on the glass .  m- medium body and carbonation .

really nothing interesting or noteworthy .  appearance : very pale yellow with a quickly dissapearing white head .  m : surprisingly light in body live a clean , watery finsih .

smell is exceptionally weak . only detectable odour is a corny , sweet , malty smell .  the pour was weak with almost no head retention .  this beer is way too carbonated , it ruins most of the other aspects of it , this one is very hard to enjoy .

smell is heavily scented with spices and of course , pumpkin . taste is medium bodied typical ale .  this beer was a slight step above some of the latin american imports or cheaper us macro brews , but not much . poured to a pale golden yellow , with snow white head that dissipated quickly to little lacing .  f : not there at all . way too watery for a scotch ale and the carbonation is near non existant .

nice mellow butter and vanilla notes with a helping of raw sugar and a bit of earth to bring it down . this has some nice amped-up witbier characteristics , very nice . taste is'nt as brillant , but it 's not awful .  it pours out a black-ruby hue ... really fizzy head that died quickly .  341ml bottle poured into tulip 26/6/11 a particles chunk sized to tiny suspended little guys floating around in a dark amber body with very little carbonation and zero head or lace even after an angry pour s peaty candied fruit with some vanilla and booze , smells sweet with some smokey toffee t a little grapefruit rind on top of what i smell but little in the way of a dipa , lots of barrel aging evidence but not heaps of peat but woody whiskey notes are there for sure m flat and watery , this one has no life to it at all , there 's a medium body but nothing else o as a dipa its pretty average lacking all the characteristics i normally associate with the style , as a strong ale or a similar style perhaps something more but as a dipa pretty average i do n't get the barrel aging dipa 's and i doubt i ever will , i did n't mind this beer but grading it as a dipa is a little hard . other then the complete lack of carbonation this could do well as something other then a dipa but what can you do ?

pretty much no hop presence , grainy malt flavor , a bit of corn , and some malt sweetness . goes down like any other adjunct lager fizzy , light , yet has a bit more flavor than the typical suspects . overall not terrible , yet for a pilsener it isn '' t very good at all . for an american adjunct though , i 'd buy it over any bmc .  the beer pours a very clear and pale yellow color that is close to water .  very light and watered down . any good flavors fade out quick and leave a tea-like taste in your mouth which equals a bad aftertaste .

s : a refreshing , sweet pine scent hits the nose with some lemon and spice behind it .  putting aside for a minute the fact that this is an ab product ( and im guessing most raters arent ) this is not a bad beer at all . in fact , im guessing in a blind taste test , it would do better than many of the fruit , smoke and other gimmick beers ive seen and had .  mouthfeel is way too weak , no carbonation .

a : clear reddish brown that pours a decent head that lingers for a while s : alcohol and stale hops .  this `` draughtflow system '' pint can pours with a huge head of quickly-dissipating bubbles and no lace .  very little body or mouthfeel .

very faint aroma . some slight fruit , im thinking peaches ?  bottle inspection : great label art , but no useful info . appearance : short lived white head on a pale , very clear , amber with wide yellow edges . head dies quickly leaving only feeble carbonation streams to show any sign of life .  thin mouthfeel , no aftertaste .

aroma was basically missing .  it is not completely horrible , bu is one of those beers you try just once . it is a very light shade of yellow , the head is too much , the aroma is extrememly skunky and it tastes very bland an non-descript .  appearance : gold with a 3/4 '' white head that dissipates quickly ; transparent smell : blueberries with a malty lager smell taste : blueberry mixed with a pale ale ; little bit of banana flavor too mouthfeel : very thin : ( drinkability : light and pleasant flavor so you could do two or three in a night

nice to see more and more rye beers out there being produced by brewpubs , this poured a lighter copper with a thin lacey white head.real funky in the nose almost like a wet blanket and bleu cheese just kinda unpleasant , now the flavors were not representative of aroma thank god mild rye notes a little tanginess and sharpness otherwise somewhat dry and grainy.kinda odd it was in a few different places and it just kinda ended abruptly .  appearance : clear and golden with thin , fizzy white head . `` not impressed '' is what the rating is telling me ; i agree . could easily mistake this for a german pilsner . i 'm catching whiffs of caramel and ... alcohol . taste : this bottle seems to taste hoppier than the previous ones ( which were drank two days ago ) . i remember we mistook this for a pilsner or at best a weak pale ale . there 's not a whole lot to it which probably makes it easier to drink more of them .  mouthfeel is thin and tinny .

a big porter with lots of roasted tastes and subtle cherry notes . the only negative i had was with the smell . i was n't getting much of a smell .  a - pours a cloudy yellow with almost zero head .  the mouthfeel is watery and awkward .

s- smells so good . nutmeg and cinnamon are the main players . very interesting . the pumpkin and cinnamon come on later in the taste .  on tap at sign of the whale in dc appearance is a bit watered down , with a light , copper-tinted head .  mouthfeel was surprisingly thin for the style .

not much to the aroma with is a very faint hint of malt , hops , and a little alcohol . tastes much better than it smells , but this is n't saying too much , just to say that it actually has a taste .  clear copper color with no head whatsoever .  taste : far too faint in the mouthfeel to really count as a porter , this enters the mouth limply , and exits just as weak . really needs to have bigger body to be a porter worth it 's roasted barley , and this ai n't working .

very light roasted malt aroma , maybe some caramel hints coming through .  this is a very sweet beer . it 's a good beer to drink when you are plowed . drink it very cold .  kind of watery overall , almost no `` mouthfeel '' beyond the simple taste .

smell- faint floral and grain smell , the odor is not overpowering and does n't add much to this beer experience .  dark orange in colour , with pratically no foam . a lot of yeast particles in suspension , not clear .  thin body , weak on wheat malts and a fluid mouthfeel . nothing off or offensive here , just understated for the style .
aroma : terrificic for sytle . very floral . low malt .  ugh . murky dark rusty color .  the body is way too light and this beer could use a little higher mash temperature .

s : weak and unimpressive . pale malt and sweet grain . kind of musty , too .  pours from the can a pale fizzy looking yellow , medium head with big bubbles and very little retention .  it is thin and watery , with just some lingering salt in the aftertaste .

aroma , at 1st i got a sour fruit than as it warmed got the sweet raspberriers and honey , floral , and than the malts came out . flavor i hope the flavor is as good as the aroma , nope the honey , raspberry and malts all weak  was luck enough to get a few bottlles of this from a friend who does the comapny 's pos displays . smell reminded me of a pabst , and the golden colored lager did not produce much of a head .  no mouthfeel . very watery and hardly any body .

admittedly , i have not had much experience with black-and-tans , but of all those i 've tried , yuengling 's canned creation is the best . the lager only becomes evident when the beer passes almost fully over the tongue . then the smooth taste of a quality medium lager flows over the porter start and leaves the mouth almost totally free of aftertaste . it is a true beer drinking experience , and even people who claim little interest in the character of their beers say without doubt that yuengling black & tan is unique .  appearance was a cloudy dirty amber - the most sediment i 've ever seen in an ipa . smell was n't very impressive - made out an unpleasant hoppy smell.. almost moldy .  m - disappointment . light viscosity and fullness in mouth matching the original smell .

aroma is tart and tangy raspberries , all the way .  this can poured a big head but died down to almost nothing and leaves 0 lacing on the glass . it 's a kind of odd , light gold color that is very , very clear . mostly smells like cheap lager cereal malts that you 'll get in pbr , coors , etc .  m : thin and watery .

s : very mild smell of sweet malt with a hint of hops . t : light flavor of caramel , i guess from the sorgum , maybe some honey with a mild hop flavor towards the end .  a : watery straw yellow s : sweet carbonated water with a hint of hoppy undertones buried way down deep in the nose . it 's probably the best of the american macro 's .  same with the mouthfeel , it was forgettable .

no aroma . nicely executed caramel malt flavor .  '' a : pale yellow , no head whatsoever .  m : thin viscosity and low carbonation . o : a decent schwarzbier that could benefit most from a better mouthfeel .

i 'm not saying that i 'm a diehard coors fan but other beers in this section are much worse . not very aromatic but most people who stock up on coors do n't care about that anyway .  drank from a bottle . it 's color is a clear pee yellow .  and the carbonation is too high , like a warm coca-cola in the mouth and thats not okay with me .

s - very slight . not much . earthy and malt . t - malty , earthy , dry , light cherry , finished sweet .  what little head there is on top of the cola-coloured body diminishes quickly . there 's almost a complete lack of carbonation , which i have n't seen before in the style .  aside from the bitter , it tastes a bit like carbonated water .

s : fantastic nose on this . perfect for the style .  it looks like a flat apple cider .  lightly bittered , yet overtly dry due to the high attenuation . thin in body and only a notch above watery . a simplistic and unimpressive dunkel .
s=all three tries resulted in a musty smell , like wet laundry , combined with hops .  appearance - straw yellow with a quickly evaporating white head .  m : low due to virtually no carbonation .

smell : like a macro with some yeast .  this is a really good beer when you wanting something cheap and okay . i recently went to a bar and this was better than bud light .  smells of light hops , corn , and water . tastes average really , nothing good about it but nothing bad , better than most american macro brewed lagers , especially the light ones , i think it gets a bad rap but it is n't that undrinkable .

over all just a bad burn .  pours out a slightly hazy ( read : too clear ) tamarind drink color . head is fizzy and wears itself out quickly . overall this is drinkable .  body and mouthfeel were watery and light . carbonation was adequate . overall this is absolutely an entry level stout not far removed from ye olde classic guinness ( but for guinness has a far superior body and mouthfeel ) .

good tasting beer and at the right price . schaefer beer taste good and has a nice look does anything else matter . if your looking for a good value i paid $ 13.99 for a 30 can case .  the first thing i noticed about this beer was the nonexistent head .  mouthfeel - very thin .

smell : there was hardly any smell to this beer at all . except for a ever-so-slight adjunct aroma , i could have been sniffing a glass of water .  also the appearance was much worse , murky and unappetizing .  thin very one sided mouthfeel .

smelled great with a malty earthy scent .  pours a rather insipid yellow colour , very clear , and with a muddled patchy head of large white bubbles . looks very minimal and rather unappealing .  very flat on the tongue .

s - i ca n't put my finger on it , but it smells awful . luckilly there is some raspberry scent to pick it up off the curb . t - somehow through the awful smell this beer manages to taste wonderful .  from a 750ml green bottle with a cork/wire closure . took several minutes for the head to die down enough so i could drink some . cloudy orange-amber color . for a bottle that cost me $ 9.75 , i 'm pretty unimpressed .  mouthfeel is way too light , especially for the style .

a - one finger of head dissipates awfully quickly on top of a hazed amber beer , hits of lacing s - toffee and caramel hit first , after that comes nice mix of piney/citric hop notes , a little tobacco and guava round out the smell . t - flavor does not live up to the nose , a little caramel and orange , some resiny hops , a little heat and some crushed aspirin in the finish , nothing bad , nothing spectacular m - a little bit thin , moderate carbonation , wonderfully resinous though o - something falls short when you sip this one , smells so good , tastes so bland ( comparatively ) .  it poured an almost rusty-orange colour with a cloudy appearance and some kind of sediment in there .  feel is very very thin .

the smell is malty , sweet and a bit citric . sadly , i think , its just too weak .  light yellow with a large white head ( large because of the pour from the mini keg , i think ) bad smell a sweet grain taste with some hops , watery .  m : too thin .

very little spiciness and nose overall is very subdued .  double crooked tree , vintage 2011 served in dfh signature glass a : pours murky light amber-brown with a modest off-white head . honestly , this beer looks like iced tea .  1 dimensional . flat bland like water . creamy .

very pale , very clear . smells like a stinky wet dog . nothing tos peak of here . the only thing i ddi n't really like about this beer was the aroma , which was rather dull , if not somewhat offensive .  this beer poured a pale yellow with a fluffy two-finger head that did n't last long .  mouthfeel : very effervescent . light , close to watery body .

s : virtually none . maybe a little orange , but thats only noticeable if you jam your nose in the glass and try to find something .  shiner blonde appearance - very clear , very pale yellow with almost no head .  this is a pretty dark lager.it 's honey colored , but the head is small and disappears fast.this smells a little hoppy , with some fruitiness and yeast.this is n't a bad tasting lager.it 's hoppier than most with a hint of cooked veggies or fruit.the big problem with this beer is the weak head and the poor m/f.this is very weak and watery , which leads me to say i do n't think i 'd buy this again .

aroma - aromatic hops with the usual lager veggie quality appearance - clear golden color with a thin white head and a good amount of residual carbonation .  it is a definite classic . however , the appearance is actually quite horrendous to be honest , it reminds me of when i used to work at the hospital and i would occassionally see hematuria in the catheter bags . still , it is a great tasting sherry , sorry i meant beer , and immediately reminded me of my mother 's homemade christmas cake . it also reminds me of one of my long lost favourite beers , brooklyn monster ale , which sadly i am unable to get hold of down here in florida . i think a few years ago , it was probably worth it because it would have been so much better than what was around then , but today , thankfully for us craft beer enthusiasts , there 's so much excellent competition at really good value for money prices .  mich ultra amber , 5.0 abv , 114 cals p12ozs reviewed as a `` light lager '' , poured bottle & gt ; tulip style glass a 4.0 - solid amber/malty/copper color , very unique for a light lager , very small head gone quick s 3.5 - almost non existent smell , but was not skunky like some american light macros can be t 4.5 - clean , mild balanced amber taste , much more taste & body that many american light lagers , a must try on the taste for this light beer , it 's a surprise mf 2.0 very light body , high on carbonation , very thin body d 4.5 - this is a very solid session light beer , great price , great on calories , and great on abv @ 5.0 % .

you do get a bit of coffee and vanilla , followed by an odd , chemical smell that reminds me of the smell of a burger king bag . like someone rubbing on vanilla lotion right next to you , or the way you feel about vanilla after a rare vanilla vodka hangover m/ decent mouth-feel .  pours an opaque , dull gold color with no head to speak of..just leaves a trace of oily film behind with each sip .  m : the mouthfeel is dull , lacking in any bubbly , effervescent aspects .

a - brown - reddish body with an off white head resting on top s - sweet malts , caramel notes , toasty malted notes , brown sugar t - some caramel , malty sweetness that then gives way to a light sourness .  its a pete 's , it 's wicked , but it is not my idea of a true helles . the beer had poor head retention , was excessively carbonated , tasted dry and did not have the underlying maltiness you look for in a helles .  syrupy , lifeless mouthfeel is incredibly viscous and oily that it lends very little to this brew , even though it 's expected .

beery and not hoppy aroma , but initial taste is hoppy grapefruit then the malts take over .  ellicottville blueberry wheat beer is a crystal clear , pale straw colored beer with a small white head that quickly fades to a thin white blotch . lemon and wheat tones lie underneath .  this beer is very weak , thin and watery .

smell is slightly skunky with an unmistakable lager smell . beyond the skunk smell there 's a decent amount of caramel and cereal in the nose with some mineral notes as well .  woody 's wheat is an golden ale that pours with a decent amount of carbonation briefly creating a loose pillar of foam that falls flat quite quickly . i make an extra effort to get the yeast out of the bottle , and the beer in my glass gets very cloudy -- almost turning the color of the beer from gold to amber .  m - under carbonated and watery .

it has a kinda of stale smell , and same thing with the taste .  description on their pint glass : a pale ale made with hallertau hops the colour and appearance is too pale to be a pale ale . in some ways , it looks like a cold pilsner with a weak half inch head .  slightly flat . ends up feeling a bit watery .
the aroma is very light , a bit of apple and rice .  a - pours without much of a head , and does n't leave much lacing .  very thin mouthfeel .

there is no smell to this beer . i simpy ca n't smell anything . no aroma .  this beer is watery , effervescent , refreshing , and not very flavorful . this beer had very little body and not much flavor with the exception of some light , and not altogether unpleasant , corn adjunct flavor .  the palate feels thin for the style and the flavors that it 's supporting .

the nose is awesome for an apa . it is a tad drying in the finish , and there is some leafy bite in the finish as well , but this beer is quite good , refreshing , enjoyable , with a mouthfeel that is a bit citrusy and an aftertaste that is very mild .  look : pours a little darker than pale golden yellow with good clarity and a little fizzy head with poor retention .  not much to it really , kinda thin .

quite a gusher ! the nose is still a bit rough on this beer . there are fruity notes , but theyre definitely still hidden below a weird layer of bleu cheese funkiness and bile . the nose is still a major turn-off for me , but the flavors good .  pours a three finger white head that fades quickly to a ring leaving no lace .  m - the biggest disappointment of this beer - very watery thin mouthfeel that makes it seem like a macrobrew with the ipa flavor added in .

has some herbal/ citrus aromas , but there is some funk and cheese and rubber too . yuck .  it pours a real nice color , and the bottle is pretty nice if you collect , but the taste is vile .  tastes sweet and watery . becomes somewhat more flavorful as it warms , but still fairly watery . very drinkable , though . and very cheap .

the nose is skunky , and i immediately think of beck 's and wan na pour this or feed it to the dog , but resist as i 'm thirsty and the dog ai n't around . aside from that beck 's skunk on the nose this is aint bad for a session lager , and its practically tailor-made to cut the greasy bar snacks and pub-grub .  thanks to chris for the arkansas tick . a - orangish copper beer with a finger of head that had good retention and left a bit of lacing .  nor is there any body to it , thin and watered down seems to be a theme here .

the beer has a somewhat unpleasant funky barnyard smell with some fruit in the background .  i like to try new things and i never drank sour ale before but i did not anticipate how sour , sour could be . to me it tasted like vinegar . i spent half an hour trying to drink the blasted stuff hoping that i would `` develope a taste '' for it . the bottle cost me $ 7 ( 750ml ) and i consider it money well spent since i now know that sour ale is not for me . there are many good reveiws of this ale , apparently there are those who like sour tasting beer , but it is not for everybody .  overall considering there was nearly no carbonation , this is a good example for the style . although there was no carbonation , there was a medium body .

the only problem is that unibroue beat brick to the punch , offering la bolduc in the traditional stubby , not the twist-off mutant used by brick . there as hardly any nose to speak of . the flavour was what i expected - grainy , some corn , no discernable hops with respect to scent , flavour , and bitterness .  pours a dim sort of orangy golden color with lots of white creamy head that is positively clinging to the glass .  it 's looks nice enough with a pitch black body . again , there 's the big , black grains along with a distinctly english yeast milk or cream-like flavor . but there 's an awful astringency that throws it all off and makes me frown and put my glass down .

second beer of the day at the rattle n hum 's kuhnhenn event . as with the hefe i had before this , the bartender seemed to be pouring to minimize the amount of foam topping the beer . the aroma is great , it 's pungent and very heavy on the tangerine , with some of the expected coriander shining through as well . while it did n't come across this way in the aroma , on my palate it seemes like kuhnhenn just went a little too heavy on the tangerine for the beer 's own good .  served in a tulip glass . a - pours with a big off-white foam that eventually settles to a thin collar and some hazy film , leaving behind spotty lace .  m - i think the mouthfeel is where bud really missed the mark . thin , watery , and fizzy .

s- the smell is very weak . not impressed . very subtle . but nothing remarkable here .  wow ... this was n't that great really . had a good head when i poured it but that was about it .  the taste has similar notes of the aroma but the beer is so light feeling that it is distracting to the drinker . i want a fuller feel . however , the feel and finish just destroy this beer .

s : like sour candy .  color is near white with a nice thick tight head . in the end its just a weak white and is not a brew i whould go out and look for .  m/d : a light body that is thin and watery .

not a guiness sour , but kind of an unpleasant nose . overall a pretty nice easy drinking stout .  nice orange colour , good looking but not persistant foam s. strong smell t. rather spicy and sweet , strong taste m. persistant malty mouthfeel d. easy to drink but not enjoyable ok to try it once but wo n't do it again , anyone interested in my other bottle ?  slick , somewhat buttery mouthfeel ; the diacetyl really detracts from the texture .
at first this one poured nice , looked appealing , smelled great .  a-pours a yellow-golden color w/a rich white soapy head that lasts a long time .  m : rather unbalanced .

weak nose , some very mild english hop aroma and faint toasted pale malt .  three floyds needs to expand out of it 's hop profile , and try something new . this beer tasted similar to the dreadnaught with a touch of coffee on the finish .  however , this is very thin , making this taste rather stale . this beer is light in body , moderately carbonated and a little watery to boot .

i could not place the aroma , but i did notice that it was slightly `` off '' somehow . initially , it tasted a bit offensive .  it 's dark brown in color with a nice rich ruby highlights . it is cloudy , light passes through easily enough , but you ca n't see any clear images .  its light bodied and very effervescent and a touch watery . its an okay beer but lacks many body and malt characterstics that i find desirable for my sessionable , drinkable brews .

it actually tasted a bit skunky to me..i 've never seen this beer in the czech republic ... maybe this is why ... not a bad beer but certainly not up to czech standards  a hard pour yeilds a thick , rootbeer foam colored two finger head that holds firm then slowly fizzles to a bubbly , glass sticking crown .  the aroma is lackluster , the flavor is completely out-of-balance , there is no discernable mouthfeel and the only reason i can think of to try another one is to make sure i had a representative bottle .

the nose on this is heaven ... i 'm such a sucker for intense coffee beers . i get dark and milk chocolate and strong coffee notes . a light roasted malt character is detectable in the background , but there is no doubt that this is all about the coffee and chocolate . i was expecting something thicker and more coffee flavored , but thats not what i got . the coffee flavors and the chocolate take a backseat to the roasted malts , which are actually very bitter .  a = poured a golden yellow with a thin foam head . looked great .  theres a fruity sweetness up front , and a very light hopiness . overall , id describe this beer as watery and uninspiring.another gimmick beer .

s - metal and corn , some grassy hops , a bit harsh t - corn and light barley malt nice dry grassy hopped finish m - nice amount of smoothness and carbonation , really clean o - a good beer for when you just want a plain beer  the appearance is actually very nice . a pretty clear copper reddish color with a decent foamy head . head was gone pretty quick and pretty much no lacing throughout the drink .  does n't really linger in the mouth at all . it says it is a light beer , and it is certainly light . this is a slight step up from water and just as easy to drink . nothing really interesting about this lager .

tomato paste ? i do n't know if it 's the spices short-circuiting something in my head or what , but it totally reminds me of tomato paste out of the can . very weird and disconcerting . there 's a sweet-ish malt base to the aroma , though . drinkability : the smell still disconcerts me ... it 's an alright oktoberfest beer , but i probably wo n't get it again .  looks nice with good head retention and a pretty good lacing .  m- thick , syrupy , and too sweet . carbonation is too low for my tastes .

s : strongly metallic ( copper ) . slight hops .  appearance : gold with a red tint and a nice white foamy head .  t : more of the same from the nose , and as watery as expected . m : not much going on here . i imagine leaving a club soda open for an hour and then drinking it would feel about the same .
smell is a mild malt with something sour .  pours out a hazed orange-peach color with a fluffy head and some ringed lacing patterns .  this beer tasted and felt watered down .

soft copper color , not much smell . soft and earthy malty taste . not bad for a lager .  hazy gold with a creamy white head . very similar to a german weissbier like franziskaner .  m - i was not impressed . seemed watery and thin .

s : tough to find , i got some caramel like malt and a hint of hops , but very light in this style . t : nice biscuity malt flavour with some stone fruit and orange .  tried this beer for the 3rd time and came away with the same feeling each time ... .could be better . appearance - very nice golden color with tiny bit of cloudiness .  m : carbonation is fairly high , but it does n't stop this beer from having a pretty unpleasant mouthfeel .

nose - off putting cheese like aromas and over ripe fruit . taste- big improvement over that off putting nose- , lighter bodied with a hop zip of pine and pineapple , sweetness is subdued which follows to a biscuity pale malt finish . once you get past the amount of floaties and bizarre nose , its actually quite drinkable for a 9 % brew .  a - pours golden with a 2 fingered white head . dissipates moderately and leaves nice lacing .  it steals the flavor as the mouth is filled with bubbles rather than beer . the aroma was fantastic for this beer , the foamy mouthfeel highly reduces the overallness of this beer .

what gives ? taste : has the belgian funkiness but where are the hops ?  reviewed 11/17/2005 ( bottle ) : pours with a big head that is slightly off-white .  watery . mild . not much other than the head and lace . almost no character . what finish ? go elsewhere if possible .

appearance : nice golden color with a head that starts at about half the glass and slowly gets smaller during the pouring process smell : it had the smell of a typical hops beer , and was really nothing special .  alas , i endeavored to infestingly enjoy this beer , but only succeeded in cooperating with it . my initial thoughts on aroma were barnyard , sauteed mushroom , blue cheese , and flower - each of which i enjoy . luckily , the palate , perhaps by virtue of liquid , perhaps by temperature , the anus , limburger and durian were held in abeyance , though maybe only slightly so before finishing dry , and painting my tongue with three coats of its threatening vomitousness . it was bordering on nasty .  m - watery , thin , and weak .

almost no aroma , but it does have a nice clean crisp taste .  the beer appears dark brown with a small , beige head .  m : the major weakness here . the taste was off earlier i feel due to the watery nature and the lack of carbonation d : an easy drinker , i could down a bunch of these .

little to no hops in aroma or taste makes this a very easy drinking beer . if you ever get a beer craving in a mexican restaurant , this and dos equis are your only two real choices .  look : two finger white soap bubble head , hazy orange/peach ( about a hazy 11 srm ) , good lacing .  m : thin d : so thin , it is almost like water !

s- smells really nice . quite a bit of things jumping at me ... little bit of a sour funk , fruity mainly apples , yeasty , and some peppery spice .  very much let down ... i 'm hoping that maybe there was just a bad batch on tap as the overall scores for this beer seem to be around the b+ range and i '' m pretty sure mine 's going to come out lower ... appearance : dark , no light was coming through at all . there was about a 1/2 finger of tan head that looked a little chunky , so the appearance was nice enough .  a carbonation that reminds me of ginger ale and the consistency of pumpkin bread , though a lot thinner . consistent throughout , but a little dry on the back end , rolling into a soft , creamy finish , with the exception of the lack of body .

s : i definitely get a lot of fruit in the nose . orange and pineapple stand out . i also , however , am getting some veggie aromas like tomato ( really tomato juice ) and carrots . there is also a sweet smell which i ca n't tell if it is from malts of the fruit flavorings . notes : i ca n't get over that smell . i really turned me off to this beer . the taste was alright but it did n't make up for the ridiculous smell ...  this is not an ipa by any standard i 'm sorry the apperance is good a amber color but the taste is literally like someone took wet leaves and fermented them and the aftertaste is a bit like a chili pepper i guess as others have said but nowhere do i get a bitter hop profile or nose .  mouthfeel/drinkability- disappointingly watery in the mouth , and very lightweight overall . frankly , it does nothing to improve or accentuate any aspect of the beer at all ... it just falls flat . interestingly , the carbonation of this beer diminished so quickly over this tasting that by the end , it was almost completely gone .

nose is roasted and slightly sweet . tasty but not terribly distinctive .  pours a medium brown with a nice head .  this beer was not meant to be on cask , or it was not treated properly , because it has zero carbonation .

a bit bland on the nose , no hops , little malt , and a little cardboard staleness which eases gently into the taste as well .  heavy condensed top floats over the totally clear light gold brew .  the mouthfeel was thin with a bitter finish .

can barely smells any scent to this beer , a bit like vanilla what i could find .  reviewed 9/5/2006 ( 550ml bottle ) : pours a dark brown , color , tan head , good-sized , diminishing .  thin to medium bodied , though undercarbonated and a touch metallic .

poured a decent enough amber brown color with no head to speak of.not much aroma-your basic beer smell id say.slight malt flavor and no real discernable hop bitterness to it.very slight caramel or toffee flavor.nice smooth body but again nothing special.overall an ok choice to go with your mexican meal-sure beats a corona or a sharp stick in the eye.seems to be a bit `` brighter '' when i have had it in a bottle-might be dirty lines or something similar here .  poured a very nice dark brown almost black .  almost a watery feel .

tis allergy season , but i had no such problems with their ales .  appearance : a nice straw color that has a two finger foamy white head .  body is thin , too thin for my liking , it tears apart the balance of the beer and make all the nice spiciness and candysugar appear to be less intense .

you can smell the molasses used in brewing immediately and it lends a nice sweet character to what would otherwise be a fairly roasty beer .  color was a beautiful golden-yellow with ne-quality clarity . ok , i am not stupid , i get the point - it is a cheap buzz at 10.5 abv in a low-priced 24-oz .  m - starts off well with a medium body and carbonation , but it quickly dies to almost no carbonation , and a watery mess .

this has to be one of the most complex , incredible aromas i 've experienced in a beer . this is a big improvement on the blithering idiot .  this beer sure looks better than it tastes . such a dark brown , with little visibility through the glass . a lot of head develops , looking like a root beer float .  i think the lack of carbonation did n't allow the flavor to fully penetrate my tongue upon first sip because the following sips are great . the carbonation is missed but i guess thats not a problem with taste . m= really smooth i wish it had carbonation . the carbonation problem is the only downfall for this beer . could be one of the best in the world but , well as i already mentioned it has no carbonation .

very drinkable , no aftertaste that seems to characterize some of the budget brews . definitaly worth a try .  i took the cork retainer off of this beer and the cork shot , out i started to pour into a 40oz mug got maybe a double shot in and the mug was full of foam ( not head ) this stuff is volatile , . nice colour , not much smell , all down hill from there , taste like dead cola which is weird when its so over carbonated .  mouthfeel a bit thin for a stout with too much carbonation .

i am really not a fan of leffe any more . i drank gallons of their brews these last three weeks and they really didnt do much for me .  deep brown-red , with a muted off-white head . unfortunately , this first beer i 've had from brooklyn will be put into service as one to cook with through the remainder of the winter .  the taste , is quite watery and thin .

awesome aroma . best i 've had in a long time . interesting taste profile -- not nearly as much citrus as i expected from the aroma . very nice , fairly complex ipa . great beer .  a -- crystal clear amber with 1 1/2 fingers of white head that recedes at a moderately slow pace leaving decent lacing s -- bread crust , grass , light hints of fruit t -- where are the apricots ?  the mouthfeel is hurt by excessive carbonation and fizziness .
the smell is kind of a `` standard beer smell '' ... some faint hops and grain ... not much to say .  hmmmm ... upon pouring , looked like a decent stout .  m - light body . slightly watery finish .

a bit musty as well which is n't attractive . d - an ok beer , but the smell was very disappointing .  nice looking beer , mildly hazy and warm orange-gold with a hefty head and some decent lacing .  m= this is the biggest problem here i think . it finishes too dry and the carbonation is too low .

pretty pale , closer to an american style mega . slightly `` beery '' smell , then the taste '' at first an odd sweetness , but that goes away .  i think stone should retire their belgian yeast strain and burn all samples , this beer is that bad . pours a beautiful orange amber . the cake is a lie !  mouthfeel was the most disappointing part - it was thin and watery , and a little fizzy .

aroma , the moment the bottle was cracked open , was of raspberries . once in the glass , there were notes of chocolate/cocoa , raspberries , raisins , dark fruits and hints of molasses . there is a lot of sweetness in the nose . taste is very tart upfront , which i think was not unexpected , considering raspberries were used in brewing this porter . overall this is a decent porter .  the beer pours a yellow-orange color with a white head .  the feel is too light and way too unassuming . like drinking watery seltzer water .

fresh cut grass and ... sour apple ? nose is a bit disappointing compared to other fresh hop ipas , but still tasty .  this porter is a very very stout dark . the head is small , light brown , and does n't hang out very long at all . and what i got was a bitter , faintly coffee and roasted malt flavored , fizzy dark beer .  the palate is thin .

there is only a weak grain nose . the taste is typical of this beer style .  bottle : poured a clear black color stout with a big dark foamy head with some good retention and small ring of lacing .  beer was incredibly flat and not full and heavy which caused a poor mouthfeel .

s- nothing phenominal in the nose unfortunately ; if i were blindfolded i may have confused this with an american macro-lager . very grainy- the presence of hops was not detected . d- the primary saving grace of this beer is the fact that it is very easy to drink and is a decent thirst quencher , especially when enjoying hot mexican food .  a- straw/ honey color with a nice foamy head .  it had hardly a mouthfeel to it so i suppose i 'm being genorous in my rating , hardly any of the `` chewiness '' i 'm used to in porters .

aroma of vanilla , chocolate , whiskey , and alcohol .  appearance : wonderful dark amber smoky body with an off white crown that looks as patient as the tide .  it 's bitter but not much on the hop flavor side n m- very thin with medium carbonation o- this is very underwhelming , beer is thin and one demensional .

smell is or rich , chocolate , yeasty as hell disaster , and malt craziness . there seems to be too much going on with something a tad bit unsettling and bizarre . mild amount of a plastic smell too . taste is similar to the crazy aromas with an almost wine like taste lingering .  a - nice and dark , held it up to a light and could not see through it . maybe a 1/4 inch of tan head . s - i smell coffee , some alcohol and chocolate , and something else , not sure what . i would n't sneak this into a hobo 's stick and bindle , that 's how bad it is .  no mouthfeel but easy to finish and perhaps order another .

the bottle does n't lie in speaking of dry hopping , which has produced an exceptional nose by belgian standards , fully flowered above whiffs of banana , apricot , strawberry and toast . ( i understand these ratings should be just for the beers on their own , and rightly so , but as an aside i should add that , after tasting notes were completed , this was great with a spicy chili .  looks good , nice soft golden color , tall cap with lacing , looks desireable .  however , it also had a quite a watery mouthfeel which was remiscent to me of yoohoo , which i did not greatly appreciate . mouthfeel was watery .

i 'm drinking it straight out of the bottle so i dont know how much head and etc there is but based on drinking it , there 's not much head , lacing , etc .. basically this beer doesnt need a review , it just needs to be known as a very slightly creamy sweet version of heineken without that heiny aftertaste . if its cheap and you just want to pound some beers that go down easily and stay that way for a while , go for it .  a - this is a tasty looking summer beer . no lacing , but that is expected of a light summer brew .  mouthfeel the carbonation also failed to show up at crunch time .

mostly grain in the nose . it tastes fine , i guess . really nothing to get excited about .  appearance was great at first and then the head fell .  almost no mouthfeel whatsoever . this beer needs more body to be truly drinkable . too damn thin .

pale yellow . real carbonated faint smell metallic grassy citrus taste like a macro lager of the region . nice for a hot weather lunch on the go type thing .  appearance - white one finger head with good retention . super pale straw body .  watery mouthfeel with no sweetness left on the tongue .

wonderful . t : vanilla and caramel to begin .  i was crystal clear and ruby orange . there was a creamy white head that gradually dissipated .  my major criticism of this brew is the carbonation - there 's virtually no carbonation in this thing , and it leaves the beer a bit flat ( no pun intended ) . do n't get me wrong - i 'm not asking for a tingler here , but this thing could use some more carbonation to give it a bit of life . something needs to be done about that mouthfeel before i give this one another look - just too flat .

hardly any aroma though ... seemed very strange .  beer poured a clear light amber with a nice head of pure white foam .  it gave me cotton mouth a bit . the mouthfeel was disappointing . it looked well carbonated but it drank like it was flat . this beer would 've been ten times better if it had better carbonation and increased complexity .
