smell is slightly sweet and grain , specifically corn scent .  the beer poured nice clear , light amber color , the smell ... not so great , not bad just not like a hop garden like i was hoping for .  mouthfeel : light , almost watery .

nose is a nice roast coffee , a nice sweetness also of turbanado raw like sugar . this smells real nice . taste is bitter coffee , and a bitterness that follows on the palate into a hop bent angle .  a- foamy with a good retention , crystal clear tawny hue .  mouth feel is your basic club soda .

still quite good . the beer has good thickness and breadiness .  appearance is a deep amber , moderate head , very good lacing .  nothing offensive taste wise , a tad bit of hops and more of the caramel malt , but the mouthfeel and body are just too weak/thin to make this a great red ale .

the smell is skunky as can be expected being in a green bottle .  though it did pour like one , all crystal and golden in color and with a nice fluffy white head . but the lacing down the glass was extraordinary -- too bad the beer sucked .  dayton , oh alefest : a small sized ivory head that consisted of fine sized bubbles that was mostly lasting.the body was clear and carbonated.the hue of this beer was yellow and the nose was malty , hoppy and also of alcohol.it had a lingering bitter flavor and it was also acidic.this beer had a burning sensation as i was drinking it.there was virtually no lacing with this beer .

nose is flat . medium roasted malt flavors . fairly long finish ( more than i expected for a beer like this ) .  a : hazy copper/amber . lasting off-white head and lacing .  i had the same problem as shiloh ; absurdly huge head and way too much carbonation .

s : not much to be honest . little sweetness , little toffee , and little roasted malt . t : some roasted notes and sweet .  pours with a thick even head that gently subsided leaving fine even lacing . it has an opaque murky amber color with a very light unimpressive apple-citric smell .  very watery feeling . no body at all . the carbonation is very low . feels like bleech .

smells a bit like a concentrated budweiser , in fact . the aroma is a big dose of pale malt . a slight citrus hop sneaks in too , but it 's barely identifiable .  forms a rocky biege head of fine bubbles after a strong pour , sitting atop a clear honey-colored brew . carbonation is medium , forming a nice stream of bubbles from the bottom of my goblet . retention is good , lacing is adequate .  m : really watery mouthfeel .

this beer had no discernable scent whatsoever ! it is the deep brown/black one expects from a stout .  nice clear brown with a small yellowish head .  a typcial american lager . pours out with medium light carbonation and a short lived head . refreshing flavor of a straight forward lager - a touch on the watery side , but none the less tolerable . this is supposed to be the beer of texas , and if that is so , i would n't mind living there all that much . recommended for those who like macro-regional brews .

brewed by carlow for the british retailer chain marks & spencer as part of their line of bottle conditioned ales . the smell is roasted with sweet notes of grains and cream .  appearance was fine , a deep ruby/cooper color going with decent head and retention .  m : medium body . old krusher finishes way too crisply for the style .

smell - no smell . vaguely like clamato . no offensive or off smells , just odorless .  appearance- pours a crystal clear light to medium gold , supporting a full three finger white head that gingerly pops away .  mouthfeel : sorry ... . i do n't like the watery , yet creamy nature of these nitro cans ... give me some more carbonation .

1 1/2 fingers of pearl white head forms a bit rocky and holds for a minute or 2 . raw grains and wheat make up the entire nose . t/m : again , very grainy and raw . mayber oberon has ruined me .  12oz bottle poured into my narke tulip ... a dark but clear copper , lots of light tope head , good retention and lacing ... at first the aroma is really nice and sweet but then the alcohol comes through , too strong so it starts to turn me off ... the taste takes the aroma to a new level , all piney alcohol and incredibly strong , i almost gagged my first sip .  the mouthfeel was thin and the drinkability was okay although i did n't really like the beer .

nice piney grassy hop smell given off that smelled better than it tasted . d : thought it was pretty average overall but had a great smell for me .  the beer pours a brown color with a white head .  mouthfeel : not so good here . thin and watery with a dissatisfying tingle of carbonation , but not enough to break the beer by any means .

aroma-grainy malt , low hop aroma , and a sort of grassy , vegetal aroma . the aroma was a bit off and the flavor , while not bad , was nothing special .  appearance : it has a nice pale/golden slightly cloudy colour to it . it has a nice white head that dies down moderatly and has some lacing .  not much in the way of carbonation , which wold have helped this beer , imho .

aroma really just is n't there . very very mild .  if you are a drinker of stouts , and like founder 's mainstay stouts , then this will be a disappointment . definetly a stout for beginners who like hazelnut coffee . she hates stouts but said this was a `` good '' one . ordered a oatmeal stout next to get the taste out of my mouth .  sticky and drying , but completely flat . very tasty , but so flat that it hurts the beer tremendously across the board .

s : lightly roasted sweet malt aroma . not impressed . if the aroma was more robust , and the chocolate milk flavor was toned down this would be a really good beer .  poured a reddish hue with about 2 inches of thick head .  this is definitely a flavorful beer , but the feel in my mouth and stomach is pretty similar to that of your bmc lager . thin , watery , and generally just empty feeling . overall i 'd call this one very average .

smell is faint but is sweet with maybe a hint of citrus .  poured into a tulip , it has a clear , light copper color . the head is newspaper white , with a film of foam and really good lacing . there are quite a bit of bubbles floating in the glass , creating a more lively looking carbonation than most beers in this style .  m - really , really watery d - this beer had a very weak flavor and a watery feel to it .

it is cloudy light orange in appearance , with very little aroma , but a classic light bodied wheat beer , with maybe a slight wisp of spice .  good retention is noted . lacing is quite nice .  cloying sweet & way too thick for my taste . it tasted more like a thick tart wine than a beer - carbonation , where are you ?

smells of malt and corn .  it pours a dark , dank brown , flashing deep ruby at the borders . two fingers of thin light brown head shrink away quickly to a foamy tan puddle .  taste is ok - same roasted chocolate malt that was in the nose again no coffee - weak flavors - i have had stronger porters mouthfeel - a very thin light body with low carbonation overall - maybe this was past its prime or i got a bad bottle - but after drinking this i would not buy this beer again

a really skunky smelling beer . there is a grain and some vegetables but the main aroma seems to be the corn & alcohol .  a : really light gold , completely clear . decent head - fluffy white , recedes pretty slowly for the style , nice retention .  malt dominates the nose , sweet as if honey , clean and fresh to the senses with a sweet malt laden start , top is thin and a bit to watery for me .

the smell and taste are mostly grain with enough hop balance to make it smooth . mouthfeel tends to be light in body with good carbonation . overall it is a decent drinkable beer .  afterall , it has a high abv , it 's a dark burnt amber in color , and the label/name is cool .  the mouthfeel is pretty disappointing .

a : pours a slightly cloudy orange color , small white head , good lacing down the glass s : really not much here , very faint scent of hops t : slight malt followed by harsh bitterness of chinook hops .  a : dark pumpkin color . looks heavy . thin head and lacing .  medium mouthfeel way too thin for a wee heavy .

s : aroma is faint , with little that is distinguishable . though decent , it pales in comparison to some of their other flavors .  nice amber coulour ( a bit hazy ) and fine foam .  the beer seemed to `` fizz out '' a little when i poured it , and as i drank it seemed thin and definitely lacking carbonation .

overall , a nice sweet scent , with light hints of fruitness , and just the right amount of spices . perfect for a winter warmer . hints of ginger and nutmeg are most pleasant . the beer has the perfect level of sweet maltiness , enhanced by the spices . m : perfect . medium body , with enough carbonation , but not too much . o : winter warmers are far from my favorite style , but great lakes makes a wonderful one .  pours a deep amber with a pretty good sized head . great retention with some spotty lacing sticking to the sides .  m - there 's a huge amount of grittiness and carbonation burn - it actually makes it very difficult to taste anything , as all i get is tingle , burn , and grit .

the aroma is syrupy sweet with a bit of grain .  it started well with a nice dark pour with a head that did n't last very long which was n't unexpected given the abv .  mouthfeel - thin and under-carbonated .

nose is damp and unremarkable , but then this is a `` low-carb light lager '' .  no balance here , just tons of bitterness . well , i guess taste is very subjective and relative to a baseline ... some see a glass half full and some see ... i wo n't be buying it again .  m : carbonation dominates . watery .

the nose was actually very nice . quite a chocolatey mild ale overall .  lienenkugel 's `` classic amber '' pours stunning golden amber from a 12 oz twist off cap brown glass bottle with a freshness date of 06229 , or june , 22 , 2009 . head went to well over 2 fingers before dropping to a thin ring of foam with a freckle or two of foam here and there on the otherwise flat surface .  m= flat as a board . wish it was carbonated but there is nothing here . flat as a board .

overall you get a bitter funkiness , not particularly nice . the taste , however , is quite lovely . a refreshing tartness right up front . nicely carbonated , contributes to the overall refreshing nature of the beer , and that 's the most important thing with a saison . incredibly drinkable , went through the bottle in no time .  once poured , it glowed a hazy golden orange with hay-colored highlights . the foam quickly rose to just under two fingers thick and left minimal lacing along the glass .  pretty sweet on the tongue with plenty of dms butterscotch flavors . does have substantially more hop bitterness than your standard macro , but the label claiming 'pilsner ' is a bit farfetched . loses alot of carbonation when poured into a glass and imo tastes better straight from the can .
smell is of pilsner malt , a little sweet , maybe a hint of caramel - not bad .  poured into corsendonk tulip glass .  mouthfeel - not so great . it does remind me of soda .

s - sweet nose of bananas , cinnamon , and cloves . t - caramel apples come to mind initially , but after that fades a nice wave of nutmeg and spice rolls in .  fairly clear golden hue with a one finger white head that lasts to the bottom of the glass .  mouthfeel : thin for a dark beer but syrupy to the point where it sticks to your cheeks .

nose - a little funky and not very good . some earthy hops in there but , unfortunately not enough to cover the sour aroma .  pours a clear golden color with two fingers of foamy white head and heavy carbonation .  this is one beer that truly needs some carbonation .

nose was roasted dark malts , coffee , some chocolate but a strange smell that was almost like spoiled milk . i am not fond of the latter .  a - reddish-brown color with two-finger , off-white head which sticks around a while .  mouthfeel is very weak and watery , however , leaving me quite disappointed .

s : i could barely smell anything . i could only smell a faint bite of sweet malts . t : i looked at the bottle and thought the beer was a aml .  pours a clear gold color with a 2 finger foamy snow white head that lasted a while and left good lacing clinging to the glass .  m- way too watery , especially for a stout d- its average , not bad but not great . this beer is way too thin , too watery . this beer has potential , especially if they give it a little more mouthfeel and a little more cocoa .

smell was utterly neutral , no defining odors whatso ever .  maybe half an inch of quick dying tan foam . looks quite attractive .  the taste , mouthfeel and drinkability are the same : watery , thin , and forgettable . i was going to whip up some extra spicy hot sauce into some chips and salsa to pair with this beer , but i do n't think there 's a hot sauce on earth that would justify how watery and thin this beer is .

aroma is not coming off to pleasant to me right now . the aroma was very strange to me . i 'm not sure if it was the spicing , or the chilies , but i did not find it very appealing .  pours with a decent light lager head .. lacing is also pretty good for a light lager ... smell of some grass and lite skunk ... a nice effort that is enjoyably toned down of the original ... all in all : a nice light effort that i could drink when on diet at the beach in houston pretending i am in holland , but most dutch would point and laugh so ... ... '' sometimes i wonder , did he buy the frisbee ?  the mouthfeel is unexpectedly flat and heavy on the tongue .

the aroma score is low but that could be cause it tended to lack an aroma over all .  poured a small head with a rosy tint . beer was ruby red with very little nose .  mouthfeel too thin , in my opinion .

aroma is sour , yeast and unpleasant although beer has n't reached the expiration date yet .  a nice looking , if only decent tasting beer .  mouthfeel was terrible . very thin and unusually high in carbonation .

nice tan head caps this frothy brew . another surprise , almost no aroma here , just some lite pops of chocolate coffee malt . very sharp and cutting taste of plums , raisons and figs .  a- a nice smooth color , just a shade lighter than black , with a two finger foamy tan head .  s - um ... leaves something to be desired , a bit skunky and reminescent of a pharmacy t - much better than the smell let on , pleasing malts , a little corn m - not impressed with the mouthfeel , really light , carbonation comes through too weakly for a adjunct d - totally average , no place for taste in this bottle

as it warms i catch a little bit of fruitiness but a grainy scent still owns the smell . taste : much more appealing than the smell . the grains from the smell do transfer over to the taste . much better than any macro , however it does remind me of an adjunct lager , which i guess is expected given the description of the style .  lemon yellow with straw hued highlights and a whipped creamy crown of bone colored froth that has a surprising amount of stick-to-it-iveness .  way too watery for a stout .

the nose comprises roasted malts , chocolate syrup , light-ish coffee , and dark chocolate powder .  while pouring an attractive dark red color and having a large head ( at least for a minute or two ) , this beer has very little smell or taste .  m - the porter felt a bit flat and thin in my mouth .

aroma : huge pine hop aroma , citrus , earthy and grapefruits . mouth watering bitterness . mouthfeel : full bodied . the belch was a reminder of how hoppy this beer really is .  22 oz bottle pours a nice burnt orange/ amber color with a good amount of head that dies down to leave very little left behind .  mouthfeel is a disappointment , with a nearly flat , slick character . [ note : upon opening the can i noticed nothing that would indicate problems with carbonation . aside from the weak mouthfeel , this is a solid take on the style that first got me into craft beer several years ago ( altbier , that is , not `` american amber ale '' as denoted on this website ) .

s : delicious spicy cinnamon and nutmeg burst from the glass , creating a nice tingle in the nose . emulates fresh pumpkin pie very well . not much is discernable beyond the spice . d : a nice pumpkin ale , with great smell and good flavor . not the best i 've had but certainly good enough to have another . likable & drinkable ; my wife voted this beer as 'pretty good ' .  heard great things about this , found it in buffalo bought a 96 vintage.started promising i liked the color and the nice head , after that all downhill.had little to no smell , the taste was peppery ( overpoweringly so ) and way to sour !  this is canada 's version of budweiser and it does n't even come close to the king of beers . the only thing different in their process must be where they are getting water from . the water from lake ontario must not be as fresh as the water in st. louis ( or where ever my local anheuser-busch plant is ) because this stuff tastes like pond water .

blossoming cream colored head that stays at 1 1/2 '' scents are chocolate covered lemon cookies with hints of vanilla , banana & clove . heavy on the chocolate component - nice . the deep roasted flavors follow from the scent . no spiciness detected which was apparent in the nose . overall a great beer that i 'm very delighted i found at the cloverleaf in metro detroit .  a : deep brown pour that resembles root beer . decent retention and some nice lacing .  mouhfeel is crap , with absolutely no carbonation to add any bite .

sorta skunky , though certainly not over powering ( its not heineken after all ) - which i 'll chalk up to a green bottle and a big thank you to my 'local grocer 's ( well lit ) freezer ' . taste : remarkably good considering the smell . crisp with a little lingering sweetness .  i get the spicy rye malts up front , then i dive back in and get citrus hops and a metallic/minerally odor . the rye and hops are too out of balance for my preferences . i love good rye beers and this is not one of them . if your going to mail in the malt bill you have to at least have late hops additions for nice hop flavors , but this does n't have any . after making a lot of great beers in this 100 barrel series , harpoon seems to have mailed in the last couple .  carbonation could be likened to seltzer water . body is light , thin .
no aroma .  this naughty girl pours a hazy lemon yellow , with a ivory cap floating gently on it as it leaves a sticky lace ring .  mouthfeel imo was extremely light .

the smell is clean , too clean , it 's got almost nothing in it . just a faint smell of hops .  pours a nice ruby red / mahogany body topped by a short , but dense cream colored head .  but the body was too thin and the flavors were too weak .

smell : very little notice of hops with a slight fruity hint .  this beer has pretty much turned itself into something that somewhat resembles gueuze-lambic .  fewer hops than corona as well . bland , bland , watery , bland . there are worse beers out there .

there was a complete absence of aroma . the taste was that of `` purple .  a-light gold with a thick white head , some lacing s-smells like very sweet hops .  m- thick . extremely rough . i 'm puckering as i type this , mixing my beer with a bottled water .

the aroma is exceptional . a slight citrus smell is backed with untones of cinnamon , maybe even a little pepper .  ( bottle coded b3209 510 e ) : pours a very dark brown color body , with a huge tan head , average sized bubbles , somewhat diminishing .  very watery body .

malts are n't quite enough to balance an otherwise fantastic bouquet , though . with balance , this aroma is exceptional . the flavor in this hop monster is pinw qith a big resinous aspect though it goes a tad `` rindy , '' the rind flavor adding a hint of saltiness before an astingently bitter floral finish .  a : pours a tea-like amber color with a substantially frothy head with strong retention and decent lacing .  m - feels very thin and watery .

smells weird . an off vegetable scent and an odd meaty smell .  a : rich amber color ; produced a foamy head that was at first impressive , but did n't last too long .  also suffers from a somewhat odd mouthfeel , finishing with a dryness that offsets oddly the sweetness that it starts off with .

kind of a soapy fining note on nose with orange peel and maybe some annise ; on the whole , a sedate bouquet that is difficult to pull out .  appearance this is a nice , thick , brownish-orange in color with tons of floaties and a pure white head that showed good retention .  mouthfeel : thin for a red ale .

roast , pepper , vanilla and roasted piquant notes come bashing through the empire of horrid smells that it produces !  appearance : pours a low mocha colored head that has decent retention , at least at first . the beer is a deep , dark brown in color .  mouthfeel : it is watery and needs more body , it really does n't have a finishing burst of flavour .

first impression off the smell for this beer is rank off-putting . it hints at an orange or other citrus fruit , but it 's as if the citrus fruit went bad or is at least going rotten . this does not smell nice at all .  review from notes poured a hazy incandescent gold with a fluffy white head that lasted the entire time .  m : thin , watery , not really much to talk about , but not horrible either .

the smell is pretty much ... not there , not in this bottle anyway .  on tap at ord , in a weizen glass , for what it 's worth . the body gradients from pale straw to golden , hazy . nice lace . the wheat character is nice , with faint sweetness and hints of banana , but sparse .  m : low carbonation , too bitter for a chocolate stout d : i wo n't be buying this in the future .

hops run across the nose . sweet and rindy citrus -- orange , lemon , and grapefruit . it 's nice for a couple of sips , but i 'm left wanting something more well rounded .  decent retention and excellent lacing .  damn near flat . with ample carbonation , this would be a nice experiment .

i can not believe that the same brewery that puts out delirium tremens , puts out this henouis brew . bottle declares it only has barley and hops , but my god , how much mint did they use ? smell of mint , and soft malt . avoid this toxic garbage . elle offre aussi une amertume lgre rappelant aussi l'utilisation d'un houblon aromatique de premire qualit .  appearance is a hazy red copper color with tons of carbonation coming from the bottom of the glass . the head seems to retain pretty well .  mouthfeel is probably the weakest point . light body .

not much on the nose , some malt and ... beer ? lively carbonation , light , fluffy head which quickly turns sparse . tastes very crisp , a bit of sweetish malt and some hop finish . incredibly light , clean taste . this beer is actually surprisingly drinkable and an ok example for the style - very crisp , good served cold and paired with snack food .  the beer appears bloody crimson with a one finger off white head .  the mouthfeel is very thin .

a very clear porter . not what a beer should smell like ; though there isnt any horrible off aroma . t/m- light roast , light flavor .  the beer poured a nice dark amber with a small off-white head , but that was the highlight .  feels rather insipid and severely lacking . this really is missing body , sweetness and depth . it tastes watered down and not particularly inspiring .

smells really cheesy . lots of strong barnyard smells- horseblanket , wet hay , some leather , oak , and something that smells similar to body odor .  a - poured a clear amber red with a nice white 3 '' head in a tulip that actually kept longer than i expected , but still diminished soon after . an intense stream of bubbles erupting from the apex of the tulip trying to keep the head alive but failing . laced surprisingly well . the nice appearance drew me in but is very dull in taste and what taste is apparent does not serve any well purpose at all .  m- thin and watery in the mouth ... which was completely unexpected from the appearance . the carbonation was moderate and reasonably soft ... but the thin mouthfeel was a big turn-off .

barnyard aroma . the taste does not make up for the off-putting aroma . yes , some pepper and lemon sourness offset by malt , candi.appropriate carbonation.herbal ,  this pours out of the bottle a rich dark ruby color .  watery thin body , low carbonation , and somewhat tart finish .

s- worst smelling beer ever . t - weird malt with hop overtones = not great m - truly this beer 's saving grace .  alba has a nice reddsh brown hue with a decent white head , from a rough pour .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with no carbonation .

the looks was like any lager beer , golden see-through liquid with thin quick receding head and nothing fantastic ... the smell was not really there .  the beer is dark orange , a reddish tint , clear with some fine floaties , thin frothy layer that never quite dissipates .  in terms of mouthfeel , this beer was way too carbonated .

the smell is nothing much , maybe a little hoppy .  poured into a tulip . this one pours a hazy golden straw color with about a finger of white foam .  mouthfeel : very water , very highly carbonated , very unwanted .
aromas are barely detectable .  good color for a tripel .  mouthfeel is thin and watery with a mouth-puckering astringency .

s : smells like water with a hint of wet clothes and mildly sweet malts . no choco smell in mine for some reason .  dark , dark brown with a big , tan head . i get an initial hit of pineapple but this is completely covered up by burnt rubber and a touch of roast .  mouth feel : thin , with aggressive carbonation , a bit rough .

i was interested to try something other than a generic yellow lager since that 's pretty much how they roll in central america . the nose somewhat redeems this with some legitimate dark malt .  this beer pours a clear spun gold color . the head is small , but creamy and lasts until the beer is gone .  the mouthfeel is too thin , though heavy and oily , and somewhat under-carbonated .
s : corn . maybe some malt . but mostly just corn .  look : pours a clear yellow-straw color with a white head .  mouthfeel : pretty much like straight water .

stella artois pours a clear yellow with tons of carbonation rushing to the top and a clean white head that lasts a couple of minutes . unfortunately the smell is between ick and ordinary .  pours a dark brown color with some ruby clarity through the body . a thin khaki head appears care of a violent pour that produces a scant amount of large bubbles .  mouthfeel : overly carbonated and thin . not the best and close to the worst mouthfeel on a winter warmer i have had .

the beer smells like a typical tripel , but the alcohol scent is very noticable . thankfully , the alcohol does n't dominate the flavor nearly as much as it dominates the aroma . the flavor is great . the beer 's flavor overwhelms the alcohol , and the only hint of the strong alcohol ( other than the smell ) is a moderate alchol bite at the end of the drink . i highly recommend this tripel .  poured into my old guardian snifter pours a black , with some light underneath it 's a really dark red , 2 finger head with very little retention .  m : flabby , sticky and syrupy , with enough effervescence to make it tolerable .

the smell is grainy , maltly , and a hit of skunk . the taste is somewhat grainy with some sweet notes , but luckily the skunk does n't come through .  cloudy orange colour with a part bubbly , part foam very slightly off -white head finger sized head .  m : very thin and astringent , not full at all .

i did not detect much of an aroma at all . great initial hops bite .  nicely thick and creamy head , on a very pale transparent golden color body .  mouthfeel - kinda thin , kinda lifeless . some weak bubbles make it feel kind of watery , too bad .
smell : dirty rag of wood floor cleaner , vanilla and musty basement .  ( a ) - pours a pitch black color . produced a decent tan colored head .  thin bodied beer .

the bouquet is perfect . hops with alcohol and fruity accents .  a : poured black with a light brown or amber hue and a one-finger cream head that leaves a little lacing .  light bodied with a thin texture .

the beer smelled sweet and somewhat skunky .  came in a clear bottle , with a shape reminicent of a bud light bowling pin bottle . pour vlear , with a nice amber color .  carbonation is way over the top , too prickly .

this doesnt smell like an ipa right off the bat , very unbalanced malt dominant nose .  bright ruby / amber with a thin whispy white lace .  mouthfeel is thin for the style , and drinkability is average .

s : a stale sort of vegetal macro lager smell with a hint of grape juice .  a : nice little head that settled but did n't disappear leaving me to the excitement that would be coming next ! not a fan of this , especially since i side by side comparid it with the non-light lager which was great , and this beer just does not even get close to stacking up !  in the mouth it is thin and watery lacking concentration of flavor and depth .

all i could really smell was the warm stinging bite of alcohol and little else ; this beer was missing the nutty and roasted malt elements i 'm familiar with and enjoy in other brown ales . just wish the aroma was better , but that 's my only complaint .  a- pours a nice 3 finger head into my large weizen glass . the head has decent retention s- for those of you who homebrew , you 'll know this smell .  as for mouthfeel - holy carbonation , batman . so spritzy in the mouth it 's like soda , which really detracts from the flavor . mouthfeel is medium-bodied otherwise but it 's too overcarbonated .

aroma : metallic notes , something like the odor of rust dominate the aroma . there is also a musty , stale note to the aroma .  a- nice copper color with off-white head . pours with about a finger of head and constant head retention .  not even much belgian character m : thin ... would expect a bigger mouthfeel d : this one is drinkable ... but not great per the style .

straw colored with a ridiculously snow white colored 1 finger head that quickly dissipates to a fine 1/8th inch lace on the top . in terms of smell , i really do n't get much of anything , but that 's pretty typical of an american macro lager ( though straub is decidedly micro with distribution in only ohio and pa ) . barbecue , lawnmower beer , after work beer , it 's one of our family 's go-to session beers . this is one of my alternative to american macro lagers .  do n't get me wrong , i love grolsch , but it ai n't renowned for its exteme flavour .  mouthfeel equals water thus it is easy to drink but not enjoyable to drink .

the mouthfeel is silky smooth and creamy , however there is virtually no outstanding odor or taste .  appearance : very dark with ruby highlights . brownish with hints of red in the head retention .  mouthfeel is too lightly carbonated ; almost flat . too sweet , strange mouthfeel and an unappealing lactic aftertaste .

the smell on this one just does not approach expectation . yes , i get some molassess and coffee malts and a little licorice . no notice of any hops . like i said very disappointing .  it is too much alcoholic , bitter , coffee-like something which is really far from regular beer .  the palate is thin .
weak nose overall .  pours out as all foam and ends up light brown with a light creamy head as it quickly settles .  this has a water thin mouthfeel too .

a-clouded deep orange color ... .little head s-bright citrus ... .mandarin oranges , tangerines , clementines..along with a tropical malibu rum like aroma ... .very intriguing ... t-sweet , bright citrus again ... .same fruits ... good hop flavors and a mild bitterness on the finish ... not jagged or abrasive at all.. m-full bodied ... this is a sipper ... carbonation is about perfect ... .drying bitterness on the finish .  this bier pours up krystall clear and builds up a big porous head .  mouthfeel is watery - like any other light beer .

frothy head , moderate retention highly unusual scent . pickled eggs ? thankfully it tastes better than it smells .  the beer did have good color and lots of impressive white foamy head when poured into a frosted pint glass .  taste is also on the light side with lots of sweet malt , a quite thin body and no discernable bitterness at the end .

smell is pretty unfulfilling . typical for the style , maybe slightly more ricey than some .  now onto the beer itself ... when i poured it into my samuel smith pint glass , the color was dark brown in color with plenty of ruby highlights through out the beer . nice color ! i got only the smallest skim of white foam and even that dissipated really fast into nothing .  mouthfeel is extremely thin/watery .

appearance vibrant orange and clear body ; decent sized head that settles fast smell wonderful nose-juicy citrus hops as well as some nice dry malt taste & body taste does n't quite follow the delicious smell . the bittering hops seem to be outweighing the flavor hops , and the body is a bit on the weak side .  a- pours a clear reddish copper with a large foamy head . decent lacing left on the glass .  thin and watery feel yet quite quaffable with no negative flavors . surely better directly from the bottle removing the look and aroma from the equation where it 's smooth and pleasant .

smell : grassy and citrus hops in the nose , also a subtle apple scent . i do n't usually pick up pale ales because i 'm a hop head and i figure , why not grab an ipa ?  pours with a fine white head that stays , leaving a some lace . very light carbonation .  mouthfeel is too carbonated and thin .

aroma is kinda skunky . pretty tasty brew , but the aroma is not so pleasant .  appears brown with amber highlights , 1/4 '' off-white colored head .  well for a macro beer this one 's probably my favorite . but for a good old quantitiy beer it can 's be beat- does a good job cleansing the palate between real beers , is never offensive , it 's always on sale cheap , and is well tolerated ( at least by me ) meaning it does n't go straight through me like a lite and has a curious lack of the crappy physical effects most macro beers have .

barely any aroma .  355ml bottle poured into pint glass 26/7/11 a clear straw yellow with lots of bubbles feeding a two finger head that hangs around for a few minuets leaving random patches of lace s lime soda but the limes a little sour t a little grainy skunk with the sour fake lime m quite watery and carbonated like a pop o why do i bother ?  i felt it was mostly malt but had a thin watery mouth feel . nothing special but went down pretty easy .

the aroma is a very bland , herbal cherry malt vinegar with a touch of earth .  a good color for a dopplebock . pours with a good amount of foam and leaves some lace .  it is water with a lingering bitter finish . it was also pretty flat , but enough to keep me interested .

pale yellow , with no real scent .  since it 's a lambic , which typically has a sour taste to begin with , being combined with a cranberry flavor , which is also sour , the taste is overwhelming and the beer is unpleasant to drink .  very thin body with high carbonation . the weak body dooms this brew .

s - light grainy note , but overall a very sterile nose . t - light malt sweetness and some caramel notes .  smithwick 's has a gorgeous amber-red colour with an extremely tightly knit white head .  mouthfeel was a thin tasting carbonated drink - at times with an oily feel .

it smells slightly citrusy , a little grainy , and a little sweet . there is not much going on in the smell . the taste is comprised of a tad bit citrus flavor a mild malty sweetness and a nice mild bitterness to round the flavors together .  pours a rusty bright reddish color with a one-finger tan head that has average retention . the appearance is nice . unfortunately , that 's pretty much where it ends .  the mouthfeel is just wrong . fix the mouthfeel and get back to me .

the taste is a mix-mash of yeast , oak , and brett , has a sharp acidic bite i 'm not a huge fan of . interesting profile but not a flavor i enjoy .  appearance - 4.0 pours an inch of white foam head which gradually receded to a thin layer , leaving rings of lace over its slightly hazy , golden body .  m/d : mouthfeel sucks , like weak carbonated water .

the aroma is very skunky , and thats all thats detectable .  best before 06/07 outside of the standard looking fizzy yellow beer , its got great head retention .  mouth is pretty thin and flat feels like drinking a flat coke to be honest .
the smell is dry and a little roasted . some soap , hay and a touch of rye bread .  nice looking beer .  after a few sips , the burps from the fizzy carbonation began to set in .

the smell is a nice , complex blend of sweet malt , slight roast and vanilla aromas .  this stuff pours nice but it really gets weird from there .  unfortunately , i think this is the best part of this beer - the smell is weak , neither raspberries or beer , but a lot like a mike 's hard cranberry . the taste was just as unimpressive - a lot like drinking water , and if it was n't for the slight ( and i mean slight ) buzz i caught off of it , i 'd swear i was drinking a watered down raspberry smoothy .

there 's also some sort of off aroma at the back end , kind of like moldy bread . t : the flavor is better than the aroma , thankfully , but still a bit off . d : the nose was just off-putting and the flavor was n't good enough to really off-set that problem .  the color was a medium bright amber with a nice gold highlight in the light .  it was watery and thin , but no off flavors - just a little adjunct flavor on top of the water , and lo and behold - i actually percieved a mild gummy hop bitterness and aroma ! i 'm used to seeing empty cans of these piled all over my brother 's sleeping body when i peak in on him most saturday mornings .
these was no smell , just none . i could barely smell anything and my nose certainly was n't twerked .  poured a nice dark golden brown with very little foam .  mouthfeel , what mouthfeel ? watery .

nose : fantastic bouquet here , one of the best smelling ipas i 've had to date .  an unusual looking brew this one is ... a light golden yellowish brown with a very thick creamy head ... cloudy hazy and hoppy looking ... an earlier review said something about funyuns and i could n't agree more ... this ... is ... .funky ... not in a good way though ... the earthy spiciness of the summit hop is definitely not something to be single hopped with ... its just too funky and dank ... the malts do their best to peek through but that dank hoppiness cuts it to ribbons ... well ... it tastes like funyuns too ... very prominent salty onion-like hoppiness abounds and dominates this brew from start to finish..i 'm really really trying to like this one but i just ca n't do it ... 3 sips and its down the drain for me ... the dank hoppiness of this one just is n't my thing ... big disappointment obviously ... wanted to be one of those that fell in love with yet another ob offering but this one missed the mark in my book ...  mouthfeel was thin with a honey-like lager sweetness on the tongue .

very pale beer that seems to be somewhere between pbr and heineken to me . it has a grainy smell with a bit of skunk , and the light adjunct/corn sweetness that i find not unpleasant .  smelt it and it smelled very bitter for a beer , especially a belgian one . poured nicely with a cream white head , which gave it some potential .  mouthfeel is medium-full bodied and the sweetness is just too much . none of the crispness or dryness that a saison should offer .

not super complex , but good overall t : budweiser with slightly more hop presence .  actually , it was extremely bubbly , it was really impressive even though there was no head .  i was a budweiser drinker for many years before getting into craft beers . its funny , after several months of nothing but good microbrewery beers , you 'd think your taste buds would have developed and you would notice a huge difference between bud and miller lite . and i have to give some props to miller lite after all these years of neglecting it in favor of budweiser .

s : a good whiff of this boy is nothing but rich deep caramel notes . hops seem to be completely eliminated from this beer .  pours out a hazy lemonade with lots of bubbles rising to the top which maintain the foamy head . there is lots of lacing going everywhere .  mouthfeel is pretty close to water .

pours an awesome head and a very spicey scent . tastes of corriander and orange peel .  although listed as a `` pale '' the color of this lager was a deep amber with a quickly fading small white head .  mouthfeel is diluted by the alcohol content and lack of carbonation .

this beer poured a clear straw color with very little lasting head . the appearance and aroma were pretty average for a standard decent quality lager , but the taste was something more .  pours out a a golden orange color with a nice white head a finger high . dissipates slowly and ok lacing to the beer .  the mouthfeel is flat and not fun .

smell of dry pine wood and chocolate and a lot of vanilla . the aromatic smell was enticing ! t : i would have expected this to taste a bit smoother than it did .  poured cold from the bomber into the pint glass this shows an anemic clear gold color with a giant foamy white head and real chunky lacing .  very watery . low carbonation .

smell : corn with a bit of skunkiness . a bit off-putting and not particularly pleasant . taste : marginally better but other than a cereal-like aspect to it , there 's not much going on taste-wise .  this doppelbock is not as smooth as others in its class . this has an immediate bitterness/crispness from the hops . the flavor and aftertaste leave a lot to be desired for its style .  mouthfeel is just way too carbonated to enjoy the beer , it makes it a bit too hard to drink .

it started off real nice . the beer , poured for me at andy 's , came bright yellow topped off by a rather small , brilliant white lacing head . nose was perfumy from the hops and showed a little malt if you look for it . pungently floral and perfumy though .  poured from a bottle into a tulip glass . a- pours a dark brown color with two fingers width of tan head .  unfortunately , the look and smell of this beer were the best part . it 's bland to the tongue , blah to the mouth . calling it kenya 's version of budweiser is too mean , but i could probably reproduce the flavor of this beer by mixing singha , budweiser , and water .

s- no real distinct smells besides a faint hint of grain and malt .  a - crystal clear straw with a big chunky head with good retention and some lacing .  .could benefit from slightly higher alcohol mouthfeel : thin . watery . .carbonation seems high .

almost no aroma - just a vague roasted malt smell .  poured a clear , light golden yellow with a fairly thick white head that retained well -- the visual aesthetics were definitely a strong suit .  mouthfeel is very watery .

the aroma is a very pleasant mix of pine and citrus .  appearance : bright yellow , nice head and beautiful lace .  m/d : very thin , and almost under carbonated . way to watery and lifeless . the sharp/astringent hops is to much , and too thin of a body .
but the smell is all nickel and creamed corn , save for a hint of vanilla ( ?  appearance orange in color with a modest head that left some good lacing .  mouthfeel - medium light body , watery .

initial nostril hit is metallic blended with malts . the nose , in my opinion is dominated by the metalliness , and its gon na cost it a big score .  pretty good retention , very nice lace . looks nice for the style .  mouthfeel is way too thin for a ris .

pretty light , but similair to most macro lagers . again , imagine any macro and thin it out with rice . probably ok for a rice lager , but i wouldnt be looking for this again .  very nice honey , amber color and a translucent haze . there is a somewhat below average head which receded to spotty lacing . an enjoyable beer to look at .  way too carbonated and pretty thin for the style .

s : mostly metallic , some faint yeasts and sweetness . t : somewhat yeasty sweet malts , a bit of medicinal hops , rounded out by a pumpkin creaminess and sweetness , diacetyls , and a bit of pumpkin spice .  poured into a flute with a medium frothy off white head . good lacing of the glass and head retention .  i drank this from the tap into a snifter . the aroma does n't exist , ca n't smell anything.the taste is the same with hardly any flavor and its way to watery . all you can taste is a little hops .

corny , skunky , off-putting aromas run rampant here .  yellow cloudy color .  quite a harsh carbonation which obscured what i think was actually a decent flavour , genuinely reminiscent of the belgian strong dark ale style .

hazy brownish color , almost a malted milk . smell of sweet malt . taste is mild and easy drinking , a little sweet , with the slightest hints of the start of stout flavors like chocolate and coffee .  appearance : amber with a nice 1 '' head off the tap smell : some cereal malts ?  palate is extremely watery and hurtingly bitter .

smells a lot like a macro lager .  appearance - very dark , looks like black coffee . it is very black with the appearance , smell , and taste of black coffee . the head is thin with a nice caramel color which nicely compliments the color of the beer itself .  mouthfeel : indistinguishable from budweiser , not much thicker than water .

smell : little hop aroma . smells mainly of malts . hops smell citrusy . nothing to write home about .  it is a very dark ( black looking ) stout that does filter some light in a crimson hue . the head is a rock solid 1 driven by the nitro tap but is surprisingly light on lacing .  carbonation on this is tough to handle for me . very fizzy .

it 's like trying to get an odor from tap water .  honestly i think there most have been something wrong with the tap line ... a : looked good .  ) the mouthfeel on this is watery and flat.. again an apple juice likeness . i would have preferred more carbonation and either a lighter or denser mouthfeel .

it pours your typical pale lager golden yellow with a small fizzy head that disappears quickly . smell is hard to detect and does n't really smell like much at all . taste is pleasant ... it is mildly hoppy and enjoyable . mouthfeel is smooth and finishes dry just as the bottle reads .  color dark , head average , nose mostly malt and the start sweet and malt laden , top cadaverous , finish mildly acidic , the hops `` awol '' , aftertaste dry and lingering , ca n't say i find any redeeming qualities accept for the color .  mouthfeel- thin and watery , carbonation is appropriate for a light beer .

smells of caramel and cocoa . sweet and malty with hints of bread and yeast .  poured with the mosher method ... which doesnt work well with sedimented bottles . a. tight white lace , slight haze , orange/amber .  mouthfeel- thin , watery with hard water , highly carbonated , low hopped , and medium light bodied .

aroma - a mild sweet graininess , a touch of yeast . little if any classic aroma of banana , clove , etc .  this beer is nearly flavorless . poured inky black with a healthy light-brown head that held all the flavor . it 's not enjoyable for beer geeks at beer bars , it 's not familiar enough for the lawnmower crowd , and who on earth would buy a six pack of water-guinness for a fireside or front porch session ?  quite thin bodied , bit of a hop bite , not too much else .

aroma was not appealling in the least and try as i did , i could not identify any specific smells . highly carbonated ... after puring in the bottle , it fizzed like sode for a short time . i ended up not wanting to finish this beer .  original rating date : august 30 , 2008 pours dark chestnut brown , enticing brown .  whoa , i could only take a small sip at first , massive liquid smoke feeling in the mouthfeel . ugh . if you like smoked beers , then check this out .

smell : very faint if anything at all . sigh .  on tap at on photon ... clear darkish gold , an off white head with good retention ... the aroma is horrendous , eucalyptus , medicine , lotion , just garbage , makes me want to gag and not even want to taste .  unsatisfying feel .
